<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL SHANE GET OSCAR?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The biggest fight ever in Los Angeles. One would
think local products Oscar De La Hoya and Shane Mosley would be
thrilled to be a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   And they are, but for reasons that have little to do with civic
pride. Oh, they say the right words. They say how exciting it is to
be fighting in front of the home folks, but clearly this isn't what
has driven them as tonight's bout before an expected crowd of
21,000-plus at Staples Center has approached.
</P>
<P>
   This is a tremendously important fight in the careers of both
men.
</P>
<P>
   For De La Hoya, this is a chance to regain some of the respect
he lost as a result of his debacle against Felix Trinidad in
September, in which he lost a fight he was winning by running the
final three rounds.
</P>
<P>
   If he loses again, the De La Hoya we've come to know - the
Golden Boy, the money-making machine - could be only another
marketable fighter.
</P>
<P>
   For Mosley, one of the most complete fighters in the world, this
is a golden opportunity to claim stardom and his piece of the
lucrative boxing pie.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, such a chance comes only once in a career.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this is big for reasons other than the fact the fight will
clear a state-record $8 million gate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I've waited for my whole career for,'' Mosley
said.
</P>
<P>
   This rivalry actually started when the fighters threw their
first punches as grade-school amateurs.
</P>
<P>
   They fought one another when Mosley was 12 and De La Hoya was 11
and sparred many times later in their amateur careers, although it
remains unclear who got the better of the sessions.
</P>
<P>
   What !ital!is!off! clear is that their careers went in separate
directions as a result of the 1992 Olympics: De La Hoya won the
nation's only gold medal and went on to become one of the richest
athletes in the world; Mosley didn't go to Barcelona and has had to
work harder to make his name.
</P>
<P>
   Today, De La Hoya (32-1, with 26 knockouts) remains among the
biggest draws in boxing, but his hold has never been more tenuous.
</P>
<P>
   The De La Hoya who destroyed one opponent after another at
lighter weights has not given a spectacular performance for years,
often fighting tentatively and barely squeaking out victories in
his biggest fights - against Pernell Whitaker and Ike Quartey, for
example.
</P>
<P>
   And his last big fight, against Trinidad, was a public-relations
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   It could've been worse. He could've been beaten up and rendered
a has- been on the spot. However, it was bad enough. He outboxed
Trinidad - as unsatisfying as it was - for nine rounds only to
shift into reverse and cruise the final nine minutes, which cost
him the decision and sullied both his perfect record and
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   He says he's learned the error of his ways. He's promised four
knockouts in four fights this year, tonight being KO No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   His objective: Regain that big-punching reputation and take the
result out of the judges' hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``My style is an aggressive style,'' he said. ``That's what I
am, what comes naturally to me. I'm going back to the basics, what
got me here today.''
</P>
<P>
   With no gold medal and a novice promoter early in his career,
Mosley (34-0, 32 KOs) has built his impressive record in relative
obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   He has rarely been seriously challenged but simply hasn't fought
the same class of opponents as De La Hoya. He's faced such solid
fighters as Philip Holiday, John John Molina, James Leija and
Wilfredo Rivera, but that's nothing compared to faces De La Hoya
has stared into: Whitaker, Quartey and Trinidad, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley's career began to take off only after he signed with
promoter Cedric Kushner, with whom he won a world title at 135
pounds - against Holiday - and is in position now to become a star
and earn huge sums of money.
</P>
<P>
   He'll make as much as $5 million or $6 million tonight (to De La
Hoya's $15 million) and this would only be the start if he were to
win.
</P>
<P>
   However, some believe that De La Hoya is too much too soon for
Mosley, who has fought only twice since moving up to 147 while De
La Hoya has fought 10 times at the weight.
</P>
<P>
   The significance could be that De La Hoya is too strong
physically for Mosley at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mosley's going to get to the top,'' said Robert Alcazar, De La
Hoya's trainer. ``But this is a little too soon for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The magnitude of the fight doesn't appear to have had an impact
on Mosley, who is as even-keeled as anyone you'll meet. He
dismisses the doubts of others.
</P>
<P>
   The fact he recently moved up to De La Hoya's weight class? He
struggled desperately to make the 135-pound limit toward the end
and walks around heavier than De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in big-fight experience? He fought in hostile
territory many times as an amateur when the U.S. team traveled to
compete against other countries and knows what it is to fight for a
professional title.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, he has the ability - which no one disputes - and
the confidence to use it on the biggest night of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``De La Hoya has a lot of casual boxing fans,'' he said. ``They
support him, they follow him. Me? The real boxing fans know who
Sugar Shane is.
</P>
<P>
   ``After this fight, everyone will understand how great a fighter
I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he must convince De La Hoya.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
