<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-KNOBLAUCH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTIFIED AS EVER, KNOBLAUCH GOES BACK TO WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (ADDS grafs 6-9 with game result)  
(See also BBO-KNOBLAUCH-PSYCHOLOGY) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chuck Knoblauch explained that the first thing he did
after leaving Yankee Stadium on Thursday night was to call his
mother, he intimated that he had received some undisclosed
treatment for his chronic throwing difficulties after the 1999
season and he claimed that he is not thinking about retiring from
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The second baseman who does not always throw straight was back
at the Stadium Friday night, and back in the lineup and back trying
to cope with the unexplainable.
</P>
<P>
   A little anxious and a little tentative, Knoblauch talked about
feeling as if he has little control over the simple act of throwing
a ball from second base to first base. It is something that
Knoblauch had done successfully since he was a boy, but he has been
plagued by his wobbly throws for about two years, and that problem
exploded when he made three errors in a 12-3 loss to the White Sox,
and ended up departing before the game was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wondering if I was in Central Park,'' said Knoblauch,
``not Yankee Stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   But Knoblauch knew he was definitely in Yankee Stadium Friday
night as the fans gave him a standing ovation before he batted in
the first inning and gave him a partial standing ovation when he
corralled a pop fly in the second. There were banners supporting
Knoblauch through his ordeal, including one that said, ``We love
you Knobby and our teams needs you.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, there were no grounders hit to Knob-H lauch in the
eight innings that he played in a 3-1 loss to the White Sox, so he
did not need to make any throws.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, Clay Bellinger replaced Knoblauch, who injured his
left ankle on a slide, and handled one grounder flawlessly, causing
some apparently inattentive fans to howl because they thought it
was Knoblauch.
</P>
<P>
   It was one game, one step, but Knoblauch still felt something
was missing. He said he still felt as uncomfort- able as he had
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is different,'' said Knoblauch, who had two of the six
Yankee hits in the game, but was disappointed that he did not have
a chance to make a throw. ``Nothing has changed. It's not gone
away.''
</P>
<P>
   As manager Joe Torre discussed how Knoblauch was being embraced
as a sympathetic figure after Thursday's fiasco, he said, ``I think
he only proved that he was human.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch ended some of the suspense about his future by showing
up for work with teammate Jason Grimsley at 2:30 p.m. About 50 fans
cheered Knoblauch when he sauntered from the parking lot to the
Stadium and they also scolded a television camera operator who was
filming the second baseman. Knoblauch kept his eyes focused ahead
of him, mostly oblivious to the attention.
</P>
<P>
   After a security guard escorted Knoblauch to the Yankees'
clubhouse, the Yankees kept the doors closed to reporters for an
extra 20 minutes so Knoblauch could meet with Torre. Torre asked
Knoblauch what he wanted to do and also told him, ``You're my
second baseman.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Knoblauch had spoken to Torre, he basically invited
reporters over to his locker. Knoblauch said he had received so
many calls from teammates that he called it a ``suicide watch,''
but he stressed that despite trashing some items in the clubhouse
Thursday night, he would not have ``done anything crazy'' because
of his current funk.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as last October, Alan Hendricks, Knoblauch's agent,
had said that he did not want to talk about Knoblauch's throwing
problems and he did not want his client to discuss them either. But
Knoblauch acknowledged that he will now seek some treatment,
although he refused to specify what kind. He has previously
mentioned a sports psychologist or a hypnotist as options.
</P>
<P>
   Before saying Friday night that he would seek treatment,
Knoblauch first said, ``You got to remember you guys don't know
exactly what I did last winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's speculation that I didn't do anything,'' he
added, before inferring that he had. ``Obviously, through the
Yankees, something's going to take place. Whatever road that might
be, we're still deciding.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Torre and General Manager Brian Cashman said that whatever
Knoblauch does or does not do will be a personal decision and will
not be divulged by the Yankees. When Cashman was asked if it
behooved the Yankees to ask Knoblauch, who will make $6 million
this year, to seek treatment, he said, ``I think it's a good idea
that we support him as best as we can. To define that, I won't do.
We're in it together. We'll work it out together.''
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old Knoblauch won a Gold Glove with Minnesota in
1997, when he made just 12 errors. Last year, he made 26, 14 of
them throwing. This season, he has eight throwing errors, and 12
overall, more than any other second baseman in baseball. His .938
fielding percentage is the worst at his position.
</P>
<P>
   In speaking of his dilemma Friday, Knoblauch was
self-deprecating at times and private in other moments. He would
not say why he tapped Torre on the knee and asked to speak with him
after the sixth inning on Thursday, even though the answer was
obvious. Torre said that Knoblauch, his eyes filled with
frustration, told him, ``I don't know what to do. I'm tired of
hurting the team.'' That is when Torre and Knoblauch agreed that he
should leave the game, return to his apartment in Manhattan and
thus avoid having to talk to reporters after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're stuck for anything to say,'' Torre said Friday. ``You
just want to hug him.''
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, Knoblauch said that the wild throw that he made in
Chicago on May 24 was actually worse than Thursday's three errant
pegs to first base. In a similar moment of frustration three weeks
ago, Knoblauch spoke about retirement three weeks ago, but he said
he did not think about it in this instance and gave ``very little''
consideration to not showing up Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the desire,'' said Knoblauch. ``This is what you
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Knoblauch said he was not sure if playing was the best
thing for him. Knoblauch, who singled in his first at-bat Friday
night, declined to take any infield practice while joking that he
knows how to catch grounders. Knoblauch sifted through words like
scared and apprehensive to vainly try to express how he felt. He
said his life is ``great,'' refusing to blame his father's
Alzheimer's disease or a complicated divorce after the 1998 season
for his throwing woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't fix something like this,'' said Torre. ``This is
something you have to endure more than you fix.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch, who had deep bags under his eyes and who had not
shaved in a few days, was standing beside Roger Clemens' locker
after doing two rounds of interviews. He was relaxed and loose as
he talked about how many people called him and how his mother,
Linda, wished she could fly from Texas to New York and hug him.
</P>
<P>
   Then Knoblauch glanced into Clemens' locker and pointed to a
miniature stone football on the shelf. Knoblauch told a reporter
that Clemens had given him one of the footballs with a saying from
Vince Lombardi inscribed across it. Lombardi's words were
meaningful to Knoblauch, who nodded in agreement while he read
them, ``The harder you work, the harder it is to surrender.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
