<SLUG> BC-NY-RATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATS MAKE NEWS AS FOOD, SYMBOLS AND VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)   By EUN LEE KOH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rats were very much on the agenda, as well as the
menu, this week.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night's episode of ``Survivor,'' the CBS game show,
contestants on the island of Pulau Tiga skinned, roasted and ate
rats to stay in the running to win $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, the very next day, New York's labor unions
paraded their favorite props _ giant inflatable rats, representing
nonunion workers _ through Union Square.
</P>
<P>
   And Friday, the most striking convergence of all occurred: At
the exact moment that animal rights advocates were in front of a
CBS office protesting the culinary choices on ``Survivor,'' public
officials were discussing the growing rat menace on another island,
Manhattan, and in the city's other boroughs, where by some accounts
they outnumber people 8-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bite children,'' Councilman Bill Perkins said at a City
Council hearing on rat eradication. ``They are dangerous. They
carry diseases. They contaminate food. They are unsightly. We live
in a culture where rats aren't friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor are they usually for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   And they certainly should not be eaten for television
entertainment, said members of People for the Ethical Treatment of
Animals, protesting outside a CBS office on 57th Street Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because they are not cute and snuggly, it doesn't mean
they don't feel pain,'' said RaeLeann Smith, 27, a spokeswoman for
the group who traveled from Norfolk, Va., to attend the
demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and seven other demonstrators _ including one in a furry
rat costume _stood outside the office for two hours Friday morning,
pumping their fists and chanting: ``Don't kill animals. Rats have
rights. Survive on veggies. Rats have rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Ender, a CBS spokesman, said the network respected the
protesters' views, but added, ``We truly believe our viewers
recognize that hunting and fishing for the purpose of sustenance
has been acceptable since the dawn of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ender said the contestants on the show were instructed not to
harm monkeys, lizards or other creatures indigenous to Pulau Tiga,
a deserted Pacific island.
</P>
<P>
   But rats are not indigenous, he said, having arrived on the
island aboard ships.
</P>
<P>
   At the City Council hearing, where officials talked quite a bit
about getting rid of rats, the subject of eating did not come up.
</P>
<P>
   And Perkins declined to step into the ``Survivor'' controversy.
``They can do whatever they want with rats on that island,'' he
said after the hearing. ``But for us, in a civilized society, we
don't need rats.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
