u a BC-NJ-CASINOS-NYT &LR;      06-17 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-CASINOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSAL WOULD END BAN ON ODDS ADVERTISING BY N.J. CASINOS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gamblers would be able to weigh their odds of winning at
different casinos in New Jersey under a proposal by state
regulators to lift a ban on odds advertising. The ban was written
into the New Jersey Casino Control Act, which legalized casino
gambling in the state in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The change is one of several amendments to the gambling law now
being drafted by the Division of Gaming Enforcement and the Casino
Control Commission, the two state agencies that regulate New
Jersey's 12 casinos in Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   The enforcement division had already notified the casinos, in an
April 19 letter, that it would no longer enforce the ban, following
a June 1999 decision by the U.S. Supreme Court. The court
overturned a similar, federal ban involving Indian casinos after a
lawsuit was filed in 1994 by the New Orleans Broadcasting
Association.
</P>
<P>
   As it was written, New Jersey's gambling law banned casinos from
advertising odds-related elements, like the frequency of
slot-machine jackpots and the house's winning percentage at
blackjack tables.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators also propose lifting bans on advertising the size of
a casino and the types of table games and electronic gambling
available. J.P. Suarez, director of the gaming enforcement
division, said the amendments would be submitted to the New Jersey
Legislature this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Suarez, who is an assistant state attorney general, said that
the amendments would merely bring state law in line with the
Supreme Court's ruling, and that he fully expected them to be
approved and signed by Gov. Christie Whitman. ``Commercial speech
such as advertisement of odds is good for the consumer,'' Suarez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the odds advertising ban had been intended to
prevent what were considered deceitful advertising practices by Las
Vegas casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Laura M. Letson, executive director of the New York Council on
Problem Gambling, agreed that odds advertising might be a useful
tool for casino visitors, but she cautioned that it might also
aggravate compulsive-gambling problems. She said the state must be
willing to ensure truth in advertising, and Suarez vowed that his
agency would do just that.
</P>
<P>
   But within the gambling industry, there is concern that odds
advertising could lead to an ``odds war'' among casinos that are
now able _ even obligated, by demands of the marketplace _ to
advertise their odds. While beneficial to consumers, it could hurt
New Jersey's gambling industry, which employs tens of thousands of
people and provides hundreds of millions of dollars in annual tax
revenues to the state each year.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Feldman, a spokesman for MGM Grand, which is developing an
Atlantic City casino with Boyd Gaming of Las Vegas, said, ``I think
our industry needs to use a lot of discretion in the way it
promotes itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
