<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASUAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AREA BUSINESSES ENJOYING MORE CASUAL ROUTINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK DAVIS  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Todd Isom's hangers
dress better than he does.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Isom wears a golf shirt and jeans to work most days. Pressed
cuffs and collars stay home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had almost all white shirts,'' he said. ``Now, they just sit
in the closet, waiting for a wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   Isom didn't change jobs. He still mines data from computers at
American Century Investments. But he does it at a company site with
a relaxed dress code.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City mutual fund company has gone business casual.
Not everyone gets to wear jeans. But almost no one routinely has to
meet a business-professional standard anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last summer we had sort of a trial run,'' said Jerry Bartlett,
whose title is chief people officer.
</P>
<P>
   The company had allowed business-casual dress on Fridays for
some time. Last year it made every day a dress-down day between
Memorial Day and Labor Day. At most sites the suits and ties came
back into vogue with autumn.
</P>
<P>
   This past May the relaxed dress code became policy year-round.
</P>
<P>
   The same happened last month for the 200 lawyers at the Kansas
City offices of Blackwell, Sanders, Peper, Martin. The staff
already had gone casual, but policy expanded casual Friday for
lawyers to cover the entire week, for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``You come to our firm these days, you see a mixture of business
professional and business casual,'' said Jim Borthwick, a partner
on the executive committee at Blackwell Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Suits still circulate, because they are needed in courtrooms and
for some client meetings, Borthwick said. And some lawyers still
wear the coat and tie just because they want to.
</P>
<P>
   Business casual also became permanent last month for area
employees of Aventis Pharmaceutical, which is what remains of the
old Marion Laboratories Inc. in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Spokeswoman Traci Seaman said the policy changed in mid-May.
Normally, casual would not kick in until after Memorial Day and
would expire with summer's end.
</P>
<P>
   But Aventis is shifting its headquarters to New Jersey. That
affects people in sales, marketing and administrative posts. By the
end of summer, most of them will be gone, having transferred or
left the company's employ altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The relaxed code, however, will stick around for the several
hundred Aventis workers who will remain. Many already have a
relaxed dress code because of their jobs in production, Seaman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Business-casual dress is nothing new. It spread so widely and
quickly that it shook up the apparel industry for a time.
</P>
<P>
   But casual still is finding open ground for new roots in Kansas
City. American Century, Blackwell Sanders and Aventis are just the
latest to give in.
</P>
<P>
   Butler Manufacturing Co. went business casual year-round last
year, said Phil Jones, corporate human relations manager. It, too,
had started with dress-down Fridays, then a few relaxed-standard
summers until turning business casual for good.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Hersh, with Robert Half and Accountemps of Kansas City
Inc., said many of the clients who hired permanent or temporary
employees through the firm had been business casual throughout the
year for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, most workplaces are business casual most of the
time, said Ann Marie Sabath, the Cincinnati author of Beyond
Business Casual: What to Wear to Work If You Want to Get Ahead.
</P>
<P>
   But Sabath said the trend was merely that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business casual will go away,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, she said, younger workers would drive it away. Sabath
said she heard from employees in their 20s and 30s that casual
dress had gone too far. They want a professional image at work, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Thursday, 35-year-old Dana Spoor wore a
double-breasted suit to work in American Century Tower I, where
business casual became the norm five weeks ago. Although she took
part in casual Fridays, she has taken advantage of the new weeklong
policy only once.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice option if you wake up on a Wednesday and say, `I
don't want to put on hose,' '' said Spoor, an intranet project
manager. ``I just feel more professional when I dress nice.''
</P>
<P>
   American Century still requires business-professional attire in
some circumstances. For example, an employee who travels to a
client or company that is not business casual should dress to that
firm's standard.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the e-mail that announced the full-time relaxed
standard reminded employees that business casual did not mean there
was no standard.
</P>
<P>
   Jeans qualify only in a few buildings where customers and
clients do not visit. Isom works on Broadway with about 275 others
who can wear jeans. Jeans are OK for the 850 employees in American
Century's Ward Parkway offices, for 400 in Denver and sometimes for
the 200 in Mountain View, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   No jeans are allowed in the American Century Towers, where about
1,000 work, or the Plaza Steppes Building, where 350 work.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, business casual still bans ``spandex, Lycra and other
body-clinging fabrics, jeans of all colors, anything tight,
tattered or ripped, leggings, shorts and skorts, sweatshirts,
sweatpants and jogging suits, flip-flop sandals or tennis shoes,
hats, caps and sunglasses,'' the e-mail said.
</P>
<P>
   Even under the relaxed standard, American Century employees need
to show up in ``neat, ironed clothes,'' and they have to wear
hosiery or socks. Permanent press counts.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, khakis, polo shirts, ``flat shoes or loafers'' and
even denim shirts and dresses pass muster.
</P>
<P>
   Not so at Blackwell Sanders, despite the business-casual dictum.
Borthwick said there was not a written description of business
casual, but a lawyer wearing Dockers slacks likely would attract
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody probably would be saying, `You know, that's not
really what we were talking about,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in the business world nothing happens without a
motive. Bartlett, American Century's chief people officer, said the
new, relaxed apparel ought to make employees more productive.
</P>
<P>
   He said the total work environment affected how productive
workers could be. That is especially true when folks put in nine,
10 or 11 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's not a fulfilling experience, pretty soon you have a
lot of people who don't want to be here anymore,'' Bartlett said. (
30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
