r f BC-GAS-KAN &LR;      06-17 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIKING GAS PRICES PROMPT KANSAS CITIANS TO RE-EVALUATE THEIR
SPENDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ ``Holy moly!''
thought Phil Wall as he watched the dollars and cents on the gas
pump tick higher and higher.
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the time the nozzle clicked off, Wall had spent almost twice
as much money as he did a year ago to fill the tank of his 1994
Toyota 4Runner.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City has historically enjoyed low gasoline prices, but in
the current price surge Midwesterners are paying well above the
ever-rising national average.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in the fact that area motorists drive almost one-third
more miles than the average American urban driver, and high gas
prices are hitting harder here than almost anywhere in the country.
If current prices keep up, an average two-car family could see an
extra $1,300 a year go toward filling up their gas tanks.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many people are shifting their spending priorities,
or at least thinking about it. And businesses that depend on
gasoline are feeling the reverberations as well.
</P>
<P>
   As for Wall, he's changed his vacation plans. Originally, he and
his girlfriend, Cynthia Harris, and her dog, Cody, were going to
drive to the Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they're cutting the number of miles they're willing to
drive by half and will end up somewhere in western Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Wall has switched from premium grade gas to mid-grade,
and sometimes regular. And when Wall gets back from vacation, he's
going to start looking for a used, four-cylinder Toyota Camry for
trips around town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure I'd have to budget at least a couple of hundred
dollars more if I wanted to go ahead and go to the Grand Canyon,
but why should I?'' Wall said. ``I have better things to spend my
money on.''
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reason _ tight supplies, a pipeline problem and new
cleaner-burning gas are among those suggested _ Kansas City area
residents no longer enjoy below-average gas prices. AAA of Missouri
surveyed prices at area pumps Friday morning and found consumers
paying $1.73 on average for regular unleaded. But by Friday
afternoon, some stations had boosted regular unleaded to $1.80.
Meanwhile, the national average was $1.63.
</P>
<P>
   The American Petroleum Institute, a lobbying organization for
the gasoline industry, says that in today's dollars, Americans were
paying $2.55 a gallon for gas in 1981. But the distant past is no
comfort, especially when pump prices were below $1 just last year.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the most sprawling cities in the United States, the
Kansas City area has the lowest population density among metro
areas of more than 1 million people. Additionally, the area has the
highest number of freeway lanes per capita at 120 miles for every
100,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is Kansas Citians do a lot of driving, and it's
getting more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the math for an average two-car household in the
metropolitan area. If each vehicle is driven 18,480 miles _ 32
percent above the national average _ and gets the national average
21.4 mpg, the household was spending $1,727 a year for gas when it
cost $1 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   At $1.80 a gallon, that household is paying $3,109, a difference
of $1,382.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a vacation, that's a washer and dryer,'' said Mike
Right of AAA of Missouri. ``What this means is that household
expenditures are shifting from disposable _ eating out, travel, new
furniture _ to essentials.''
</P>
<P>
   If people have less disposable income because they're spending
more on gasoline, Right said, it's logical to surmise that those
types of businesses that have enjoyed and prospered from America's
long-lived economic expansion will get hit first and hardest.
</P>
<P>
   It's too early to see evidence of that, Right said. But he
thinks if prices stay where they are, or move higher, effects soon
will be apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Kite Singleton, a Kansas City area architect, noted that it took
the oil crisis of the 1970s to get the automobile industry to start
making more fuel-efficient vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``But during the 1990s that whole tendency changed considerably
because fuel costs were so much lower relative to people's
incomes,'' Singleton said.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel efficiency peaked in 1997 at 21.7 mpg but dropped to 21.4
in 1998, the last year for which figures are available.
</P>
<P>
   Because nearly half of the vehicles sold in the United States in
the past few years have been sport utility vehicles, some of which
get 12 mpg in the city, fuel efficiency has probably declined.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Right said, if prices stay at these levels or higher, he
thinks people will again turn more of their attention to fuel
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to move much higher on the radar screen
when people are buying a new car, whereas two years ago it wasn't
even a factor,'' Right said.
</P>
<P>
   But John Michaels, new vehicles sales manager at Jay Wolfe
Chevrolet in Kansas City, Kan., said pump-price shock so far
doesn't seem to be slowing sales of SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   Most people buying SUVs, Michaels said, are 35 years of age to
55. They're used to seeing swings in prices, whether it's at the
gas pump or the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tug on the gas tank doesn't seem to be hurting us,''
Michaels said.
</P>
<P>
   But others are already making adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Wall Street analyst David Tannehill said he had
turned cautious on his outlook for the recreational vehicle
industry because of the rise in interest rates and gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   And calls to Rideshare, a program that helps area residents
coordinate car-pooling and other commuting options, are up 20
percent over a couple of months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Area Transportation Authority official Dick Davis
thinks higher gas prices will spur bus ridership.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take (people) a couple of times to look at gas prices
for them to re-evaluate their transportation options,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Cab drivers also are feeling the squeeze, although on Thursday
the Kansas City Council approved a 50-cent per trip surcharge for
whenever the average cost of unleaded regular in the area exceeds
$1.40.
</P>
<P>
   Others are taking action as well, including Bill Nigro of
Torre's Pizzerias, who said his delivery drivers were getting a
raise of 25 cents an hour to help offset their increased costs for
gas.
</P>
<P>
   Right isn't surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any business that uses a car, a truck, a snowblower, a weed
chopper, a forklift, a lawn mower, is going to feel the effects of
this,'' he said. ``Those costs are going to have be absorbed
somewhere _ either by the business or the customer.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who will be hurt the most, Right said, are those on the
lowest rungs of the economic ladder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of full employment those on the bottom rungs have been
able to find jobs, and to have jobs they have to have a way to get
there and get back,'' Right said. ``When they have to start paying
these kinds of prices, it can knock them right out of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Right doesn't hold much optimism for the future, at least for
the near term.
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil prices are staying above $32 a barrel; wholesale
gasoline prices are at about $1.10 a gallon; there's been a
drawdown in stocks; output hasn't picked up much; and OPEC is
sending signals that its members are going to stick together and
not increase production.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may just be posturing on their part,'' Right said. ``But
if not, we're going to be in for even more dire straits.'' ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 0023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
