r a BC-DINOSAUR-KAN &LR;      06-17 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINOSAUR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KU PALEONTOLOGISTS UNEARTH T. REX FOSSIL ON WYOMING RANCH  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MHARI DOYLE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ ``Dinosaur bones
stick to your tongue.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   That's the advice Craig Sundell, a University of Kansas
paleontology graduate student, gave a few Wyoming rancher friends
who wanted to help scout for dinosaur fossils.
</P>
<P>
   If you wanted to know whether something was rock or bone, touch
it with your tongue, Sundell said. Because a bone is porous, your
tongue _ for a brief second _ will stick to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Sundell's advice seems to have paid off. On a tip from the
ranchers, Sundell and a small digging team from KU two weeks ago
uncovered fossil bones from what is believed to be a
65-million-year-old Tyrannosaurus rex.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The ranchers) were moving their cattle,'' Sundell said at a
news conference Friday at Olathe (Kan.) North High School, where he
graduated in 1971. ``They were looking for some strays and found a
piece of dinosaur bone.''
</P>
<P>
   Sundell's team, which already was in Wyoming hunting for
Triceratops bones, first scouted the area and found scattered on
the ground hundreds of bone shards belonging to a meat-eating
dinosaur.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found a tooth socket,'' said team member Matt Christopher,
who graduated from KU in 1999. He was too excited to say then that
it could be a T. rex fossil. ``We brought it to Craig, and all we
could say was, `This isn't a Triceratops.' &UR; ''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher said when Sundell identified it as a T. rex tooth
socket _ because of the composition of the bone and the double
serration of the tooth _ ``we were blown away.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon a major excavation was under way. About two weeks ago,
Sundell's wife, Jackie, brushed away soft shale sediment to reveal
the upper jaw and a tooth from the beast, which the team named
``Monte'' after the owner of private land in east-central Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Major skull parts already have been recovered, including an
upper jaw with teeth in place. We've also found a majority of the
ribs,'' Sundell said. ``These indicate that much of the skeleton is
present and is yet to be unearthed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sundell's team also has found some gastralia, which are bones
formed in the skin that encase the lower abdomen and act as ``belly
ribs.'' Sundell said he'd uncovered about 15 percent of what he
hoped would be a complete skeleton of what was a 45-foot-long,
10-ton carnivore.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Brochu, a research scientist at the Field Museum of
Natural History in Chicago, knows Sundell and has heard of his
recent T. rex excavation. Brochu said Sundell's findings could
prove to be important. Brochu said about 20 nearly complete T. rex
fossils were on display, including the Field Museum's ``Sue,'' the
largest and most complete T. rex fossil to date.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding a T. rex isn't as rare as we thought, but it's still
an exciting find,'' Brochu said, adding that finding a complete
skeleton was difficult. ``All dinosaur fossils are potentially
important. I'm looking forward to hearing more about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The slow uncovering of Monte follows closely on the heels of the
May 17 unveiling of Sue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sue is 90 percent complete,'' Brochu said. ``Finding a more
complete skeleton is not as common.''
</P>
<P>
   Sundell hopes Monte will prove to be at least as complete as
Sue, but he acknowledges that he and his team have a long way to
go. Most paleontologists don't announce a find until all the bones
had been excavated, Sundell said. But he wanted to go public to
share Monte's uncovering on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to go from dirt to digital,'' Sundell said, calling
the project ``rexcavation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to bring daily updates, and let people see what's
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Through a Web site, which hasn't been established yet, Sundell
also hopes to attract a home for Monte once it's completely
unearthed.
</P>
<P>
   Sundell said he held the press conference Friday at Olathe North
because he didn't want to pressure KU or other institutions to make
on offer for the fossils.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, museums buy dinosaur skeletons for between $2 million
and $4 million, Sundell said. He added that because Monte was found
on private land, the land owners would receive the money.
</P>
<P>
   Monte's fetching price depends on how much of the skeleton
Sundell's team can uncover.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still finding new bones every day,'' Sundell said.
``That's a good sign....The story will continue in the shales,
clays and sands of Wyoming.'' ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
