r a BC-SERIAL-KAN &LR;      06-17 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECKS, MAILBOX LINK JOHN E. ROBINSON SR. TO MISSING MOTHER,
DAUGHTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD ESPINOZA and MARK MORRIS  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ John Edward Robinson
Sr. picked up what appeared to be monthly government checks for two
missing women at a commercial mail center in Olathe, Kan., the
center's owner said Friday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sheila Dale Faith, who would be 51 now, and her daughter, Debbie
Lynn Faith, who would be 21, have been missing since 1994, when a
neighbor said they left their Pueblo, Colo., home with a man named
John. Robinson collected their checks regularly until police
arrested him this month, said Mailroom owner Randy Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Faith box has a lot of checks,'' Davis said. ``They each
got one every month.''
</P>
<P>
   When Davis saw news that police had arrested Robinson _ whom he
knew as Jim Turner, an alias police said Robinson used _ he told
investigators about the mailbox where the June checks would be
arriving.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, 56, of Olathe is not charged in the Faiths'
disappearance. On Tuesday, he was charged in the beating deaths of
five women whose bodies were found in barrels on his property in
Linn County, Kan., and in a storage locker in Raymore.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Faiths, police are looking for three other women and
a 4-month-old baby who disappeared as early as 1984 and had
connections with Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   One of the bodies in the Raymore locker was Beverly J. Bonner,
who received mail in another box at Mailroom. According to her
ex-husband in Cameron, Mo., her mail included monthly checks he
sent to that box as part of a property settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson picked up her mail after she disappeared in 1996, Davis
said. That box was closed for non-payment about a year later, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments:
</P>
<P>
   - Agents from the Social Security Administration have joined the
criminal investigation into Robinson, an agency spokesman confirmed
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   John Garlinger, regional communications director for Social
Security, said the administration's Office of Inspector General
recently entered the probe.
</P>
<P>
   Garlinger said federal agents were participating ``essentially
to provide expertise in matters that relate to Social Security as
(state investigators) ask.''
</P>
<P>
   The Office of Inspector General is Social Security's
investigative arm and looks into allegations of fraud and abuse in
the program.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security's participation in the Robinson probe began
about the time investigators were considering asking the public for
help in locating the Faiths.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the Faiths were receiving a monthly income of $1,016 in
Social Security benefits, The Orange County (Calif.) Register
reported then in a feature article about needy people.
</P>
<P>
   Garlinger said that federal privacy laws do not allow him to say
whether Faith or her daughter were receiving federal benefits when
they disappeared in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   - Colorado school records appear to narrow the period in which
the Faiths vanished to the summer of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Deb Darrow, a spokeswoman for School District 60 in Pueblo, said
Friday that after Debbie finished the 1993-94 school year, she did
not appear the following September for the 1994-95 session.
</P>
<P>
   Darrow further noted that district documents reflect no request
from any other district for Debbie's academic records from the
Pueblo district. Such requests are routine for students
transferring to new districts so they can receive credit for
courses they already have taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no record of a request for a transfer,'' Darrow said.
``She was a no-show.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado records also confirmed that Debbie transferred from a
school in Fullerton, Calif., in September 1993. Though family
friends have said Debbie suffered from cerebral palsy, school
records show her condition as spina bifida. Friends have said she
used a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   Darrow said Debbie, who school records indicate was born in
Dallas, attended regular classes at East High School in Pueblo and
participated in sessions with physical therapists.
</P>
<P>
   - The task force investigating Robinson will be cut in half
Monday, to about 15 investigators, and officials plan to meet
toward the end of the week to discuss how the investigation should
continue, Lenexa Sgt. Rick Roth said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   No investigators assigned to the case will be in the office to
answer calls this weekend, but Lenexa, Kan., dispatchers will take
tips for them at (913) 477-7300. ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
