<SLUG> BC-DNC-BAILOUT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY COUNCIL RECEIVES $4 MIL REQUEST FROM DNC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; A formal request for $4 million in city funds was
made to the Los Angeles City Council on Friday to help bail out the
committee paying for the Democratic National Convention in August.
</P>
<P>
   Council President John Ferraro introduced the proposal,
scheduled for consideration next Tuesday, saying it is important
for the city to present a good image.
</P>
<P>
   ``They set very high goals and I think they did well,'' Ferraro
said. ``But now is the time for the city to step forward. We don't
want to have an event that is embarrassment to the city with the
whole world watching.''
</P>
<P>
   But Councilman Joel Wachs disagreed, saying he didn't believe
the city needed to provide any money for the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The convention will go on whether we give this money or not,''
Wachs said. ``I can't believe the disconnect there is here in City
Hall with the rest of the city. We can't pay for sidewalks and now
they want us to pay for a bunch of parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Wachs said his Public Works Committee has held hearings around
the city and it continues to receive the same complaints over the
need to repair streets and sidewalks, trim trees and provide other
governmental services.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do we tell them we can't do the basics, but can find $4
million for this convention?'' Wachs said.
</P>
<P>
   A letter from the Host Committee, dated Friday, urged the city
to advance the money, saying the committee expects the convention
to generate $135 million for the city, and pointed to the financial
contributions from other cities that host conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago gave $7 million to the Democrats in 1996 and
Philadelphia and the state of Pennsylvania are contributing $7
million each to Republicans this year. New Jersey, which also will
benefit, is giving $3 million to the GOP, the committee said.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles already has agreed to provide up to $7 million in
in-kind services - such as security and traffic control.
</P>
<P>
   However, the letter signed by committee co-chairman Eli Broad
and chief executive Noelia Rodriguez said the committee still has a
$10 million gap for its obligations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This includes not only its remaining cash obligation to the
DNCC (Democratic National Convention Committee), but also the Los
Angeles Community Celebration, the Media Festival, Volunteer
Appreciation Festival and other special projects,'' the letter
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the final preparations are made for this world-class event,
it is important for all parties to work together to maximize this
moment in Los Angeles' history.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidential nominating convention, to be held Aug. 14-17 at
Staples Center, is expected to draw attendance of 35,000, including
delegates, media representatives and others. Protesters also plan
to descend upon the city.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Sheriff Lee Baca wrote to the Los Angeles County
Board of Supervisors, telling them he has been asked by the Los
Angeles Police Department to help with security by having deputies
on the buses of delegates as they travel from their hotels to
various convention events.
</P>
<P>
   Baca took note of the riots that marked the World Trade
Organization meetings last November in Seattle and pointed out that
the convention offers a similar opportunity for disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Supervisors is scheduled to consider the proposal
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Most City Council members said Friday that they want to hear the
debate next week before deciding whether to support the spending
request.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Alex Padilla seconded the Ferraro motion and
Councilman Nate Holden said he thought it was appropriate for the
city to provide funding.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Cindy Miscikowski said she believed more
information was needed before she would support it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told us they would be able to raise enough money,''
Miscikowski said. ``I'd like to know what they have done and what
they plan to do. I have a number of questions.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
