<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TAX-CUT DISPUTE DELAYS PASSAGE OF STATE BUDGET  &HT;     By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Attempts to pass the state budget stalled early
Friday morning because Assembly Republicans don't want $850 million
in new tax cuts to wipe out an old tax cut to reduce vehicle
license fees.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cut debate torpedoed Democratic efforts to send a $95
billion spending plan to Gov. Gray Davis before the midnight
deadline Thursday for legislative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think the taxpayers should be paying for their own
tax cut, which in essence is what would have happened if we didn't
object,'' said George Runner of Lancaster, the Assembly's chief
budget negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike their Senate counterparts, who helped pass a budget
Thursday morning on a bipartisan 31-to-9 vote, Assembly Republicans
voted as a bloc to stop Democrats from reaching the two-thirds
majority needed to approve a spending plan for the fiscal year that
begins July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Their stated reason for doing so lies in the mechanics of a cut
in the vehicle license fee approved by Davis' GOP predecessor and
the Democratic majority Legislature in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats agreed to a 75 percent cut in the license fees that
California's 23 million vehicle owners pay every year, phased in
over five years.
</P>
<P>
   The cut began with an initial 25 percent decrease that would
grow over time, if the state had enough revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Davis accelerated the effective date of another 10
percent reduction.
</P>
<P>
   What caused Assembly Republicans to object this week is a caveat
in the license fee cut that says new tax cuts might cancel out the
license fees.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say legislative Democrats reneged on a pledge that
such a thing would not happen this year.
</P>
<P>
   GOP lawmakers this year said that $850 million of the new
budget's $2.7 billion in tax cuts not only would cancel out another
10 percent decrease in license fees scheduled for 2002 but would
slash the existing 35 percent cut to 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a Democrat, told reporters Thursday, ``If I had my
druthers, no tax relief we provide would impact on any tax relief
provided before.''
</P>
<P>
   Runner said by early Friday morning _ the Assembly quit at 2
a.m. _ a deal was struck with Assembly Speaker Robert Hertzberg,
D-Sherman Oaks, that would make the new tax cuts not count against
the next scheduled license fee cut.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of CALBUDGE (15234 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  But, Runner said, Senate President Pro Tem John Burton, D-San
Francisco, could not be found to make sure he agreed to such a
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I run both houses?'' Burton said in an interview, adding
that he opposes whatever deal the Assembly is working out on the
license fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``My position is: We passed a budget, 31 to 9,'' he said. ``They
don't want to pass a budget _ that's their problem. You can't have
tax cuts on tax cuts on tax cuts because eventually you end up with
no money to spend on other programs like education.''
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Democrats have a different version of the deal than
Runner. They said they offered to correct the license fee problem
in return for Assembly Republicans voting for the budget, a
commitment Republicans refused to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're wondering what the real problem is,'' said Paul Hefner,
Hertzberg's press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Runner also said Assembly Republicans are not enamored of a $224
million tax cut proposed by Davis that would reduce each of the
state's tax brackets by 0.55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two-thirds of the tax savings would be reaped by
Californians earning $100,000 or more a year. And even that relief
would not be much, Runner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you earn $60,000 you would get something like $7 in
savings,'' said Runner. ``If you earn $250,000 you get maybe $250.
Neither of those groups really needs that kind of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Runner said his caucus was ``evaluating'' the income tax cut _
and he recommended Democrats do the same in light of the cut's main
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly will take up the budget again on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
