<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6870 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GLF-OPENSIDE-NICKLAUS     06-17 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPENSIDE-NICKLAUS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE LAST BEAR HUG FOR NICKLAUS, FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ As the mists drifted in over the 18th
hole late Friday afternoon at Pebble Beach Golf Links, Jack
Nicklaus faded out, finishing at 11-over-par 82 to miss the cut in
his 44th and probably final U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Bear didn't go without one final roar - knocking a
3-wood 245 yards to reach the green in two shots and set up an
eagle putt on that 543-yard, par-5 hole.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't to be. Nicklaus couldn't even get birdie, settling
for a tap-in par for his highest total in 160 Open rounds. He
stared at the ball on the lip of the cup and then shrugged at the
heavens, as if in agreement that perhaps it was time for his
lengthy Open odyssey to end.
</P>
<P>
   What a journey it was. No one has played in more U.S. Opens than
Nicklaus, who has won four of them - including the first held at
Pebble Beach, in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   His dramatic 1-iron tee shot to within two inches of the
flagstick on No. 17 cemented that win, but there was comparable
drama in his other Open victories. He set tournament records at
Baltusrol twice - 275 in 1967 and 272 in 1980 - and upset Arnold
Palmer on the King's home turf at Oakmont for his first Open title
at age 22 in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   He exits with an Open legacy that could be measured by the size
of the roar that went up on No. 18 Friday, when a 60-year-old man
set up an eagle putt worth no more than an 80. Nicklaus appreciated
the show of support that left him misty-eyed. He claimed later with
a wink it was the wind but 'fessed up in a final press conference
that produced a rare round of applause from the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure I get emotional,'' Nicklaus said ``Absolutely. It's
difficult ... knowing it will probably be the last time you're
going to come up a U.S. Open fairway.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's fairly certain this was his last:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say the chances would be very slim if I would ever play
(the Open) again,'' said Nicklaus, who will miss the experience not
for the memories but for the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. Open to me is a complete examination of a golfer,''
he said. ``The competition, what it does for you, how hard it is to
work at it, how hard it is to make it happen. When the conditions
aren't your conditions, you have to persevere and work at it - I
enjoy that. I enjoy the punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   He wished only that he could have worked at it two more days
this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still dumb enough, I guess, whatever you might want to
say, to think that .... I was thinking that I could play well
enough to compete in this tournament. Maybe I still feel that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   As late as the eighth hole Friday, Nicklaus felt in contention
to make the cut. Then, ``I hit three shots as good as I could hit
them and walked away with a double bogey.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a matter of sniffing the flowers from the rest of a round
in which Nicklaus said he hit the ball well but ``couldn't get it
on the green, couldn't make a par.'' In the end, he had to settle
for the memories of past Opens and Pebble Beach, where Nicklaus
also won his second U.S. Amateur in 1961 and won Crosby National
Pro-Ams in 1967, 1972 and 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing Pebble Beach,'' he said, ``even shooting 82
</P>
<P>
   what difference does it make what I shot? The place sort of
started in many ways my golf game .... almost 40 years later, it's
a pretty fitting place to stop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
