<HEADER>
A6871 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GLF-OPENSIDE-LONGDAY-     06-17 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPENSIDE-LONGDAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG DELAY DRAINS GOLFER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ It wound up more sweeter for some than
others, but Friday's second-round yawner in the 100th U.S. Open was
draining on everyone.
</P>
<P>
   The problem started with fog that rolled in Thursday afternoon
and prevented 75 players from completing first-round play at Pebble
Beach Golf Links. That set up the second-round long day's journey
into nightfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard work,'' said England's Nick Faldo, who finished
5-over par for his 23 holes Friday and almost certainly will make
the cut with his 69-74-143. But he never worked so long in any of
the 48 previous rounds he had played in U.S. Opens, completing his
second round 11 hours after he arrived at the course Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was up at 4 (a.m.) and I was out in position at 6:45. Then
they all came back in again.''
</P>
<P>
   They came back because the fog came back, pushing resumption of
first-round play back to 7:45, then 8:15, when play finally resumed
and concluded with no further weather interruptions.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:30 - three hours after its originally scheduled starting
time - second-round play got underway, making historical footnotes
out of Ken Krieger, Rick Heath and Rodney Butcher.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled for the final tee time of the second round, they
stepped to the first tee at 8 p.m - 37 hours after they launched
this championship on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The delay proved more costly to Jack Nicklaus, the 60-year-old
Hall of Famer who had to play 27 holes Friday in what was likely
his last U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   In contention to make the cut at 1-over par through nine holes
when play was halted Thursday, Nicklaus finished his first round at
2-over 73 but slumped to 82 in his belated second round and wound
up 13-over 155, missing the cut for only the ninth time in a record
44 consecutive appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how the greens got so hard overnight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Costan, a 44-year-old qualifier who has run a golf academy
for the past six years, found himself near the leaders after
finishing his interrupted round at 70, but he said it was a
difficult proposition:
</P>
<P>
   ``The delay was challenging, especially when you're playing
well,'' Costan said. ``I was kind of in a groove, so it was tough
not to finish the round.''
</P>
<P>
   He made the most of the delay, sinking a par-saving putt on 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm elated, very elated,'' he said. ``I'll remember that putt
forever.'' Perhaps because it seemed to take forever for him to get
to the 18th hole.
</P>
<P>
   Hale Irwin wound up happy with his position after shooting 68 in
his interrupted round, but slipped to 78 in the delayed second
round. Sitting at 146, he will have to sweat out today's continued
second-round play to see if the projected cut score of 149 holds
up, or if he will go home early.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tough part is getting up at four o'clock,'' Irwin said. `I
don't usually see four o'clock very often. You know I'm on the
senior tour. We have those nice, relaxed starting times.''
</P>
<P>
   Loren Roberts, who also shot 68 in his interrupted round, said
afterward he ``thought it was a nice break because the golf course
is very playable right now,'' then went out and shot 78 in his
second round to join Irwin among the worried waiting.
</P>
<P>
   They'll wait for 56 more golfers to finish today - 10 of them
having completed only five holes - in a tournament that could
extend into Sunday due to the twosome format the USGA uses for the
final two rounds of the Open.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
