<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6872 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-PARK-POLICE-1STLD-     06-17 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PARK-POLICE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5 NEW YORK POLICE OFFICERS FACE DISCIPLINE AFTER PARADE MAYHEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (Updates throughout with new arrest)  
 (With NY-PARK-CRIME)  
 By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police Commissioner Howard Safir said Friday that as
many as five officers would probably be disciplined for failing to
respond properly to people who complained about a group of men
attacking women in and around Central Park on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Safir also announced eight more arrests in the attacks, which
occurred after the National Puerto Rican Day parade, bringing to 16
the total number of young men arrested after the frenzy of sexual
assaults, including seven who turned themselves in after seeing
their pictures broadcast on television or published in newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives have also identified 14 more suspects being sought in
the attacks, in which men poured ice and water on dozens of women,
tore at their clothes and groped their breasts and buttocks.
</P>
<P>
   As detectives continued to hunt for the attackers, investigators
from the department's Internal Affairs Bureau pursued their own
inquiry, looking into complaints that some officers failed to
respond properly to people who notified them of the roving bands of
men. By late Friday, department investigators had questioned more
than 100 officers, mostly supervisors, a senior investigator said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without prejudging, my sense is that we will probably find
four or five police officers who acted inappropriately, while the
vast majority acted appropriately,'' Safir said. ``Those who acted
inappropriately will be subject to discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior investigator said that the Internal Affairs Bureau
had identified three or four officers who they said they believed
had acted improperly, and said they were close to identifying one
or two others. The official said it was possible that one or more
of the officers would face dismissal, but called that possibility
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   One of the police officers who has become a focus of the inquiry
was assigned to a traffic detail and was seen on a videotape on
which a man who is not visible is upbraiding him for failing to
take some action, a senior police official said. But the
investigation has not yet determined whether the officer had failed
to take any action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the problem is identification,'' the official said.
``We have to be clear who was where.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior investigator pointed out that if the Internal Affairs
Bureau determines that an officer behaved improperly, the
department would bring administrative charges against the officer,
who would then be tried before an administrative law judge. The
judge's recommendation would be given to the police commissioner,
who makes the final decision on departmental discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said that of the seven victims who reported their assaults
to police immediately after the incident, two complained about the
officers and five praised their behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The eight suspects arrested Friday were Julio Delacruz, 22, of
7717 Bergenline Ave. in North Bergen, N.J.; Isaiah Forbes, 18, of
119 Beach 56th St., Queens; Mark Daniels, 21, of 67 Harrison Place
in Irvington, N.J.; Anthony Bryant, 25, of 312 Delancey St. in
Manhattan; Leslie Marcano, 19, of 995 Simpson St. in the Bronx;
Soto Jensen, 16, of 99 Varet St., Brooklyn; Trevor Britton, 29, of
1401 East New York Ave., Brooklyn and David Gar- cia, 33, of 2406
Grand Avenue in the Bronx. The police said all would be charged
with first-degree sexual abuse and and first-degree riot.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I can tell you is there is no pattern here as far as
groups of people who are associated with each other,'' Safir said.
``This appears to be something that happened relatively
spontaneously.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir also urged the other men involved in the attacks to turn
themselves in.
</P>
<P>
   He also thanked the public for its cooperation, saying the
department's release of photographs of the suspects, lifted from 10
amateur videotape recordings, prompted scores of calls to the
city's Crime Stoppers phone line. One tip came from as far away as
Italy, where someone who had been in New York on Sunday sent an
e-mail to the police with what Safir said was helpful information.
</P>
<P>
   The new suspects whose photographs were released Friday had all
been identified by one or more of the 47 victims who the police
said had been molested, and in some cases, assaulted or robbed.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
