<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIMATE-WARMING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 RECORD HOT SPRING FUELS GLOBAL WARMING DEBATE  &HT;     By CARL T. HALL  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Spring 2000 has been the warmest on record in the United States,
government climate trackers reported Friday.
<P>
   Adding one more bit of fuel to the debate over global warming,
the National Climatic Data Center reported the national average
temperature from March to May was a balmy 55.5 degrees _ 3.3
degrees above the norm for the past 105 years and beating the
record of 55.1 set in 1910.
</P>
<P>
   All the 48 contiguous states experienced warmer-than-normal
temperatures for the three-month period. The pattern was
particularly notable in California and much of the West, where the
lilacs and honeysuckle have been blooming earlier and earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite amazing,'' said Kelly Redmond, deputy director and
regional climatologist at the Western Regional Climate Center in
Reno, Nev.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the La Nina phenomenon, which has been lingering
in the equatorial Pacific, produces shifts in sea surface
temperatures and wind patterns that usually translate into
cooler-than-normal temperatures for big sections of the country,
particularly north of the Bay Area on up into Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, that effect appears to have been wiped out for
reasons scientists cannot explain _ at least not to everybody's
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a La Nina year, it's been rather out of character,''
Redmond said. ``It certainly has been warm through much of the
western region.''
</P>
<P>
   Average temperatures in 23 states this spring ranked within
their top 10 warmest springs in 106 years of record-keeping. Texas
had its warmest spring on record, while New Mexico had its
second-warmest since records began in 1895.
</P>
<P>
   California and Nevada averaged 56.0 degrees, 3.4 degrees above
the norm, while the Northwest region _ including Washington, Oregon
and Idaho _ showed a 47.4 degree average for the three months,
compared with a 45.3 degree norm.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was it strictly a springtime phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   The new data _ based on preliminary readings from 344 `'climate
divisions'' nationwide _ showed a record temperature of 48.5
degrees for the five-month period from January through May. The old
record was 47.4 degrees set in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The data came from the Climatic Data Center located in
Asheville, N.C., which is part of the federal National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration. The Western regional weather center in
Reno, which is financed by NOAA, is part of the independent Desert
Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Experts on all sides of the global-warming issue cautioned
against jumping to any conclusions. In fact, global data for this
year so far showed the worldwide temperatures have been 0.07 degree
below average, apparently due to the cooler-than-normal Pacific
waters.
</P>
<P>
   Still, those concerned about potential cataclysmic climate
shifts due to human activity saw Friday's numbers as one more
telling piece of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is certainly consistent with the projections of global
warming that are being made,'' said Peter Frumhoff, director of
global resources at the Union of Concerned Scientists in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean this particular episode is direct evidence
of global warming, but it's consistent with the trend over time,''
he added. ``The fingerprint of global warming is beginning to
emerge from the noise of natural climate variability.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that some ``conservative projections'' show California
in line for a 4 to 6 degree warming shift by 2030, which could
bring more rain than snow at lower elevations in the mountains,
increase wildfire hazards and produce some profound biological
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Dire forecasts aside, the increasingly predominant view among
scientists is that warming trends are indeed showing up, and are
likely to be at least partly due to human activity, most notably
the burning of fossil fuels.
</P>
<P>
   But global warming critics remain skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas Friday, H. Sterling Burnett, senior policy analyst at
the National Center for Policy Analysis, a think tank that promotes
private-sector solutions to public policy issues, spoke of enjoying
cool 80-85 degree days around his North Texas lakeside home,
ordinarily sunbaked this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago we were in the 100s in May, and we haven't
broken 95 this year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new numbers, he added, ``are just a bit of evidence, and
there is other evidence on all sides. One particular three-month
period does not stand out as particularly telling to me.''
</P>
<P>
   (For more details on the national and regional data, go to the
National Climatic Data Center Web site at  &UR; www.ncdc.noaa.gov.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
