<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-SUGAR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ASTRONOMERS SAY THEY'VE FOUND SUGAR MOLECULE INSIDE THE MILKY WAY  &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astronomers hunting for radio signals far out in space have
discovered the first molecules of sugar inside a huge cloud of dust
and gas near the center of the Milky Way galaxy, they reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery makes it increasingly likely that the chemical
precursors of life formed long before planets developed around
their parent suns, said Jan M. Hollis of NASA's Goddard Space
Flight Center in Greenbelt, Md., the leader of the research team.
</P>
<P>
   The sugar molecule, called glucolaldehyde, is a simple one,
composed of only eight atoms containing carbon, oxygen and
hydrogen. But its importance lies in the fact that it can combine
with other molecules to form more complex sugars, such as ribose
and glucose. Ribose, in turn, is a building block of RNA and DNA,
the genetic material that is the basis of all living organisms,
Hollis noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This discovery may be an important key to understanding the
formation of life on the early Earth,'' said Philip R. Jewell of
the National Radio Astronomy Observatory in Green Bank, W.Va.,
another member of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Hollis and Jewell, together with Frank J. Lovas of the
University of Illinois, detected evidence of the sugar molecule in
signals from the National Science Foundation's 12-meter radio
telescope atop Kitt Peak near Tucson, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Organic molecules reveal their presence as they tumble
end-for-end in space emitting faint radio waves at precise
frequencies that differ with each molecule. More than 100 of them
have been discovered during the past 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   The radio frequencies identifying the sugar molecules were
detected in the giant star-forming cloud of gas and dust known as
Sagittarius North, 26,000 light-years away, the astronomers
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The interstellar molecular clouds are extremely rarefied
compared with clouds that form in Earth's atmosphere, and they can
be many light-years across. But they are the sites of increasingly
complex chemical reactions that occur over hundreds of thousands
and even millions of years, Hollis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding glucolaldehyde in one of these interstellar clouds
means that such molecules can be formed even in very rarefied
conditions,'' Hollis said. ``We don't yet understand how the
glucolaldehyde could be formed there,'' he added, and it will take
more astronomical observations ``and theoretical chemistry work''
to solve the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The three astronomers have submitted a full report on their
discovery to the Astrophysical Journal Letters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
