<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HATE-CRIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TAKING ACTION ON HATE CRIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, June 17:
</P>
<P>
   For 11 years the New York State Assembly has passed bills to
increase punishment for bias-related crimes committed against gays
and minority members. For that entire time, Republicans in the
State Senate have blocked the legislation because they were
unwilling to include gays as a protected group in any hate-crime
bill.
</P>
<P>
   This month, at the request of Gov. George Pataki, the Senate
finally dropped its objections and approved a bill increasing
penalties for crimes that single out victims because of their race,
gender, national origin, age, disability or sexual orientation. But
now this effort may be jeopardized because of a ridiculous contest
of egos and credit-taking in which the two houses appear to be
engaged.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed the governor's bill, and insists that it will
not vote on any other bill. The Assembly, which passed its own
bill, has not approved the Senate legislation, perhaps because it
has championed this issue for years and does not want the Senate to
get credit now for producing the final legislation. There is some
difference in the language of the two bills, but they would both
achieve the same goal _ increasing punishment for crimes driven by
hatred.
</P>
<P>
   There should be no difficulty reaching a workable compromise.
The legislative leaders need to start behaving like grown-ups, stop
this spat and enact a measure that has been held up by politics for
more than a decade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 0115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
