<HEADER>
A6882 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-GAS-PRICES-NYT &LR;      06-17 0366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GAS-PRICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: OIL PRICE MYSTERIES  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, June 17:
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline prices have risen above $2 a gallon in Chicago and
Milwaukee, about 25 percent higher than two months ago, angering
drivers and sending political shock waves through Washington.
Drivers blame retailers. Refiners blame federal regulations, the
courts and OPEC. Federal regulators suspect price fixing. Some of
these charges are just plain wrong. Others have more merit but do
not account for the whole problem.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that gasoline prices across the country are about 25
percent higher than they were a year ago is unsurprising. OPEC
refuses to keep crude oil prices under $28 a barrel as it promised
in the spring. As of June 1, refineries have been required to sell
cleaner-burning gasoline _ which refiners say creates production
problems. A federal court recently ruled that the Unocal Corp.
could charge refiners royalties for a specific technique for
producing cleaner-burning gasoline _ forcing refiners to turn to
more expensive methods.
</P>
<P>
   As for the particularly high prices in Chicago, the industry
points to problems specific to the Midwest. A broken pipeline has
reduced gasoline flow by 20 percent. The Midwest relies on ethanol
to satisfy a federal requirement to cut down on carbon onoxide
emissions. But the use of ethanol makes it hard to also satisfy the
June 1 requirements, leading to supply disruptions in the Midwest.
For gasoline, it takes only a small reduction in supply to trigger
large price hikes.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities are unconvinced by the industry's laying
blame elsewhere. They say the companies have known about the June 1
requirements for five years. And they challenge industry estimates
showing that gasoline supplies are low in the Midwest. The Federal
Trade Commission will investigate price fixing. But previous
investigations of the oil industry have proved fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   No clear explanation for $2-a-gallon gasoline may emerge. The
price surge could well turn out to be the product of a combination
of factors that will dissipate as quickly as they emerged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 0116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000617.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6884 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-AFRICA-REFUGEES-     06-17 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-AFRICA-REFUGEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AFRICA'S SWELLING REFUGEE CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, June 17:
</P>
<P>
   The recent fighting between Ethiopia and Eritrea and the war in
Sierra Leone are adding to Africa's outcast multitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees and the internally displaced _ those who flee their
homes without crossing borders _ are among the saddest byproducts
of the continent's wars. Africa has more than 3 million refugees
and some 15 million internally displaced, a much higher number than
10 years ago. These outcasts are straining the resources of their
host communities and the good will of donors, and yet there is no
end to the stream of people fleeing for their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The average refugee from Kosovo received more than $1 a day from
the international community. In Africa, the average refugee gets 11
cents. The internally displaced, who are only now starting to
receive assistance from the outside world, most often get nothing.
</P>
<P>
   In many refugee camps, the only nourishment provided by the
World Food Program and the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees is
flour and oil. Powdered milk is sometimes available, and
nutritional biscuits are given to malnourished children.
</P>
<P>
   Because donor nations are giving less, the refugee agency has
had to cut back on health care and education, which only goes
through age 10 or 12. Some refugees from Somalia and Sudan have
lived in these conditions for 20 years, unable to return until
their homelands are at peace.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some of these refugees are not much worse off than their
hosts. Guinea, a very poor country, now has more refugees per
capita than any other nation. Some countries, such as Sudan,
produce refugees in one region and host them in another. Host
nations get some reimbursement from the United Nations and
sometimes get food aid, but they must provide land and some social
services and keep order in the camps.
</P>
<P>
   African countries, historically generous to refugees _
especially when they were fleeing colonial oppression _ are now
balking at the burden. Many politicians are finding it profitable
to restrict refugees' rights and blame them, rightly or wrongly,
for problems like crime.
</P>
<P>
   The exodus from the Rwandan genocide in 1994 illustrated a new,
debilitating obstacle to protecting refugees. Perpetrators of the
genocide fled to the camps across the border, turning them into
internationally funded military bases. Rwanda was an extreme
example, but many camps _ which host countries tend to build on the
border to emphasize their temporary nature _ become recruiting
zones or rest stops for combatants.
</P>
<P>
   It is common for camps to be controlled by one side in the
conflict. Some camps of refugees from Sudan in Ethiopia, for
example, are essentially run by the Sudan People's Liberation Army,
and relief workers must carefully negotiate their access.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations' refugee relief agency is weakly managed and
needs more oversight _ in part because member nations use it as a
patronage pit _ and its dependence on host countries to provide
services is another breeding ground for corruption. But the agency
is struggling with a difficult and dangerous mission: 24 members of
its staff, and 23 workers for the World Food Program, have been
killed since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The reluctance of donors has also crippled the agency, which
finds it easier to raise money for emergency appeals than to
alleviate the chronic miseries of most African refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Although current refugee aid is meager, its most important
shortcoming is that it does not go to the vast majority who have
not crossed a border. The internally displaced should get aid when
countries request it, or when a state has collapsed to the point
where no one can give permission.
</P>
<P>
   Improving the lives of refugees also requires new attitudes
within Africa. Host governments should not build camps close to
borders. Countries such as Tanzania, Kenya and South Africa have
joined many European nations and the United States in passing or
considering laws that would turn away refugees or restrict their
rights. These laws are pernicious everywhere. But what refugees
need most is what all Africans need most _ an end to the wars that
have diverted the continent's resources and created so much
suffering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 0117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
