r s BC-GLF-OPEN-LADN     06-17 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS STAYS ON TOP WITH PLAY SUSPENDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ First the fog, then the sunset.
</P>
<P>
   The interminable centennial celebration of the U.S. Open
continues to play catchup at Pebble Beach Golf Links, where play
was suspended for a second straight round Friday.
</P>
<P>
   More than 12 hours play wasn't enough to make up for Thursday's
fog-out, and it didn't help that more fog delayed resumption of
competition early Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Once they got the second round started, it began to look an
awful lot the the first round - with Tiger Woods continuing to lead
the field.
</P>
<P>
   His 30-foot birdie putt on the 12th hole put an exclamation mark
on the decision to halt play at 8:15 p.m., dropping Woods to 9
under par and giving him a three-stroke lead over Miguel Angel
Jimenez, who was 6-under through seven holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a long way to go,'' Woods said. ``We're not even
finished with the second round. And we need to go out - I need to
go out and play early tomorrow morning and continue to play well.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't a problem Friday, almost from the time Woods made
his 4 p.m. start.
</P>
<P>
   He birdied three holes on his front nine and added a fourth
birdie on No. 11 before draining the dramatic 30-footer as the
decision was being made to suspend play.
</P>
<P>
   He thought a 15-foot put to save par on the second hole was
critical to his early success.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything it was a good, solid way to start,'' said
Woods, who added birdie putts of 30 feet on No. 3, 15 feet on No.
6, 10 feet on No. 7 and 12 feet on No. 11.
</P>
<P>
   He is confident he can keep up the solid play for a second
straight interrupted round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here before, I've done this before,'' said Woods,
who has won a Masters and PGA Championship in less than five full
seasons as a pro. ``It's nothing new. Only difference is, it's the
U.S. Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods and Jimenez were well-separated from the remainder of the
pack, led by Thomas Bjorn of Denmark (2 under through 16) and
Argentina's Angel Cabrerra (2 under through nine).
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Triplett, who won this year's Nissan Open at Riviera, and
Robert Damron are tied at 1 under - Triplett with a completed round
and Damron through seven.
</P>
<P>
   John Huston, Hal Sutton, Tom Lehman, Rocco Mediate, Spain's Jose
Maria Olazabel, New Zealand's Michael Campbell and Ireland's
Padraig Harrington were all even as play was halted, none more than
14 holes into the round.
</P>
<P>
   Should the fog accommodate, second-round play will resume at
6:30 this morning, followed by a determination of cut survivors,
who will then go out in the traditional U.S. Open twosome format
that might force yet another carryover Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Woods said he tried to remained focused only upon the play, not
how difficult it has been to get it completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waiting at the U.S. Open is not exactly the best thing to
do,'' he said. ``If you're playing a golf course that's a little
bit easier and a golf course that's more forgiving, it's no big
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Triplett, who completed a first round of 70 Friday morning,
followed with five birdies in his delayed second round and seems to
have the game going that earned him his first PGA Tour win at
Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   He thought steady play was the key to survival at Pebble Beach,
given the narrow fairways, deep rough and hardening greens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me the kind of tournament where you don't think
about the score so much,'' Triplett said. ``Pars are so precious
that you just spend all your energy (thinking) I've just got to par
this hole in front of me, and on we go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
