<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-ORIOLES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER INJURY STRIKES ANGELS IN LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Almost as though it were on cue, an Anaheim Angels
starting pitcher went down with an injury, creating room on the
roster for another.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Schoeneweis had to leave Friday night's game against the
Baltimore Orioles with a strained muscle on the right side of his
rib cage after his first pitch of the fourth inning in a game
eventually won by the Orioles 4-3 before 45,006 at Camden Yards.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the injury coincides with the return of Tim
Belcher, who will make his first start of the season tonight after
recovering from offseason elbow surgery. The Angels anticipated
sending down a reliever to make room for Belcher, but now they
won't have to because Schoeneweis was placed on the 15-day disabled
list.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Schoeneweis means none of the five pitchers who
began the season in the starting rotation - Ken Hill (rib cage),
Kent Bottenfield (shoulder), Jason Dickson (hip), Ramon Ortiz and
Schoeneweis - are there now. All are on the disabled list except
Ortiz, who was demoted to Triple-A Edmonton. They also lost pitcher
Kent Mercker, who had a life-threatening cerebral hemorrhage, Mark
Petkovsek, who has recovered from meningitis, and shortstop Gary
DiSarcina, who had shoulder surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen it to this extent,'' Angels manager Mike
Scioscia said. ``You expect to have a couple of nicks here and
there, guys that might have to be shut down for a while. It's part
of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meningitis, a cerebral hemorrhage, pulled ribs, pulled hip
flexors, it's a little out of the ordinary. But I'll tell you what.
This club is going to be there. This club is going to get it
done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in curses, but (gosh darn),'' first baseman Mo
Vaughn said. ``Two ribs, a brain and a hip. I don't know what to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis has overcome testicular cancer and reconstructive
elbow surgery during his pitching career, so he's dealt with worse.
Still, he was near tears in the clubhouse after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to start the whole year,'' he said. ``I wanted to
keep going and pitch a lot of innings. This is a real big
disappointment. It's pretty frustrating. I went through a lot of
stuff ... it's too much for one person to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   What is even more exasperating to Schoeneweis is that he
believes he suffered the injury in his previous start in Arizona
when he was batting in the National League ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   `'I narrowed it down to hitting,'' he said. ``It was the only
thing I did different in the last couple of weeks. I hadn't picked
up a bat in the last eight to 10 years, so that must be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he left the game, Schoeneweis (5-5) got a double dose of
Albert Belle, who hit a three-run homer in the first and a solo
homer in the third to account for all four Oriole runs. Belle also
hit two homers Thursday and has hit nine homers in his past 13
games.
</P>
<P>
   Orioles starter Mike Mussina (5-6) continued his mastery of the
Angels, even though he wasn't dominating. He gave up single runs in
the second and seventh innings, allowing eight hits in 6 innings
overall to improve to 12-4 in his career vs. the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was the Angels' third in a row, their longest losing
streak of the season. All three losses were by one run. They also
fell four games behind first-place Oakland in the AL West, their
largest deficit of the season.
</P>
<P>
   For the Orioles, the win was their sixth in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis said he felt tightness in his side throughout the
game, but it got gradually worse and finally was too much when he
made his first pitch of the fourth inning to Will Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I can't even hardly move,'' said Schoeneweis, who
said he had the same injury in 1997 while in Double-A and missed
more than a month.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis also said he'll be more sensitive about needling
other players who are injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``What goes around comes around,'' he said. ``I was giving guys
a hard time in a joking manner. I'll never do that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite it all, the Angels remain in the race with a rotation
that includes three pitchers - Jarrod Washburn, Seth Etherton and
Brian Cooper - who began the season in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said it before, we have a lot of confidence in the depth
of our starters in the organization, but it's been tested to the
limit,'' Scioscia said. ``We've got a whole new rotation from
opening day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
