<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELAYS PLAGUE PLAY AT PEBBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ Golfers started showing up at 5 a.m. for
a tee time. Play was painfully slow. Groups sat bunched on hole
after hole.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the U.S. Open at Pebble Beach; it's the Saturday
morning men's club at Pacific Grove Muni.
</P>
<P>
   For two days, things have been so backed up in this national
championship, from fog and slow-playing players, rush hour on the
Golden Gate Bridge looks inviting by comparison. We might have a
winner by next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the roadblocks, the Open leaderboard boasts a guy from
the Pacific Northwest and a bunch of incomplete scorecards.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, the tourney favorite, first-round leader and our
next president, stood at 9-under-par overall when the sun went
down, three shots better than his closest pursuer. Trouble was, he
played only 12 holes Friday. He teed off on the first hole at 4:45
p.m., something he probably hadn't done since high school. He
started his second round nearly 28 hours after the end of his first
trip around Pebble.
</P>
<P>
   The only guy to post two rounds under par is the man from
Pullman, Kirk Triplett. He played five holes in the morning to
finish off a round of 1-under 70, then came back in the afternoon
with a 71.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he's the leader in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do they write a check based on that?'' Triplett joked. ``Is
that something we can do, maybe a partial deal, split it up, day
money or something? It feels great. I love this place, Pebble
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``A win would just be a dream come true. If I could pick one
course to win a tournament on or be a champion, this would be the
one.''
</P>
<P>
   No champion will be determined any time soon. Play was stopped
at 8:15 p.m., with 56 players still on the course. Weather
permitting, the third round won't start until 10:30 this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Local forecasts call for morning fog Saturday, with afternoon
clearing, meaning more backups and incompletes are likely. NBC is
supposed to televise this thing, but so far the only coverage has
come from the Weather Channel.
</P>
<P>
   When play resumes, Triplett will have to contend with Woods, who
hasn't let much bother him. The prodigy had four birdies and two
bogeys among his partial second round, dropping a 25-foot birdie
putt to put an exclamation mark on his final hole last night.
</P>
<P>
   One player who won't be around is Jack Nicklaus. He followed up
an 82 with a 73 and won't make the cut in what has been advertised
as his final U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   The projected cut is 8-over-par, which means Washington's
three-man contingent will make it through the weekend intact.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle natives Fred Couples and Jeff Coston were at 3-over 145
and 5-over 147, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Coston, the Semiahmoo Golf Academy teacher and former PGA Tour
player, endured a 6-over 77 after posting a 70. He was still
smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on the respirator,'' he joked. ``Stick an IV in me and
we'll see what happens (Saturday).''
</P>
<P>
   Said Triplett, ``It's a good Northwest showing. These are
Northwest kinds of courses, really, with the greens and the
grass.''
</P>
<P>
   Triplett had an adventuresome second round, literally finding
the beach on the 10th hole _ he sent a ball over the bluff and into
the oceanside sand. Three holes later, he took a penalty stroke for
an unplayable lie after failing to convince two rules officials
that his ball had landed in a mole hole 125 yards from the green.
</P>
<P>
   Both situations resulted in double bogeys and helped drop his
overall score from 5-under to 1-under. But he took it in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the nature of Pebble,'' he said. ``Always will be.''
</P>
<P>
   On the 446-yard 10th, Triplett was 200 out, staring into a stiff
breeze. He couldn't keep a 4-iron from leaking right and heading
for the Pacific. He climbed the embankment and found his ball. He
momentarily thought about chipping up but took the safe route.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in a big, deep footprint,'' he said. ``If I had a good
lie, I could have hit it. I was smart enough to pick it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Triplett found his ball in what he described as ``a trough'' in
deep grass on the 399-yard 13th hole, short of a bunker. The
discussion that followed with two rules officials took 20 minutes,
to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a mole tunnel; I could put a hand inside for a
foot in each direction,'' he said. ``It was totally a judgment
call. There was no obvious evidence of an animal, no droppings. I
just got in a bad spot.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be the only one. Otherwise, he's first and finished,
a major accomplishment in this muddled major.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
