<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWINS INTERRUPT SELE'S CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Aaron Sele has never pitched in an All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   After Alex Rodriguez and Edgar Martinez, Sele went into the game
Friday night with a 7-2 record and as the player most likely to
represent the Mariners on July 11 in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But Sele didn't win any votes in his campaign stop in the
Metrodome, lasting just four innings of a 7-2 defeat to the
Minnesota Twins.
</P>
<P>
   He went into the game with an 11-2 career record against
Minnesota. And he went in hot _ with five victories and a 2.95
earned-run average in his previous six starts.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Twins had been all but frigid, having lost
three in succession.
</P>
<P>
   Go figure. The Twins scalded Sele for five runs on 10 hits in
winning behind Brad Radke, the only pitcher on the Minnesota staff
to have pitched in an All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Sele and Radke are similar pitchers in many ways, but Sele
pitches for a team that gives him lots of run support _ almost
eight runs per game _ and Radke pitches for a team that gives him
no offensive backing _ about 2.5 runs per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may have a (4-8) record, but he's never pitched like that
kind of pitcher,'' Mariners leadoff hitter Rickey Henderson said of
Radke. ``He's always tough. Always.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele, who was picked to the 1998 American League All-Star team
but didn't pitch in the game, said Radke ``is one of the best
around, and you know he'd have that (4-8) record turned around if
they'd scored some runs for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, the Twins did just that. Radke, whose only
All-Star Game was in 1998, hadn't gotten more than five runs all
year before the Twins finally broke free against Sele.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous when we got four runs (in the fourth inning),''
Radke said. ``When I got a lead like that, it would have been
terrible to blow it. If I'd blown it, it would have been a long
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Radke didn't blow it, but it was a long night _ for Sele and for
the Mariners. Sele, who had fewer than six runs to work with just
once in his previous seven starts, got just a fraction of his usual
support.
</P>
<P>
   Sele was staked to a 2-0 lead when the Mariners touched Radke
for runs in the second on a Mike Cameron RBI single and in the
third on Tom Lampkin's solo homer.
</P>
<P>
   After that, however, the offense dried up for Seattle _ after
Mark McLemore's single in the third, the Mariners didn't get
another hit _ while the Twins hadn't even warmed up their bats.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota shortstop Cristian Guzman, who would finish the night
with a career-best four hits, singled home a run in the third. With
the game tied at 2 in the fourth, Guzman's laser triple to
right-center brought home two more. Guzman scored on Ron Coomer's
RBI single, and Seattle was staring at a 5-2 deficit, from which
Radke would not let the Mariners escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about support,'' Twins All-Star candidate Matt Lawton
said. ``Tonight we finally got some for Brad. He'd been pitching
good, but we haven't been scoring for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Radke, who gave way in the ninth inning to reliever Bob Wells
after throwing 125 pitches, retired the last 10 men he faced. Of
the 20 men Radke faced after McLemore's third-inning single, the
Mariners went 0-for-17 with three walks. Just the kind of stuff to
impress the handful of scouts from other organizations in the
stands _ not to mention the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came right at us,'' hitting coach Gerald Perry said. ``He
had the good changeup, like always, and he had a nice cut fastball.
Tonight, we were no match for him. Once he got the lead, he shut
the door on us.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that kind of ability that has the Twins trying at one
moment to sign Radke to a new long-term contract, and in the next
talking with the Yankees, Mets, Reds, A's and Devil Rays about a
trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'd trade for him,'' Sele said.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear that the Twins have to do something. Radke will walk
as a free agent at the end of the season if the Twins can't get him
signed. If he doesn't sign in the next week or so, the pressure to
trade him might be irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a guy we've been wanting for a long time,'' manager Lou
Piniella said. ``Besides that, he's got good blood lines. He went
to Jesuit (High School) in Tampa.''
</P>
<P>
   In case you hadn't guessed, that's Piniella's alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, the Mariners might have been in the running for
Radke, but he was never available. Now that he is _ or at least
might be _ available, the Mariners don't list starting pitching as
their top priority.
</P>
<P>
   But Seattle could do a lot worse than make a run at a pitcher
who could be dominant for them _ or against them, if the A's win
the Radke derby. After winning 8-3 Friday night in Kansas City,
Oakland is one game ahead of the Mariners in the West.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
