<SLUG> BC-NJ-KOREANS-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR KOREAN-AMERICANS, SUMMIT TALKS OFFER HOPE
</HEADLINE>
  By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALISADES PARK, N.J. _ Along Broad Avenue here, where most of
the businesses are owned by Korean-Americans, the summit meeting
this week between ``the two Kims'' _ Presidents Kim Dae Jung of
South Korea and Kim Jong Il of North Korea _ was universally hailed
as the first tentative step toward reunification of a country that
never should have been partitioned in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a fault line, it was generational, evidenced in the
comments of Lisa Joo, 54, and her daughter, Jeannie Joo Aigner, 31,
as they worked Friday in the family-owned Benjamin's Pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really want it, and we really want to believe it,'' said
Joo, the mother, explaining that many like her with relatives in
North Korea feel they have a large stake in the easing of tensions
and want very much to believe it will happen. But for her daughter
there is a deep skepticism, born of being raised in the United
States, within a community that until recently condemned all things
North Korean.
</P>
<P>
   ``The older generation's belief may be outrunning the reality,''
Joo Aigner said. ``I have never met those relatives in the North,
and so they are not as real to me. Many younger people believe that
North Korea wants something now and once they get it, they will
close down like in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a community in which cynicism seems to reside more with
the young, weaned on Cold War pieties created by their elders.
</P>
<P>
   Joo concedes that much of the haranguing of the North by the
South was propaganda, intended ``to make you hate more, dislike
more.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``But I have changed a lot in the last two days.''
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 400,000 Americans of Korean descent in
the New York City metropolitan area and about 150,000 of them are
in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The heaviest concentration is along the Hudson River, from Fort
Lee north: some 80,000 Korean-Americans live there, said Kun Y.
Lee, president of the New Jersey Korean Chamber of Commerce and an
appointee to the State Commission on Civil Rights. In fact, some
have jokingly suggested that Fort Lee was named for a Korean.
</P>
<P>
   But for the last two days, wherever Korean-Americans gathered,
the talk was of the summit meeting in Pyongyang, its meaning and
interpretations of subtle gestures between the two leaders.
</P>
<P>
   At the offices of the Korean-American Senior Citizens
Association in Palisades Park, the tiles for Jangki, the
traditional, chess-like strategy game, and the black and white
stones of the game Badook were put aside.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the table was strewn with Korean-language newspapers,
and about a half-dozen elderly men pored over them. They talked
about the leaders' body language and tried to gauge the meaning of
Kim Jong Il's decision to meet Kim Dae Jung at the airport and to
provide a military honor guard.
</P>
<P>
   Chung Yun Taik, 76, with a smile that enveloped his face,
pronounced it all ``very wonderful because we are all the same
race.''
</P>
<P>
   His enthusiasm for the prospects of better relations and even
reunification of the two Koreas was not dimmed even as he recalled
that just a year ago a North Korean submarine was seized in a
provocative attempt to penetrate South Korea's border.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some distrust, but we must try,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The most important feature of thawing relations is the
possibility of reuniting with brothers, sisters and other relatives
in the North who were last seen 50 years ago, said Chu Ok Kun, 67,
the association's president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Family reunification is the most important thing for the
seniors,'' he said, as Kun Y. Lee translated his Korean into
English. ``They are the ones who are anxious to reunite. That is
their first priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Park, 40, the president of the Korean-American
Association of Northern New Jersey, said that the community was not
naive and understood that the opening that North Korea had made to
the South was required if the diplomatically isolated and
famine-riven country was to get help in solving its problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kim Jong Il is involved too deeply now to pull back,''
said Park, noting, as other Korean-Americans did, that there had
been very secretive past diplomatic attempts at easing tensions
between the two countries that came to nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole world has been watching Pyongyang for the last three
days and I think he cares too much about what the world community
thinks about him to pull back,'' Park said.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways the real story of the summit meeting to
Korean-Americans here was the humanizing of the North Korean
leader, who, like his despotic father, Kim Il Soong, has been
shrouded in a mythic secrecy that was fertile ground for demonizing
him. To see him smile and joke with Kim Dae Jung and reporters
about his reputation for being reclusive, and to see him physically
embrace his counterpart from the South, had a powerful impact, Lee
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is a leader who can do whatever he wants without
consulting anyone, and he chose to do this,'' Lee said. ``That has
a lot of meaning. Before, no one knew who this guy was and he chose
the leader from the South to be the one to bring him out from
behind his curtain. This is no joke. This is no baloney.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 0143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
