<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, June 17.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-PARK-CRIME (New York) _ Long before the worst of the violence
in this year's Puerto Rican Day Parade, the central elements of
mayhem were already starting to gel in dangerous and unpredictable
ways. Just as a thundercloud is fueled by wind and moisture,
Sunday's wild, uncontrolled mob attacks on women in Central Park
were fueled by a complex alchemy of alcohol, marijuana,
mind-numbing heat, male idiocy and errors of police strategy,
tactics and communication. By David Barstow and C.J. Chivers. 1,100
words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SINGER-HEIR (Jackson, Miss.) _ The legend was that if you
touched Robert Johnson you could feel the talent running through
him, like heat, put there by the devil on a dark delta crossroad in
trade for his soul. It is why Claude Johnson's grandparents would
not let him out of the house that day in 1937 when Robert Johnson,
his father, strolled into the yard. Robert Johnson, the famous,
almost mythical blues man, had come to Lincoln County to see Virgie
Jane Smith and a son he had never seen. Claude wants to believe
that Robert came for him that day, and he always wondered what
would have happened if he had run across that porch to him, so that
everyone would know he was Robert Johnson's son. Now, 63 years
later, the Mississippi Supreme Court has ruled that Claude Johnson,
a retired gravel truck driver who lives quietly in Crystal Springs,
truly is the flesh and blood child of a man so mythologized that
many people do not know where the legend ends and the truth begins.
By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT15 is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-NAGAKO (Undated) _ Dowager Empress Nagako of Japan, the
97-year-old widow of Emperor Hirohito, died Friday after a life
that spanned the transformation of her homeland several times over.
Nagako spent her life insulated deep inside a Japan that no longer
exists. Indeed, she was one of the last Japanese who could remember
life inside the aristocracy early in the 20th century or in the
palace during the time when people spoke an archaic, imperial form
of Japanese that has largely disappeared. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   MAFIA-DADS (Undated) _ Two sons who tried to follow their
fathers' career paths in the family business have instead followed
them into prison. The fathers are John J. Gotti, the convicted boss
of the Gambino crime family, and Carmine J. Persico, the imprisoned
leader of the Colombo family. By Selwyn Raab.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-ADS (Washington) _ Following the debate over soft
money. By Don Van Natta Jr. and John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-AMAZON (Maues, Brazil) _ For decades, this remote town
overlooking the chocolate-colored waters of the Amazon River has
been the main source of guarana, a bright red, highly caffeinated
berry that is believed by many Brazilians to be an aphrodisiac.
Inspired by a legend that guarana originated from a tempestuous
affair between two teenagers from rival Indian tribes, Brazilians
have consumed guarana in the form of teas, tablets and even soft
drinks. These days, guarana provides a clear example of the way
Brazilians living in the Amazon River Basin are seeking to harness
the region's exotic flora and fauna to promote economic
development. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-FRANKEL (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Martin Frankel, the
fugitive American financier wanted on charges of embezzling more
than $200 million from insurance companies, may soon be returned to
the United States. Frankel, arrested in Germany in September after
evading the FBI for months, pleaded guilty Friday to German charges
that he evaded taxes on about $5 million worth of diamonds he had
brought to Europe to finance his flight from the United States.
Friday's plea removes the main obstacle to Frankel's extradition to
the United States, where he faces more than 30 charges of fraud and
money laundering, as well as civil suits claiming damages of $600
million. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Frank Rich writes about free speech.
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Anthony Lewis writes about George Bush
and the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-KNOBLAUCH-PSYCHOLOGY (Undated) _ In baseball, the second
baseman stands about 50 or 60 feet from first base and is often
called on to throw the ball to first before the batter can get
there. It's not a particularly difficult play _ in fact, it might
be one of the easiest in baseball _ and yet Chuck Knoblauch, an
All-Star-caliber major leaguer, finds himself almost overwhelmed by
the task. The problem is clearly in his head, but why? By Erica
Goode. 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARTS AND ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JULES-FEIFFER (Undated) _ Jules Feiffer's moody modern dancer,
the comic strip figure who has leaped and stretched interpretively
to every spring, summer, autumn and winter for over 40 years, is
finally hanging up her tights. The reason? Her only venue,
``Feiffer,'' Feiffer's doodly comic strip of personal, sexual and
political rants, is ending on Sunday. By Sarah Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   GARBAGE-STUDIES (Undated) _ Increasingly, academics are finding
that garbage _ the previously ignored contents of wastebaskets and
dumpsters _ holds vital clues to American culture. By Katherine E.
Finkelstein.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-PANTHER-MEMOIR (Undated) _ Thirty years ago, Kathleen Neal
Cleaver, instantly recognizable by her iconic Afro and knee-high
leather boots, was writing polemics for the Black Panther Party.
Today she is plumbing her turbulent past for a book aptly entitled
``Memories of Love and War.'' By Somini Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-MAN-PROFILE (New York) _ A talk with Craig Bierko, the
lead in ``The Music Man.'' By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   NYCBALLET-DANCE-REVIEW (New York) _ Some ballets can be faked.
``Liebeslieder Walzer'' is not one of them. Without first-rate
performers, the ballet is like too much chocolate cake. But the New
York City Ballet presented a shining performance of this
problematical ballet on Thursday night. By Jennifer Dunning.
</P>
