<HEADLINE>
RUSTY RELIEVERS FAIL DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After a five-day vacation of sorts, the Los
Angeles Dodgers relievers returned to work Friday.
</P>
<P>
   They were rested, refreshed - and rusty.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen failed to keep the Dodgers in the game as St. Louis
beat L.A. 6-3 before 43,971 on Friday at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Things have been slow lately because the Dodgers starters have
been taking care of business. Three of the last five, including
Kevin Brown on Thursday, pitched complete games. The other two went
at least seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I don't have enough innings to keep the bullpen
sharp,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said before Friday's game.
``They're not overworked at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest ended with Orel Hershiser starting for L.A. Making his
first start since being recalled Tuesday from Single-A San
Bernardino, Hershiser had a rocky first inning on the way to giving
up five earned runs and six hits in four-plus innings with three
walks, one hit batter and one strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson planned to limit Hershiser to 60-80 pitches (he threw
76).
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Dodgers, when Hershiser left in the fifth
inning with two runners on, none out and the score tied, Matt
Herges couldn't retire the side before those two runners scored.
</P>
<P>
   Herges started by striking out Mark McGwire and Ray Lankford.
But then he gave up RBI singles to Eric Davis and Mike Matheny for
a 5-3 St. Louis lead.
</P>
<P>
   Herges walked one and struck out a career best-tying five,
including McGwire twice, in three innings. He retired seven of the
last eight batters he faced. Terry Adams went one inning with one
walk and a strikeout, and Mike Fetters walked one and gave up Jim
Edmonds' second home run of the game in the ninth. It was Edmonds'
first multi-homer game as a Cardinal and ninth in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser (1-3), who entered with a 10.70 ERA, retired the first
two batters before giving up a home run to Edmonds. Then he hit
McGwire and walked Lankford. Davis followed with a double that
scored McGwire, and Lankford came home on the throw to second for a
3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   That took care of the scoring, but Hershiser wasn't out of
trouble yet. He threw inside to the next batter, Matheny, and the
ball hit Matheny's bat and went foul, prompting Cardinals manager
Tony LaRussa to come out of the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Matheny eventually walked, and Hershiser ended the inning by
inducing Placido Polanco to ground to third.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers got on the scoreboard on Eric Karros' 19th home run
in the second inning off St. Louis starter Pat Hentgen (6-6), then
tied the game with two runs in the fourth. Shawn Green doubled in
Mark Grudzielanek and Gary Sheffield. For Green, it was the 42nd
consecutive game he has reached base.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the inning, L.A. loaded the bases, but Hershiser
grounded to third to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Hentgen gave up three earned runs and seven hits in six-plus
innings. That included getting Green to ground into a 1-6-3 double
play to kill a fifth-inning rally. Hentgen walked two, struck out
three and hit a batter.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Matthews and Alan Benes combined on two scoreless innings,
and Dave Veres pitched the ninth for his 12th save.
</P>
</TEXT>
