<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOBE CRASH LANDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Maybe this was about the way the ball bounces.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this was about the unpredictability of youth.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this was about life's inevitable ups and downs.
</P>
<P>
   Choose your cliche, and it will fit Kobe Bryant's performance
Friday better than the cliche that people rushed to apply to his
performance Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   That was the cliche about the Lakers' 21-year-old guard being
the new Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Two nights back, Bryant was floating somewhere over basketball
countrylike a god, dropping 28 clutch points on the Indiana Pacers
in the overtime victory that put the Lakers in charge of the NBA
Finals with a three games to one lead.
</P>
<P>
   He was Jordanesque. But, we would soon see, he was not Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Kobe came crashing back to earth as the Lakers were
crushed 120-87 in their first attempt to wrap up the championship.
</P>
<P>
   He does everything else spectacularly. So why not failure?
</P>
<P>
   Finding an occasion to which he could not rise, Bryant missed 16
of his 20 shots and finished with 8 points, his playoff low if you
don't include the June 9 game at the Staples Center in which he
sprained an ankle and went to the locker room early.
</P>
<P>
   The only part of the Jordan legend that should have been affixed
to Bryant this time was the cologne, Kobe having stunk up Conseco
Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed in the game I played,'' he said afterward,
appearing characteristically unfazed by the flop. ``But you put it
behind you, move on and get ready for Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Was his ankle bothering him? That's an unlikely excuse. It
hardly slowed him down Wednesday, and he'd had Thursday to continue
healing.
</P>
<P>
   He slipped quickly into foul trouble, though. He earned his
second and third fouls on consecutive Reggie Miller possessions
shortly before halftime, his fourth and fifth before the end of the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   And he appeared tight early on. He missed shots he normally
makes. He missed shots he shouldn't have tried.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers fell behind by 10 in the first quarter. That was no
cause for panic because the Pacers were making 75 percent of their
shots, a pace they couldn't possibly maintain. It's just that by
the time the Pacers cooled off, the Lakers were behind by 20 going
into halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like every time we try to close it out, the whole
(opposing) team is in a zone,'' Bryant said, referring to the
Lakers' failures in their first attempts to eliminate Sacramento,
Phoenix and Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant had been in a zone Wednesday, sinking 4 of 5 shots and
scoring 9 points in the overtime that tipped this series.
</P>
<P>
   He was in the 0 zone Friday.
</P>
<P>
   For the second game in a row, Bryant failed to earn a trip to
the free-throw line, this in a stretch in which he has taken 47
shots from the floor. A player with his quickness and finishing
ability who can't draw fouls is either a victim of the referees or
doing something wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Not that failing to live up to the Jordan comparison is
something wrong. The NBA is populated entirely with young men who
are not Michael Jordan, and most of them don't rate an MJ allusion
even on their best days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Michael play maybe 115 playoff games. He probably had 90
games at the level (Bryant has) had this one,'' Lakers coach Phil
Jackson had said before the game, when he was asked to explain why
he dances around the natural comparison questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to take anything away from Kobe, but we (in Chicago) got
used to the way Michael played and the level he played at. To see
someone reach close to the way he could play is enough of a hint to
want to make us recapture that lure that Michael held out for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Kobe's young. He's probably a better player at 21 than
Michael was at 21 ... He's got a lot of years to develop into that
(Jordan) role.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Jackson again was measured in his assessment,
this time tempering his criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kobe was game for it, but he just didn't find his shot,''
Jackson said. ``Indiana did a nice job on him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers guarded him mostly with Miller and Jalen Rose and
threw some bigger players at him too.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant missed 10 of 11 shots in the second half before going to
the bench for the last time with three minutes left and the Lakers
down 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just played defense on him. Anytime you're a young player,
you're going to have your great moments and you're going to have
your moments when you struggle,'' said Rose, the Pacers' leading
scorer with 32 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kobe Bryant held himself to eight points,'' Miller
said.
</P>
<P>
   What went up just came down. Kobe and the Lakers are comforted
by the assumption the Pacers, 57 percent shooters Friday, a whole
team of Michael Jordans for a night, will fall to earth in Game 6.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
