<HEADLINE>
WOODS LEADS OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ For nearly two days, an intrusive fog
hugged the rugged coast of Monterey Peninsula, blocking any view of
what had been rumored to be the 100th US Open.
</P>
<P>
   But that all changed late Friday afternoon as two eras passed in
the twilight, an almost symbolic handoff that seemed to turn on the
power at Pebble Beach Golf Links. As Jack Nicklaus, arguably the
greatest player the game has ever known, was playing the 18th hole
in what most likely will be his 44th and final US Open appearance,
Tiger Woods, who has made Nicklaus's records his personal crusade,
was on the first tee, preparing for his second round.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus, who rarely came up short of expectations in his
heralded career, did so with his eagle bid, then missed his birdie
attempt to finish at 82_155 and miss the cut.
</P>
<P>
   That left it up to Woods to demonstrate the magic that Nicklaus
is only able to remember. He did not disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   Showing a fire that was needed to guard against a winterlike air
blowing in across Carmel Bay, Woods closed down the curtain with a
30-foot birdie at the par-3 12th that pushed him to 9 under in a
performance that is looking more like his coronation, which, up
until this point, was somewhat unofficial as he has yet to win a US
Open.
</P>
<P>
   Play was suspended for the day at 8:15 p.m. with Woods and 55
others on the course, including Spain's Miguel Angel Jimenez, who
birdied the par-5 sixth and is 6 under through seven holes. But,
for all intents and purposes, it appears as if only Woods can beat
Woods, and images of Augusta 1997 are taking shape.
</P>
<P>
   Aren't they?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not at all,'' said Woods, whose 12-shot victory at the
Masters three years ago turned on the Tiger Mania that has not
slowed a lick. ``There's still a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means some will return with flickering hopes, including
Denmark's Thomas Bjorn (playing the 17th) and Argentina's Angel
Cabrera (though nine), who are both 2 under. Robert Damron (through
seven) is at 1 under, tied with Kirk Triplett (71_141), who is
fondly referred to as your ``clubhouse leader.'' In theory, all
that means is he's warming the seat for Woods, who will get to the
course early, most likely complete his round in favorable
conditions, then go home for a nap before a late-afternoon tee time
to play Round 3.
</P>
<P>
   Still, having a lead in the US Open is OK with Triplett, the man
who wears the funny fisherman's hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did they write the check based on that,'' said Triplett,
smiling. ``Is that something we can do?''
</P>
<P>
   No, not really, not unless they change the rules, which is
something that might have to happen if Woods is to be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   In search of his fifth win of the year, in just 11 starts, Woods
did not tee off until 4:42 p.m. thanks to all the fog woes
Thursday. No one knows if they gave him the twilight rate on greens
fees, but it appears more and more that he could shoot 64 at 3 a.m.
in a blizzard.
</P>
<P>
   Woods drained a 15-foot par-save at the second, then a 25-footer
for birdie at the third. He recovered from his first bogey of the
tournament (he missed the green at the par-3 fifth and failed to
get it up-and-down out of a bunker) with a two-putt birdie at the
par-5 sixth, then birdied the par-4 eighth to get to 8 under.
</P>
<P>
   A bogey at the par-4 ninth slowed things _ but not for long. At
the difficult 11th, Woods almost made an eagle 2, but settled for
tapping in a 3-foot birdie putt. Seconds earlier, Jimenez had made
his birdie to get within a shot, but when Woods made his birdie in
falling dusk at the 12th, the lead was back to three.
</P>
<P>
   All of this took place hours after Triplett had left the course,
most likely headed right to bed.
</P>
<P>
   Triplett was one of 75 players forced back to Pebble Beach Golf
Links early Friday morning to complete Round 1, which was rudely
interrupted Thursday by what they call ``June Gloom'' out here.
That is a thick soup that hovers over the coast, confused by cooler
temperatures over the Pacific and stifling numbers inland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got out here at 6:45,'' said Triplett, who was 3 under
through 13 when play was halted Thursday, ``and things were pretty
soft and calm.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, they weren't clear, so the start of play was
delayed until 8:15, at which time Triplett, unlike most of his
peers, held things together by losing only one shot to par. After
signing for that 70, he went directly to the first tee, did not
pass Go or collect $200, and made birdie to jump-start an explosive
front side.
</P>
<P>
   Triplett made four birdies, but made bogey at the ninth, then a
double at the par-4 10th to fall back to 2 under.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have recognized the fact that the golf course was
playing different,'' said Triplett, who misjudged the wind and his
approach to the 10th onto the beach right of the hole. It's been
done many times before, but Triplett did not make the mistake
others have made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was smart enough to pick it up, go up, take my drop,'' only
he hit a poor wedge and three-putted from about 60 feet to give
back two shots.
</P>
<P>
   But in this championship, said Triplett, who won earlier this
year for the first time in his 10-year PGA Tour career, you take
that medicine and go forward because ``the guys breaking par are
playing great.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there's one guy who is really breaking par _
which means by midday Saturday, Triplett and others may be battling
for second place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
