<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAKERS-PACERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS STAY ALIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The yellow ribbons on the lightposts along
Meridian Road can stay where they are. The same goes for all those
``Go Pacers'' signs that dot the windows in downtown office
buildings. Even the Pacer window flags _ only $13.99 at Osco _ can
stay in all those SUVs for another few days.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite son Larry Bird lives to coach another game. Facing
elimination, not to mention the end of his three-year coaching
stint, Bird Friday night left Conseco Fieldhouse for the final time
a most happy fellow. Or as content as an NBA coach can be these
days.
</P>
<P>
   His Pacers routed the Lakers, 120-87, in a thorough whuppin' in
Game 5 of the NBA Finals. Shaq &AMP; Co. still are in good shape; they
lead the series, 3-2, and have two games to win one, both in
Staples Center, the site of their first two wins. Game 6 will be
played Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still have the upper hand and we know that,'' Bird said.
``It's up to us to keep the pressure on. I still think they feel
good about themselves, up 3-2, with two at home, and Shaq playing
well. We're 96 minutes away from winning the championship. We
understand that. We have to win two in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird hoped for an energized, intense, celestial effort from his
on-the-brink boys similar to the one they had given him in a noble
losing cause in Game 4. He got that _ and more. The Pacers were
juiced from the get-go, putting the complacent Lakers on their
heels with an early jaw-dropping shooting display (75 percent in
the first quarter) and some tough defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers who, by the way, are improving as the series
progresses, shot 57 percent overall. They got 57 points from Jalen
Rose (32) and Reggie Miller (25), had 33 assists, hit 32 of 36 free
throws, had a 46-34 rebounding edge, and trailed only once, 1-0.
The Pacers knocked down 10 treys, including six in the first
quarter, and were in control throughout as the Lakers, again,
failed to close out a series. The Lakers are 0-4 in
first-opportunity closeouts this postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a team is shooting like that, there's not much you can
do,'' said Shaquille O'Neal, who had 35 points in a losing cause.
``They played inspiring basketball. It was Larry Bird's last home
game and they gave him a great show.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed they did. You know it's a blowout when a coach references
a first-quarter play as a key. But that's what Lakers coach Phil
Jackson did. He cited a 4-point play by Miller _ he made a trey and
was whacked by Ron Harper _ that ended a run that snapped the
game's last tie (8-8) and put the Pacers ahead, 22-11.
</P>
<P>
   From there, it was fast-forward, as Indiana raced to an 11-point
lead after one quarter (scoring 39 points) and a 19-point bulge at
the break. Rose had a sensational first half, scoring 22 points, as
he more than atoned for a disappointing outing (5-of-16 shooting)
in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to be steady, I try to be persistent, and I understand
we have what it takes to beat LA,'' said Rose, who was 12 of 18
from the field in 44 minutes. ``But it means nothing talking about
it. And since I felt like I've been doing nothing but talking about
it, especially when they got up, 3-1, I figured I was going to shut
up and go out and play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers made one half-hearted run in the third, pulling to
within 70-57 at the 7:18 mark after drives by that dynamic duo of
Glen Rice and A.C. Green. Bird, understandably, had seen enough. He
called time and then Mark Jackson (10 points, 7 assists, 6
rebounds) made a big hoop, sinking a running hook as the shot clock
expired. That seemed to pump life into the Pacers, who then got a
couple hoops from Rik Smits (14 minutes, 12 points) and soon the
lead was back to 19 after three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth quarter quickly turned into garbage time with yet
another 4-point play by Miller (four free throws on a technical and
fouled trey) and appearances by the likes of Jonathan Bender and
Devean George.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was worried about giving Indiana new life, Phil
Jackson smiled and said,``I guess that would be an obvious yes.''
</P>
<P>
   But the ever-cryptic LA mentor was even more concerned about his
own team. O'Neal came through, as usual, but Kobe Bryant looked
more like Vernon Jordan than Michael Jordan. He was 4 of 20 from
the field (1 of 11 in the second half) as he never found his rhythm
and tried to do too much with too little. Brian Shaw and Derek
Fisher were a combined 0 of 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a good game,'' Bryant said with a shrug. ``You
bounce back. You put it behind you.''
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, Jackson saw little to no defense from a team which
specialized in that department over the course of the season. The
margin of defeat was the largest for the Lakers in the postseason,
topping the 29-point humbling at home to Portland. And the 120
points? That was the most any Laker foe scored all season and 38
more than their average points allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that bothers us most as a coaching staff is
defensively,'' Jackson said. ``We bounced back from games like this
before. I don't like to think of a team that has championship
quality in it that loses by 33 points. We have to prove something
to ourselves when we go back home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
