<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSE A THORN IN LAKERS' SIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Surprise, it was not. Not anymore, anyway. Jalen
Rose has established himself now. People have come to expect this.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even those certain that the 6-foot-8 forward would rebound
well from his poor showing in Game 4 of the NBA Finals, could not
have foreseen this.
</P>
<P>
   Not the kind of first half that helped ignite the Pacers to a
stunningly easy 120-87 victory Friday night over the Lakers in Game
5.
</P>
<P>
   Rose hit on nine of his first 12 field goals, including 4 of 5
on 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers jumped out to a 19-point lead at the half, and it was
never a game again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jalen's very good with the ball, can take quick dribbles and
pull up,'' Indiana coach Larry Bird said. ``He keeps the defense
off balance. When he's hitting his shots, it's almost impossible to
stop him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose finished with 32 points on 12 of 18 field goals. He added
six rebounds, five assists, two steals and a block.
</P>
<P>
   This after he went 5 of 16 in a tough overtime loss in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipated that Jalen was going to respond, not quite like
this, but going to respond,'' Lakers coach Phil Jackson said. ``He
had some first half against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose is still something of a slight secret among casual NBA
followers. The frustrated point guard did not become a starter
until this season his sixth in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   By midseason, he blossomed into a star. He even did the
unthinkable surpassing Reggie Miller as Indiana's leading scorer.
He finished the year averaging 18.2 points and 4.8 rebounds per
game and was named the NBA's Most Improved Player.
</P>
<P>
   If Rose had just a routine night in Game 4, maybe the Pacers win
the game and lead the Finals by one, instead of the other way
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, you're disappointed any time you don't play the way
you're capable,'' Rose said. ``The thing that makes it
disappointing is when your team doesn't win. I could live with 5 of
16 or 1 for 16 if we win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose wasted no time in trying to make amends Friday. He hit his
first four shots, including three 3-pointers as the Pacers jumped
out to a quick 12-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the way he was scoring early in the first half,'' Bird
said. ``Then in the second half, he was making plays for people.
He's unselfish, moving the ball, his defense excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose hit from outside, hit medium-range jumpers, drove to the
basket. The Lakers had no answer for any of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jalen is a tough matchup problem for anybody,'' Pacers
guard Mark Jackson said. ``He's a 6-9 guy that can handle the ball,
post, that's strong, a slasher.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put a bigger guy on him, a smaller guy on him, he's going
to have an advantage one way or another. And when he gets going,
he's extremely tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rose found himself guarding Kobe Bryant for much of
the night. Bryant, coming off his sensational Game 4 performance,
hit just 4 of 20 field goals.
</P>
<P>
   When Rose started hitting, Miller quickly joined him. Miller
finished with 25 points, hitting 4 of 6 from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jalen had it flowing tonight, and that made it a lot easier
for me,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   It took awhile, but once Miller and Rose learned to play
together, they evolved into a troubling pair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to see,'' Jackson said. ``From a point guard's
perspective, watching them from Day One to now, it's just a drastic
change. They really play off one another so well right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Miller: ``It took some time for us to find our balance with
each other, to get our rhythm. Now that we've found a comfortable
balance between us, it's starting to show a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   For those still learning Rose's game, know this: He has never
not even in five years of coming off the bench in Indiana and
Denver lacked for confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm a tough matchup for a lot of guys,'' Rose said.
``I'm taller than people expect. Then I have the ability to shoot
the three as well as dribble, drive and post. There aren't too many
guys who can do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
