<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANA SENDS FINALS BACK TO L.A. WITH ROUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ They were like middle-aged parents checking up on
rebellious teenagers left home alone on a Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana Pacers wanted badly to spoil an unwanted party.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did they blow away the Los Angeles Lakers with a 120-87
Game 5 victory Friday night in Conseco Fieldhouse, but the Pacers
sent the NBA Finals back to the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Pride, the security of playing on their home court and a
relentless offensive explosion were enough for the Pacers to avoid
having the best-of-seven series end on their home floor.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers still lead the series 3-2 and will host Game 6 Monday
in Staples Center. If necessary, Game 7 would be Wednesday in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers' 33-point victory made a statement: They refuse to
become innocent bystanders, waiting around for the Lakers'
championship coronation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard about the parade that they had planned,'' Indiana's
Jalen Rose said. ``That won't be tomorrow, though.''
</P>
<P>
   To say that Rose took the apparent disregard personally is an
understatement.
</P>
<P>
   The wiry, 6-foot-8 forward scored 11 of his team-high 32 points
in a first quarter that embodied the game. There was little the
Lakers could do to stop Rose, who rebounded nicely after a 5-for-16
performance in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   He made all four shots he took in the first, including three
3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand we have what it takes to beat L.A. But it does
nothing to talk about it,'' said Rose, who shot 12-for-18 from the
floor. ``I feel like I've done nothing but talk about it, so I
decided to go out and play.''
</P>
<P>
   With Rose leading the way, Indiana whipped Los Angeles in every
way imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers beat the Lakers off the dribble, dropped 3-pointers
(10, to be exact) on their heads and controlled the boards.
Defensively, Indiana held in check every Laker except center
Shaquille O'Neal, who finished with 35 points and 11 boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played as well as we can play,'' Pacers coach Larry Bird
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sluggish effort by the Lakers, whose only lead was 1-0.
Indiana held a double-digit lead for the last 36 minutes of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   After the Lakers cut a 21-point deficit to 13 with 7:20 left in
the third, the Pacers went on a 23-11 run. They led 93-68 after
Reggie Miller's 3-pointer with 10:44 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Miller and Rose each sank four 3-pointers as the Pacers shot 57
percent for the game. Miller was feeling so good from long range
that he made a couple of 30-foot shots _ one that did not count,
because the basket came after the shot clock expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good that we continued to attack them,'' Miller said.
``That was key. It would be nice if we could have put some of those
points in the bank. I'm sure we're going to need them. But staying
on them was key.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it Pacer pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people got ready for a celebration tonight, which was
disrespectful to us and our character as a basketball team,''
Pacers point guard Mark Jackson said. ``We wanted to give ourselves
a chance to go back to California and see what we can do. ... We
look forward to going back to California, because we're in it to
win this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't the first time the Lakers failed to close out a
series. They held a 2-0 lead over Sacramento, but the first-round
series went the distance. It took five games to dispatch Phoenix in
the Western Conference semifinals. And after taking a 3-1 lead
against Portland in the conference finals, the Lakers miraculously
won Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we try to close it out, it seems like the other
team is in a zone,'' said Lakers guard Kobe Bryant, the hero of
L.A.'s Game 4 overtime victory, who didn't help matters by shooting
4-for-20 and finishing with eight points.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Lakers have not lost three consecutive games all
season. Nor have the Pacers won at Staples this year. Indiana would
have to accomplish both to win the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came here to get a ballgame and we did it,'' said Lakers
coach Phil Jackson, who seemed disappointed, but not dejected, by
the loss. ``We're sitting in the driver's seat, and we're not in a
situation where we have to get in a panic mode.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers, on the other hand, have conditioned themselves to
push on.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
