<HEADER>
A6907 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     06-17 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORY SUGGESTS IT'S JUST A BUMP IN ROAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ So the Los Angeles Lakers couldn't close out
Indiana on the Pacers' home court Friday. So they fell behind by 20
points in the second quarter, couldn't catch up and squandered one
of their three match points in this best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   So what.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, these Lakers are a little careless with the dagger.
If they had been standing in for Macbeth, King Duncan wouldn't have
died until the final act.
</P>
<P>
   These Lakers aren't natural-born killers. Their 120-87 loss in
Game 5 simply confirmed that which has been self-evident throughout
the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely laid an egg,'' said starting guard Ron Harper.
</P>
<P>
   Any more eggs and they'll have enough to make creme brulee.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' inability to put away opponents doesn't necessarily
make them soft or spiritless. Unless, of course, those are the
adjectives you'd use to describe the 1987 Lakers' championship
squad with Magic Johnson and Kareem Abdul-Jabbar or the 1993 and
1998 Chicago title teams with Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Give the Pacers their proper due; they were desperate to play
another day and they rode a wave of emotion that broke on the
Lakers, leaving them gasping for air.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant, especially, was sputtering and flailing so badly,
the temptation was to throw him a life preserver. Two days removed
from his transcendent performance in Game 4, Bryant fought against
his own energy current all night.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's heart was in the right place but his head was buried in
the clouds. So eager was he to cuddle and kiss the championship
trophy, the 21-year-old swingman forgot everything coach Phil
Jackson has been speaking in his ear all year about picking his
spots.
</P>
<P>
   He missed 16 of 20 shots, accumulated more fouls (five) than
assists (three) and generally wasted enough energy to keep all the
air conditioners whirring in the Valley. As much as Indiana's
Reggie Miller would have liked to have pumped himself up for
Bryant's poor performance, he was gracious enough to give credit
where credit was due.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kobe Bryant held himself to eight points,'' said Miller, who
finished with 25 points on the strength of his unconscious
perimeter shooting.
</P>
<P>
   In his misery, Bryant has plenty of company. The Lakers were
looking to close out the Celtics in Boston in Game 5 of the 1987
NBA Finals after stealing Game 4 - not unlike the Bryant-led Lakers
did Wednesday - on Johnson's baby hook in the final seconds of
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Remember what happened? James Worthy missed 13 of 19 shots,
Byron Scott went 7 for 10 from the field, Abdul-Jabbar misfired 13
times in 21 tries and the Lakers lost 123-108. Just like that, the
Hollywood Hills were alive with the sounds of people griping about
how the Lakers were a few guts short of intestinal fortitude.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Lakers returned to L.A., clinched the championship by
beating Boston 106-93 in Game 6 and the vibrations were so good in
the Forum that Johnson called it the best team he ever had played
on and then head coach Pat Riley guaranteed a repeat in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The 1993 Bulls broke to a 3-1 lead over Phoenix and the city of
Chicago immediately began planning its championship parade, only to
see the Bulls lose Game 5 at home (they won Game 6). Five years
later, the Bulls took the first three games against Seattle and
gave back the next two before winning Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   There's a pattern there. We trust the Lakers will study it as
though it were a Rorschach test.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're just waiting to get home,'' said Indiana coach
Larry Bird, who, as a Celtic, had a close-up view of the Lakers'
1987 travails and ultimate triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm the Lakers,'' Miller said, ``they still have to feel
good about themselves. I'm sure they'll throw this game away.''
</P>
<P>
   Before they put the game through their memory shredder, the
Lakers should give it one more close look, no matter how much it
pains them. In particular, the Lakers should note how an Indiana
team not known for its rebounding during the regular season won the
battle of the boards, 46-34.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a matter of height but of heart. In the next two
days, the Lakers have to find a way to match the Pacers' will. That
was their biggest matchup problem Friday, not Jalen Rose on Robert
Horry or A.C. Green.
</P>
<P>
   Said Jackson, ``We have to prove something to ourselves when we
go back home in that regard.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what the final win in any championship series usually is:
Not a war of attrition but of self-affirmation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
