<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WISE-GUY PACERS LEARNING HOW TO PLAY LAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Believe it or not, the Indiana Pacers began the
NBA Finals with a game of 87 points.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Reggie Miller missed 15 of 16 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Seems so long ago, the contest might have been played in short
pants.
</P>
<P>
   At the current rate they're going, the Pacers might be putting
up summer gas-pump numbers by a seventh game.
</P>
<P>
   They have to get there first, of course. But after a 120-87
bonking of the Los Angeles Lakers Friday night in Game 5, the odds
no longer are as goofy as Miller's ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had they beaten us by 33 points, I'm pretty sure we would have
been wrote off,'' said Indiana's Jalen Rose. ``So we'll see what's
said about this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, here's one view: The Lakers still lead the series, 3-2,
still need to win just one of two at home, which they will be
favored to do. And one more thing that is becoming virtually
inarguable:
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers are getting smarter, faster, about playing the Lakers
than the Lakers are wising up about the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers missed a sweep of the 2-3-2 series' Indiana segment
by three inches _ the distance Miller's potential game-winning trey
fell short in the overtime of Game 4 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On offense, the Pacers followed a 118-point overtime game with
Friday night's net-shredding, in which they shot 57 percent,
including 10-for-20 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; rr &LR; On defense, they have shifted power forward Dale Davis onto
Shaquille O'Neal instead of foul-prone center Rik Smits, and Friday
night had 6-8 forward Jalen Rose harassing L.A.'s Kobe Bryant _
morphing from Golden Child into the Addled Adolescent in 48 hours _
into 4-for-20 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't mean the Lakers can't get smarter too, over the next
couple of off-days. But losing this badly this deep in a series,
well, even the inscrutable Phil Jackson is scratching his gray
beard a little more furtively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to think of a team that has championship quality
in it that loses by 33 points,'' said the somber Lakers coach.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't appear rattled, said all the right things about not
panicking, noted it was the purple fellows in the series' driver's
seat. But still ...
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-three points, virtually wire-to-wire, not even a Lakers
run ... jeez. The margin equaled the worst fifth-game defeat in
Finals history, and was the fourth-worst whacking in any Finals
contest.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Pacers were closing out a splendid year in their new
Conseco Fieldhouse, and it was the last home-state game in the
coaching career of the folk hero, Larry Bird. Predictably, emotions
ran to flood stage.
</P>
<P>
   As Bird said, ``We've had such a great year here, so it was
extremely important for us to play well because of the support.''
</P>
<P>
   But after that adrenaline petered out, the Lakers figured to
bust a move.
</P>
<P>
   Never happened.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson outlined before the game three must-do's: Keep Smits
from easy baskets; contest closely Miller and Rose; win the
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Smits had 12 points in 14 minutes, Miller and Rose scored
57 points on 19-for-30 shooting and the Pacers had a 46-34 rebound
edge.
</P>
<P>
   Mission Implodable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We laid an egg,'' said Lakers guard Ron Harper. ``There's
nothing I can really say. We just laid an egg out there. We didn't
have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Rare words so late in a series for a potential champion.
</P>
<P>
   Again Friday night, the laconic Lakers played with games to
give; it has been their playoff pattern. They had chances in each
previous playoff series to put early close-outs on Sacramento,
Phoenix and Portland. L.A.'s record in those games: 3-5.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's 3-6. The saving grace is that they recovered to win all
those series.
</P>
<P>
   The worrisome aspect for L.A. is that the Pacers are the
craftiest team they have met. Indiana is taking notes, finding
weaknesses, gaining confidence. In playing two straight superlative
games against a more physically gifted opponent, the Pacers have
shed whatever intimidation factor compromised them in the first two
defeats in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We absolutely, positively have nothing to lose and everything
in the world to gain,'' Miller said. ``From the get-go, they were
supposed to sweep us. We can come out and play free and loose,
which I'm sure a lot of guys are going to like, especially
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   It's possible Game 5 was a one-time aberration, a gift of
Indiana's manic fans and their wonderful house of hoops, the best
building ever for modern pro basketball. Now that the series
returns Monday to sterile, soulless Staples Center, which is to
hoops atmosphere what a first scratch is to a new car, the Lakers
figure to muster a response more becoming a team that won 67
regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't played well there this year,'' said Miller,
referring to an 0-3 mark in the new building. ``But now, we have
more confidence than we ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the Pacers have gone to school. It's hardly
cap-and-gown time for them yet, but the dunce cap they once wore is
woefully outdated.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
