<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS CAN'T PUT PACERS AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ An opportunity came and went Friday, and a Lakers
team searching desperately for a championship identity instead had
to settle for playing a more familiar role: themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Tantalizingly close to greatness. Excruciatingly prone to
big-time failure before they can reach it.
</P>
<P>
   That's been the story of the Lakers all season, so it almost
wasn't a surprise - and seemed oddly appropriate - when they moved
within one win of the NBA championship ... then fell 33 points
short of grabbing it.
</P>
<P>
   Only the magnitude of the pratfall was shocking, as the Lakers
suffered a 120-87 rout at the hands of the Indiana Pacers, who
staved off elimination before 18,345 at Conseco Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers still lead the NBA Finals 3-2 but must cope once more
with their most familiar and most frustrating character flaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it and I say it's a sad thing that we couldn't
celebrate tonight,'' said Rick Fox, ``but maybe it wasn't meant to
be. And whether that's just the way this team seems to roll, you've
got to hang in there with us, because we always seem to find a way
to cap it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Because, of course, the Lakers' other most notable trait has
been that these sudden dives are almost always followed by a sharp
U-turn and an equally rapid burst back into the stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   That part will have to wait a couple of days. The Lakers flew
back to Los Angeles early this morning and will try to close out
the series Monday night in Game 6 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to be home. Our place is going to be rockin', our
place is going to be loud, our place is going to be hostile,'' said
Shaquille O'Neal. ``We'll be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers need improvement all around if they are to christen
their new arena with champagne and not tears.
</P>
<P>
   They got nothing after O'Neal's 35 points, shooting 40 percent
as a team and allowing the Pacers to score at will. Indiana shot
57.4 percent, riding the hot hands of Jalen Rose (32 points) and
Reggie Miller (25 points).
</P>
<P>
   Indiana took two of three games at Conseco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're just waiting to get home now,'' said Pacers
coach Larry Bird. ``They didn't play that well tonight. We played
extremely well. They know that they have the lead, they came here,
got the game they needed. It's up to us to put the pressure on
them.''
</P>
<P>
   After O'Neal, Glen Rice was the only other Laker in double
digits, with 11 points. Kobe Bryant, fresh off his incredible
28-point effort in Game 4, came out flat, got into foul trouble and
missed 16 of 20 shots. He finished with eight points - or as much
as he scored in overtime alone on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's all right,'' said backcourt mate Ron Harper. ``He will
respond in Game 6. I'm not worried about him.''
</P>
<P>
   This kind of setback in a series might be familiar - the Lakers
are 3-6 in elimination games - but it's not comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, we're upset with ourselves,'' said coach Phil
Jackson. ``There's no one to blame but us in this situation. We're
not going to be angry about it one way or the other. We're
frustrated that we didn't execute very well, we did too many things
off the dribble. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that bothers us most as a coaching staff is
defensively. Our inconsistency, really playing the kind of defense,
coming off screens, challenging shooters and putting some pressure
on the ball so that they haven't got the rhythm that they like to
play with.''
</P>
<P>
   First the Lakers lost control of the game, falling behind by
double digits in the first quarter. Then they lost control, period.
</P>
<P>
   They trailed by a manageable 15 points late in the third and
might have been able to mount another storybook comeback. Then they
got panicky.
</P>
<P>
   Fox collared Austin Croshere for a flagrant foul and it turned
into a four-point play. And it got worse. Croshere made both free
throws, and as the Pacers retained possession, Bryant picked up his
fifth foul, sending Mark Jackson to the line for two more free
throws. With 1:52 left in the quarter, the Lakers trailed 84-65.
</P>
<P>
   Then they opened the fourth quarter by giving the Pacers another
four- point play. Derek Fisher was called for a foul as Miller
attempted a 3- pointer, then earned a technical for jawing at
referee Jack Nies. Miller made the technical free throw, then three
more for the foul.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight seconds into the fourth and the Lakers had sunk
themselves into a 90-67 hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an unfortunate situation. I think we tried to get a
little bit too feisty,'' Phil Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, the Pacers looked like anything but a team
ready to roll over, as they raced to a 64-45 halftime lead that had
the Lakers shaking their heads in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   Rose and Miller came out firing, each going 4 for 4 to start the
game, each scoring 11 points by the end of the first quarter, as
the Pacers established a 39-28 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy gets into a groove like that, it's hard to stop him,''
Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   It's also proved difficult to sustain the incredible energy
level that carried the Lakers to victory in Game 4. Or to suppress
the obvious excitement of being on the verge of a title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's always a comedown,'' Fox said. ``There's a lot
of emotion, in terms of buildup towards the game, what the game
meant, the anticipation of becoming champions, their energy of
obviously not wanting to be eliminated on their home court and
watch us celebrate. We did not match that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
