<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS FIGHT TO KEEP SHARP FOCUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS -- There was only one task left for coach Phil
Jackson on Friday, prior to potentially the Lakers' last game of
the season: Eliminate overconfidence.
</P>
<P>
   And, Jackson admitted before tipoff, ``it's a mystery to me''
how to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can talk about it, it's just difficult to do. There's too
much speculation and plans,'' Jackson said before Game 5 of the
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Losing focus seemed to be the only thing that would stand
between the Lakers and a fourth victory over the Indiana Pacers to
claim the NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had to talk some period of time today about being in
the moment, you know, simple, task-oriented kind of details,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no question the Lakers were feeling the excitement
of being on the verge of winning it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a natural excitement that you can feel about this team
and I'll work on that before the game,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Mike: The overtime heroics and 28-point night in Game 4
naturally elicited comparisons between Kobe Bryant and Michael
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Michael play maybe 115 playoff games. He probably had 90
games at the level (Bryant)'s had this one,'' Jackson said. ``And
not to take anything away from Kobe, but we got used to the way
Michael played and the level he played at. To see someone reach
close to the way he could play is enough of a hint to want to make
us recapture that lure that Michael held out for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Kobe's young. He's probably a better player at 21 than
Michael was at 21. He has a wonderful future and we hope that he
can fill those mighty big shoes. The chances are, he's not. Because
he's just a special player, but he's still going to be a terrific
player. He's got a lot of years to develop into that role.''
</P>
<P>
   Idols: Shaquille O'Neal expressed his great respect this week
for Indiana coach Larry Bird, calling the former Boston Celtic
``one of my favorite players.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was growing up, I had this game (with a friend), his
name was Mitch Riles, he was my best friend. A white guy. Of
course, he was Bird and I was Magic (Johnson),'' O'Neal said. ``We
used to go back and forth, back and forth, back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   ``But watching my friend play, I learned to appreciate what Bird
did for the game. I knew Bird was good when that one time where he
had the ball, he was falling out of bounds, he didn't have anywhere
to pass it to, he shot it over the backboard. I knew (then) he was
the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Idols II: O'Neal's list of role models at the center position
offered a surprise or two. Among the obvious, he named Patrick
Ewing, Hakeem Olajuwon and David Robinson. But he raised eyebrows
and got a few laughs with his other choices - Charles Shackelford
and Rony Seikaly.
</P>
<P>
   Seikaly? ``No really. Remember how Seikaly used to dunk at
Syracuse, he used to lift his legs up? That's why Seikaly,'' O'Neal
said. He called Shackelford ``my favorite center'' and ``the
original Shaq.''
</P>
<P>
   But as for his all-time favorite, it was Olajuwon, ``and still
is Hakeem, because he was a competitor, never really complained
when he played against me. He was a warrior, never raised his
voice, always smiled. Off the court, he was a nice, calm guy. I
always said to myself, if I was compared to anybody, I would like
to be compared to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Bryant continued to receive treatment Friday on the
sprained left ankle he suffered a week ago and Jackson said the
injury is ``about the same. I don't think there's a lot of
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   The sprain will require a few weeks to heal, but Bryant was able
to play 47 minutes on Wednesday without aggravating the injury. He
was limited to light work at Friday morning's shootaround.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
