<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUGH STUFF BREAKS OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Series have a way of getting rougher the deeper
they go, so it came as no surprise that each team was tagged with a
pair of technicals Friday in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise, according to Pacers guard Reggie Miller, is who's
initiating the rough play: Not the nasty guys from the physical
Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the scuffles are coming from them, which is a
shock,'' Miller said. ``Everyone thinks they're so nice and pretty
and, you know, they're the glamour boys. It's Los Angeles, Evian,
cafe latte, all that crap.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing all the pushing, the holding. They look at the
refs like they're not doing anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, it should be noted, gave an elbow to Rick Fox as he
walked by him during a stoppage in play in the fourth quarter. Fox
started walking closely behind Miller and was tagged with a
technical, as was Pacers guard Mark Jackson, who wouldn't stop
barking, irritating Indiana coach Larry Bird.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's nonsense,'' Bird said. ``He wouldn't quit. The
referees told him at least three, four times to get away, and he
wouldn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if he's going to give Rick Fox a kiss, get away
and let's get on with it. We had a good lead at the time. Just play
and get the game over with.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, naturally, had a different take.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coach has his opinion,'' Jackson said. ``He's the head
coach. But I think we have to step it up. I think as leaders of
this basketball team, we have to spark something, to make a
statement that we're not going to lay down.''
</P>
<P>
   Say goodbye, Larry: Bird wasn't caught up in winning Friday
because it was his last game as the Pacers coach in Indiana, as
much as wanting to keep the Finals alive and not end the season at
home on a losing note.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had such a great year in this building,'' Bird said.
``We were very disappointed we lost on Wednesday. You hate to end
the year losing two in a row. Our fans have supported us. We've had
great success here. We didn't want to go out here with a loss
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Players, too, were too concerned with the bigger picture to get
sentimental over Bird's last game at Conseco Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the last game here for a lot of guys, not just Larry,''
said Miller, one of six Pacers who can become free agents.
</P>
<P>
   The Best of it: Left-hander Travis Best, who sprained his left
shoulder when slammed to the floor after a flagrant foul on
Shaquille O'Neal in the previous game, played 10 minutes in the
first half, hitting both of his field goals and passing out three
assists.
</P>
<P>
   With the Pacers up in double-figures throughout the second half,
he did not return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we got into the second half, it was too sore and too
tight,'' Best said. ``And we were up by 20 points, so there was no
need to go back in the game. Hopefully, with a couple of days rest,
it'll be better.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an attitude thing: Forward Austin Croshere, who added 13
points and nine rebounds off the bench, said the Pacers' confidence
had been dragging after Wednesday's overtime loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have much of a pulse after Game 4, to be honest,''
he said. ``In the locker room after the game, in practice the next
day, it was like a morgue around here. Confidence builds from
humble beginnings, and certainly now, we feel like we're right back
in this series.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Miller: ``We absolutely, positively, have nothing to lose
and everything in the world to gain. So we're going to play free,
loose, we don't care. There's no pressure on us. All the pressure's
on them. From the get-go, they were supposed to beat us. They were
supposed to sweep us. We have nothing to lose, ... so who cares?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
