<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-OSCAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA TO FACE BATTLE IN COURT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the ring tonight, Oscar De La Hoya will face
one of the toughest challenges of his boxing career.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime around 8 p.m., De La Hoya will defend his welterweight
championship at Staples Center against a challenge from Shane
Mosley. But, when the fight's over, win or lose, De La Hoya has
another battle on his hands. He must defend himself in Los Angeles
Superior Court against civil charges that he raped an underage girl
after getting her drunk.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya and members of his camp vociferously deny that the
welterweight champion of the world forced himself upon 15-year-old
Nicole Rao in June 1996. Rao, now an adult, claims she was raped by
the boxer after meeting him in a Cabo San Lucas nightclub. She was
visiting Mexico with high school friends.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya denies Rao's claim, which is graphically detailed in
court papers filed by Rao's attorney in May.
</P>
<P>
   While there is no physical evidence linking De La Hoya to the
alleged crime, a former De La Hoya bodyguard, identified as Eric
Purvis, could provide some damaging testimony if ever called to
testify in the case.
</P>
<P>
   In a deposition, Purvis told Rao's attorneys that it was a
common practice for De La Hoya to go to nightclubs in search of
underage girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``(One time) Purvis declared he saw Oscar and a friend in a
bedroom in De La Hoya's condominium in Whittier with a girl who
looked, at most, 17, and De La Hoya was trying to take the girl's
jeans off, despite her express protestations of `no, no' and her
appearance of fear,'' the court papers read.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Arum, De la Hoya's promoter and president of Top Rank, Inc.
said he doesn't take the comments of Oscar's ex-bodyguard
seriously. Many of those comments were printed in Sports
Illustrated earlier this week
</P>
<P>
   ``No, of course not,'' he said. ``That piece was one of the
worst pieces of journalism I've seen. Oscar's attorneys are
considering taking legal action against SI. That article is
slanderous. Oscar doesn't deserve anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The court papers also contain accounts from Rao's friends that
indicate De La Hoya knew he was leaving the Cabo Wabo club with an
underage girl. He has denied those claims.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of Rao's said he yelled to the boxer, ``Oscar, what are
you doing? She's only 15 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Another classmate said she yelled to De La Hoya in Spanish,
``Quince anos'' - 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the boxer, Rao has filed suit against his brother, Joel
De La Hoya Jr., and friend Joey Gonzales. Both men have denied
Rao's claim that they assisted the boxer and attempted to cover up
for him.
</P>
<P>
   A key point of Rao's case relies on depositions from Joel De La
Hoya Jr. and Gonzales that greatly differ from Oscar De La Hoya's
account of his meeting with Rao.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the court papers - essentially a motion asking for
detailed financial information about the boxer - describe the
alleged assault in graphic detail.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing on the motion, originally scheduled for Wednesday, has
been postponed until Aug. 17. Trial in the case is tentatively
scheduled for Nov. 13. Rao is seeking an unspecified amount of
damages.
</P>
<P>
   Attending a weigh-in for tonight's fight, De La Hoya's father,
Joel De La Hoya Sr., admitted he knows little about the allegations
against his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say nothing because I don't know nothing,'' the elder
De La Hoya said. ``These things only Oscar knows. I don't know
nothing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 0301EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000617.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 03:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6913 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-CARDINALS     06-17 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-CARDINALS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' HERSHISER DISAPPOINTING IN RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ That April afternoon at Dodger Stadium seems like
ancient history, the exception rather than the norm.
</P>
<P>
   Orel Hershiser believes he can still pitch, but nights like
Friday's 6-3 loss to St. Louis are disheartening for everyone
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Making his first start for the Los Angeles Dodgers since being
recalled from Single-A San Bernardino on Tuesday, Hershiser (1-3)
gave up five earned runs and seven hits in four-plus innings. Three
of those runs came in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser blamed shooting pain in his hip as a factor but added
he wasn't feeling all together anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw pretty poorly,'' he said. ``It's been a struggle.
Including the minors, that's the worst I've been throwing.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Hershiser remains in the rotation (his next start will
be next week in Houston), but one wonders how many more chances he
will get with more starts like this.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring the first two batters he faced, Hershiser gave up
the first of Jim Edmonds' two home runs. Then he hit Mark McGwire
and walked Ray Lankford and gave up an RBI double to Eric Davis,
Lankford scoring on the throw to second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I battled through it but didn't get results,'' Hershiser said.
``You need to execute enough good pitches to have the breaks of
baseball go your way. I didn't give us continued opportunities to
do well.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Hershiser left, his ERA had increased from 10.70 to
10.80, and his six innings of one-run ball in the home opener April
14 against Cincinnati seemed as far away as 1988.
</P>
<P>
   He left the game with two runners on, none out and the score
tied at 3-3. Matt Herges failed to retire the side before those two
scored on RBI singles by Davis and Matheny.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser's woes seem to be lower on Johnson's priority list.
With suspensions looming, the personnel juggle continues.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Johnson said third baseman Adrian Beltre, who
has been disabled since May 28 with a strained hamstring, will be
activated today. That leaves a roster move to be made.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said something will be done with catcher Adam Melhuse,
who was recalled from Triple-A Albuquerque earlier Friday. Melhuse,
who came up when pitcher Al Reyes was sent down, made his
major-league debut in the ninth inning as a pinch hitter and struck
out against Dave Veres. Veres earned his 12th save in relief of Pat
Hentgen (6-6).
</P>
<P>
   Melhuse either will be optioned or traded but doesn't know
which. He said the Dodgers told him to report to the stadium today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know as much as you do,'' Melhuse said. ``All I know is
Beltre's coming off. They need a spot and I'm the spot. I think I
could help this team, but (he shrugged his shoulders) that's just
my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds, the former Angel playing in his first game in Los
Angeles as a Cardinal, added a ninth-inning home run off Mike
Fetters. It was his first multi-homer game for St. Louis and ninth
overall.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros hit his 19th home run in the second inning, and the
Dodgers tied the score with Shawn Green's two-run double in the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Hentgen went six innings and gave up the three earned runs and
seven hits with two walks, a hit batter and three strikeouts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
