 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, June 18:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-DEFENSE (Washington) _ The remarkable summit meeting
between the Korean leaders has left the Clinton administration
widely divided over North Korea's intentions, but has not so far
diminished its resolve to move ahead with a missile defense,
administration and defense officials say. By Steven Lee Myers and
Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GUARD-BOSNIA (Eagle Base, Bosnia-Herzegovina) _ For
years, the National Guard and Reserves have had to endure lingering
doubts within the regular Army that their part-time soldiers have
what it takes to carry out important military operations. But as
the Army relies more heavily on Guard and Reserve units, Guard and
Reserve commanders argue that the nation's citizen-soldiers bring
something else that their active-duty counterparts cannot:
experience and skills honed in the civilian world. ``In the
National Guard, we deal with civilians a little better,'' said Lt.
John K. Bahrami, a computer consultant for IBM and a member of the
49th Armored Division of the Texas National Guard. (A Special
Report. This is part of an occasional series about the experiences
of the 49th Armored Division of the Texas National Guard.) By
Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-DISSENT (Tokyo) _ Crowds build ever so slowly around
Zensaku Sakurai, a sidewalk crusader who berates Japan's leaders
for what he calls their arrogance, corruption and failure to serve
the needs of real people. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICAL-SATIRE (Moscow) _ In what looks to many here
like a twilight struggle over the future of free speech, the
Kremlin has handed one journalist over to Chechen guerrillas,
demanded that newspapers obtain federal licenses and, on Tuesday,
slapped Russia's leading press baron in a notoriously lice-ridden
prison. But the litmus test of the Kremlin's intentions may be
whether it tries to crack down on a bunch of grotesque, legless
latex dolls. The dolls _ a jug-eared, sheep-eyed President Vladimir
Putin; his Rasputinesque staff chief, Alexander Voloshin; dead-on
renditions of balding Communists, woolly-headed right-wingers and
other famous rogues _ are the cast of ``Kukly,'' which has long
been the most popular television show in Russia. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA (Damascus, Syria) _ Syria's Baath Party, the structural
support beneath the 30-year rule of the late Hafez Assad, gathered
Saturday to pledge allegiance to his 34-year-old son, Bashar, and
to vest him formally with the political authority he had quietly
exercised from the shadows in the last two years of his father's
illness. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-REGULATIONS (Rome) _ Vittorio Giunta, 48, is a rebel with
an unlikely cause. He is fighting city government, two
hairdressers' unions and dozens of small trade associations for the
right to keep his hairdressing shop open when the moon is full. He
and some of his clients believe that the best time to cut hair is
under a full moon, an ancient superstition that has not entirely
died out in Italy. That belief, however, clashes with a more
widespread superstition about free market ``chaos,'' a fear that
has kept rigid and jealously guarded regulations on hundreds of
thousands of small family businesses in place. By Alessandra
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   CZECH-JEWISH-CEMETERY (Prague, Czech Republic) _ A dispute over
remnants of the 13th century Jewish cemetery discovered in downtown
Prague during construction three years ago is heating up again,
despite a compromise reached in March that was intended to end the
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-POLITICS (Harare, Zimbabwe) _ President Robert Mugabe
and the opposition leader, Morgan Tsvangirai, will each hold their
last big rallies this weekend in a campaign before parliamentary
elections that has grown increasingly violent. By Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ARIZ-BORDER (Douglas, Ariz.) _ With new law enforcement
resources making other crossing points along the 2,000-mile border
with Mexico harder to penetrate, the rugged area around Douglas has
come under siege by desperate migrants seeking illegal entry into
the United States. After federal agencies bolstered security at
once-popular crossing points, hundreds of thousands of illegal
immigrants began flooding the Douglas area two years ago, risking
inhospitable desert conditions, including poisonous snakes and
daytime temperatures well above 100 degrees. But lately, they have
encountered another threat: angry ranchers on the outskirts of
Douglas who have grown so weary of border crossers tramping across
their land in groups of 50 and more that some ranchers, taking
matters into their own hands, have detained them at gunpoint until
Border Patrol agents arrived. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-JOBS (Undated) _ For the last 10 years, fewer teen-agers
and young adults have been venturing into the summer work force.
Last year, even with desperate managers dangling finder's fees,
tuition plans and other lures, just 62 percent of America's 16
million people between 16 and 19 years old were in the labor force.
That compared with a high of 71.8 percent in 1978, and was the
lowest percentage since July 1965. The trend is most pronounced
among young men, whose summer employment rate of 65 percent is down
from 73.5 percent in 1989 and is the lowest since the Bureau of
Labor Statistics started keeping track in 1948. By Mary Williams
Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   CRIME-STATS (Undated) _ With the number of homicides in some of
the nation's big cities rising in 1999 and the first five months of
2000, after eight years of sharp drops, concern is rising among law
enforcement officials and criminologists about whether the decline
in violent crime has finally come to an end. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   ALLIGATOR-FARM (Camilla, Ga.) _ Mark A. Glass is one of the
largest alligator farmers in Georgia, and one of 10 in the state
who are exploring the synergies of raising chickens beside gators.
Officials with various poultry associations said that there might
be a few such operations in other states but that Georgia, which
calls itself the largest chicken-producing state, seemed to be the
epicenter of experimentation. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-SLUSH-FUND (Sacramento, Calif.) _ The office of
California's insurance commissioner has been hit by a scandal that
threatens to cost him his job and the tottering California
Republican Party some of its hopes for rejuvenation in Election
2000. The commissioner, Chuck Quackenbush, one of only two
Republicans currently holding statewide office, is fighting charges
that he allowed half a dozen insurance companies to shortchange
earthquake victims, and that in return the companies financed
nonprofit foundations he set up to funnel himself political slush
money. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ECONOMY-POLITICS (Orlando, Fla.) _ Eight years after the Clinton
campaign adopted ``It's the economy, stupid'' as its mantra, the
presidential race of 2000 has raised an intriguing question: Has
the new economy changed some of the old rules of politics? By
Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   JANITORS-MOVIE (Los Angeles) _ What kind of movie premiere is
held in midafternoon, without a foot of red carpet in sight and
with most of the audience wearing the same outfit? A premiere that
knows its target audience, most of whom had to get to work by 5:30.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-NOMINATION-PROCESS (Washington) _ Most politicians do not
go out of their way to say the public does not know what it is
talking about. But Jim Nicholson cheerfully takes on the
three-fourths of the American people who say they want a national
primary to pick their presidential nominees. Nicholson, the
chairman of the Republican National Committee, responded to that
finding, in a New York Times/CBS News Poll in May, by saying the
public was ``wrong, wrong, wrong.'' By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   VA-SENATE-RACE (Alexandria, Va.) _ The last Democrat standing
between Virginia Republicans and a sweep of statewide power this
year is Sen. Charles Robb, a politician unceremoniously rated
``toast'' a year ago by political handicappers. The senator trailed
12 points behind a formidable Republican challenger, former Gov.
George F. Allen, prompting widespread speculation that Robb might
wisely retreat and call it a decent career after 12 years in the
Senate. But to the surprise of Democrats as much as Republicans,
that gap has now closed to a 1-point tossup in the face of an
unexpectedly galvanized Robb. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-DRUGS (Washington) _ With the House about to begin two
weeks of intense debate over competing proposals to add
prescription drug benefits to Medicare, the differences between
President Clinton and Republicans in Congress are widening by the
day. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Stop sharing, please. By Maureen
Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Progress, then and now. By Paul
Krugman.
</P>
