<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 11:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6927 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-REVIE     06-17 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU WANT OPPOSITION, JUST CRUSH AN OPPONENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ By any standard measure of democracy, Russia now more
than ever desperately needs a credible political opposition. But
until last week, President Vladimir Putin didn't really have any _
not in the Parliament, not in the regions, not among top business
leaders, and certainly not among a population that, more than
anything, wants someone to put its unruly society in order.
</P>
<P>
   After ten years of democratic bedlam, many Russians seem to have
rediscovered an ancient yearning to obey that makes them a perfect
match for Putin, a KGB veteran who prefers loyal servants to
political partners in this vast and cumbersome country.
</P>
<P>
   But now, with the jailing last Tuesday of Vladimir Gusinsky,
Putin may have actually stirred up some real opposition. Gusinsky
was charged with embezzlement and released Friday. And as the
Gusinsky affair moves to its next, more political, phase, the
spotlight will be on Putin's ability to handle a challenge that has
now spread far beyond the boundaries of Gusinsky's media empire.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time, during Boris Yeltsin's tenure as president,
when Gusinsky _ himself no slouch at the rough and cynical game of
Russian power politics _ enjoyed the Kremlin's favor. But by the
time of his arrest, his media empire had become a rare, if not the
last, center of resistance to the Putin political machine.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky made his dramatic break more than a year ago, when he
and his media outlets took aim at Yeltsin's cozy cabal of insiders
and intriguers, henceforth labeled the Family. As the Family's
fortunes kept rising, together with Putin's popularity and eventual
election, Gusinsky fell ever further from favor.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Putin set about bringing his other political
opponents to heel. Some, like the governor of St. Petersburg,
Vladimir Yakovlev, jumped into his lap; others like Mayor Yuri
Luzhkov in Moscow needed first to be shown their place before they
were allowed back into the inner circle. The rest of Russia's
rambunctious governors will be reined in by new laws that tighten
the Kremlin's control of the regions through the installation of
seven superloyal ``supergovernors.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gusinsky _ whose television station has not only criticized
the president and his war in Chechnya, but also regularly mocked
him on a popular Sunday-night puppet show _ never even got a chance
to make amends. According to Kremlin insiders, Putin has frequently
wondered aloud why Gazprom, Russia's half-state-owned natural gas
company and a shareholder in Gusinsky's Media-MOST, should help
subsidize flagrant ``anti-state'' thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Even this sliver of an opposition seems to irk Putin, who,
unlike Yeltsin, shuns confrontation and bristles at criticism.
Yeltsin's eight years in power were marked by his running fight
with a Communist opposition, and by his laissez-faire approach to
other power centers _ in the regions, in the press or among
Russia's rapacious capitalists, known as the oligarchs.
</P>
<P>
   As Putin rose to power, riding a wave of nationalism let loose
by the Chechen war, these alternate power centers offered no
resistance. The Communists, who have long posed as Russian
patriots, were hard-pressed to challenge Putin's bellicosity in
Chechnya. The liberal intelligentsia (including some of the press)
was alarmed by Putin's background and his sometimes dim
understanding of democratic norms, but they no longer carry much
weight in a society which, after the disappointments of the last
ten years, views liberal Western values with suspicion. Businesses
are hoping Putin will abide by his promise to restore the rule of
law and treat them equally (though others point out that his words
were ``dictatorship of the law'').
</P>
<P>
   Then, last Tuesday, while Putin was in Madrid dining with the
Spanish royal family, Gusinsky was thrown into one of Russia's
toughest and most antiquated jails. Whether the charges are
eventually proved or not, they are widely considered here to be a
pretext to finish off the last of the anti-Kremlin opposition.
</P>
<P>
   But if that was indeed the plan, events don't seem to be
cooperating. Politicians, journalists and businessmen have rushed
for the microphones to denounce the move against Gusinsky, a media
magnate who also happens to be a leader of Russia's Jewish
community. Suddenly Putin's hold on Russia's slippery political
scene looks less firm than it did just a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians and journalists condemned the arrest, but perhaps
the most significant voices were those of 17 representatives of big
business _ oligarchs _ who signed an open letter of protest to
Putin. ``They are looking at Gusinsky's story as if in a mirror,''
said Grigory Yavlinsky, leader of the liberal-democratic Yabloko
party.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Putin himself ordered the arrest, or whether he was set
up by schemers inside the Family, he stands a good chance of coming
out a loser. If he distances himself from the arrest, many Russians
say, he could look weak, even foolish. If he supports it, he will
confirm every Russian democrat's worst fears about the dangers of
putting a former KGB officer in charge. Some commentators have
noted that the arrest of Gusinsky may actually be popular: Most
Russians hate rich businessmen, particularly if they are Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   But opinion polls are not what drives politics in Russia:
politics here are a zero-sum game, which is all about getting
power, not sharing it. In a front page editorial, Vitaly Tretyakov,
editor of Nezavisimaya Gazeta, summed up the stakes: ``Either
Gusinsky is right, and the Kremlin is wrong, or the Kremlin is
right and Gusinsky is wrong. The one who will win this juridical,
political and propaganda war will be right. The winner will take
all.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 1143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000617.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 11:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3591 &Cx1f; var-z
