<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 11:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6928 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-NKOREA-SYRIA-REVIEW-2     06-17 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-SYRIA-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF DAD WAS A DICTATOR, CAN YOU BE MR. NICE GUY? 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The images sent imaginations soaring.
</P>
<P>
   On the airport tarmac in Pyongyang last Tuesday, the reclusive,
elusive leader of North Korea, Kim Jong Il, reached forward and
greeted his guest, President Kim Dae-jung of South Korea, with an
honor guard and a gripping, two-handed handshake. Behind the grins,
it was tempting to see a melting of a half-century of hostility
across the Korean peninsula, one of the world's most dangerous
flashpoints.
</P>
<P>
   Half a world away, Bashar Assad, a 34-year-old British-educated
eye doctor who is the new ruler of Syria, stood stoically near the
flag-draped coffin of his father, President Hafez Assad, receiving
condolences from a parade of visiting foreign princes and
dignitaries. One of those visitors was Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, expressing hope _ ever so tentatively _ that the new
Syrian leader might cool off the most enduringly hostile corner of
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   It was, of course, pure coincidence that the two events took
place the same day. But beneath the surface, there are profound
similarities in what was happening last week.
</P>
<P>
   Both North Korea and Syria are relics of another age _
dictatorships based on internal terror and hostility to external
neighbors, threatening to explode at any time in new conflict. And
now Syria, like North Korea six years ago, has embarked on a
dynastic transition that may _ or may not _ give reason to hope for
an easing of those tensions.
</P>
<P>
   In each place, power has passed from a dictator to his son, and
the son shows signs of a more modern, outward-looking approach to
solving his country's deep problems. Perhaps that can make the
world more peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also the disquieting feeling that it won't be easy;
terror and isolation remain hallmarks of the systems in which these
two sons rule, and whether they can _ or even want to _ tame parts
of those systems may be the most important factors in determining
whether a real transformation is under way. Change, for both sons,
will be risky: moving from a terror-based society to a more open
one always is.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of North Korea, Kim Jong Il appears to have made a
strategic, possibly desperate, decision to reach out to the rest of
the world. Even before he pledged during the summit that he would
visit South Korea, he established diplomatic relations with Italy
and secretly visited China. President Vladimir Putin of Russia has
said he will visit North Korea next month, and Japan is negotiating
a possible resumption of relations.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Syria, the younger Assad, an English- and
French-speaking Internet enthusiast in a country where free speech
is a fantasy and the Internet has been branded a threat to
security, made clear even before he assumed the reins of power that
he was different from his father. ``I am not one of those who keeps
power for himself,'' he told the Egyptian weekly Al Ousboua in an
interview before his father's death. ``I believe in the need to
open up to all opinions and listen to all viewpoints.''
</P>
<P>
   But for both men, success is not at all guaranteed, and for
remarkably similar reasons. Neither Kim Jong Il nor Bashar Assad
got his job the way his father did _ as a military leader who
grabbed and consolidated power. Even though both countries are
called ``republics,'' the sons did not get their jobs because of
the will of the people. They did not even get their jobs in the
most traditional dynastic way _ through the legitimacy implicit in
royal blood lines.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the two sons came into power only because of the
political manipulations of their fathers while they were alive,
abetted after their deaths by military and terror apparatuses
bequeathed to the sons as pillars of their respective systems. That
means that their claim to legitimacy is dangerously thin, and any
bold move either at home or abroad is fraught with risks. Both
men's fathers left them societies in bad economic shape, North
Korea's disastrously so. Westerners sometimes see that as a force
dictating an opening to the outside world. But both sons must be
aware that a wrong move in that direction could bring down the
wrath of the military or the ruling party. At the same time,
isolating potential rivals and suddenly placing new power in the
hands of foreign businessmen, or the press, or the people
themselves, could bring down the entire structure of power.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
