<P>
   With his expensive platform of tax cuts, Social Security
overhaul and a national missile defense program suddenly looking
more affordable, Bush could have been forgiven a smirk. The Texan
even gained room to claim that he would be committed to debt
reduction, just like his opponent. Yet Bush's insistence that
Washington is profligate and would have to tighten its belt in most
areas other than the military began to ring hollow.
</P>
<P>
   We've got peace and prosperity and a surplus,'' said James
Thurber, a professor of government at American University in
Washington. ``That creates a new kind of politics. They no longer
have to make tough decisions to balance the budget. They no longer
have to cut popular programs to get tax cuts, or to increase taxes,
God forbid, in order to pay for things.''
</P>
<P>
   But to the degree that they no longer define themselves through
the fight over how to allocate scarce resources, the two parties
may have to retool their ideologies or risk losing their
identities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old left-right guideposts are no longer reliable,'' said
Will Marshall, president of the Progressive Policy Institute, the
research group for centrist Democrats. ``They hark back to the
conflicts of an industrial society that is being eclipsed by the
new economy. Ideologues in Washington and activists at the grass
roots level have an investment in maintaining the old polarities,
but the electorate is less and less interested in them.''
</P>
<P>
   David Brooks, the author of ``Bobos in Paradise: The New Upper
Class and How They Got There,'' a look at how affluence has made a
hash of traditional value systems and cultural identities, said
prosperity is creating ``a style of politician who goes off in both
directions at once.'' In trying to merge opposing views of the
world, he said, politicians are combining elements of left and
right under rubrics that are given fancy names like the Third Way
but could equally be viewed as ``ideological mush.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not that traditional politics and ideology do not matter
at all. It may only have been divided government that has kept
Republicans from using the surplus to slash taxes in a way that
would starve the government of revenues and power in the long run,
and the Democrats from pushing through expensive social programs.
This year's presidential race is in many ways about whether one
party should have a mandate to use the bounty of the long
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   But the partisan lines are blurring. Republicans in Congress
have grown more willing to spend money and tolerate, if not
embrace, big and powerful government _ a sea change from 1995, when
the Gingrich revolution promised the elimination of entire cabinet
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what I only half-jokingly call the curse of the surplus:
You can't get anyone interested in cutting anything,'' said Stephen
Moore, president of the Club for Growth, a conservative political
action committee. ``Politicians are in the game of being able to
give away rather than take away.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the same on the other side of the aisle. Earlier this
month, 65 Democrats in the House voted in favor of repealing the
federal estate tax, and nearly all Democrats voted to slash the
estate tax substantially _ a move the party had long held up as the
epitome of a giveaway to the very richest people at the expense of
the poorest. Class warfare, many Democrats seemed to be saying,
does not make as much sense when most voters are solidly middle
class or above.
</P>
<P>
   In such a fluid situation, the rules of the political game are
uncertain. Gore began a push last week to wrap himself in the
strong economy, assuming that voters, as they always have, will
tend to favor the incumbent party when times are good. But polls do
not show much evidence that Gore is seen as prosperity's steward.
What if voters see the economy as a the creation of rapid
technological change, and no longer connect it with Washington?
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of who wins, the next president will have a long list
of immediate and looming issues to address, and fewer fiscal
constraints in doing so than any president since Lyndon B. Johnson.
Or maybe the carnival will pull out of town and leave behind
another mess.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
