<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6937 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-SUBWAY-OPENING-3Takes     06-17 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUBWAY-OPENING-3Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBWAY PROJECT NEARS END
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Saturday in story refers to June 24.) 
By HARRISON SHEPPARD  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Six years of perilous effort by thousands of
workers have come down to this: The last leg of the $1.3 billion
Red Line subway finally is about to open, offering suburban San
Fernando Valley residents an easy, congestion-free way downtown.
</P>
<P>
   But finishing Los Angeles' subway system has come at a great
cost: $4.5 billion, budget overruns, a street cave-in, business
disruptions, and political wrangling and scandal that rocked the
Metropolitan Transportation Authority.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the MTA throws open the doors to its new Red Line
subway extension to North Hollywood, hoping the prospect of zipping
under the Santa Monica Mountains at 70 mph will attract enough
riders to make the massive investment worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on whom you ask, the subway either is a waste of
sorely needed transportation money, or it transcends the geographic
divide that has split Los Angeles in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a way for the huge population in the Valley to come
through into the (Los Angeles) basin, and it is equally important
that people in the basin can get to the Valley on one line without
having to figure out how to get over or around that mountain,''
said MTA General Manager Julian Burke.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really breaks into an entirely different set of people,
simply because it is on the other side of the mountains,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new Red Line extension consists of stations at North
Hollywood, Universal City and Hollywood Boulevard/Highland Avenue.
It follows the Hollywood Freeway through the Santa Monica
Mountains, diving as deep as 900 feet at some points.
</P>
<P>
   Ridership on the entire MTA subway system is now about 145,000
boardings a day. With the new extension, plus new, faster bus lines
in the Valley that link to the stations, ridership is expected to
climb to 200,000 daily boardings by next year.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if MTA estimates are right.
</P>
<P>
   Valley residents who have previewed the new stations at North
Hollywood, Universal City and Hollywood/Highland say they are
impressed and expect many of their neighbors to start using public
transit.
</P>
<P>
   But ask them if they plan to use it themselves and they hedge.
</P>
<P>
   It depends, they say, on where they need to go and whether the
subway cars remain clean and safe.
</P>
<P>
   Mort Allen, a Studio City Realtor who sat in traffic on the
Hollywood Freeway for more than an hour returning from a recent
trip to City Hall, said he might consider taking the subway. But
he's worried about safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the New York subway in the movies and I see the
crime on it,'' Allen said. ``If nice people are riding on it, I'm
going to ride on it.''
</P>
<P>
   MTA officials say they have a host of safety features and have
managed to keep crime low on the existing lines. Among their
efforts are regular patrols by transit officers, security cameras
and stations with open-air designs that keep everything in public
view.
</P>
<P>
   The three stations were built on time and under budget for $1.3
billion, unlike the rest of the Red Line, which went over budget by
about 12 percent. Overall, the Red Line subway cost $4.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood segment of the line, in particular, was beset by
problems. In 1995, a 70-foot sinkhole opened up on Hollywood
Boulevard during construction. A short time later, the MTA fired
the contractor, who promptly responded with a lawsuit. Several
workers died and many more were injured during construction.
Federal occupational safety officials issued multiple fines to
contractors involved in Red Line construction.
</P>
<P>
   The North Hollywood segment had its own problems. Congress,
losing confidence in the MTA, had considered withholding money for
the line. At one point, Congress held up funding until the MTA put
together a plan that reduced rail projects in other parts of the
city.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate subcommittee cited the subway's history of cost
overruns, redesigns, corruption, mismanagement, accidents and
political infighting.
</P>
<P>
   Merchants along Lankershim Boulevard complained that they lost
millions in dollars in lost business, while the street itself
suffered more than $1 million worth of damage during the
subterranean work.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Stark, the MTA's top construction official, said the
agency kept costs under control in this last segment by learning
from past mistakes, keeping a tight rein on the contractors and by
removing certain nonessential elements.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a massive ventilation shaft in the middle of the
Santa Monica Mountains was not built. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It will not be needed until the system is running at a higher
capacity several decades from now, Stark said, so room was left for
it to be added in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tremendous achievement of any agency and especially the
MTA, given the fact that our history hasn't been that good,'' Stark
said. ``For us to have brought in a project, which had very
difficult tunneling conditions both in North Hollywood and under
the Santa Monica Mountains, without any of the incidents that we
had suffered in the past and still bring the project in under
budget, makes us tremendously proud.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL 2ND TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
