<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6942 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-SUBWAY-OPENING-3rdtak     06-17 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUBWAY-OPENING-3rdtake-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: employment centers. 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If you look at the roads in the area overall, and the rate of
increase in population in Los Angeles County picking up, it's our
thesis that within a couple of years, access to rail mass transit
is going to be very critical,'' Kyser said. ``The Valley is well
situated, because you have the two Metrolink lines and then you'll
have the Red Line coming in. That's going to give you a competitive
advantage in getting people around and attracting a work force.''
</P>
<P>
   An MTA spokesman said approximately $1 billion in economic
development has been built or is planned for the areas around the
Metro Rail stations.
</P>
<P>
   RED LINE FACTS:
</P>
<P>
   _ Extension consists of three stations: North Hollywood,
Universal City and Hollywood/Highland
</P>
<P>
   _ Travel time, North Hollywood to Union Station: 29 minutes
</P>
<P>
   _ Length of extension: 6.3 miles
</P>
<P>
   _ Length of Red Line subway: 17.4 miles
</P>
<P>
   _ Total length of all Metro Rail lines: 59.4 miles
</P>
<P>
   _ Deepest point under the Santa Monica Mountains: 900 feet
</P>
<P>
   _ Cost of extension project: $1.3billion
</P>
<P>
   _ Total cost of Red Line subway: $4.5billion
</P>
<P>
   _ Cost of Red Line plus above-ground Green and Blue lines:
$6billion
</P>
<P>
   _ Cost of each Red Line car: $1.8million
</P>
<P>
   _ Passenger capacity of each car: 180 seated and standing
</P>
<P>
   _ Maximum speed: 70mph
</P>
<P>
   _ Highest number of workers on site at one time building the
extension: 1,500
</P>
<P>
   _ Number of lanes that would have to be added to the Hollywood
Freeway to get the same capacity to move people as the two Red Line
tracks: 13
</P>
<P>
   _ Current ridership of entire subway system: 145,000 boardings
per day.
</P>
<P>
   _ Expected ridership a year from now: 200,000 a day
</P>
<P>
   _ Amount of steel used in construction of Red Line: 274million
pounds
</P>
<P>
   _ Number of automobiles that could be built with that steel:
90,000
</P>
<P>
   _ Amount of dirt excavated for Red Line: 4.9million cubic yards
</P>
<P>
   _ Number of times the Rose Bowl could be filled with that much
dirt: 3.5
</P>
<P>
   _ Number of concrete mixing trucks used to pour the Red Line
tunnels: 100,000
</P>
<P>
   _ Distance a 5-foot-wide sidewalk could be built with that much
concrete: From Los Angeles to Boston
</P>
<P>
   _ Jobs created by all Metro Rail construction: 141,600 direct
jobs; more than 200,000 indirect jobs
</P>
<P>
   _ Operating costs per passenger-mile for subway: 79cents
(expected to decline as ridership increases with new stations)
</P>
<P>
   _ Operating costs per passenger-mile for light-rail system:
32cents
</P>
<P>
   _ Operating costs per passenger-mile for buses: 50cents
</P>
<P>
   Other things $1.3 billion could buy:
</P>
<P>
   _ Los Angeles Lakers teams (based on total salary of
$53million): 24, plus enough to cover announcer Chick Hearn.
</P>
<P>
   _ Teachers for Los Angeles Unified School District (average
salary, $44,000): 29,540
</P>
<P>
   _ Boeing 737 jets ($33million each): 39
</P>
<P>
   _ Space shuttle ($2billion each): two-thirds of one
</P>
<P>
   _ James Cameron blockbusters (based on the $200million
``Titanic''): 6.5
</P>
<P>
   _ One-time bonus for every person in Los Angeles: $341.
</P>
