<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6963 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-STUDENT-SORTING-REVIE     06-17 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENT-SORTING-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN TESTING UPSTAGES TEACHING 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 By KATE ZERNIKE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As every child knows, school these days is spelled t-e-s-t:
preparing for them, taking them, passing them _ or else.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the 1990s, American educators, lusting after the
academic successes of European and Japanese schoolchildren,
imported the idea of a rigorous system of tests, which those
countries use to cull the elite from the merely literate. But
educators here insisted that America would instead use testing to
snap schools to attention, forcing them to raise standards for
everyone. They would lift up, not weed out.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the evidence so far suggests that schools here
are doing the very sort of gardening they promised to avoid,
employing tests to sort children, often by the time they are in
grade school.
</P>
<P>
   In several other countries, it is illegal to track students
before they are teen-agers, said Marc Tucker, president of the
National Center on Education and the Economy in Washington. But in
the United States, teachers have decided by the early grades who is
bright and who isn't, giving some students the message that they
will never rise out of the lower track.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the country that has the most vicious tracking system
in the world because we start to do it so young,'' Tucker said.
``The results are far more irrevocable than we will admit to
ourselves. If you've assigned kids in fourth and fifth grade to the
lower rungs of the English ladder, there's no way in the world for
them to become accomplished readers and writers. It creates an
utter disaster in terms of expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder there has been a well-publicized outbreak of cheating.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who think about testing didn't think through the
implications,'' says Philip Altbach, professor of education at
Boston College. ``They just thought, the Europeans are doing this
and they have a good outcome. But what comes along with their
system is an entire baggage of selection.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans, of course, have always tested their students. But the
tests used in decades past _ apart from the SAT, which was never
intended to drive how schools teach _ tested samples or groups of
students. The European or Japanese notion was to test individual
students.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Chicago schools use test scores to hold children back a
grade, an example President Clinton would like to replicate
nationwide. In New York City, tests are used much like SAT cutoff
scores by some competitive middle schools; in other communities,
the scores determine who enters the ``gifted'' track.
</P>
<P>
   The result is what Merry White, a scholar of Japan and a
professor of anthropology at Boston University, calls ``a great
American mixed message.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to say that at any point in life you can make
yourself over, that's part of our ideology,'' she said. ``We're
supposed to believe that getting off track is okay. We had this
idea of equality. But we don't know how to implement it in a
meritocracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of the tests argue that American schools have always
sorted students, and the new tests sort more fairly and more
openly, so that the bald test scores force teachers and parents to
pay attention and demand more from all students.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there is some evidence suggesting that tests may spur
children to perform at higher levels. Scores are up across New York
state in the second year of the fourth-grade reading tests. Texas
offers perhaps the best example. There, scores have gone up
dramatically in the 10 years since the state began publicly
reporting school-by-school scores. With a large state and local
campaign to do better on tests, Texas has begun to shrink the
stubborn test score gap between blacks and whites.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to know, however, what the scores mean. New York
City schools chancellor Harold Levy cautions that the improvement
in his students' scores may simply reflect more familiarity with
the new tests. And even those who applaud the Texas example
question whether those students are really learning at high levels.
</P>
<P>
   William Schmidt, the director of the U.S. branch of the Third
International Math and Science Study, a widely respected survey of
about three dozen nations, has examined dozens of the new state
tests, as well as more traditional tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of reform may be to say do more algebra, but the
tests are pushing basics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that when the United States imported tests, it
did not import the rigorous curriculum that shapes other countries'
schools. Teachers in most states still don't have a clear sense of
what the tests are supposed to be testing, or what constitutes high
achievement. Instead, everyone becomes obsessed with the scores.
</P>
<P>
   That might explain why American students continue to lag in
international comparisons, even as their scores on national tests
improve.
</P>
<P>
   Countries that continue to outperform the United States, Schmidt
said, are teaching the math that Americans learn in the eighth
grade at the fourth and fifth grades.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, they also have well-defined sets of standards
about what students need to learn, which dictate a curriculum that
is narrower, but deeper. That curriculum is tightly tied to the
test, and students are not sorted until the upper grades, by which
time they have been thoroughly schooled in the curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, ``the whole notion has been deformed in
some ways,'' said Sue Bastian, head of Teaching Matters, a group of
former teachers devoted to teacher training. ``The standards which
should have guided us have bowdlerized into standardized tests,''
she said, which are then used to punish low-scoring schools, rather
than improve the curricula or teachers' skills.
</P>
<P>
   The result is essentially the same system as before, only with
more tests squeezing teachers' time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are some people making state policy who think
that teachers have known all along how to raise performance,
they've just been lazy, that all you have to do is raise the bar
and they will do it,'' said Tucker. ``I don't think that's true at
all. All the tests will do is measure kids' performance. But you're
not going to improve performance unless teachers do something
different in the classroom.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 1216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000617.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3609 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-STUDENT-SORTING-REVIE     06-17 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENT-SORTING-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN TESTING UPSTAGES TEACHING 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
