<DOCNO> NYT20000617.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6967 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-MONTENEGRO-REVIEW-NYT     06-17 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTENEGRO-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TROUBLE WITH DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To hear some in NATO talk, Montenegro is the
unsinkable aircraft carrier in the West's unfinished war against
Yugoslavia's president, Slobodan Milosevic. But last week, the
carrier took a few shells from Montenegro's voters, a sizable
minority of whom want to remain inside Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro is the last republic of Tito's Yugoslavia that
remains alongside Serbia in Milosevic's incredible shrinking state.
But Montenegro has barely more than 600,000 people _ a third of
Belgrade's population _ and represents only 5 percent of
Yugoslavia's people.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Milo Djukanovic, its young president, broke away from
Milosevic and barely defeated a Milosevic ally in 1997. He has also
moved sharply toward the West on a platform of virtual and then
eventual independence from an undemocratic Belgrade. He opposed
Milosevic's policies toward Kosovo and then defied him during the
war there a year ago, raising fears that Montenegro could be the
next flashpoint in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But now, an ambiguous election result has reduced the pressure
for Montenegrin independence just when few in NATO have much taste
for another confrontation with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   In local elections last week in the capital, Podgorica, and in
the seaside town of Herceg Novi, Montenegrins split over competing
notions of the republic's future. A coalition called ``For
Yugoslavia,'' which supported Milosevic, won a handy victory in
Herceg Novi, while losing in Podgorica, where Djukanovic is strong.
</P>
<P>
   It's always easy to make too much of local elections, but the
message to American policy-makers was clear: Milosevic has won a
round in fair elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Djukanovic clearly thought he'd get a better result, and he
didn't,'' one senior American official said. ``It's not a disaster,
but it's a signal.''
</P>
<P>
   For Djukanovic and his coalition, it is a clear warning that any
referendum on independence for Montenegro would not win by the kind
of thumping majority that could prevent civil strife. In fact, it
could produce civil war and partition.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important, these deep splits could allow Milosevic and
Belgrade to foment civil strife in Montenegro with a high degree of
deniability, even without a direct use of the Yugoslav military
units that are based there. While the NATO alliance has not
promised to come to Montenegro's aid if Belgrade moves forcibly
against it, NATO leaders have warned Milosevic against doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Senior American officials insist that any effort to move against
Djukanovic with force could have consequences in Belgrade, with new
bombing attacks. But few in NATO want another bombing war after
Kosovo. One senior NATO official said acerbically, ``Kosovo was
such a resounding success that no one in the alliance wants to
repeat it ever again.''
</P>
<P>
   So Djukanovic's awkward limbo continues, with him caught among
competing pressures _ from some supporters to move more briskly
toward independence, from Washington and NATO not to precipitate a
crisis, and from Belgrade aimed at undermining him.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade's pressure is not just political and psychological,
Western and Montenegrin officials insist, but also physical, with
the skillful assassination, 10 days before the vote, of one of
Djukanovic's closest bodyguards. American officials say they have
no evidence of Belgrade's involvement. Still, the assassination
seemed like a message to the Serbian political opposition, too _
one that was underscored by what appeared to be an assassination
attempt on the Serbian opposition figure Vuk Draskovic late
Thursday night in Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vote just puts Djukanovic further into the maze, trying to
chart a middle course, but to where?'' said John Fox, a former
State Department official who specializes in the Balkans. ``This
limbo in which Montenegro is supposed to remain becomes more
difficult and more costly for Djukanovic in political terms.''
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious loser in the election was the Liberal Alliance,
which favors rapid independence and precipitated these elections by
pulling out of a coalition with Djukanovic. But Djukanovic has also
lost, because some significant part of the pro-Yugoslavia vote was
an anti-Djukanovic protest against corruption and arrogance in this
small state where, as in Belgrade, a few people live extremely well
on their political and criminal connections. In small Herceg Novi,
Djukanovic's brother, Aco, is a major figure, and he is widely
disliked for his shady business practices.
</P>
<P>
   But Djukanovic matters to the West. He has provided shelter to
Serbian opposition figures who were afraid for their lives, both
during the war and afterward, as well as to Serbian draft dodgers
during the war. And he has provided a platform for broadcasting
anti-Milosevic material into Serbia. In return, he has received
Western adulation and millions of dollars in aid.
</P>
<P>
   As a part of Yugoslavia, Montenegro can also have an impact on
the fate of the country's president, Milosevic. That is why
American officials _ and much of the Serbian opposition _ are
pressing Djukanovic to take part in federal elections Milosevic
must call by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic has opposed the idea, rejecting the legitimacy of the
currently constituted federal government or Parliament. But the
Americans and the Serbian opposition are convinced that they can
win the elections if Montenegro participates, weakening Milosevic
before next year's crucial parliamentary elections in Serbia. A
Montenegrin boycott, on the other hand, could give Milosevic an
excuse not to have the elections at all.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox thinks the strategy is wrongheaded. Montenegro's
participation would legitimize Milosevic more than undermine him,
he says, and in any event the West should call the elections unfree
and unfair, given the restrictions on the media in Serbia. ``The
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia is already illegitimate and
dysfunctional,'' Fox said. ``And here we are saying to Djukanovic
that we won't talk to the war criminal that heads it but that you
have to participate in his election.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 1225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
