<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6969 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-17 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEADLINES OF THE WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Police Response an Issue After Central Park Attacks
</P>
<P>
   By the end of a turbulent week, the New York City police had
arrested more than a dozen men in connection with the rampage of
sexual assaults in Central Park on June 11.
</P>
<P>
   The incident, which came at the end of the Puerto Rican Day
Parade on Fifth Avenue, was another black eye for the New York
Police Department. More than 30 women came forward to complain of
being attacked by a mob of men who doused them with water and tore
at their clothes, and many of the victims said police officers had
ignored their pleas for help.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani at first played down the complaints, but
after videotapes of the attacks emerged, he promised to investigate
the behavior of the police.
</P>
<P>
   Loophole in Arms Treaty
</P>
<P>
   Administration lawyers have provided President Clinton with a
new legal interpretation of a 1972 arms control treaty with Russia
that could allow him to begin building the first phase of a
national missile defense without violating the accord.
</P>
<P>
   The new interpretation, drafted at the White House's request,
offers a way for Clinton to avoid breaching the Antiballistic
Missile Treaty, a prospect that has already threatened to undercut
relations with Russia and European allies.
</P>
<P>
   The Boss Stirs the Pot
</P>
<P>
   New York City police union leaders urged their members to
boycott concerts by Bruce Springsteen, who has begun performing a
new song about the shooting of Amadou Diallo, the unarmed immigrant
from Guinea who died in a hail of police gunfire last year.
Ignoring the criticism, Springsteen performed the song, ``American
Skin,'' at Madison Square Garden, where he began by singing the
words ``41 shots'' nine times.
</P>
<P>
   Four officers fired 41 shots at Diallo in the vestibule of his
Bronx apartment building. They said they thought he was reaching
for a gun; it turned out to be a wallet. The officers were
acquitted of murder charges earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Oil Prices Soar
</P>
<P>
   It may be a rough summer for vacationers in their campers and
sport utility vehicles. Oil prices shot up to more than $32 a
barrel, amid growing fear that the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries might decide not to lift production when
ministers meet this week in Vienna. OPEC has already discarded an
informal agreement to automatically raise production by 500,000
barrels a day if the 20-day average price climbed above $28.
American motorists are already paying the highest gasoline prices
in a decade; in the Midwest, some gas is selling for more than $2 a
gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Strikes Back
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, in the first part of its appeal of an antitrust
ruling against the company, accused the judge who tried the case,
Thomas Penfield Jackson, of ``an array of serious substantive and
procedural errors that infected virtually every aspect of the
proceedings.'' In its brief, Microsoft asserted that the district
court ``largely suspended application of the federal rules of
evidence, admitting into evidence numerous newspaper and magazine
articles and other rank hearsay.''
</P>
<P>
   Runway Danger Is Seen
</P>
<P>
   In a study of runway safety, the National Transportation Safety
Board cited an increased risk of on-the-ground collisions, and an
increase in the number of times that planes or trucks blunder onto
active runways. The Federal Aviation Administration has plans for a
computer system to provide warnings, but it is 10 years behind
schedule and the board said it was insufficient anyway. The board
proposed procedural changes as a short-term fix, but said those
changes might worsen airport congestion.
</P>
<P>
   Legal Victory for Nixon
</P>
<P>
   Six years after his death, former President Richard Nixon scored
a legal victory. The Justice Department agreed to pay Nixon's
estate $18 million for White House papers, tapes and photographs
seized by Congress after his resignation in 1974. Nixon's
contention that the documents were his personal property was backed
by an appeals court, but critics accused his heirs of profiting
from public papers that implicated the president in obstruction of
justice and other crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Fined $13 Million
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Martin Marietta Aerospace, now part of Lockheed Martin,
provided technical advice to a Hong Kong client that was trying to
solve a problem with China's commercial satellites. To settle civil
charges filed by the State Department, Lockheed Martin agreed to
pay $13 million for failing to get a United States license before
helping the Hong Kong company, which had strong ties to the
government in Beijing. No one knows if the technology helped the
Chinese with their military satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Putin Names Chechen Cleric
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to consolidate Russia's hold on Chechnya, President
Vladimir Putin appointed a Muslim cleric to govern the breakaway
republic. The new leader is Mufti Akhmed Kadyrov, a Chechen who
urged accommodation with Moscow after Russian troops intervened
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Many Chechens, however, resent leaders who have sided with the
Russians, and it will be difficult for Mufti Kadyrov to establish
control. Aslan Maskhadov, the president of Chechnya before the
Russians intervened in 1994, has denounced the mufti as a traitor.
</P>
<P>
   Death Penalty Appeals
</P>
<P>
   When Illinois declared a moratorium on executions recently,
after 13 condemned men were found innocent, some death-penalty
supporters called the state an aberration. It isn't. A new study
found that nationwide, two-thirds of death-penalty convictions over
two decades were overturned on appeal, with 7 percent of the
condemned later found not guilty. And, typically, the appeals
process takes nine years.
</P>
<P>
   Pardon for Papal Gunman
</P>
<P>
   Ceding to Vatican wishes, the Italian government pardoned Mehmet
Ali Agca, the Turkish gunman who tried to kill Pope John Paul II in
1981. The pardon, which came during a Holy Year of the Roman
Catholic Church, did not set Agca free. Agca, who was forgiven long
ago by the pope, was extradited to Turkey, where he faces an
eight-year sentence for the 1979 murder of a Turkish journalist.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 1231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
