<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6970 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-SYRIA-ART-2TAKES-NYT     06-17 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYRIA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSAD'S SON GETTING SYRIAN PARTY'S BLESSING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT8 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SUSAN SACHS c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria _ Syria's Baath Party, the structural support
beneath the 30-year rule of the late Hafez Assad, gathered Saturday
to pledge allegiance to his 34-year-old son, Bashar, and to vest
him formally with the political authority he had quietly exercised
from the shadows in the last two years of his father's illness.
</P>
<P>
   Only the ceremonial start of the Baath congress was open to
outside observers. But in the first few effusive speeches lauding
him, party delegates indicated they were ready to install Assad, an
ophthalmologist by training, as a member of their national
governing board and to endorse him for the job of president.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting of the more than 1,500 delegates is scheduled to
last three days. Assad's nomination would then have to be ratified
by the Parliament, which is overwhelmingly dominated by the Baath
Party, and confirmed in a public referendum in which voters could
say yes or no to his ascension to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Assad's father used to chalk up 99.9 percent of votes in his
re-elections over the last three decades.
</P>
<P>
   The congress, the first in 15 years, was scheduled when the
elder Assad was alive and intended to change his son's status from
unofficial heir apparent to regent by giving him his first formal
party and government titles.
</P>
<P>
   When Hafez Assad died a week ago, apparently of a heart attack,
the party leadership moved quickly to convert the congress into a
vehicle to ratify his son as successor.
</P>
<P>
   Assad, towering over all those who gathered around him during a
break in the proceedings, was mobbed by party officials shoving
each other aside to shake his hand and whisper congratulations in
his ear.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has not held any official position, Assad does not
enter the public spotlight unprepared. Diplomats, Syrian
businessmen and analysts said he had already exercised considerable
control over a number of foreign and domestic policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past two years, he's been acting like the chief of
staff at the White House,'' said a European diplomat who was
summoned several times to Dr. Assad's office for working meetings.
``He wasn't in the line of command, but he made things move.''
</P>
<P>
   Assad's internship as Syria's chief executive officer began with
the forced retirement in July 1998 of his father's longtime aide,
Hikmat Shehabi, the Syrian army chief and first of many influential
old-guard figures to be toppled or ruined by corruption allegations
in the state-run press.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Assad has quietly built a power base by courting the
country's business elite, negotiating with foreign diplomats,
installing allies in the military and intelligence hierarchy,
changing two-thirds of the government ministers to his liking, and
cultivating a public image of openness and probity.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian officials have gone to great pains to insist that Assad
is the spontaneous choice of the public and the party. State-run
television has shown almost nothing but Assad since his father's
death and the party distributed thousands of posters with his
photograph on the eve of the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``The late President Assad was very, very sick in the last two
years, but not once did he say his son should be his successor,''
said Riyad Ghassan Agha, the chief of the presidential political
bureau, in an interview on the Al-Jezeera satellite television
channel. ``Now people have spoken,'' he added. ``Didn't you see all
this support at the funeral for Bashar?''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats in Damascus said the referendum on his presidency
could offer an early sign of whether Assad's style of leadership
will differ much from his father's secretive and authoritarian
rule, which relied on staged rallies, ubiquitous intelligence
agents and state-run propaganda to create a personality cult.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't spend the billions they usually do to promote
the single candidate, that will be a good sign,'' said a Western
diplomat. ``The next sign we will be looking for is if he renovates
the government. There are some ministers who have been there for 30
years. Then, will we know who are his advisers? Under his father
they were never named.''
</P>
<P>
   As president-in-waiting, Assad has already had more intimate
contact with the Syrian public than any previous modern leader by
virtue of the Muslim mourning traditions. For four days he stood
for hours in a receiving line in the village of Qardaha, where his
father was buried, and shook the hands of tens of thousands of
ordinary Syrians who came to offer condolences.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from those who have hovered close to his side and those
he has placed in positions in the military and intelligence
services, Assad may rely even more than his father on members of
his Alawite sect. The Alawites, an offshoot of Shia Islam, are
thought to represent about 10 percent of the Syrian population, but
a far higher percentage of army and security officers.
</P>
<P>
   Assad has relied on Ali Aslan, the chief of staff who replaced
the ousted Shehabi; his brother-in-law Asef Showkat, who holds an
important post that deals with promotions in the military
intelligence branch; and Suleiman Bahgat, head of the domestic
intelligence services. Assad has also been surrounded by friends of
his own age from the politically privileged, including the sons of
high-ranking army and Baath Party officials.
</P>
<P>
   In carefully screened interviews over the last few months, Assad
has expressed interest in bringing Syria, where satellite
television dishes are still officially illegal, into the modern
information age. He has reassured frustrated entrepreneurs in the
country that he sympathizes with their complaints about bureaucrats
who demand bribes, the absence of a private banking system and
murky laws on investment.
</P>
<P>
   Assad would often summon people he wanted to consult to his
office in the hills above Damascus, sending a limousine from the
presidential protocol office to pick them up. One diplomat recalled
that he once complained about corrupt government officials who kept
delaying action on a foreign aid project. Assad, he said,
interrupted briskly to say: ``I understand. You have the same
problems I have.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But now that he is to assume public office, Assad may be limited
in his ability to impose modernization on a hidebound one-party
system that has run the nation's economy and social life for its
own benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Assad will not make the dramatic changes that many Syrians may
expect, predicted Dr. Imad Fawzi Shuebi, a Damascus University
political scientist who said he is close to the Assad family.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not in a hurry,'' Shuebi said, using a phrase often
applied to Assad's father, who moved deliberately. ``Doctor Bashar
will be like a fighter pilot,'' he added. ``A pilot goes out and
makes observations, then returns to go over his possible decisions,
then he collects the reactions, then he thinks, then he observes
again. Then he takes a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   In foreign policy, Assad's options may be especially limited.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus among diplomats and Syrian officials is that, as a
matter of principle and political survival, he cannot be more
flexible than his father on the substantive elements of peace
negotiations. He will insist, they said, that every inch of the
occupied Golan Heights must be returned by Israel to Syria.
</P>
<P>
   On the symbolic components of making peace, according to some of
Assad's acquaintances, he may be capable of bending.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials involved in the negotiating process have long
said that a few friendly gestures and a little warmth _ a
willingness, at least, on the part of Syrians to shake the hands of
their Israeli negotiating partners _ might reassure the Israeli
public that giving up the strategic Golan would bring real peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may see some gesture in a speech from Bashar soon,'' said
a Damascus businessman who grew up with Assad. ``His father was too
proud and too ideological for that, but Bashar is a more open
man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
