<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6973 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-NATIONAL-GUARD-BOSNIA     06-17 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONAL-GUARD-BOSNIA-ART-1220(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL GUARD ADAPTS TO NEW ROLE AS PEACEKEEPER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Colo., Ga.)   A Special Report  
(Eds: An abridged version of this story, slugged
NATIONAL-GUARD-BOSNIA-ABR, is being sent. This is part of an
occasional series about the experiences of the 49th Armored
Division of the Texas National Guard.) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT2, 3 and 4 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAGLE BASE, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ When hunters came across the
wreckage of an aircraft on a remote mountainside in April, Capt.
David B. Webb of the 49th Armored Division of the Texas National
Guard volunteered to join an Air Force team sent to figure out
whose plane it might be.
</P>
<P>
   Webb, an operations officer at the U.S. headquarters here, had
no particular experience in recovery operations, but he had
expertise that even the airmen did not: When not on active duty, he
works in Fort Worth, Texas, for Lockheed Martin, maker of the F-16.
</P>
<P>
   And as it turned out, the wreckage he helped identify was the
F-16 belonging to Capt. Scott O'Grady, the American pilot shot down
on June 2, 1995, during NATO's air raids in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see F-16s every day on the floor,'' said Webb, a 34-year-old
property manager for Lockheed, who has served in the National Guard
for 14 years. ``To see one in pieces when I got to Bosnia was,
well, strange.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, the National Guard and Reserves have had to endure
lingering doubts within the regular Army that their part-time
soldiers have what it takes to carry out important military
operations. But as the Army relies more heavily on Guard and
Reserve units, Guard and Reserve commanders argue that the United
States' citizen-soldiers bring something else that their
active-duty counterparts cannot: experience and skills honed in the
civilian world.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when it comes to peacekeeping operations like the one in
Bosnia, which does not involve direct combat, there are many who
argue that the Guard and Reserve are in fact better prepared for
the subtle tasks of rebuilding a nation devastated by war.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is only a personal opinion, but in the National Guard, we
deal with civilians a little better,'' said Lt. John K. Bahrami, a
computer consultant for IBM and a member of the 49th Armored
Division, who serves in the unit overseeing security at Eagle Base,
the U.S. headquarters near the town of Tuzla. ``We're business
people. We work with people. You don't have that sense they do in
the regular Army that everyone is either a friend or an enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the nearly 650 men and women of the 49th deployed here in
March, its officers have commanded the U.S. peacekeeping mission,
trying to advance a peace that, more than four years after the
fighting stopped, is still struggling to take hold.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time since the Korean War that the Army has
deployed a Guard headquarters overseas and the first time ever that
it has put one in charge of regular Army troops _ in this case,
2,500 soldiers from one of the service's elite cadres, the 3rd
Armored Cavalry Regiment from Fort Carson, Colo., as well as 40
reservists, and nearly 1,000 guardsmen from a dozen states.
</P>
<P>
   Until they mobilized in February, the men and women of the 49th
were computer programmers, teachers, lawyers and laborers _ and
their skills have already paid dividends.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, civilian skills are incidental to the military
mission, as happened with Webb. When the Air Force team arrived at
the wreckage on the remote hillside near the Croatian border, it
was Webb who knew that a stamp on a bulkhead identified it as an
F-16 and a contract number on another part showed that it was a
U.S. Air Force jet.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, the usefulness is by design. Since the Vietnam
era, the Army has deliberately transferred soldiers with specific
skills to the Reserve, especially doctors and nurses, press
officers and civil affairs specialists who serve as liaisons to
local communities. These reservists are among the busiest in the
Army today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Show me where the Army has an investment banker or someone who
runs an electrical grid,'' said Brig. Gen. Bruce B. Bingham, a
reservist who is commander of the Army's Civil Affairs and
Psychological Operations Command and partner in the accounting firm
BDO Seidman in New York. ``We bring civilian skills that the Army
doesn't have.''
</P>
<P>
   By the measures that matter most to the Army and the Pentagon _
avoiding casualties and keeping a lid on sporadic eruptions of
violence _ the 49th's mission has so far been a success. But the
49th is also winning praise from unexpected quarters, including
critics of the U.S. operation who credit the National Guard with
bringing a civilian sensibility to what has been a solely military
mission.
</P>
<P>
   The 49th's commander, Maj. Gen. Robert L. Halverson, who served
as deputy commissioner of insurance for Texas before retiring when
the deployment order came, has made his highest priority the return
of Bosnia's refugees to their homes. One of the most difficult
areas is the village of Srebrenica, where Serbian soldiers drove
out the Muslim population and killed as many as 8,000 men.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to help clear the way for Srebrenica's former residents
to return, Halverson sent the division's chief engineer, Col. Larry
N. Patterson, to inspect the city's damaged water system. It was no
coincidence that Patterson, when not on active duty, is the
assistant director of the Water Utilities Department of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of cooperation from Serbian workers, he
inspected the plant and was able to determine the purification
process that the plant once used, when he spotted a discarded
chemical control panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me who else could walk beside that water treatment plant
and look at a piece of metal trash lying in the weeds and recognize
it as a chemical control panel,'' Halverson said in a recent
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson has served in the Texas National Guard ever since he
graduated from the Reserve Officers Training Corps program at Texas
A&AMP;M University in 1972, rising through the ranks as an officer and
as an engineer in the water utility industry. He had little idea
his experience in providing water for nearly 2 million people in
Dallas would come in handy in a place like Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Within days of his visit to the plant, however, Patterson
outlined what the plant would need to produce minimally potable
water and what it would cost _ $266,701, he estimated.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is for Patterson to try to coordinate the
necessary repairs by meeting with officials in charge of the
civilian aspects of the Dayton peace accords, as well as with other
military engineers and representatives of aid agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like going to a city council meeting back home,''
Patterson said, reaching back to his civilian life for the right
explanation. ``You have 15 different districts, and they all have
competing interests. Hopefully, we can get something done.
Everybody wants to do something for Srebrenica.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Pentagon, the success or failure of the 49th's mission
will shape overseas operations for years.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Cold War, the National Guard was held in reserve.
Its units _ serving under the command of the governors of 50
states, the District of Colombia and three territories _ evolved
into a distinct force, separate and unequal. Guardsmen were
activated more often for natural disasters than for military
operations, leading to derision from full-time soldiers and
commanders.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the pace of military operations has increased, from the
Balkans to the Persian Gulf, the Army plans to turn more and more
to its 564,000 reservists and guardsmen to relieve the strain on
its nearly 480,000 regular troops.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Bosnia, as in other operations, the Army is planning to
increase the participation of Guard units. Today, the Guard and
Reserve constitute nearly a quarter of the U.S. troops in Bosnia;
by 2003, nearly two-thirds of the troops here will be part-time
citizen-soldiers, called up for nine months at a time.
</P>
<P>
   While the 49th largely provides the headquarters staff at the
main U.S. base, the next rotations will include operation units,
which officials say will become a greater test of the Guard's
contribution. Those units include the 48th Infantry Brigade from
Georgia, a unit that was activated during the Persian Gulf War but
was then deemed by Army commanders to be unprepared for combat in
the desert.
</P>
<P>
   A new study by the General Accounting Office noted significant
improvements in training of brigades like the 48th, but said that
many of them still faced shortfalls in combat readiness.
</P>
<P>
   For the 49th, the assignment here has been a chance to prove the
Guard's abilities after it sat on the sidelines for decades. And
they point to achievements like Webb's and Patterson's.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't just any mission for us,'' said Col. Garry D.
Patterson, the division's chief of staff and Larry Patterson's twin
brother. ``We felt like we had to make a mark on the wall for the
ones that are going to follow us.''
</P>
<P>
   The performance of the 49th appears to have impressed not just
Army commanders but also critics of the U.S. presence in Bosnia
since NATO troops arrived in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Lyon, the Bosnia director of the International Crisis
Group, a private foundation that has sharply criticized
developments since the Dayton accord, credits the National Guard
for changing the tenor of the U.S. operations. With the war over,
he said, the biggest challenge in Bosnia is not separating armies
but working more actively with the local governments and
international organizations that in effect make Bosnia tick.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 49th arrived, Lyon said he had seen a greater
coordination with international organizations and local
governments, as well as increased foot patrols in tense villages,
despite an overall reduction in U.S. troops from 6,900 two years
ago to today's level of 4,200.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish the National Guard had come in 1996,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
