<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, June 18, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A wavering front in the Middle Atlantic states will bring bouts
of showers and thunderstorms Sunday as low pressure moves east
along the front. Some places will receive numerous showers, with
daily totals exceeding one inch in spots. Farther south, showers
and thunderstorms will once again develop in the Southeastern
states, although the heaviest concentration will be in the
Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   As moist air begins to flow to the north across the Texas
panhandle and eastern New Mexico, isolated strong thunderstorms
will develop during the afternoon and early evening. Meanwhile,
showers will develop near coastal Texas as thunderstorms form where
a sea breeze front undercuts and lifts warm, humid air.
</P>
<P>
   An area of low pressure moving into the Rockies will yield
showers, especially on the high peaks. Much of the West will turn
slightly cooler, though the deserts will remain hot.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: ROCHESTER'S RAIN
</P>
<P>
   The rain this month in Rochester, Minn., is reaching historic
proportions. The month began with a deluge of 4.81 inches.
Recurrent rain since then has brought the total rainfall to 10.05
inches making this month the second wettest June on record in
Rochester. Jet stream winds have remained unusually strong over the
northern tier of states. On several occasions, disturbances in the
vigorous jet stream have combined with plumes of moist air from the
south, to produce clusters of thunderstorms with copious rain. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
