<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7013 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ZIMBABWE-POLITICS-NYT     06-17 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMBABWE'S LEADER TRIES TO BOLSTER ELECTION SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ A week before fiercely contested
parliamentary elections, President Robert Mugabe on Saturday urged
thousands of flag-waving, cheering supporters to keep the peace as
they rally behind the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe blamed opposition party members for provoking the
violence that in recent months has claimed at least 26 lives and
left more than 150 people wounded, most of them black supporters of
the new party, the Movement for Democratic Change. ``We don't want
to break the law,'' he said. ``We want the people to go and vote in
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   He reminded his supporters that the ruling party had led the
country to political independence and he promised that it would
continue to fight for the people by redistributing white-owned
commercial farms to blacks and by reinstituting price controls on
basic food stuffs.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that the battle ahead would not be easy,
particularly here in the capital, where residents have grown weary
of promises of a better future amid chronic fuel shortages,
skyrocketing inflation and official corruption.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a survey of 6,000 voters conducted by the Public
Opinion Institute here suggested that the opposition would win 70
of the 120 parliamentary seats up for grabs. Officials from the
ruling party, which currently controls all but three seats in
Parliament, quickly dismissed the survey as biased.
</P>
<P>
   But as Mugabe stood behind the microphone in his charcoal suit
overlooking the crowd in the sports field here, it was clear that
his support had waned. Despite the availability of free transport
and the heavy publicity surrounding the rally, which is expected to
be the president's last major address in the capital before the
vote, the field stood nearly half empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should remain united,'' he urged. ``The revolution
continues to the very end.''
</P>
<P>
   The elections, to be held over two days next weekend, represent
the toughest challenge that the ruling party, ZANU-PF, has ever
faced. In February, the party suffered its first major defeat since
independence 20 years ago when voters rejected a draft constitution
that would have expanded the president's powers and enabled him to
seize land from white farmers without compensation.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in Zimbabwe's history, opposition candidates
are contesting all of the 120 parliamentary seats up for grabs and
some ruling party officials have conceded that they will probably
lose their near-total grip on power after a heated and often
violent campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International, the human rights group, and other foreign
observers say the government has either instigated or condoned the
political violence in an effort to hold power, dismissing the
claims of Mugabe and other ruling party officials, who blame the
opposition for most attacks.
</P>
<P>
   And in recent days, the ruling party has seemingly responded to
the barrage of criticism. On television and in the state-controlled
press, government officials have repeatedly denounced violence. The
state-controlled media has offered air-time to the new opposition
movement, which is routinely derided as puppets of whites on
television and radio. And officials have also vowed to accept the
result of the vote, whatever the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the very unlikely event that ZANU-PF is defeated, we will
accept the result in the same way as we accepted the result over
the draft constitution,'' said John Nkomo, the campaign manager for
the ruling party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
