<HEADER>
A7017 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-ART-49     06-17 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-ART-495&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTY DIFFERENCES ON MEDICARE DRUG BENEFITS CONTINUE TO GROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the House about to begin two weeks of intense
debate over competing proposals to add prescription drug benefits
to Medicare, the differences between President Clinton and
Republicans in Congress are widening by the day.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare drug benefits have emerged as one of the more potent
political issues in this year's elections, as lawmakers and
candidates continually hear voters complain about high drug costs.
Both parties say their goal is to make drug coverage available and
affordable to Medicare beneficiaries in every corner of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans want more choices and options for beneficiaries,
a larger role for private insurance companies, a smaller role and
lower costs for the government.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, by contrast, want more uniformity in premiums and
benefits. They say the Republicans' free-market approach will
confuse beneficiaries and encourage insurers to seek out healthy
customers with relatively low drug costs, a practice known as
cherry-picking.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Thomas of California, the architect of the House
Republican bill, said Republicans would push it through the Ways
and Means Committee this week, with a view to securing passage by
the full House by the July 4 recess.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats are planning a major assault on the legislation.
Indeed, they rehearsed their arguments at congressional hearings
last week, before details of the legislation were disclosed. Their
strongest argument is simply that the Republican bill will not
work, will not draw many private insurers into the market and
therefore will not provide reliable coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican proposal assumes that insurers can be induced to
offer drug coverage subsidized by the government, just as health
maintenance organizations have been induced to sign contracts with
the government to care for 6.2 million Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked if insurers would be interested in offering drug
coverage under Thomas' bill, Charles N. Kahn III, president of the
Health Insurance Association of America, said: ``No, I don't think
so. They would not sell insurance exclusively for drug costs. The
government may find some private entities to administer drug
benefits, but the government would have to accept all or nearly all
of the financial risk.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton would offer the same drug benefits to all 39
million people on Medicare. House Republicans, by contrast, would
describe a model insurance policy, known as ``standard coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Insurers could offer alternative policies, with different
premiums and benefits, provided the value was equivalent to that of
the standard coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans oppose a ``one size fits all'' drug plan.
Beneficiaries, they say, should be able to choose a plan tailored
to their needs.
</P>
<P>
   But Nancy-Ann Min DeParle, administrator of the Health Care
Financing Administration, which runs Medicare, said elderly people
could be confused if they had a large number of choices.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It's difficult for seniors to navigate among plans,'' DeParle
said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, DeParle asked: ``Do seniors want and need all these
choices? If you let plans design all sorts of benefit packages,
that promotes choice, but it also promotes cherry-picking of the
healthiest seniors. That's why we need defined benefits. Seniors
want to know what's covered. It must be predictable.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said DeParle had apparently not read their bill.
Under the legislation, premiums and benefits would be subject to
approval by Medicare officials. And the government could terminate
its contract with any insurer that ``engaged in activities intended
to result in favorable selection'' of beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats fear that the market for drug insurance would be
filled with turmoil as insurers went in and out from year to year.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, dozens of HMOs have pulled out of
Medicare or curtailed their participation, disrupting insurance
arrangements for more than 700,000 elderly people, and more health
plans are expected to withdraw this year.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans refer to their bill as a bipartisan proposal
because two Democrats, Reps. Collin C. Peterson of Minnesota and
Ralph M. Hall of Texas, signed up as co-sponsors when Thomas
introduced the bill on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the measure, a Republican initiative, is strenuously opposed
by many Democrats, who say drug benefits should be fully integrated
into Medicare, like coverage of hospital care and doctors'
services.
</P>
<P>
   The bill says Medicare officials must ensure that every
beneficiary has a choice of at least two plans providing
prescription drug coverage. One could be an HMO; at least one must
be a traditional insurer.
</P>
<P>
   But, Democrats say, even if beneficiaries have two options, both
may be high-price plans.
</P>
<P>
   Under the House Republican proposal, Medicare officials could
offer financial incentives to get insurers to enter markets in
which no drug plans were available. The purpose of such incentives,
as described in the bill, is to guarantee access to coverage.
</P>
<P>
   But Chris Jennings, the health policy coordinator at the White
House, said the availability of these incentives would encourage
insurers to hold out for more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would encourage insurers to hold Medicare hostage,''
Jennings said. ``The policy says that if insurers don't participate
in the marketplace, we'll give them more money. Now, if you're an
insurer, when do you decide to participate in the market? Is it at
the beginning, when you get less money? If you hold out a little
longer, you might get more. This is the most inefficient,
ridiculous incentive mechanism one can imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicare generally does not cover drugs for people outside the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Drug spending for the elderly, from all sources including
private insurance and the patients themselves, is unevenly
distributed, and that complicates efforts to create new drug
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office says that 13 percent of Medicare
beneficiaries have no drug costs, while 57 percent have costs of
less than $1,000 a year. Only 5 percent of beneficiaries have costs
exceeding $5,000 a year, but they account for 29 percent of total
spending on drugs for Medicare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Republicans agree that drug coverage should be
voluntary. Rep. Greg Ganske, R-Iowa, said he worried that ``only
sick seniors will sign up,'' while those with low drug costs would
not see insurance as a good buy.
</P>
<P>
   Under the ``standard coverage'' envisioned in the House
Republican plan, the beneficiary would pay an annual $250
deductible and 50 percent of the next $2,100 in drug costs.
</P>
<P>
   Most patients would then become responsible for their drug
expenses, but the beneficiary's out-of-pocket costs would be
limited to $6,000 a year. The government would pay costs above that
level, with a small contribution by private insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders hope to pick up support from some moderate
Democrats, but they may also lose some conservative Republicans,
who oppose the expansion of federal programs. Rep. Tom Coburn,
R-Okla., said he would vote against Thomas' bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are adding new benefits to a program that is bankrupt from
an actuarial point of view,'' said Coburn, a family physician.
``Maybe the American people want us to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans would create a new agency in the Department of
Health and Human Services to negotiate with drug plans and HMOs.
Republicans say the existing Medicare agency is a heavy-handed
regulator that stifles competition by setting prices for thousands
of medical goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Sherrod Brown, D-Ohio, said the Republicans were simply
``manufacturing a new bureaucracy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 1339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000617.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7021 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-JANITORS-MOVIE-NYT &LR;      06-17 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JANITORS-MOVIE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM CHRONICLES STRUGGLE BY JANITORS FOR BETTER TREATMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds. No Byline) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What kind of movie premiere is held in
midafternoon, without a foot of red carpet in sight and with most
of the audience wearing the same outfit? A premiere that knows its
target audience, most of whom had to get to work by 5:30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bread and Roses,'' a film portraying the local janitors'
struggle for better pay and benefits, was screened on Thursday for
nearly 250 of the people who had inspired it. Dressed in bright red
T-shirts emblazoned with ``Justice for Janitors,'' the workers
arrived in busloads, carrying mops and brooms and shouting their
slogan, ``Si se puede!'' (``Yes, it can be done.'')
</P>
<P>
   Entering the theater, they passed within yards of the high rises
of Century City, the complex of office towers and shops where a
strike resulted in a riot between the police and janitors 10 years
ago. It was also here, in April, that a strike brought many of the
janitors above-poverty wages and health care benefits for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so important that this is happening today in Century
City,'' said Rocio Saenz, an organizer for the Service Employees
International Union, which represents 8,500 janitors. For the
organizers, June 15 has become Justice for Janitors Day, in
recognition of the organizing efforts that grew out of the clash in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bread and Roses,'' directed by the British filmmaker Ken
Loach, features a fictional group of downtown janitors. Many of the
janitors at the screening worked as extras in the film, or inspired
the screenplay by Paul Laverty, a Scottish-born writer who spent
six years following their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The script switches constantly between English and Spanish, and
many members of the audience used hand-held translators to help
them catch every word. At several points, people in the crowd
shouted and laughed when they recognized themselves on the screen,
or when the janitors got the better of the building owners.
</P>
<P>
   But other moments struck a less celebratory chord.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scene when the supervisor fired some of the workers for
organizing, that really hit home for me,'' said Rosa Ayala, who has
worked in a building in downtown Los Angeles for 11 years. Ayala,
who was in the background of several scenes, shook a large plastic
baby bottle filled with coins instead of clapping her hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottle is a symbol of justice for me because it shows how
our money can go to feed our children,'' Ayala said.
</P>
<P>
   This preview audience also had no shortage of critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie left out big chunks of a lot of the hard work that
goes on,'' said Aida Cardenas, who led picket lines in Century City
during the recent strike.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, the reception was enthusiastic.
Estela Aldana, who has attended strikes ``all over L.A., and in
Oakland and San Jose,'' left with a big smile on her face. ``I was
in many, many scenes,'' she said proudly.
</P>
<P>
   The janitors' emotional response echoed that of an audience at
the Cannes Film Festival last month. There the screening came only
weeks after the Los Angeles strike, a coincidence not lost on Tom
Ortenberg, co-president of Lions Gate Films, the U.S. distributor
of the film, and a one-time political organizer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been looking my entire career for a picture like this,''
Ortenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Ortenberg, whose company sponsored the screening along with the
Service Employees Union, said that ``Bread and Roses'' was
scheduled for nationwide release in February, and added that the
janitors and other community groups would share in box office
receipts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no other way. We have to give some of the proceeds
back to the community,'' Ortenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the film's message of ``it can be done,'' the producers
and filmmakers said they hope to spread the word to an audience
much broader than labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really important that people should believe the film and
know the success of your campaign,'' Loach told the janitors after
the lights came up. ``And there's no better way to do that than to
have the real people on the screen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
