<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7032 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BOOKS-WALKER0618-COX     06-17 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-WALKER0618-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Walker tells the story of his gypsy songwriting life
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Singer/Songwriter Jerry Jeff Walker was born and
spent his early years in a small upstate New York town. While still
in his teens, he traveled across country many items, stopping along
the way in such diverse places as Key West, Florida, New Orleans
and Greenwich Village, Manhattan. At each stopover, he learned new
songs, new ways to sing them and new guitar licks to stir into his
developing style as a ``songman.''
</P>
<P>
   The songs he wrote as he traveled tell the story of his life and
way of living and making music. Now, he's written this book that
fills in the details. It's a fascinating tale, whether or not you
are a Jerry Jeff fan.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently you had to look real close to catch a hint of why
young Ronald Clyde Crosby, which was his name in those days, turned
into Jerry Jeff Walker the gypsy songman. But that's what he did,
starting in his late teens when he might have been in college. You
would have had to look very close and be very insightful to see
that kind of future for young Ronald Clyde because, as Jerry Jeff
puts it: ``it was an Ozzie and Harriet life for me. Tuna sandwiches
and Oreo cookies after school. Crewcut boys riding thick tired
bicycles with old playing cards chattering in the spokes. Shooting
hoops in the backyard until dark. I had free run of the
neighborhood. No fences between the neighbor's back yards. so it
was one big playground.''
</P>
<P>
   He started borrowing a neighbor's guitar and that Christmas his
grandmother bought it for him.
</P>
<P>
   And so he wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``And I was lucky. 'Cause I used her gift
</P>
<P>
   To get in touch with how to live
</P>
<P>
   And looking back I realize
</P>
<P>
   Music changed my life
</P>
<P>
   Yes, music filled a void in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   He began hanging around a pizza joint downtown where
neighborhood kids too young for bars and night life would talk and
sing with the jukebox. A man named Jim Mosca owned the place. he
was a big lumbering man, who played guitar and ``sang
beautifully,'' as Jerry Jeff recalls him.
</P>
<P>
   After listening to young Jerry's early attempts at playing the
guitar Mosca gave him a ukulele, much easier to play, and taught
him a few chords.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he didn't acquire the name Jerry Jeff Walker until
some time later, after he wound up in New Orleans' French Quarter
as a street singer, picking and singing on street corners for tips.
He hung out there with other street singers, learning new guitar
licks and songs and beginning to write more of his own songs. He
liked the name Jeff and had become known in New Orleans as Jerry
Ferris. The name Walker was partly as a tribute to Kirby Walker, a
colorful black jazz pianist who had befriended him many times by
calling him up from the crowd to sing with him.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his best stories, episodes, are set in new Orleans,
where he met many legendary street singers, some who went on to
become nationally known and some who didn't. It was there that he
wrote ``Little Bird'' and ``Drifting Way of Life,'' and started
singing them and others he had written along with the folk songs
that had made up his program exclusively for awhile.
</P>
<P>
   He spent time in Dallas, performing mostly at the old Rubiate,
where he often played with harmonica virtuoso Donny Brooks and
added a neck-mounted harmonica to his own act.
</P>
<P>
   He wound up in Austin because, as he once told a radio audience,
``the roads going out of Austin go everywhere and the roads from
everywhere come to Austin,'' or something like that. Pure Jerry
Jeff reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   He formed his own band in Austin, the Lost Gonzo band, bought a
house, met an Austin girl named Susan Streit, got married and more
or less settled down, after a fairly brief adjustment period. To
quote from Bud Shrake's foreword: ``The beautiful Susan turned out
to have a hard head for numbers and a powerful personality. She
gets what she wants, and one thing she wants is for her husband to
thrive.''
</P>
<P>
   And the rest is, if not history, then widely known in the crazy
world of country/pop/folk/cow jazz music. To quote again from
Shrake's foreword, ``Jerry Jeff does his own music as he desires
it. And when a fan buys an album through the catalog or over the
internet, it is bought from Jerry Jeff and Susan, not from a mogul
in Los Angeles or Nashville. Jerry Jeff is now a troubadour with a
big database.''
</P>
<P>
   I've known Jerry Jeff for years and many people have asked me
where in this world he came from, for gosh sakes. Now I know and
you can too, by reading his new book, aptly titled ``Gypsy
Songman.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
