<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN0618-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dads teach kids to take their place
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There was something about my husband bending over the
rain gauge after a recent sprinkle _ not enough rain to call it a
shower _ that reminded me of his dad. The only difference in their
anxious reactions during a drought is John yells back at the
Weather Channel, while W.T. Ezzard surely would have blamed the
Farmer's Almanac.
</P>
<P>
   If John were growing vegetables on the North Georgia farm as his
dad used to do, he could anticipate an even worse summer than with
the vineyard he's cultivating on the same land. Grapes like dry
weather, although not to the extreme the Southeast is experiencing
just now.
</P>
<P>
   The farm boy in my husband has been the subject of family humor
for years _ years when he and I were raising three children in the
city. Even then, he insisted that Shelly, Lisa and John Jr. learn
how to make squash mounds, tend tomato plants and hoe a few rows of
corn in a backyard garden. They complained at times, but as they
grew up, they came to appreciate the joy of growing things. It was
only lately, though, that the children and I really understood how
strong the link was between farm work and the lessons John's dad
passed on to him.
</P>
<P>
   My father-in-law died three years ago, but recently we stumbled
upon some faded military postcards in the back of an old family
scrapbook. They were written when John's father was in North Africa
during World War II. Aimed at encouraging a young boy to be good
and do his chores without a dad to oversee him, the postcards speak
powerful messages in simple words. They were sent in 1943 when
John, the oldest son, was 6 years old:
</P>
<P>
   Dear John,
</P>
<P>
   Your daddy is having a good time living in a tent with three
other fellows. It has been mighty cold here though. How is your
garden doing? Fine I am sure. You will have to take Daddy's place
around the place for a while so you want to learn managing things.
Be a good boy and say your prayers every night. _ Love, Daddy
</P>
<P>
   Dearest John,
</P>
<P>
   How is daddy's fine boy by now? I am anxious to receive a letter
from you. You should be a regular farmer by the time Daddy gets
home! How is your red calf? She should be a big cow by now. Also
your garden is doing well, I hope. It won't be long until you are
old enough to be a 4H Club member. Take good care of Lucy, Henry
and Joanne (John's siblings) and give them my love. _ Your Daddy
</P>
<P>
   There were a few special cards before Christmas and birthdays.
No matter the occasion, though, there were always the lines about
tending the garden, learning to be a real farmer, taking daddy's
place. Just in case.
</P>
<P>
   Dear John,
</P>
<P>
   Wish I could be there with you for your birthday, but I guess
that is impossible this year. Anyway, it makes me feel good to know
that my big boy is growing up to be a young man who is capable of
taking a place in the world. Hope you will always be as good a man
as you are a boy. . . . That was a good picture of you hoeing in
the garden. I wish I had some more like it. All the gardens over
here are dried up now. _ Love, Daddy.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was wounded in the war, John's dad made it home to
the family and the farm he loved. But the letters he wrote might
have been written today by any caring dad to a son, although in the
context of a much different lifestyle. Whether driving a tractor or
surfing the Internet, playing baseball or studying the stock
market, dads are still at it _ passing on the ``how-tos'' to their
sons.
</P>
<P>
   The timeless message lives on for the Ezzard sons, as it does
for a lot of others: You will have to take Daddy's place around the
place.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
