<P>
   DAYTON HEARTLAND POLITICAL PROJECT
</P>
<P>
   HEARTLAND-MAIN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ When national Republicans gather
Monday in Dayton to talk about improving Social Security and the
nation's schools, they'll be trying to get the attention of voters
like Dayton elementary school principal Gwen Jarvis. Jarvis is
among thousands of undecided voters across Ohio, Pennsylvania,
Michigan and Illinois whose support both Republican Gov. George W.
Bush and Democrat Al Gore need to win the presidency. Those four
states from the industrial heartland are the biggest prizes among a
handful of states that both parties consider competitive
battlegrounds in their efforts to gather the 270 electoral votes
necessary to get to the White House. Together the four states
account for 84 electoral votes. The states are known for farms that
grow corn and soybeans and for factories that turn out steel and
automobiles, but they also regularly determine the winners in close
presidential elections. ``The South and Mountain West have
basically been conceded to Bush, and California and New York have
basically been conceded to Gore, so the heartland states like Ohio
are it for these two guys,'' said Allan Lichtman, history
department chairman at American University in Washington, D.C.
(Hershey/Wagner, Dayton Daily News). 80. MOVED Friday in (a)
General News categories and (p) Politics.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   HEARTLAND-SWING _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The battle in the heartland is
really a battle for ``swing voters.'' These are people who haven't
enthusiastically backed one candidate or the other. To get an idea
of who these voters are, here are four mini-profiles of the kinds
of voters who will likely tip the balance in November: Demonica
Sikes, a 22 year-old community college student from Michigan, voted
for McCain; in November she says she'll probably vote for Gore but
will plug her nose. (Hershey, Dayton Daily News). 6-8. WITH PHOTO.
MOVED Friday in (a) General News categories and (p) Politics.
</P>
<P>
   HEARTLAND-UNDECIDED _ CLEVELAND _ Jim Hamulock, a mailman in a
Hispanic neighborhood in Cleveland, says if the economy is so good,
people should follow him on his route. He is undecided about who
he'll vote for. (Wagner, Dayton Daily News). 6-8. MOVED Friday in
(a) General News categories and (p) Politics.
</P>
<P>
   HEARTLAND-FARMER _ WILL TWP. Ill. _ Will Twp. (Ill.) farmer
Everett Schurman is a 70-year-old Republican who will lose his
farmland in favor of the proposed new airport in Peotone, southwest
of Chicago. Has always voted Republican, but this year he's not so
sure. A Republican administration will likely approve the airport,
he thinks, robbing Schurman of his land. (Bebbington, Dayton Daily
News). 6-8.
</P>
<P>
   HEARTLAND-STEELWORKER _ Profile of a steelworker from
Pennsylvania. (Montgomery, Dayton Daily News). 6-8. MOVED Friday in
(a) General News categories and (p) Politics.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SIDE_ DAYTON, Ohio _ He may not be on the ballot this
year, but President Clinton draws stronger reactions from many
voters across the heartland states than do either Democrat Al Gore
or Republican George W. Bush. (Hershey, Dayton Daily News). MOVED
Friday in (a) General News categories and (p) Politics.
</P>
