<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   EZZARD-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ There was something about my husband
bending over the rain gauge after a recent sprinkle _ not enough
rain to call it a shower _ that reminded me of his dad. The only
difference in their anxious reactions during a drought is John
yells back at the Weather Channel, while W.T. Ezzard surely would
have blamed the Farmer's Almanac. (Ezzard, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Tom Teepen writes about the 527s,
special-interest political players who raise and spend literally
untold millions secretly and who are named for the tax-code section
that provides the loophole for them. They can retain their
anonymity as long as they pull up just short of directly urging the
election or defeat of a specific candidate. (Tom Teepen is national
correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ If Cuban exiles want to declare war on Fidel
Castro, they should not fight that war in the United States and TV
ads should not be their weapon. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service.)
MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ It seems that in every U.S. election
cycle, pundits pluck out a group of voters for in-depth study who
are said to be in flux. In the 1996 race for the White House,
President Clinton was widely seen as winning out with so-called
``soccer moms'' _ shorthand for married middle-class women with
young children seeking to juggle competing demands. This time
around, so-called ``wired workers'' have taken an early lead in the
media contest to see who will emerge as the key group of ``swing
voters.'' (Glass, Cox News Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   FATHERS-DAY _ I have done the math and the math does not lie. At
age 62 _ my age _ my father suffered his first serious illness. It
happened on an early-spring morning in 1954, the day we were to
take the mules and the turning plows and begin to plow the fields
for planting. Tedious work, yet, in my memory, good work. The
slicing of the ground, rolled over to the right of the plow-blade,
leaving ripples. At day's end it was pleasing to lean against the
crossbar of the plow handles and see the evenness of the ripples,
and to breathe in the winter dampness of the dirt _ a scent like
rain closing in over distant pine stands. We did not make it to the
fields that morning. (Kay, Atlanta Journal-Constitution freelancer;
not for use by NYTNS clients). 48. WITH ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   JAZZ-CAMP _ BIRMINGHAM - The neck of his Fender Jazz Bass seems
almost too long for Jason Turner. He squeezes down the note for a
blues arrangement, looking as if he were holding a dance partner
too tall for him. Turner has played bass for just a year. But the
13-year-old has rhythm. During an improve class at the 11th-annual
City Stages summer jazz camp, he is rhythm. With nearly 100 other
summer campers, Turner is learning how to swing. Professional
musicians are training aspiring jazz artists who will perform today
(Saturday) at a downtown music festival. You see, this is your
grandmother's jazz. Dixieland. Blues. It's the smoking riffs built
in the Deep South in the early 1900s. This is the stuff of Louis
Armstrong, John Coltrane, Miles Davis, Ella Fitzgerald. This is not
the commercial fluff from, say, Kenny G. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15. MOVED Friday in (a) General News and (l)
Lifestyles categories.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   OREGON-TRAIL _ Westward ho! _ driving the 1,930-mile Oregon
Trail, stretching from Independence, Mo., to Oregon's Willamette
River Valley. For those who go for history, particularly Western
history, the Oregon Trail remains a fascinating trip. The route
crosses enough diverse landscapes _ many of them dizzyingly sublime
_ to make the journey across this pioneering American route, even
now, worth taking. (Chaffin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution
freelancer; not for use by NYTNS clients.)
</P>
