u i BC-RUSSIA-POLITICAL-SATI     06-17 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICAL-SATIRE-1110(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV'S IMPIOUS PUPPETS: ON KREMLIN'S HIT LIST? 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In what looks to many here like a twilight struggle
over the future of free speech, the Kremlin has handed one
journalist over to Chechen guerrillas, demanded that newspapers
obtain federal licenses and, on Tuesday, put Russia's leading press
baron in a notoriously louse-ridden prison.
</P>
<P>
   But the litmus test of the Kremlin's intentions may be whether
it tries to crack down on a bunch of grotesque, legless latex
dolls.
</P>
<P>
   The dolls _ a jug-eared, sheep-eyed President Vladimir Putin;
his Rasputin-esque staff chief, Alexander Voloshin; dead-on
renditions of balding communists, woolly-headed right-wingers and
other famous rogues _ are the cast of ``Kukly,'' which wrapped up
its weekly filming late Thursday on a ramshackle sound stage near
the Moscow River.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kukly'' is political satire. But that is like calling a beaver
a rodent. By turns vicious, obscene, hilarious and knowing, it has
long been the most popular television show in Russia. At 10 p.m. on
any given Sunday, more than half the nation's sets are riveted on
the program.
</P>
<P>
   No one would be surprised to see that share jump even higher
this Sunday. Because the press baron whom the Kremlin jailed last
week, Vladimir A. Gusinsky, owns the NTV television network that
produces ``Kukly.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is a growing sense _ not least among the program's
staff _ that the rubbery stars are on a collision course with
whoever actually holds power inside the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to find the limits of freedom of expression here, and
show those limits to others,'' Grigory Petrovich Lyubomirov, a
writer and director of the program, said between breaks in filming.
``Because we have something to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lived 10 years under conditions of freedom here. And I
don't want to turn back to what was.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kukly'' regularly tests those limits. American television may
be saturated with sex and violence, but it is doubtful that New
York's corporate suits would swallow hard enough to broadcast some
of the program's most memorable political jabs.
</P>
<P>
   One, broadcast last winter, was built around a drive by Putin's
puppet down Moscow's glitziest avenue, Tverskaya Street, where he
rated major politicians. Tame enough _ except that the drive began
at Russia's Parliament, shown as a high-class bawdy house, and the
street politicians that Putin's puppet was rating were cast as
cheap prostitutes bidding to join the orgy that was his
presidential bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kukly's'' account of the politicians' charms, from
sadomasochism to virginity, cannot be fully described, at least not
in this space. But any Russian who saw the program knew precisely
what was meant.
</P>
<P>
   A famous ``Kukly'' from 1995 skewered the government's new
$10-a-month minimum wage by casting former President Boris Yeltsin
and his prime minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin, as drunken street
bums, sifting through trash to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Other episodes have cast top political figures as criminals on a
Siberian prison train and tell-all guests in a Russian version of a
Ruth Westheimer sex show. Putin was cast early as a surgeon on the
Russian body politic, armed with hatchet and blowtorch. He was
reportedly infuriated when the program adapted a German fairy tale
to depict him as a self-indulgent, tantrum-throwing infant.
</P>
<P>
   Such slights might be more easily borne if the effect were not
enhanced, sometimes outlandishly, by the puppets, which are made in
France from sculpted caricatures. The amazingly lifelike dolls are
usually operated by two actors, each of whom contributes an arm,
while dividing mouth movements, blinking and other tasks between
them.
</P>
<P>
   It is no surprise that ``Kukly'' has been in hot water before.
</P>
<P>
   Lyubomirov, a ponytailed, 46-year-old philosopher who attended
the same St. Petersburg university as Putin, said producers used to
get calls from Yeltsin's wife and daughters _ asking not for gentle
political treatment but instead that the president not be depicted
as so feeble.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is less generous to Yeltsin: His chief prosecutor
began a criminal inquiry into ``Kukly'' in 1995 after the
street-bum episode, citing a law that barred insulting portrayals
of senior government officials.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Lyubomirov said, little from the Yeltsin era
has approached the pressure that ``Kukly'' has experienced since
Putin came to high office, as prime minister, last August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things changed dramatically,'' he said. ``There were no
requests for physical changes. But we've received threats from his
political family _ not threats to close the program but that the
program may have some `difficulties.' And this Russian phrase `to
have difficulties' can mean many things.''
</P>
<P>
   The threats peaked in March in a private conversation between a
senior Kremlin official and a top executive at NTV. Yevgeny
Kiselyev, the network's general director, said the official
proffered a list of tasks the network would have to meet to escape
the government's wrath, including less skeptical political coverage
and toned-down reporting on the war in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of those demands was to get Putin's look-alike _ his
rubber look-alike, that is _ off the `Kukly' show,'' Kiselyev said
in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kukly'' responded last month in classic fashion. The program
told the biblical story of the Israelites' trek through the
wilderness and their salvation by Moses, who led them to the holy
land on God's instruction.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the Israelites were an assortment of Kremlin
politicians, and Moses _ once more Putin's right-hand aide Voloshin
_ returned from the mountain with a series of curious commandments.
</P>
<P>
   One, ``Thou shalt not kill,'' was amended to exclude killings in
outhouses _ an allusion to Putin's crude threat last year to wipe
out Chechen militants, even in the toilet. ``Thou shalt not steal''
was altered to permit petty theft after the Israelite politicians
complained bitterly about the restriction.
</P>
<P>
   As for the deity himself, he was so terrible that no one could
look upon him or even speak his name. However, Voloshin said, ``You
can call him `Lord God' or, for short, the Russian initials for the
term: GB.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody missed the fact that ``GB'' can also be short for
``KGB,'' Putin's old employer as well as the specter of
totalitarian control that critics now accuse him of resurrecting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to respond in a way that was easy _ to show that
we're not working with rubber puppets but with public stereotypes
and misconceptions,'' Lyubomirov said. ``If we want, we can not
show people. But we can set up everything so that everyone
understands what we are talking about.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It is a talent honed by decades of practice under Soviet rule,
where even the tamest observation had to be made obliquely. As the
episode filmed on Thursday showed, this is not the show's customary
style.
</P>
<P>
   The program to be broadcast Sunday night was conceived on Monday
as a satire on Russia's desire to present a modern face to the
world. After President Clinton leaves this month's Moscow summit
meeting covered with rotten tomato pulp _ `Drop dead, you limb of
Satan!' one legislator cries after him _ Putin decides that Russia
needs a new, modern image.
</P>
<P>
   He summons the state painter _ his aide, Voloshin _ to produce a
portrait of civility: a reproduction of a famous
turn-of-the-century painting, ``Meeting of the State Council,''
which depicts the czar and his advisers in greatcoated splendor.
Much of the humor turns on the efforts of politicians, from the
former Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev to Yeltsin's discredited
liberal aides, to position themselves in the updated portrait
around Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Voloshin, widely regarded as an architect of the Kremlin's
crackdown on dissent, plays the heavy as an artist with grand
designs for Kremlin power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that everybody see the true and wonderful face
of our statehood, that we do not abjure new ideas,'' Putin says at
one point in the skit. ``We are not Zulus of some sort. We have
opposition, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Voloshin replies: ``Of course, your majesty! Even two
oppositions: the left and the right. Just say how many of them you
want, and you'll have them.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the story, anyway, until the NTV chairman, Gusinsky,
was jailed on Tuesday evening. Now the episode ends with a twist:
The characters find themselves wearing not greatcoats but prison
uniforms reminiscent of Stalin's purges.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, an iron curtain descends across the stage _ an
unsubtle allusion not just to the fact that state repression falls
on both great and small but that it also cuts Russia off from the
civilized world that the Putin puppet professes to admire.
</P>
<P>
   The very fact that ``Kukly'' can broadcast such heresy on
national television, of course, is evidence that freedom of speech
lives here, something Lyubomirov freely allows.
</P>
<P>
   The question, he says, is not whether, but for how long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying we don't have freedom of speech. I'm saying
that the field of that freedom is being narrowed. There are fewer
and fewer who can speak the truth. And maybe ours is one of the
last.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
