<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3686 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-NKOREA-SYRIA-REVIEW     06-17 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NKOREA-SYRIA-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF DAD WAS A DICTATOR, CAN YOU BE MR. NICE GUY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Repeating for all needing.)  
(The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The images sent imaginations soaring.
</P>
<P>
   On the airport tarmac in Pyongyang last Tuesday, the reclusive,
elusive leader of North Korea, Kim Jong Il, reached forward and
greeted his guest, President Kim Dae-jung of South Korea, with an
honor guard and a gripping, two-handed handshake. Behind the grins,
it was tempting to see a melting of a half-century of hostility
across the Korean peninsula, one of the world's most dangerous
flashpoints.
</P>
<P>
   Half a world away, Bashar Assad, a 34-year-old British-educated
eye doctor who is the new ruler of Syria, stood stoically near the
flag-draped coffin of his father, President Hafez Assad, receiving
condolences from a parade of visiting foreign princes and
dignitaries. One of those visitors was Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, expressing hope _ ever so tentatively _ that the new
Syrian leader might cool off the most enduringly hostile corner of
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   It was, of course, pure coincidence that the two events took
place the same day. But beneath the surface, there are profound
similarities in what was happening last week.
</P>
<P>
   Both North Korea and Syria are relics of another age _
dictatorships based on internal terror and hostility to external
neighbors, threatening to explode at any time in new conflict. And
now Syria, like North Korea six years ago, has embarked on a
dynastic transition that may _ or may not _ give reason to hope for
an easing of those tensions.
</P>
<P>
   In each place, power has passed from a dictator to his son, and
the son shows signs of a more modern, outward-looking approach to
solving his country's deep problems. Perhaps that can make the
world more peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also the disquieting feeling that it won't be easy;
terror and isolation remain hallmarks of the systems in which these
two sons rule, and whether they can _ or even want to _ tame parts
of those systems may be the most important factors in determining
whether a real transformation is under way. Change, for both sons,
will be risky: moving from a terror-based society to a more open
one always is.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of North Korea, Kim Jong Il appears to have made a
strategic, possibly desperate, decision to reach out to the rest of
the world. Even before he pledged during the summit that he would
visit South Korea, he established diplomatic relations with Italy
and secretly visited China. President Vladimir Putin of Russia has
said he will visit North Korea next month, and Japan is negotiating
a possible resumption of relations.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Syria, the younger Assad, an English- and
French-speaking Internet enthusiast in a country where free speech
is a fantasy and the Internet has been branded a threat to
security, made clear even before he assumed the reins of power that
he was different from his father. ``I am not one of those who keeps
power for himself,'' he told the Egyptian weekly Al Ousboua in an
interview before his father's death. ``I believe in the need to
open up to all opinions and listen to all viewpoints.''
</P>
<P>
   But for both men, success is not at all guaranteed, and for
remarkably similar reasons. Neither Kim Jong Il nor Bashar Assad
got his job the way his father did _ as a military leader who
grabbed and consolidated power. Even though both countries are
called ``republics,'' the sons did not get their jobs because of
the will of the people. They did not even get their jobs in the
most traditional dynastic way _ through the legitimacy implicit in
royal blood lines.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the two sons came into power only because of the
political manipulations of their fathers while they were alive,
abetted after their deaths by military and terror apparatuses
bequeathed to the sons as pillars of their respective systems. That
means that their claim to legitimacy is dangerously thin, and any
bold move either at home or abroad is fraught with risks. Both
men's fathers left them societies in bad economic shape, North
Korea's disastrously so. Westerners sometimes see that as a force
dictating an opening to the outside world. But both sons must be
aware that a wrong move in that direction could bring down the
wrath of the military or the ruling party. At the same time,
isolating potential rivals and suddenly placing new power in the
hands of foreign businessmen, or the press, or the people
themselves, could bring down the entire structure of power.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   In North Korea's case, for example, Kim inherited the most
isolated regime in the world, one whose people have been fed an
extraordinary stream of propaganda and one where any sudden influx
of real information about how much better the outside world lives
could be enormously destabilizing and dangerous to the leader.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the history of efforts to remove terror from a
political system without bringing it down.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev tried and failed outright;
his system was too brittle to withstand the sweeping societal,
economic and political changes he envisioned. It simply collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   China, wary of Gorbachev's mistakes, is experimenting with
retaining its Communist Party structure and autocratic government
while opening up its economy to capitalism and foreign investment;
the ultimate outcome of this juggling act is not at all certain
either.
</P>
<P>
   And in Syria's ally Iran, yet another kind of risky transitional
experiment is under way. There clerical leaders are mixing two
volatile chemicals _ Islam and democracy _ in a struggle to
reconcile representative government and the rule of law with
theocracy.
</P>
<P>
   In North Korea, despite Kim Jong Il's opening to the world,
there is no evidence that he intends to open up the political
system for his starving population at home. North Korea is so
closed, its people apparently so quiescent, that when he postponed
the summit for a day, he felt no need to explain why. He could quip
that he knew all about South Korea from watching its television for
years, a right that is denied to his citizens, whose sole radio
station blares government propaganda that good citizens are
expected to leave on all day long. In fact, most of the images of
the two leaders meeting that were beamed to South Korea were not
shown in the North. Virtually no foreigners were allowed to attend
the summit in Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see the decision to engage as a decision to open up
North Korean society,'' said Stephen Linton, a Korea expert and
chairman of the nonprofit Eugene Bell Foundation, created to fight
tuberculosis in North Korea. ``These folks are not frustrated
democrats. They have never been educated to question authority. On
the contrary, they have been educated to be loyal to their leader.
Unanimity is a public virtue here.''
</P>
<P>
   Even to Linton, who has spent considerable time in North Korea
over the years, the country is a black hole. ``Thirty to 40 years
into Korean studies, I have no idea where this is going,'' he said.
``It's humbling.''
</P>
<P>
   In Syria, a Mediterranean country with a long mercantile
tradition, the people are much less isolated and more politically
sophisticated. Despite the closed nature of Syrian society and the
authoritarian system of decision-making today, many Syrians
remember the 1950s, when they enjoyed democratic rights under a
multiparty system. But they also remember that the period of
democracy ended in a series of coups; it is the kind of denouement
that sours repressive societies on the soft side of democracy, and
surely there is no nostalgia for that kind of instability, even in
the Syria of the Assads.
</P>
<P>
   Still, because of the stakes for peace in general, it is to be
expected that the outside world is lining up to nudge both North
Korea and, to a lesser extent, Syria, to achieve reasonable
relationships with their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   In North Korea's case, China in particular has reason to act: it
has cultivated relationships with both North and South Korea and
has endured an illegal influx of hundreds of thousands of North
Koreans fleeing the country's economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the United States is puzzling over what last week's
showmanship means. Clinton administration officials aren't revising
intelligence assessments about the need for a national missile
defense that would define North Korea as the pre-eminent threat. In
fact, one theory at the Pentagon is that Kim Jong Il's outreach
could all be a plot orchestrated by Russia to derail an American
limited missile defense initiative. ``Nothing North Korea does
short of merging with the South and democratizing would change our
calculation about the threat,'' one senior administration official
said.
</P>
<P>
   With Syria, the signs are more subtle. Both before and since
Hafez Assad's death, the United States has said that it sees little
chance in the short term for progress toward an Israeli-Syrian
peace. Israeli officials are also pessimistic, although some have
painted the new Syrian leader in a positive light.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the problem is that both societies are controlled at
the top, leaving outsiders little leverage to affect change except
through formal state-to-state relations. There are no parliaments
or newspapers or independent groups to bond with.
</P>
<P>
   ``These highly autocratic regimes can use their international
connections to enhance their domestic positions and extract
concessions from the outside world,'' said Stephen Krasner, a
political science professor at Stanford University. ``But the
nature of these regimes also limits the ability of external actors
to alter policies.'' In other words, even those intriguing images
last week of outsiders invited in can be used to keep these
societies closed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
