<HEADER>
A7066 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LOS-ALAMOS-SCENE0618-     06-17 1598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOS-ALAMOS-SCENE0618-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Los Alamos' idyllic image tarnished by blaze, missing `X files'
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. _ First came the spy scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Then the wildfire that almost swallowed them whole.
</P>
<P>
   And now the saga of the lost _ then found _ secret nuclear ``X''
files.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, events have rained like bombs on America's
Atomic City, shaking up the isolated, orderly existence this
northern New Mexico town and its nuclear weapons laboratory have
enjoyed for more than a half-century.
</P>
<P>
   This town of the elite, which once beamed with national pride
for its role in making world and scientific history, now finds
itself the butt of national jokes and the object of scrutiny. A
member of Congress jabbed last week that security at the Los Alamos
National Laboratory wasn't any better than that at any Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch. Is it any wonder the strain is showing the faces of
employees and town residents?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty worn out, you can imagine,'' said Elva Clinard, a
retired labs biochemist who's lived in Los Alamos since 1965. ``Let
alone the fires, people are still roiling over the treatment of Wen
Ho Lee, and now this (X files) news. It makes you wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinard's reference is to laboratory scientist Wen Ho Lee, who
was fired in March 1999 after an investigation into suspicions he
supplied China with nuclear weapons information. He is in solitary
confinement in a Santa Fe jail awaiting trial on 59 counts of
mishandling classified material. News of Lee's alleged secrets
sharing rocked the lab and the town.
</P>
<P>
   But since then, Los Alamos has taken a series of other hits that
have kept it in the headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, congressional leaders criticized lab scientists after
two computer files, containing information on how to deploy nuclear
weapons, turned up missing. Two investigations have been launched
by the FBI and Congress; six employees have been suspended. Late
Friday, officials announced the computer hard drives had been
located within the confines of the lab's secure area and are being
evaluated. But questions about the handling of those files remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morale was already at rock bottom at the labs,'' said Robyn
Peterson, who works in waste management as a contracted employee.
She said that budget cuts and security crackdowns have created an
atmosphere of suspicion and paranoia. And if the Lee affair _ and
X-files fiasco _ weren't bad enough, the town also had to contend
with a major fire. The Cerro Grande Fire swept through in early
May, leaving 400 families homeless, causing more than $1 billion in
property damage and wiping out 47,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't even recovered from the fires, and now this comes
out,'' said Peterson of the X-files developments, while hanging out
at the American Legion. ``I suspect people will be leaving the
labs. It's probably making some think about (whether) this is all
worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, most families stopped picking through the piles of
ash where their homes once stood and turned to filing for disaster
relief and insurance claims. Tom Stewart, a high school counselor
who is part of an outreach team with the federally funded Project
Recovery of Northern New Mexico, spoke of the emotional scars the
town has suffered.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll never get done with this civic massacre,'' he said.
``All of us, and all our kids, huddled around the TV and watched
our town burn. We were obsessed with watching it. We couldn't take
our eyes off of it. ``
</P>
<P>
   Over a free burrito lunch served to fire victims daily at the
First United Methodist Church, Stewart advised Sandi and Steve
Paglieri when and how to show their 3-year-old daughter the
blackened remains of their apartment on Arizona Avenue, where 45
houses and apartments burned.
</P>
<P>
   The young couple lost everything, including all the work Steve
Paglieri had gathered for a post-doctoral paper. ``It was a review
article with 800 references, and they all burned up. The computer,
the disc, the papers, everything,'' said Paglieri, who is a
chemical engineer at the labs.
</P>
<P>
   LIKE NO OTHER PLACE
</P>
<P>
   Los Alamos locals dub the town ``Lost Almost'' because it is a
mountain town that's difficult to reach. Thirty-five miles
northwest of Santa Fe, the town is accessible on via a winding
two-lane highway that passes through two Indian reservations and
jutting, jangled sandstone bluffs.
</P>
<P>
   Los Alamos is like no other place in New Mexico, or perhaps the
world. It is rich, smart and overwhelmingly white in a state that
is poor and ethnically diverse.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Alamos County, the average median household income is
$66,492, more than twice that of the rest of New Mexico. And you're
considered ``slow'' if you just have a bachelor's degree in a town
awash with the nation's top physicists, chemists and engineers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a town full of geeks,'' offers Joy Miller at the Los
Alamos Visitors Center. ``We have the highest rate of Ph.D.'s in
the country. Consequently, we have the best schools in the state
because a lot of Ph.D. people accept nothing less than outstanding
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents also point out the eclectic mix of people that think
like academics yet live and work in military-like settings.
</P>
<P>
   Bert Kortegaard, a retired engineer who specializes in
accelerated physics, compares the mix to that of Paris or Berlin.
``It's the same kind of worldly cosmopolitan intelligentsia
crowd,`` he said.
</P>
<P>
   But events of recent weeks have tarnished some of the town's
luster as the lab has come under fire.
</P>
<P>
   Early last month, the Cerro Grande Fire came dangerously close
to engulfing radioactive wastes stored underground at the labs. But
major research facilities and radioactive sites, scattered
throughout the lab's 43 square acres, were kept out of the line of
fire.
</P>
<P>
   However, the fire did cause at least $300 million in property
damage to the federally-owned institution before it was contained
June 6. Just as Los Alamos was recovering, the labs took another
hit when U.S. senators lashed out at director John Browne for its
second major breach of security _ the loss, however temporary, of
the nuclear ``X'' files. ``Wal-mart has greater security,''
commented Sen. Wayne Allard, (R-Colorado).
</P>
<P>
   Senators accused the lab of being encased in a culture of
indifference and arrogance, and being incapable of keeping track of
its own data, much of it considered classified and top-secret.
</P>
<P>
   Browne told Congress the labs have had a hard time keeping close
tabs on its files since the federal government declassified many of
the Department of Energy's sensitive records in 1990. Investigators
are questioning 26 scientists who had access to the sensitive
files.
</P>
<P>
   And Los Alamos's troubles may not be over. Even as ``Thank you
firefighters'' messages are posted around the town, locals and
federal agencies were sandbagging residential areas in anticipation
of flash-flooding from heavy summer rains.
</P>
<P>
   CITY OF SECRETS
</P>
<P>
   The political hits the town has taken strike many here as ironic
given that Los Alamos was created in a shroud of covert operations
and a veil of secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised to see us in the paper so often,'' said Rebecca
Collinsworth, an archivist at the Los Alamos Historical Society,
who's been overwhelmed collecting all the regional and national
press clippings the past 18 months. ``In the 1950s, (the town
wasn't) even in the weather forecast because we were not supposed
to exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Alamos was established in 1943, and, under physicist J.
Robert Oppenheimer, developed the world's first atomic bomb. The
labs, which employ nearly 11,000 people, are owned by the
Department of Energy and operated by the University of California.
The central mission of the labs still revolves around national
security, but scientists also pursue DNA sequencing , global
warming studies and other research.
</P>
<P>
   During those top-secret WWII and Cold War days, babies,
officially, weren't even born here at the local hospital. Their
birth certificate address read: P.O. Box 1663, Santa Fe. It was the
address all the residents used. And none of the kids knew what
their fathers did when they left for work every day.
</P>
<P>
   The town remained a puzzle to the rest of the state until 1957
when the government opened it to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Cloistered under a canopy of ponderosa pine, blue spruce and
cottonwood trees, the town sits in a valley of canyons at 7,355
feet and looks out at mountains that are the rolling foothills to
the Rockies. The state's largest city, Albuquerque, is 120 miles
away, and Santa Fe, the legislative capital and tourist magnet, is
a 40-minute drive down ``the hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Many residents take to the mountains on the weekends for some of
the state's finest fishing, camping and hiking. Or they check out
the myriad archaeological sites, cliff dwellings and rock drawings
left by ancient Native American cultures. And come winter, they ski
on their own mountain, Pajarito, that's run by the Los Alamos Ski
Club.
</P>
<P>
   All these pursuits used to be just a gaze away in the green
rolling shoulder of the Jemez Mountains. But now, many residents
can't even bear to look up at charred and limbless pine trees that
stick up like rows upon rows of blackened skeletons.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here are outdoors people,'' said relief volunteer
Carole Watanabe, as she looked west toward the places where she
used to find recreation and solace. ``It's sad,'' she said softly,
``it's just really hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
