<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7076 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-VA-SENATE-RACE-ART-58     06-17 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VA-SENATE-RACE-ART-580(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRGINIA'S SENATE CAMPAIGN SUDDENLY LOOKS CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT 6 and 7 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Va. _ The last Democrat standing between Virginia
Republicans and a historic sweep of statewide power this year is
Sen. Charles Robb, once his state party's savior but
unceremoniously rated ``toast'' and ``dead meat'' a year ago by
political handicappers. The general Beltway prognosis was that Robb
was the most vulnerable Democrat in the Senate in the 2000
elections.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the senator trailed 12 points behind a formidable
Republican challenger, former Gov. George F. Allen, prompting
widespread speculation that Robb, laconic and moody as politicians
go, might wisely retreat and call it a decent career after 12 years
in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But to the surprise of Democrats as much as Republicans, that
gap has now closed to a 1-point tossup in the face of an
unexpectedly galvanized Robb. As a result, this commonwealth of
Jeffersonian principles and tooth-and-claw politics is looking
forward to a classic matchup: two former governors who led surges
of state party dominance in the '80s and '90s will finally have it
out before the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to go out and shoot up all your ammunition when
you first hit the beach,'' explained Robb, a Vietnam combat veteran
with an unhurried air and a competitive gleam as he celebrates his
recent political resurrection. ``I know there are a lot of folks
who are very disappointed that I didn't roll over and play dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Not the least of them is Allen, a very popular, ebulliently
combative politician with a substantial record as governor who has
been campaigning across the state since 1998, strutting in his
signature cowboy boots, reminding voters of his down-home style.
Allen has been the campaign's nonstop leading fund-raiser, rallying
Republicans to complete their state dominance by winning a second
Senate seat to complement their sweep of a legislative majority and
all three top executive positions last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck, it's time to quit hiding behind parliamentary chicanery
and paid attack dogs,'' boomed Allen, his love of political
battling palpable, as he ignited the state party convention this
month. ``Heck, I'll bet Hillary doesn't support Bill 87 percent of
the time, but Virginia's junior senator surely does,'' Allen
declared, burnishing his favorite sound-bite denunciation of the
``Clinton-Gore-Robb crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   In reply, Robb relishes the choice voters will face between two
such familiar, experienced politicians. ``This will be like
Government 101, Civics 101,'' he said in an interview. He is hardly
flinching at the contest, and his comeback in the polls is being
attributed to nothing more complicated than his own striking
display of re-election hunger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robb refused to engage in the race until he sensed it was
time, and then he showed himself to be quite a counterpuncher,''
said Charlie Cook, National Journal's political handicapper, who
had dubbed the senator ``dead meat'' last year.
</P>
<P>
   Cook has happily amended that in view of what is developing into
the most interesting Senate contest outside New York. ``It's going
to be a great race,'' said Cook, who still sees Allen as a slight
front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very appropriate that these two candidates face off at
the beginning of the 21st century,'' said Robert D. Holsworth,
director of Virginia Commonwealth University's Center for Public
Policy. ``As governors, they each helped define and solidify their
parties at different times at the close of the 20th century as two
sort of moderate conservatives.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After months of Democratic doubts about Robb, he served notice
at party rallies in March that he still had some fire. ``Let me
assure you that no warrior I ever met at Quantico was frightened by
big talk, big-heeled boots or a big chew of tobacco,'' said Robb, a
former marine, targeting Allen's good-old-boy trappings. ``And
neither am I.''
</P>
<P>
   The choice for voters begins with two distinct styles on the
hustings. The 60-year-old Robb is reserved; the 48-year-old Allen
is a buoyant campaigner, cherished by Republicans for his feisty
one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's enjoy knocking their soft teeth down their whiny
throats!'' was Allen's memorable call to battle five years ago.
This year, he is scoring Robb for ``sipping wine and nibbling
cheese'' inside the Beltway, accusing him of being aloof from
constituent responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Allen's a very able campaigner, able to project himself as
very self-confident,'' the senator said. ``That can either be a
plus or a minus.'' His campaign aides more bluntly portray Allen as
a polarizer _ in the words of one aide, ``Virginia's Al D'Amato.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is a very gentle Allen who is being seen these nights in
an early blitz of television commercials blanketing the northern
Virginia suburbs, a key battleground that Robb carried six years
ago when he narrowly defeated Oliver North in a three-man race. The
simple biographical ads, devoid of a Republican label in this
bastion of moderates and independents, have made Allen as
ubiquitous as Bill Gates on the nighttime screen as he reintroduces
himself to the booming Fairfax County area, where tens of thousands
of newcomers have moved in the past six years.
</P>
<P>
   Allen is campaigning on his state record of cutting taxes and
reducing crime, trimming state agencies and attracting new
business. He promises federal measures in these areas and more,
including a proposed $1,000 tax credit for parents to use for
school computers and tutoring but not for private tuition. He
criticizes Robb as excessive in his proposals for stronger gun
controls and his views on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Robb is emphasizing his Senate reputation as an expert on
national security and a bipartisan conciliator, as well as his
carefully blended record of fiscal conservatism and liberalism on
social issues.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the campaign still in the feeling-out stage, Allen's early
initiatives include repeated attacks on the senator's opposition to
a constitutional ban on flag desecration and his defense of federal
gasoline taxes. But Robb cheered Democrats with his
counterpuncher's instinct. On the flag, he delivered an impassioned
floor speech, speaking firsthand of battlefield death and
patriotism for ``sacred intangibles'' more than ``a piece of cloth,
however sacred.'' On the gasoline tax, he is focusing on the
suburbs' main problem, commuter gridlock, emphasizing that fuel
taxes pay for new roads.
</P>
<P>
   The senator also seized the initiative in a recent uproar over a
state proclamation of Confederate History Month, a proclamation
originated by Allen as governor. In an obvious attempt to rally
their crucial African-American base, Democrats stress that Allen's
version, unlike the one eventually adopted, did not include the
current condemnation of slavery _ a low-blow tactic, in the
Republican's view.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's negative politics to try to divide people on race,''
said Allen, the son of a famous football coach who uses gridiron
metaphors the way Robb uses military terms. ``You have to research
your opposition and realize what kind of game plans they run. What
kind of crack-back blocks they run, how they hit out of bounds, how
they'll twist your ankles after a tackle.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook and other political observers question whether Robb can
effectively demonize the Allen style, considering Allen's
well-demonstrated popularity. Allen, delighted with the party unity
that was absent six years ago, is attacking Robb's laid-back style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what motivates him to be in the Senate,'' Allen
said, ``because he really doesn't do much, although every six years
he becomes active, and it's the first people see him outside the
Beltway.''
</P>
<P>
   Robb says his motivation is strong and increasingly clear to
voters. ``Part of it is simply maturing in terms of how you look at
the world,'' he said. ``Sometimes it takes a while to really figure
out what you believe in to your core.''
</P>
</TEXT>
