<SLUG> BC-BOOK-KIDS0618-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dandy choices for read-aloud, doodlebug dads
 &HT;    By Julie Bookman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``One berry, two berry, pick me a blueberry. Hat
berry, shoe berry, in my canoe berry. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Degen's 1983 ``Jamberry'' is one of those books I'll be
able to recite forever. That's because when my daughter Elly was
about 2, she'd drag the worn little book around, begging us to read
it to her a dozen times a day.
</P>
<P>
   Degen's new title, for ages 3-6, arrives for Father's Day:
``Daddy Is a Doodlebug'' (HarperCollins, $15.95).
</P>
<P>
   Few authors have such frisky, frivolous fun with words. Degen's
inventive rhymes keep you snickering as you read. His latest romp
affectionately celebrates the ways dads (doodlebugs) enjoy spending
time with their kids (also doodlebugs): ``We doodle things together
that doodlebugs like to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The pair padoodle a canoe, walk their poodlebug, snack on
patoodle chips. After fairytoodles, little doodlebug is tucked into
bed: ``Don't let the bedboodles bite! Sweet bug dreams and
goodlebug night.''
</P>
<P>
   Much like his words, Degen's art is terrifically bright, clever
and filled with zany surprises. In the bugs' miniature world, the
swing set is made out of pencils, and a firefly (or firefloodle)
clad in firefighter's garb dutifully blinks a flashlight.
</P>
<P>
   And if you don't own ``Jamberry,'' or your copy is as tattered
as ours, HarperCollins has just reissued it in an enlarged
(9-by-12-inch) format for $15.95.
</P>
<P>
   Also new in stores:
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-8: ``What Dads Can't Do'' by Douglas Wood, illustrated by
Doug Cushman (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $14). What should be a
tongue-in-cheek narrative about how dads operate comes off as a
tiresome, at times nauseating, ditty involving a dopey-looking dino
dad and his goofy dino kid. Examples of the clunky phrasing and
uninspired humor: ``When dads play hide-and-seek they always get
found, but they have a hard time finding you.''
</P>
<P>
   AGES 4-8: ``Animal Dads'' by Sneed B. Collard III, illustrated
by Steve Jenkins (Houghton Mifflin, $5.95 paperback). Learn how
males of 19 species care for their young. A gorilla dad helps groom
his offspring. Dwarf mongoose dads teach their youngsters how to
hunt. When the time comes for a stickleback fish mom to lay her
eggs, the stickleback dad builds the nest out of plants and then
guards it from enemies. Jenkins' illustrations nicely incorporate
torn paper and paint. Adults will enjoy this enlightening book as
much as children.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 4-9: ``John Henry'' by Brad Kessler, illustrated by Barry
Jackson, with cassette featuring narration by Denzel Washington and
music by B.B. King (Rabbit Ears Books, $10.95). Washington puts his
heart and high talents into reading Kessler's retelling of the
legend of that ``darn crackest steel-drivin' '' hero. The writing
bursts with folksy flavor and humor. Then there's the rousing music
by another legend, B.B. King. Great entertainment for the whole
family.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 5 AND UP: ``Daddy Poems'' selected by John Micklos Jr.,
illustrated by Robert Casilla (Wordsong/Boyds Mills Press, $15.95).
A collection of poems meant to be read aloud by Dad. Some works, by
notables such as X.J. Kennedy and Nikki Grimes, are light and
bouncy, or meaningful in some way, but as a whole this is an uneven
collection. Many poems are painfully trite, stilted or sophomoric,
such as Micklos' ``Bedtime Ritual,'' which begins:
</P>
<P>
   I need another cookie, Dad.
</P>
<P>
   I need another drink.
</P>
<P>
   I need another visit
</P>
<P>
   To the bathroom, I think.
</P>
<P>
   The old-fashioned illustrations are serviceable at best.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
