<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-REGULATIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMERCE EVOLVING IN ITALY, BUT HAIRCUT DURING FULL MOON STILL
ILLEGAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Under a full moon, shortly before midnight, Vittorio
Giunta, a Roman hairdresser, trimmed the hair of Isabella Morandi,
30, a client who is convinced that this phase of the lunar cycle
will make her locks grow back faster, and thicker.
</P>
<P>
   The haircut, however, also broke the law.
</P>
<P>
   No police officer raced in to arrest Giunta, but his small act
of civil disobedience is not likely to go unnoticed. Giunta, 48, an
elegant man whose white hair and goatee are set off by sleek black
shirts and trousers, is a rebel with an unlikely cause. He is
fighting city government, two hairdressers' unions and dozens of
small trade associations for the right to keep his shop open when
the moon is full.
</P>
<P>
   He and some of his clients believe that the best time to cut
hair is under a full moon, an ancient superstition that has not
entirely died out in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   That belief, however, clashes with a more widespread
superstition about free market ``chaos,'' a fear that has kept
rigid and jealously guarded regulations on hundreds of thousands of
small family businesses in place.
</P>
<P>
   Giunta's desire to set his own working hours has introduced a
frisson of American-style capitalism to a society that is slowly
and painfully adjusting its ``dolce vita'' to the free market
demands of a global economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to express myself artistically during the full-moon
hours,'' said Giunta, who owns Capellimania, a small salon in a
middle-class residential neighborhood in Rome. ``Besides, if you
move to a free market, then you can't stop individual initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Italy has changed dramatically since the days when
all shop shutters would rumble shut at 1 p.m. for lunch and naps,
opening again at 4 p.m., and no store was open on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Regulations that forbid a salami store from selling sandwiches
or a shoe store from selling shirts were removed last year. The red
tape needed to open a new store was cut back. And, in its most
revolutionary step, the same law liberalized store hours for
commercial enterprises, allowing shopkeepers to set their own hours
in a 13-hour maximum working day. In the center of Rome, some shops
now stay open even at lunchtime. A few are open on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The new law, which was only grudgingly accepted by Italy's
600,000 businesses, did not apply to a million other small
businesses that fall into the category of artisanry, which includes
bakers, auto mechanics, furniture makers and hairdressers, who
still operate under old rules, many of them 30 years old.
Hairdressers, for example, must open at 9 a.m. and shut at 7 p.m.
and have to close on Mondays.
</P>
<P>
   Giunta's daring experiment has not won the support of many
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The full moon thing is folklore _ it is quite idiotic,'' said
Danilo Garone, national secretary of Federacconciatori, one of
Italy's main hairdressing trade associations. ``What woman wants to
go out and get her hair done at midnight?''
</P>
<P>
   Italy has more than 100,000 hair salons. Garone said the vast
majority of hairdressers were adamantly opposed to liberalizing
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I close at 7 p.m. and a rival across the street stays open
until 11 p.m. I'll be forced to stay open, too,'' he said. ``I have
heard that in New York hair salons stay open all hours and even
serve food, but we are a traditional country. We don't need these
changes at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, however, Italy's economists and elected officials
feel obliged to conform with changes already sweeping not just the
United States but other parts of Europe. Chains, supermarkets and
shopping malls are competing with small family-owned shops in
Italy, though not as fast as elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Italian manual of commercial law is 500 pages long _ it is
absurdly complicated,'' said Luca Pellegrini, vice president of the
Center of Commercial Studies at Bocconi University in Milan. ``In
Italy, competition is seen as harmful, and it makes you work too
hard. We have a humane and pleasant way of life, and we have a hard
time adapting to inevitable change.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Ninci, president of the Commerce and Productive
Activities Commission for the city of Rome, does want change, and
has enthusiastically embraced liberalization of store hours.
</P>
<P>
   Ninci, who has long, thick hair, pointed out that in ancient
times lunar cycles were closely followed and said she thought the
full-moon argument might have some validity. She described Giunta's
idea as ``cute'' and said she would try to raise his request at a
meeting next week, though she said she preferred group or
neighborhood initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration cannot impose liberalization,'' she said.
``The idea has to be embraced by the businesses themselves. Many
don't see the potential economic advantages of liberalization, they
remain tied to the habits of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she dreamed of a day when Rome would have 24-hour
convenience stores.
</P>
<P>
   But even she balked at the idea that stores could someday decide
for themselves when to hold sales. The new law imposes restrictions
on when sales can occur: In Rome sales can now occur only in
February and mid-July to mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are depreciating the art of commerce, reducing the
transaction to just the price,'' she said, appalled at the notion
of wildcat sales.
</P>
<P>
   Ninci, who used to run a clothing store, said there was an
immense difference between liberalizing store hours and permitting
price wars. ``It's unfair competition and Roman retail would be
ruined.''
</P>
<P>
   Haircuts were free on Friday night at Capellimania, and the shop
was crammed with clients eager to benefit from a full-moon trim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Babylonian times, farmers planted when the moon was
full,'' Morandi explained earnestly. ``But it also makes sense to
allow salons and shops to stay open late. If a city like Rome wants
to be in the same league as Paris, or New York or London, then it
has to offer people the same choices.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
