u a BC-CRIME-STATS-NYT &LR;      06-17 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRIME-STATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMICIDE RATES IN CITIES SPURS CONCERN FOR LAW ENFORCEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By FOX BUTTERFIELD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the number of homicides in some of the nation's big cities
rising in 1999 and the first five months of 2000, after eight years
of sharp drops, concern is spreading among law enforcement
officials and criminologists about whether the decline in violent
crime has come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence is too fragmentary, and contradictory, the experts
caution, to draw a firm conclusion. Virtually all of the elements
that contributed to the drop in homicide from 1991 through 1998 are
still in place: more criminals in prisons, innovative police
strategies, intense community efforts to work with troubled youths,
a waning of the crack cocaine epidemic and a strong economy
providing more jobs in impoverished neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1999, five of the 17 cities that have more than 100
homicides a year had an increase in killings, the first time since
the early 1990s that slayings have increased in so many cities.
Through the end of May this year, seven of these cities showed an
increase from the same period last year. Together, these 17 cities
accounted for more than a quarter of the nation's 15,600 homicides
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   New York was the only city in the group to experience a rise in
homicides in 1999 and the first five months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about crime have been heightened recently by shocking
attacks in several cities. New York, for instance, has seen the
killing of 10 cab drivers, the fatal shooting of five employees in
a Wendy's restaurant in Queens in May and a rampage in Central Park
last weekend in which at least 27 women reported being groped or
assaulted by young men.
</P>
<P>
   But some police officials say that the increases in homicide in
1999 and 2000 are simply a normal statistical variation after so
many good years, which had brought homicide rates to their lowest
point nationally since 1967.
</P>
<P>
   And some criminal justice experts agree with them _ to an
extent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the increase in murder rates is simply that, at a
certain point, you can't go any lower,'' said James Alan Fox, the
Lipman professor of criminal justice at Northeastern University.
``The rates have come down so far, they simply can't be maintained
at such a low level.''
</P>
<P>
   To underscore this, Alfred Blumstein, a criminologist at
Carnegie Mellon University, said he had calculated that if the
decline in homicide in the 1990s continued at the same rate, the
United States would have no killings in 2007, an obvious
impossibility.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, Police Commissioner Howard Safir contends the
police may be victims of their own success in reducing the number
of killings to 671 in 1999 from 2,245 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the goal should be zero, but in a city of 8 million,
the reality is you can only go so low,'' Safir said in a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the other categories of serious crimes, including
robbery, assault, rape, burglary, theft and automobile theft, are
down by 8 percent this year in New York. ``So I don't think we've
bottomed out on crime, but we may have bottomed out on murder.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, after years in which New York officials have used the
homicide rate as a measure of their success in making the city
safer, Safir suggested it might be more accurate to look at the
broader range of all serious crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, New York had a 6 percent increase in homicides, and
through the end of May this year there have been 269 homicides,
compared with 248 in the same period in 1999, an increase of 8.5
percent. But Safir said that with the recent adoption of Operation
Condor, which lets police officers in high crime areas work more
overtime, there had been a small drop in homicides in May and so
far in June, and he predicted that the total for 2000 would be
about where it was in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Another difficulty in drawing conclusions from the national
homicide figures for 1999 and so far this year is that there are no
obvious patterns to account for the increases in homicide in the
cities that have had them.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, which had a 15 percent increase in killings in 1999,
Sgt. Jeff Halstead, a spokesman for the city's police department,
said the rise could be largely attributed to the city's rapid
population growth and its position near the Mexican border, with a
large influx of drugs and illegal immigrants. ``What we have seen
is an increase in homicides related to narcotics and undocumented
Mexican nationals making their way into the metro Phoenix area,''
Halstead said.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the Phoenix police put together a special homicide
task force this year, with many of its members Spanish speakers,
and the city has had a drop in homicides through the end of May,
down to 63 this year from 91 in the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
   But in Los Angeles, which had 181 homicides in the first five
months of this year, compared with 159 in the same months in 1999,
Jason Lee, a spokesman for the police department, said he did not
know why the figures were up.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, Safir said there were no discernible patterns
for the increase in killings during the last year and a half. There
had been some small rise in drug-related homicides, he said, but a
decrease in gang-related and domestic killings.
</P>
<P>
   One theory advanced by some criminologists to explain the surge
is that a new generation of teen-agers, too young to have
experienced the terrifying consequences of the crack epidemic of
the late 1980s _ the shootings, gang fights and waves of
imprisonment _ may now be looking for a new form of excitement.
That might explain, Blumstein said, an incident in Providence,
R.I., on June 8 in which five young men forced two college students
at gunpoint to get into their car outside a nightclub, then drove
them to a golf course, tortured them and shot them in the head.
</P>
<P>
   But Geoffrey Canada, president of the Rheedlen Center for
Children and Families in Harlem who works with troubled juveniles,
said he had not observed any trend of a return to the gun, drug and
gang culture among teen-agers in New York. ``I've seen an increase
in kids who are cut, with box cutters and razors, but not the
return of lethality and guns,'' Canada said. ``We haven't lost a
kid in several years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
