<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLIGATOR-FARM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ROLE FOR THE GATOR: CHICKEN FARMER'S FRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMILLA, Ga. _ Ah, American ingenuity. See a need? Find a way to
fill it. Got a problem? Find a way to fix it. And if you can make a
buck in the process, all the better.
</P>
<P>
   Mark A. Glass had a problem. A product of the Atlanta suburbs
and a graduate of Georgia Tech, he moved in 1993 to his wife's
hometown in southwestern Georgia, bought a farm and decided to
raise chickens. It was a business he knew little about, but he had
drive and ambition and an entrepreneurial streak.
</P>
<P>
   What Glass had not realized, though, was that about 5 percent of
his 500,000 birds would succumb to heat, injury or disease before
they could be processed into Chicken McNuggets at a nearby plant.
And the dead chickens, sometimes enough to fill the bed of his
pickup four times over, had to be disposed of each day. Many
farmers simply buried their dead in pits. Some tried composting,
and then spread the chicken mulch over their fields. Glass chose to
incinerate his chickens in a metal furnace, but soon found he was
spending $5,000 to $10,000 a year on propane.
</P>
<P>
   ``The volume of dead birds was overwhelming,'' said the
32-year-old Glass, blowing a swarm of gnats out of his face. ``It
just took an incredible amount of money to burn them.''
</P>
<P>
   Glass discussed his problem with a University of Georgia
extension agent, and the agent suggested an unusual disposal method
being pioneered by Gene Frazier, a poultry farmer in nearby
Americus. Glass did some research and decided to give it a try. And
that is why Mark Glass is up to his shins in alligators.
</P>
<P>
   It is, he says, the purest form of recycling. Each day, his
farmhands collect the dead from his 20 chicken houses. They toss
the birds _ feathers, beaks and all _ into a tractor-powered
grinder that quickly reduces the chicken into a white, pasty slop.
It is gathered in buckets and taken to the three low-lying
buildings where Glass now raises 6,500 alligators.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing shorts and rubber boots, Glass and his workers then
climb through wooden hatches into the 20 gator pens in each of the
buildings. As they open the doors and sunlight floods into the
darkened rooms, the gators, startled by the intrusion, slap the
foot-deep water with their tails and scramble into far corners. The
reptiles, some of them as much as 5 feet long, largely avoid the
workers as they pour the gruel onto platforms suspended just above
the surface of the water. And then it is dinner time, as the
alligators slide atop the platforms, grab a mouthful of mush and
retreat politely to enjoy their meals.
</P>
<P>
   After five years, Glass is now one of the largest alligator
farmers in Georgia, and one of 10 in the state who are exploring
the synergies of raising chickens beside gators. Officials with
various poultry associations said that there might be a few such
operations in other states but that Georgia, which calls itself the
largest chicken-producing state, seemed to be the epicenter of
experimentation.
</P>
<P>
   When the alligators reach a length of 4 or 5 feet, usually after
about two years, Glass harvests them. He and his workers wade into
the pens, catching gators with their bare hands. Once they remove
the alligators from the pens, they tape their jaws shut with a
strip of black electrical tape, kill the animals swiftly by
hammering a steel blade into their spinal cords, slice off the
hides and carve off the meat.
</P>
<P>
   If the hide has not been marred by scratches or bite marks, it
may bring $75 in Italy or some other overseas market where
alligator is used for belts, purses and shoes. The meat may bring
an additional $20 regionally. The heads are sold to a taxidermist
for $1 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Glass said, he ``figured that if I could break even
and get rid of my chickens, I'd be ahead of the game.'' But in fact
he has had to invest hundreds of thousands of dollars in the
construction and maintenance of his alligator pens, and he has
struggled to break even. He expects to turn a profit in the next
two years.
</P>
<P>
   Glass said he had made plenty of costly mistakes before finding
the right method. At first he tried raising the alligators in a
pond. But he soon discovered they were susceptible to scratches and
bite marks, which devalued their hides. He also learned that they
hibernated when air and water temperatures dropped, and showed
little interest in helping him dispose of his chickens. In his
indoor pens, the air and water are artificially heated. ``Trial and
error,'' Glass observed, ``is a very expensive way to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also occupational hazards, of course. ``If you catch
enough alligators, you're going to get bit,'' said Glass, who has
been nipped and has watched two workers suffer more serious
injuries. ``It kind of goes with the territory. And what's worse
than the bite is the infection that comes afterward, because their
teeth are so nasty. We peel open the wound and just pour the Clorox
in.''
</P>
<P>
   His own alligator bite did not break his skin, but it scared him
nonetheless. ``I had one by the tail and his head was underwater
and he just bent in half and grabbed my finger,'' Glass said. ``He
let go, but if he had locked his jaws he'd have had me. Basically,
you've just got to be faster than they are.''
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected, the working conditions tend to make hiring
difficult. ``It makes it harder to find employees,'' Glass
explained, ``when you have to ask, `Are you afraid of alligators?'
in the interview process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
