<HEADER>
A7087 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-GIULIANI-CRITICS-N     06-17 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-CRITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS ON BOTH FLANKS: A NO-WIN FOR GIULIANI 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A strange thing happened to Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
last week. A caller to his weekly radio show asked the
tough-on-crime mayor why he had suddenly gone soft _ specifically,
why a Central Park mob had been allowed to sexually assault dozens
of women last Sunday while the police, the caller said, did
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Things on the show rapidly deteriorated, at least from the
mayor's perspective, as the caller, ``Keith from Washington
Heights,'' who described himself as a big ``Rudy supporter,''
finished off with the ultimate insult. He compared Sunday's Central
Park attacks with the 1991 Crown Heights disturbance, when a black
mob killed a Jewish scholar and the Dinkins administration allowed
the violence to continue for three days.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who reviles former Mayor David Dinkins, did not take
well to the analogy. ``Maybe the picture you get is not the
absolutely accurate picture,'' he responded testily, his ``New
Rudy'' demeanor forgotten. ``Did you ever consider that?''
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, Giuliani was hit from the other side: A
248-page report from the U.S. Civil Rights Commission released on
Friday urged the appointment of independent prosecutors to
investigate any serious future accusations of police brutality.
</P>
<P>
   It also said that the New York City Police Department engaged in
extensive racial profiling in stop-and-frisk tactics against blacks
and Hispanics. Giuliani's response, in a written statement, was
swift: ``Once again the U.S. Commission on Civil Rights has
embarrassed itself by releasing a politicized report that bears no
relation to reality.''
</P>
<P>
   There has always been a siege mentality in the Giuliani-era City
Hall, an ``us against the world'' leitmotif that a Republican mayor
in a Democratic city has used as inspiration as he pushes forward
with unpopular programs. But last week was the first time Giuliani
was attacked simultaneously on both flanks, for a Police Department
said to be both too aggressive and not aggressive enough. ``Maybe
we're in a period of time in which the police can't win,'' Giuliani
said on the radio show.
</P>
<P>
   Those at City Hall said the same of themselves, particularly
during a week when the lines in a predictable world of enemies and
friends became blurred. The New York Post, the mayor's longtime
supporter, compared Giuliani's reaction to the Central Park attacks
(``tepid _ indeed, downright defensive'') with the reaction of
Dinkins to the fatal stabbing of a tourist from Utah during a
robbery attempt in the subway in 1990 (``lethargic, befuddled'').
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't win! You can't win!'' groused one of the mayor's
most senior advisers. But he also took on a war-weary tone. ``It's
no different now,'' he said, ``than it was six years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy Molinari, the Staten Island borough president and a longtime
friend of the mayor's, expressed similar sentiments of victimhood.
``You're damned if you do, and you're damned if you don't,'' he
said. ``If you have an incident where the police go over the line,
everybody attacks the mayor. And if you have an incident like
Central Park, everybody attacks the mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Harding, the chairman of the Liberal Party and another
old friend of Giuliani's, also reflected this view from City Hall:
``The main focus out of the Central Park melee following the Puerto
Rican Day parade has been the police reaction. The first issue is
that this kind of a melee occurred. I have not heard sufficient
condemnation of that. I hear condemnation of the police. I find
myself in a topsy-turvy world.''
</P>
<P>
   So topsy-turvy, in fact, that the mayor did something very rare
for him this week: He criticized the police. After his initial mild
response to the attacks on Monday morning _ a time when many of the
victims had not yet come forward _ Giuliani roared back with damage
control for the rest of the week, denouncing what many of the women
described as police brush-offs and promising punishment of the
officers if the claims were found to be true. He also called the
women's experiences ``horrendous'' after he met with several
victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``One described to me a situation in which the police did not
respond properly, which I thought was quite credible, and totally
inexcusable,'' the mayor said at a news conference. ``And she is
prepared to identify the two police officers that did not respond,
and I believe she can, because she was able to give me physical
descriptions of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a lame-duck mayor who has said he wants to spend his
last 18 months in office redefining his legacy with the poor and
minorities found the centerpiece of his legacy _ crime control _
under attack. Videotapes of the assaults opened the ``Today'' show
on Wednesday morning, playing in kitchens and living rooms all over
the country, followed by Giuliani assuring Matt Lauer that New York
City was still safe.
</P>
<P>
   It was just the kind of crisis the mayor had always feared when
he was running for the U.S. Senate. What if it had happened when he
was upstate? How would it have played with his political
contributors in the heartland, who often cited the city's
renaissance as a reason for their support?
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudy Giuliani is the man who tamed New York,'' said George
Arzt, the Democratic political consultant. ``And suddenly you have
an out-of-control group. People are thinking, `Are we going back to
wilding and whirlpooling and all of those things that have left our
vocabulary?' This is part of his legacy that at least momentarily
seems to be growing a wart.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Giuliani was outraged by the Crown Heights analogy, and
berated ``Keith from Washington Heights'' in vintage mayoral style.
``This did not take place all day,'' he said in a response so long
that at the end his words were drowned out by the show's closing
music. ``It didn't take place overnight. It didn't go on forever
and ever and ever. It did go on longer than it should. Maybe a
half-hour, maybe 45 minutes, maybe an hour. But to make a
comparison to something that went on for hours and hours and for
four days is a totally, you know, exaggerated reaction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 1509EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
