u a BC-NY-POLICE-PERFORMANCE     06-17 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-PERFORMANCE-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC POLICE SAY THEY ARE AS DILIGENT AS EVER, AND THE NUMBERS
AGREE 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The murder rate is up 6 percent. The Wendy's killings
and a spate of livery driver murders have revived a long-dormant
image of a dangerous New York. And here and there, when New Yorkers
talk about crime and remember the bad old days, many have come to
assume that a police force tired of pay disparity, relentless
pressure to produce and public second-guessing has grown sluggish.
</P>
<P>
   The impression of arms-folded indifference by the police was
reinforced last weekend when, in a city where the tiniest crimes
have long been vigorously pursued, dozens of women were sexually
assaulted in the environs of an event, the National Puerto Rican
Day Parade, that was being patrolled by 4,000 officers.
</P>
<P>
   But by several statistical measures, indications are that
whatever the slump in morale, many officers remain actively
involved in the aggressive law enforcement efforts that have become
a hallmark of the Giuliani administration.
</P>
<P>
   Arrests are up 12 percent this year, after falling by nearly 9
percent last year. Gun arrests, which declined by nearly 15 percent
last year, have increased by 1.4 percent this year, and criminal
summonses for lesser offenses like trespassing and public urination
have increased by 16.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, arrests can be an imprecise measure of enforcement
efforts, especially when they are being underwritten by a huge
infusion of overtime money, as they are this year. Arrests also
will often be sent soaring by a surge in crime.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, crime is down by 7.5 percent across the city, and
police supervisors say the reduction itself is a sign that there
has been no lapse in energy on the part of their officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, when there is a lot of criticism, it wears on morale,''
said Assistant Chief Joseph Fox, the police commander for southern
Brooklyn, where 10 percent more summonses have been issued this
year. But, he said, ``there is still that focus on crime reduction
and making arrests.''
</P>
<P>
   To many citizens accustomed to the Giuliani administration's
zero tolerance approach to crime, an approach that saw the arrest
several years ago of a man for riding a bicycle without a bell,
there was little evidence of that crime-fighting focus as the
Puerto Rican Day Parade broke up last weekend. Several women have
complained that officers did nothing when they complained of sexual
assaults inside Central Park. Several other people have said that
officers seemed to tolerate the rampant use of marijuana and
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials, who deny drug use or criminal activity were
routinely overlooked, spent several days last week compiling
statistics to show that enforcement at this year's parade was as
diligent as in the past. For example, they said, police issued 686
summonses that day for a variety of offenses like public drinking,
nearly double the prior year's total.
</P>
<P>
   If there is an enforcement issue, several officers said, it is
that police historically use more discretion at the Puerto Rican
Day Parade because many officers believe their superiors are not
interested in seeing any confrontations between a largely white
police force and Hispanic paradegoers.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials say that statistics from other parades clearly
demonstrate that officers are as aggressive at the Puerto Rican
event as at any other. For example, they said there were only 200
bottles or cans of beer and liquor confiscated at the St. Patrick's
Day Parade this year, while police took away 2,601 bottles and cans
from revelers last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   To some who spent last Sunday in Central Park, however, the
numerical data seem like a lot of statistical legerdemain. Peter N.
Duhamel, who jogs in the park each week, said that during his
afternoon run through the park that day, officers seemed to have
turned a blind eye to misbehavior like public drinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were in a stand-down posture,'' said Duhamel, a former
assistant United States attorney. ``From South Drive to 110th
Street, it was the same posture, depending on your perspective,
either cavalier or casual.''
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir has said that no one was given
orders to look the other way on any illegal activity at the parade.
Asked if it were possible that some officers did not act because
they were concerned about being accused of racial insensitivity,
Safir said, ``That is always a possibility. With all of the
hyperbole that has gone on over the years, certainly that could be
in the police officer's mind.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many officers, including those who acknowledged lapses in police
tactics last weekend, said they felt stung by the speed with which,
in the eyes of their critics, they have gone from overaggressive to
indifferent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we go to a parade and the criticism is that they did not
enforce the law strictly enough,'' a senior police supervisor said.
``I think they would like to know what the plan is.''
</P>
<P>
   The aggressiveness of police enforcement efforts has been a
source of debate for several years, in large part because city
officials have credited their focus on quality-of-life offenses and
their use of proactive patrol strategies as having been central to
the city's dramatic reduction in crime. More recently, however,
experts like former Police Commissioner William J. Bratton have
questioned whether the city's approach, which he helped fashion at
a time of high crime, is outdated, even counterproductive at a time
when the murder rate has declined by two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   The debate grew particularly heated after the police shooting
last year of Amadou Diallo, when many critics questioned whether
the seeds of the tragedy had been planted in an enforcement
strategy they characterized as overzealous. In the weeks following
that shooting, as the public outcry grew, police officials said
many officers demoralized by the withering criticism were no longer
patrolling as aggressively and cited this as a leading factor in
the rising murder rate.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But several months later, officials said that morale had
improved and that enforcement efforts, particularly seizures of
illegal guns, were returning to prior levels. Earlier this year,
the scrutiny of police enforcement tactics returned with a
vengeance when an undercover narcotics officer, pushing to make
drug arrests in midtown Manhattan, ended up in a dispute with
Patrick Dorismond, a man who had objected to being solicited for
drugs. Dorismond was fatally shot in an incident that is still
being investigated by a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of that shooting, many public officials
questioned whether patrol strategies had become too confrontational
and their targets too trivial. But the furor had died down in
recent weeks, especially after Mayor Rudolph Giuliani bowed out of
the race for the U.S. Senate. Some people inside and outside Police
Headquarters say the pressure that officers felt to produce
ever-declining crime rates has waned in tandem with Giuliani's
political ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   The department denies there has been any change in policy or any
relaxation in enforcement. A police union official, Sgt. Bernard
Pound, the president of the Sergeants Benevolent Association, said
he agreed. ``I get no sense that cops are doing anything other than
what comes naturally to them,'' he said. ``If they see something
wrong, they are righting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, several commanders said they had overheard the talk
in the locker rooms and muster rooms of the city's station houses
about whether a Police Department that has been under great
pressure to produce for several years may now get a chance to catch
its breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have heard this ever since Rudy stopped running,'' said one
investigative supervisor from Brooklyn. ``People on the job will
say, `Now maybe things will calm down a bit.' But that is just the
lazy people who are looking for an excuse. It goes back to being a
professional.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
