<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE CHALLENGES OF ABUNDANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, June 18:
</P>
<P>
   A deadly familiarity has crept into the debate between Vice
President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush. Last week, as Gore
embarked on a new series of ``prosperity and progress'' speeches,
Bush immediately derided his efforts as ``Al Gore's `I Invented
Prosperity' Tour.'' Underneath the surface of such exchanges,
however, the political terrain may be undergoing some redefinition.
For the first time in decades, a presidential race is occurring at
a time of economic abundance and budget surpluses. These unusual
circumstances are testing the creativity of both major candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, hemmed in by massive budget deficits inherited
from the Reagan years, President Clinton could not deliver on his
promises to stimulate the economy with major investments in
infrastructure and other programs. But suddenly the candidates are
now arguing over what to do with surpluses that no candidates in
recent history have enjoyed. This has allowed Gore, who has been
stumbling for months, to present the public with a detailed policy
agenda of spending proposals. It has also allowed Bush to warn _
echoing the traditional anti-government rhetoric of Republican
candidates _ that the money must not be commandeered by federal
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Their sparring is driven by new but as yet unannounced budget
projections for the next 10 years. A 10-year surplus that in April
was projected by the Congressional Budget Office to be nearly $900
billion if spending remained at realistic levels could now turn out
to be between $1.5 trillion and $2 trillion. The surplus is based
on prudent economic assumptions, but it could of course shrink if
there was an economic downturn, or if Republicans managed to ram
through a lot of their proposed tax cuts for the rich this year.
</P>
<P>
   Gore proposes to use the extra money for an accelerated program
to retire the national debt and to set up three ``trust funds'' for
health care, the environment and education. He argues that his
approach is more fiscally prudent than Bush's, especially because
it aims to make America debt-free for the first time since the
1830s. For its part, the Bush campaign will argue that its tax cut
of more than $1 trillion over 10 years is now more affordable than
before, and that spending the surplus is a decision best left to
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns seem aware of surveys showing that Americans are
not nearly as angry about the government as they were in the early
or even the mid-1990s. The Gore campaign is tapping into an
emerging American recognition that economic change has made it more
urgent for government to train workers, invest in health and
research, and protect families left behind or hurt by new rules in
the workplace and marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential contest has not caught fire with the voters
quite yet. Two men of privilege approaching the White House with a
sense of entitlement does little to fire the imagination. But if
they can make this campaign a genuine discussion of the
opportunities posed by abundance, it could mark a turning point.
The first glimmerings of such a debate should be encouraged rather
than dismissed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
