<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ROWING INTO THE AARP SUNSET 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT in parentheses has been used in
the next to last graf instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to some newspaper systems.) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHELTER ISLAND, N.Y _ Bill Lenderking, a big old guy, 6 feet 4
inches tall, 66 years old, sits on his big old porch, stretching
out his knobby old legs, sipping a beer. Finally, he says: ``It's
not like it's some real adventure. I'm not risking my life.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll find out what he's risking along the way. The
plan-in-progress is for Lenderking and three younger old guys to
row their boats from the South Street Seaport in Lower Manhattan to
Shelter Island, where he rowed as a kid. He has hardly rowed since.
This is about a 120-mile pull, four or five days through the
treacherous currents of Hell Gate, over the June millpond of Long
Island Sound along the North Shore, around the tip of Orient Point,
into the ferocious tides of Plum Gut and then the sheltered waters
between the Forks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be rowing with the tide,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hardly `Deliverance,''' snorts his wife, Susan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wanted to take a calculated risk,'' he says.
``What's the worst that could happen? That I can't handle it, that
I can't keep up? This isn't crazy, it's not Everest.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was Annapurna, 23 years ago, when Lenderking wandered
away from the group and fell down the mountain. He walked five days
back from base camp with several broken ribs. He was then in the
Foreign Service, posted to Thailand. He also served in Cuba,
Bolivia and Vietnam, where he cheerfully admits, with his ruddy,
blue-eyed confidence, that he was one of the ``propagandists''
selling the pacification program. The government pensioned him off
five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess age has something to do with all this,'' admits
Lenderking. ``After I retired at 61, I thought I'd have no trouble
getting work. I had a lot of experience. But I could see
interviewers' eyes just glaze over. Even if I had had technical
skills, which I don't, these Internet start-ups wouldn't be
interested in me.''
</P>
<P>
   He has struggled to chart a new course. He says he has made
wrong turns. He qualified to be a stockbroker, but didn't like it.
He finished a novel, which he describes as a psychological thriller
about a Foreign Service officer, but hasn't sold it. He has done
some consulting, and established an online business selling modern
first-edition books, which has accumulated more pleasure than
money.
</P>
<P>
   Lenderking is not quite sure when the rowing idea actually took
hold. The first person he called was David Stookey of Newport,
R.I., an international businessman and old friend who three years
ago began publishing a newsletter, ``Open-Water Rowing.'' He asked
Stookey if the idea was ``doable.'' It certainly was for Stookey,
57, an enthusiast fired by the image of ``unclubbable loners'' like
rowers as a group. He pulled in two of his readers, John Mullen of
Dallas and Louis Mackall of Branford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Mullen, who is 58, started rowing at 40. He says that his height
_ 6-7 _ rather than his technique or conditioning helped him become
a masters sculling champion. He has never rowed this long or in a
group. He said, ``This is a stretch for me, and I'm at an age when
I'm looking for stretches.''
</P>
<P>
   His best friend and fellow Yale-trained architect, the
58-year-old Mackall, tries to start every day with a row. He began
rowing 12 years ago. ``My theory is that all the bending mashes the
internal organs in ways nothing else does,'' he said. ``So you've
got beauty and exercise, a killer sunrise, and you feel fabulous
all day long.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he has rowed more than 20 miles of a day, Mackall has
never taken an overnight trip. He calls it an experiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not meant to be a stunt,'' said Stookey, who had to be
reminded that it was Lenderking's idea, not his. ``It's just a row,
not a race. Call it cruising or touring; some guys out to see the
world. Of course, it would be good for open water rowing and the
newsletter. There's a Web site, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, on Stookey's advice, Lenderking drove up to Ontario
to buy a 17-foot Loudon fiberglass boat for $2,200. On the drive
back, he will stop to practice with Stookey in Newport. The
schedule has the four boats going up the East River on Monday
morning, June 26. With luck, they will pull into Gardiner's Creek
on Shelter Island June 29 or June 30. Mullen and Mackall will row
to their Hamptons houses the next day.
</P>
<P>
   I'm taking requests on this one. Tell thelipsite(at)aol.com. If
you're interested, I will climb off my bike and cover this trip,
which seems to fall between the buoys of the zeitgeist. At one
marker is the explosion of extreme manufactured sports _ on my wall
is a photo, sent by her agent, of the 31-year-old ``adventure
athlete/action model'' Rebecca Rusch, climbing a rock wearing only
shoes. At the other, under a gold-plated AARP sunset, is the
implicit pressure of extreme prescription drugs _ to make us feel
mellower, to grow more hair and have better sex.
</P>
<P>
   It is not lost on people of a certain age that the first two
discards of the TV super hit, ``Survivors,'' were 62 and 60 years
old. Of our rowboat survivors, only Lenderking had heard of the
program; the other three are serious rowers with little time for
popular culture, much less TV.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 1529EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000617.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7097 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-GIANTS-ROUNDTABLE     06-17 1440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-ROUNDTABLE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOOD, THE BAD AND THE DISTRACTING: LIFE OFF THE FOOTBALL
FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Instead of draft picks and free-agent signings, much of the news
of professional football this off-season has involved prosecutors,
indictments and trials. For the first time, two active NFL players
were accused of murder. Another was charged with sexually
assaulting a 17-year-old baby sitter.
</P>
<P>
   With the new season looming _ training camps open next month _
The New York Times invited five members of the New York Giants to
participate in a roundtable discussion with Thomas George, a
reporter who covers pro football, and other sports reporters and
editors. Tiki Barber, Greg Comella, Howard Cross, Sam Garnes and
Amani Toomer spoke last week for more than an hour about many
issues, both off the field and on. Here are excerpts of their
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What did you think of the coverage in the news media of the
murder charge against Rae Carruth, the murder trial of Ray Lewis
and the charges of sexual assault filed against Mark Chmura?
</P>
<P>
   HOWARD CROSS: I think, first of all, that back in the old days
when players were doing something, they would be famous and it
didn't matter what they did. Now that we have such high standards _
quote, unquote _ that if we do anything wrong, it's in the news.
Now, these guys got caught in bad situations or did whatever they
did wrong and the media covered it. But it doesn't make us any
different than anybody else.
</P>
<P>
   Because if I get stopped in a DUI (driving under the influence),
it's on ESPN. If I go to a bar and some guy has too much to drink
and wants to fight me and I defend myself, not only am I on ESPN,
but I'm also in jail, probably. I'm getting sued by the guy. If the
guy beats me up, I get sued and beat up. So I got a lot going on
there. We do live normal lives like everybody else and we do live
our lives to a higher standard, or most of us try to. There's a lot
fewer of us making mistakes than the others. And as for the
coverage, if it was the IRS and they had the chance between getting
you and getting me, they're going to get me. That's just the way it
works.
</P>
<P>
   GREG COMELLA: I think we as athletes do have a responsibility
first of all to ourselves and to our families, and along with that,
to our teammates, to our coaches, to the organizations we
represent, to society, because whether we like it or not, you know,
people do look up to us. But at the same time, I think professional
athletes probably get into trouble no more or no less than the
average person working at Microsoft or working at The New York
Times, for that matter. The difference is when I make a mistake,
it's going to be in the paper.
</P>
<P>
   TIKI BARBER: People don't look to find the truth. They just look
to put the story out there and whatever spin they feel is going to
be more attractive. The prosecutor in the Ray Lewis case, he
charged Ray Lewis because he felt like it was going to be something
that was going to be big. He didn't get the facts. He wasn't
looking for the truth. He was just looking to charge Ray Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Most media outlets, when they first ran this story, it was Ray
Lewis is charged with murder. It wasn't that Ray Lewis may not have
been involved at all. Later down the road, that comes out. But
initially it's always the thing that's going to get the most
impact. It's always going to be the thing that sells papers. It's
always going to be the thing that draws attention to the
prosecutor. And it's not necessarily the truth. That's unfortunate,
but that's just the way society is. I mean, you'd much rather hear
bad news than good news.
</P>
<P>
   CROSS: And the funny thing is that Ray Lewis went through this
whole trial and they got him in jail and got him on TV and he even
pleads, says that he did some misdemeanor. Then the guys that were
accused of murder got off. Now Ray has to do community service. He
testifies, his friends get off and he's doing community service.
It's not right. But that's the way it works.
</P>
<P>
   COMELLA: Probably the first thing that comes to all our heads,
or at least it should, is, you know, it's obviously sad events for
the victims in this one, and sometimes that gets overlooked.
Sometimes we become numb to it, because you see it so much on
television, you see it in the newspapers, but when something hits
home, if you see a family member or a friend that's been through
something like that, certainly your heart goes out to the family
that has something tragic like that happen in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you respond when a teammate gets involved in a
situation at a bar or in a domestic problem that becomes public?
</P>
<P>
   AMANI TOOMER: When I see a story about one of the NFL players
getting involved, I may be skeptical, but I always think that the
media blows it up somehow. A month later you'll see the headlines,
the guy doesn't have anything to do with it. So I usually try to
wait and hold my judgment till after I get more facts.
</P>
<P>
   CROSS: For our team, we're here talking to a person every day.
It's like, everything OK? Yeah, everything's all right, man, thanks
for asking. We go on with our lives. We've got to. The only
distraction maybe is for the player after practice when there's a
thousand cameras there and when people have their mikes up there
and they're like, well, did you do it or didn't you do it? And
that's bad for the player, we feel bad for him, but you have to
keep going.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you concerned that people may perceive you differently
because of the notorious cases over the last seven or eight months
involving NFL players?
</P>
<P>
   SAM GARNES: I'm from the Bronx. I hang out with some of my
friends, just the typical guys that you might think look like
troublemakers, but we're just regular guys and we're not going to
change just because I'm in the NFL. I've been a good person up to
now, and I'm not going to change the way I dress or what kind of
car I have just because I'm in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   And you know, you don't see or hear about how he's got
foundations or we're giving up our tight-scheduled time to go talk
to kids. But as soon as we make a slight mistake, you know somebody
might go out to a bar, might be having dinner, have a couple of
drinks, been there a little longer than expected, have four, five
drinks. Made a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   It's no good to drink and drive because a lot of things come
from it, but they made a mistake. And as soon as they get pulled
over, it's in the paper even though there wasn't any violation.
Notice they didn't get into trouble, get into accidents or anything
like that. It's in the paper and we're a bad guy. That's all you
remember, that one pullover by the police.
</P>
<P>
   I take up my time and I love the kids. Just because I make a
mistake doesn't mean I don't love doing the right thing. I just
made a mistake just like any human being. That bothers me a lot,
personally.
</P>
<P>
   CROSS: We don't want any awards or anything.
</P>
<P>
   GARNES: No, we don't want any awards.
</P>
<P>
   CROSS: But we're doing it because we're trying to give back to
the community and everything. And I don't need the press there.
</P>
<P>
   GARNES: Definitely.
</P>
<P>
   COMELLA: What amazed me is, when Derrick Thomas passed away last
winter, it took an event like that, a death, for all those
wonderful news reports about the type of person he was. It's just
sad that you don't see more reports about the type of individuals
some of these guys are, like a Derrick Thomas, that it has to take
such a tragic event like that for that stuff to come out.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Sam, you mentioned that you hang out with your friends.
Acquaintances, entourages, hangers-on, that's become part of the
problem now?
</P>
<P>
   GARNES: Not really. I don't think so. I mean, my friends aren't
troublemakers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: No, no. Not you, but in general. That's what people were
saying about Ray Lewis, that he was hanging out with the wrong
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   GARNES: Like I said, I'm from the Bronx, so you know there's a
lot of things going on in the Bronx, and I know I had to cut
certain people off. They're still my friends, but they respect the
fact that I can't be around that. I think you have to make choices
on your own, who you hang out with, because they could do something
_ I mean, they might not even want you involved in what they're
doing _ but if you go out with them and they get in some trouble,
they're going to say, well, Sam Garnes was there also. And that's
going to sell newspapers, like Tiki said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think that now you have to be more careful?
</P>
<P>
   BARBER: I think guys take the responsibility that they have to
be careful as soon as they get into the professional ranks. You
know, people think they don't have to be role models all the time,
but we are role models, whether we like it or not. Kids are going
to look up to you. I believe it should be the parents' job to say _
OK, say I'm a good role model, a parent should say, OK, Tiki does
the right things. But say you have someone who gets in trouble all
the time, he should be able to say, well, this guy isn't doing the
right things. Compare and contrast, don't just let the kid decide,
because sometimes he'll think that the guy who's doing the bad is
the cool guy.
</P>
<P>
   But as far as hanging out with your friends, you don't want to
cut them off, because these are the guys, when you were nobody,
when you were growing up, these were your friends. They supported
you. That's when you build most of your friendships that you're
going to have for the rest of your life. And sometimes it's hard to
cut that off. But you have to when you're a professional athlete,
because things are different, times change. It's not the same. Even
though guys would like it to be, it's not.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think pro athletes are held to an unfair standard?
</P>
<P>
   CROSS: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   BARBER: Oh, without a doubt. I think athletes are held to the
standard of society is great, so they should be great. We're not
all great. We're not always doing the right things. Sometimes we do
falter and take bad steps.
</P>
<P>
   COMELLA: I don't think that we are held to too high of a
standard. I think we've been given a lot of opportunities. I think
we've had chances to do things that 99 percent of this country
never even conceives, never thinks about. So is the standard that
we're held to different? Absolutely.
</P>
<P>
   BARBER: Well, doesn't different mean higher?
</P>
<P>
   COMELLA: Yeah, it may be higher, but what I think is, we're
given a lot.
</P>
<P>
   CROSS: Blessed a lot so you're required to do a lot.
</P>
<P>
   COMELLA: That's what I believe.
</P>
<P>
   CROSS: See, the problem is not that we're held to a higher
standard, which we are. It's just that it is unfair. Because
everybody puts you, like, OK, you have made it. Blessed with
skills, whether it's speed or height or strength or whatever. I
didn't ask to be 6-6 and 270. I didn't ask for that. And thank God
for it. I didn't even want to be a football player. I thought I was
going to be in the NBA. It didn't work out that way.
</P>
<P>
   And I get a higher standard. When I go out I'm really nice to
kids. I'm really nice to people that come up and speak to me, even
when they're rude. I've had guys step up and, ``Excuse me, miss,''
put their hand on my wife and move her out of the way just so they
can talk to me. And she's like, ``Are you kidding me?'' And I'm
like, ``Honey, don't hit him.''
</P>
<P>
   COMELLA: I think the standard is such because people look at us
and very much admire what it is we're doing.
</P>
<P>
   BARBER: You know what it is, it's a dream. When you're a little
kid you dream to be a professional athlete. And now that we're
professional athletes people think that our lives are a dream. How
would you dream the perfect life? I want to be a professional
basketball player, have a big Mercedes, a big house and live a
perfect life.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So you think it's the money?
</P>
<P>
   BARBER No, it has nothing to do with the money. It's just the
dream. Athletes aren't the only dreams now. Bill Gates is a dream
now for kids. Times have changed, society has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think that the kids see you as any less of an idol or
role model than kids did when Y.A. Tittle was playing?
</P>
<P>
   BARBER: I don't think so. They have more role models now, not
just athletes. It's transcended into other sectors of life, which I
think is a good thing. But I also think it's a bad thing. They get
caught up in not experiencing life fully.
</P>
<P>
   CROSS: We've got a society of people that want to see gore,
right? Like movies with blood and gore, everybody runs to the
theater to see people get shot up. When there's an accident on the
highway, almost every car stops and looks over. We are held to a
higher standard, because our society decides we like to see blood
and gore. You guys better be good or else we're going to tell on
you.
</P>
<P>
   TOOMER: I think some of it has to do with the fact that they
want to set you up to be kind of a star and then they want to know
the dirt behind you. They want to know the faults of everybody.
They just don't want to see somebody up there who has no faults.
They kind of get bored with that. They want to know the person more
than just the good things they do. They want to know what are the
faults, what are his weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   CROSS: They don't want you to be perfect. Like how many of you
guys, in all honesty, when you watched the U.S. Open last year and
John Daly took that 11 on that hole, how many of you were like, oh,
yeah, I could do that. He kept hitting the ball, hitting the ball.
He took an 11 on the hole, everybody's done it. But John Daly, now,
he's a pro, he shouldn't do that. But it was something you wanted
to see.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some people have said that some football players have a hard
time leaving the violence on the field. Is it difficult to be asked
to be violent on the field and then to be model citizens when you
walk off it?
</P>
<P>
   CROSS: You're Christmas shopping or whatever, you're going to
the mall. Somebody accidentally cuts you off. What do you do?
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm pretty meek about it usually.
</P>
<P>
   CROSS: Ma'am, what about you?
</P>
<P>
   Q: I go nuts.
</P>
<P>
   CROSS: Exactly. You're human. I've seen people in the car, like
ladies, will just give me the finger. What are you doing? But if an
athlete does it, we can't separate our two worlds. So I want to
know what's the difference between a lady having road rage, and a
man getting upset at another man and one of the men happens to be
an athlete?
</P>
<P>
   COMELLA: The thing is, that's who we are, we're football
players. And the bottom line is on the football field we are
positively reinforced the more we destroy. That's the nature of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   CROSS: It's not close to that, Greg. You're making it sound like
that. When we're playing football, Greg has a play, the draw. The
fullback leads up on the linebacker. They're running at each other.
Linebacker's got to fill a hole; Greg's got to knock him out of the
hole.
</P>
<P>
   That's a violent play to you guys. To Greg, it's just doing his
job. That's not like a really violent thing, that's just Greg doing
his job. The linebacker's doing his job.
</P>
<P>
   When Greg gets in his car to go home that day, somebody cuts him
off and he yells at him, he's not taking his job off the field. He
didn't take his car and ram it into the guy. His insurance wouldn't
pay, he'd lose his insurance. Instead, he just keeps going.
</P>
<P>
   TOOMER: I don't know. I think what he's talking about is not
just those type of incidents. I'm talking about if you go to a club
and then somebody touches you or grabs you or something like that,
then I can understand his question.
</P>
<P>
   CROSS: Physically, I'm a meek person, I wouldn't fight for
nothing. But if you put your hands on me, I've got to defend
myself. I'm not going to let you hurt me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Let's talk a little about entitlement, which is the flip side
of being held to a higher standard. By the time you get to be an
all-American, there are people who ordinarily would not give you
the time of day who suddenly want to know you. The answers become
yes, instead of no.
</P>
<P>
   CROSS: You get a lot more of that than anything else. You get
that celebrity status and people do know you and people are
offering you meals and cutting you into the front of the line. For
every one of those that happens, there's another group of people
that are like, ``Oh, he doesn't deserve anything.'' There are some
places still in Alabama _ ``Hey, that's Howard Cross from the
Giants. He played for Alabama. That's a black guy, man.'' You're
still black. I didn't do anything special.
</P>
<P>
   GARNES: You get more good things from being an athlete, being a
professional football player. But it's just that when that one
thing happens that's negative, that's how everybody views you from
then on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
