<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-TIGER-TUSSLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWDOWN OVER TIGER COMPOUND NEARS; OWNER VOWS TO KEEP ANIMALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARIA NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON TOWNSHIP, N.J. _ To get to the thickly forested preserve
where Joan Byron-Marasek keeps 24 tigers, you have to go past the
Six Flags Outlet Mall just off Interstate 195, and through a busy
intersection with three gas stations and a Methodist church. If you
come across a new development of large, expensive homes, you've
gone a bit too far.
</P>
<P>
   When Byron-Marasek and her husband, Jan Marasek, moved to this
enclave in South Jersey 24 years ago and began acquiring tigers,
they were practically out in the wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   But now the modern world is pressing in on the 15-acre domain of
Byron-Marasek, better known as the Tiger Lady. And with development
has come a host of other forces knocking on her 25-foot-high iron
gate: angry neighbors, who have filed lawsuits saying her preserve
is incompatible with their neighborhood; the town and the Ocean
County Society for Prevention of Cruelty to Animals, who have filed
complaints in municipal court over the 35 dogs she keeps in the
compound; and the state Department of Environmental Protection,
which is nearing a showdown in its yearlong effort to close her
Tigers Only Preservation Society.
</P>
<P>
   State officials, citing poor conditions at the compound, have
given her until the end of the month to present a plan detailing
how she will remove the tigers from her property.
</P>
<P>
   But the Tiger Lady has dug in her heels. Not only has she
refused to plan for the tigers' removal, but the normally reclusive
couple have also begun a public relations effort to appeal to other
animal lovers or to anyone who agrees that she is the victim of
government intrusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are saying, `If they can do this to her, they'll do
this to all of us,''' she said of those who have come to her
support, including the owner of the fence company who donated the
chain-link barrier around a new part of the complex.
</P>
<P>
   She has even started a Web site to solicit donations and gather
names on a petition asking Gov. Christie Whitman to allow the
preserve to stay open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing is not an option,'' Byron-Marasek said, while showing
visitors through her compound. ``I have to stay positive. This is
my life. I'll fight to keep them. I mean fight legally, with
appeals, whatever it takes to legally fight them.''
</P>
<P>
   Byron-Marasek does not allow many people into her small world,
and she does not leave it very often, either. She and her husband
work full time tending to the tigers, who live in pens surrounded
by 18-foot-high chain-link fencing, connected to each other and to
40-foot trailers where the tigers can go to escape the heat or
cold.
</P>
<P>
   The couple are the only ones, save for occasional volunteers,
who care for the tigers. They spend much of their time inside the
cages with the animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not afraid of them,'' said Byron-Marasek, a small-boned
woman who, at 5 feet 2 inches tall, is dwarfed by the 400- to
600-pound tigers, which stand at the fence on their hind legs when
she approaches and rub their noses to hers. ``I understand them.
But I, too, can get tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Byron-Marasek is stingy with details about her personal life.
She will not reveal her age or where she was born. She will say
that she worked as a circus trapeze artist as a teen-ager, and that
she grew close to some of the animal trainers. She was an actress
on Broadway, performing in Tom Stoppard's ``Jumpers,'' in which she
swung from a chandelier using her teeth and legs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, she left the theater, and she and her husband bought
the property in Jackson Township. She bought five 8-week-old tigers
after obtaining a state permit.
</P>
<P>
   Byron-Marasek ended up with as many tigers as she has in part
because she allows the animals to inbreed, which some animal rights
groups say can produce unhealthy animals. She says she keeps the
tigers to help preserve the species, and because she loves them.
The state says her permit allows her to keep such animals only if
she exhibits them, but she cannot present evidence that she does.
</P>
<P>
   Her troubles began in January 1999, when police killed a tiger
wandering in the area. State officials say the tiger was
Byron-Marasek's, but she denies that.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, state inspectors have made more frequent unannounced
visits, and Byron-Marasek has made improvements to the compound,
like a concrete border to keep the tigers from digging their way
out. She and her lawyer, Valter Must, say the state keeps changing
the rules. But state officials say the rules are clear-cut and
intended to protect the tigers and the public.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the state wants her to provide up-to-date records
on how many animals she has, and their medical histories. In the
last two months, said Sharon Southard, a spokeswoman for the
Department of Environmental Protection, two cubs died.
Byron-Marasek did not report the deaths until days later, she said,
and did not provide definitive records from her veterinarian on the
cause of death, which was believed to be salmonella.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that Joan loves these tigers,'' Southard
said. ``But there are a couple of fundamental issues here, and one
is that you can't have all these animals. Period. It's against the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   As she sat under the pines, Byron-Marasek spread out a stack of
documents to make her case that the state is trying to take her
land because it has become valuable, and that the state's so-called
tiger experts do not know as much as she does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I eat, sleep and breathe tigers,'' she said. ``I never take
vacations. This is my love, my passion. The thought of losing my
animals, I just can't bear it. I just want to believe that they
won't take them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
