<SLUG> BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A MATTER OF PRISMS AND PERSPECTIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also FBN-GIANTS-ROUNDTABLE)  
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than once, Howard Cross or one of his Giants
teammates looked across the table at editors and reporters and
prefaced a remark with ``No offense to you guys'' or ``Nothing
personal, but ...'' Then the players would offer a polite but
pointed critique of the sports news media.
</P>
<P>
   This was Thursday afternoon. Five members of the Giants
graciously agreed to march behind the lines and meet with the
enemy. Cross, Amani Toomer, Sam Garnes, Greg Comella and Tiki
Barber sat in a conference room with New York Times editors and
reporters, engaged in a two-pronged discussion. We talked about the
coming football season and then tackled issues surrounding the rash
of off-the-field incidents that have marred the image of the
contemporary professional athlete.
</P>
<P>
   The impetus for this meeting was a new season, and the serious
and troubling issues surrounding the trial of Ray Lewis, who was
charged with murder and subsequently pleaded guilty to a
misdemeanor. What came through was the players' mistrust of,
frustration with and resentment of the news media. The notion that
athletes have targets on their backs, and the news media aim and
shoot, acting like a civilian review board.
</P>
<P>
   What athletes do and how the news media interpret what they do,
how reporters cover and uncover the actions, deeds and misdeeds and
disseminate information to the public, are sources of tension
between the athletes and the editors and reporters. ``What do
people want to hear?'' Barber said. ``I mean, your job is to sell
papers, right? And you don't want to put out news that nobody wants
to read.''
</P>
<P>
   Barber said what bothers him is that ``people don't look to find
the truth.'' He added: ``They just look to put the story out there
and whatever spin they feel like is going to be more attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   But even the players didn't agree on everything. Are pro
athletes held to unfair standards?
</P>
<P>
   Cross: ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Barber: ``Oh, without a doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Comella: ``I don't think that we are held to too high of a
standard. I think we've had chances to do things that 99 percent of
this country never even conceives.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of the complaints about being targets, Cross conceded
that pro athletes were also objects of affection, that they were
given many things.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get that celebrity status, and people do know you and
people are offering you meals and cutting you into the front of the
line,'' he said. ``For every one of those that happens, there's
another group of people that are like, `Oh, he doesn't deserve
anything.' There are some places still in Alabama: `Hey, that's
Howard Cross from the Giants. He played for Alabama. That's a black
guy, man.' You're still black.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Garnes disagreed. ``You get more good things from being an
athlete, being a professional football player,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked the players why public sentiment seemed to be
turning against professional athletes, particularly basketball and
football players.
</P>
<P>
   Toomer said he felt that news media portrayals and the public's
penchant to know dirt were greater factors than any problem that
might exist in the league. ``In society, people want to set you up
to be kind of a star and then they want to know the dirt behind
you,'' he said. ``They want to know the person more than just by
the good things they do.''
</P>
<P>
   The news media oblige by dredging up the dirt and dishing it. Of
course, if there's no dirt to be dredged up, it can't be dished.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I think we love heroes more; we choose the fallen and
the wretched because they are in such abundance. We love the heroic
instinct, the heroic attempt. Outside of stadiums and arenas, there
is so little room for heroes; the individual has been reduced and
minimized by the onslaught of progress. Minimized by corporations
devouring corporations. The monster eventually begins feeding on
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Professional athletes _ Cross, Comella, Garnes, Barber, Toomer,
the star goalie, the swimmer _ rely on arms, legs and muscles. They
play on a level field, or as level as possible. They play by a set
of rules enforced by officials _ sometimes for better, sometimes
for worse _ who drop the flag or blow the whistle to keep the field
level.
</P>
<P>
   The games are so unlike the real world, where wealth and power
usually reign side by side with skulduggery in pursuit of wealth
and power. The athlete, in an odd way, offers salvation. Maybe this
is the underlying reason for fan anger when an athlete falls from
grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want you to be perfect,'' Cross said.
</P>
<P>
   After more than an hour, the meeting broke up. Everyone shook
hands and headed back to his or her own world.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting raised more questions than answers. Some of us want
to see more introspection from athletes about problems in the
professional leagues. From the athletes' perspective, the problem
is we, with our pens and cameras. Taking it all in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
