<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSE AND MILLER POSTPONE THE SHAQ AND KOBE CORONATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The game was in the vault an hour before. Reggie
Miller had pulled the pin on his last 3-pointer, and Jalen Rose had
peeled and sliced a defense purported to be the league's most
stingy.
</P>
<P>
   So all the two emotional scorers for the Indiana Pacers had left
to do was not anger the gods any further, be happy with their
33-point knockout over Shaquille O'Neal, Kobe Bryant and the Los
Angeles Lakers in Game 5 of the National Basketball Association
finals. Catch a flight to Los Angeles for Game 6. Maybe a humble
statement or two, and that's it. Move on.
</P>
<P>
   But they could not help themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, a lot of the scuffles are coming from them, which is a
shock,'' Miller replied with biting sarcasm when asked about
growing tension between the teams. ``Everyone thinks they're so
nice and pretty and, you know, they're the glamour boys, it's Los
Angeles. Evian. Caffe latte, all that. They're doing all the
pushing, the holding. They look at the refs like they're not doing
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Having carved up Glen Rice and anyone else Phil Jackson sicced
on him in the 120-87 blowout on Friday night, Rose wondered openly
who could stop him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you come out on me, contest a 3 and allow me to get my
dribble-drive game going, or do you double-team me in the post and
allow me to pass and get other guys involved?'' he inquired.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the Shaq-and-Kobe coronation has been
temporarily postponed by two stick figures. Outweighed and
outmuscled, Miller and Rose are the annoying-gnat-type players you
shove aside to grab the rebound, the obnoxious, tagalong siblings
you cannot quite ditch.
</P>
<P>
   But you look further and you realize their edge _ that spiteful
guard-me-if-you-can demeanor _ is why the Pacers forced a return
trip to L.A. before their loud legions at the Conseco Fieldhouse
Friday night. They combined for 57 points and 8 three-pointers,
doing most of the damage in a barrage that hit the Lakers hard,
shook their foundation and again raised doubts about their ability
to close out an opponent ready to drop.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, Miller was staring coldly at the Laker bench, Rose
was laughing at Rick Fox. Miller and Mark Jackson each were
assessed technical fouls with 11 minutes left in the fourth period
and the game already out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   It was not Larry Bird's kind of act.
</P>
<P>
   Hoosiers play by unspoken rules. You don't show up the opponent.
Once you move to Indiana, you're supposed to play how the coach
tells you to play. Give up your urban roots and give in to
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Bird hates the taunting, the shimmying, the finger-pointing of
Jackson, Miller and Rose. But can the Pacers coach have it both
ways? As one of the game's all-time purveyors of verbal trash, Bird
is a bit of revisionist historian.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers thrive off their emotions. Rose does not care what
the score is or who is defending him. When Miller is ahead by 20,
he gets more greedy, yelling at his teammates to give him the ball
so he can plunge in another 3-point dagger.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is 35 years old. His lack of foot speed prevents him
from beating many retired players off the dribble. But there he
was, strutting down a corridor of the arena, humming an old rap
tune on Friday night _ an old-school player paying homage to an
old-school artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't put it any better than LL Cool J, who said, `We're
going back to Cali,''' Jackson said. ``That was our theme song
before tonight's game. We went with that mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   When told Bird was upset by their outbursts, he replied, ``I'm
not going to get into, you know, the coach, his opinion. I think as
leaders of this basketball team, we have to spark something to make
a statement that we're not going to lay down.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller became prickly when asked if Bird's last game at home
meant something to the team. ``It was the last game for a lot of
guys in there, not just Larry,'' he said. ``We're facing
elimination.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Rose played the game as well as it can be played on
Friday night, finding open spaces and each other, turning the court
into a Woodenesque clinic, a hoop choreographer's dream where
everyone makes the right play.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half alone, the Rose and Miller detonated for 42
points. The defining play came with Miller racing down the court,
leading the break, dumping it off to Rose for a two-handed dunk on
the left side.
</P>
<P>
   The evolution of Rose and Miller thriving in the same starting
lineup together is more impressive than Allan Houston and Latrell
Sprewell sharing the same floor space and complementing each other
games. Rose did not start last season. He took Chris Mullin's spot
and cut into Derrick McKey's playing time, adding a new dynamic to
the motion offense.
</P>
<P>
   It was so new, Miller's head spun early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took some time for us to find a balance with one another,
you know,'' he said. ``I was so used to working with Derrick as
well as Chris Mullin the last two and three years. But it took time
for us to get our rhythm, especially our motion play, on which side
both of us liked. Now that we found a comfortable balance between
the two, it's starting to show just a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers still have a steep climb, but who believed they would
last this long? Two, irrepressible, rangy scorers _ one allegedly
past his prime and the other not yet an All-Star _ giving arguably
the team with the top two players in the NBA a genuine scrap for
the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're still the team in control, but we're still the team
that has fight,'' Rose said. ``We know California is going to be
ready to celebrate. We heard about the parade that they have
planned. That won't be tomorrow, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Miller: ``We absolutely, positively have nothing to lose
and everything in the world to gain. So we are going to play lose,
free, we don't care. There's no pressure on us. All the pressure is
on them. From the get-go, they were supposed to beat us. They were
supposed to sweep us.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the coach, they were supposed to make a humble
statement or two. Catch a flight. Move on. But Miller and Rose
cannot help themselves. They're not Hoosiers at heart. They're
ballplayers, looking for one more decent run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
