<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-FATHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEN SEARCHING FOR ROAD MAP ON EVER-EVOLVING ROLE OF FATHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATT PURDY   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHASSET, N.Y. _ Children know their place, or ought to. And
mothers are mothers, those natural-born nurturers. But fathers,
after all these years, are still hunters, searching for their
perfect role.
</P>
<P>
   The search begins in places like the maternity ward at North
Shore University Hospital here, where the babies are cute, the
mothers maternal and the fathers a mixed bag. They all know that,
as one new father said, the days of ``Me Ug, you Woman'' are long
gone. But now what?
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're expected to do more in terms of changing diapers and
formula and getting up in the middle of the night,'' said Dr.
Jonathan Klein, 31, a podiatrist whose first child was born last
week. But on Day 2 of Klein's grand adventure, with his wife
recovering in bed and far-off visions of tossing a ball to young
Eric Matthew just setting in, the babe was suddenly wailing. Klein
scrambled for support staff. ``I'm looking for the phone,'' he
said, ``to call her mother, my mother. Where the hell is
everyone?''
</P>
<P>
   He was never big on holding babies. But when his was born,
``they handed him to me,'' he said. ``I had no choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that he wanted a choice _ just a road map _ as he headed
happily and inexorably toward his first Father's Day. After all,
not all fathers are like that plumber down the hall who was
handling his day-old daughter as expertly as he would PVC pipe.
</P>
<P>
   You might expect a plumber for the New York City Fire Department
to be a hands-on guy. But this?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there for the whole thing,'' said Pat Brazill, 30, of
his wife's 23 hours of labor with baby Kaitlyn. ``I didn't miss a
minute of it. I even told the doctor to give me some tools. I'll
help you out.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's fathers who need help. The playing field of
parental responsibility is leveling. But for all the magazines and
books advising fathers, they're still scrambling for footing. If
mothers teeter on the high wire stretched between home and work,
fathers are like Mr. Potato Heads, endlessly trying out
combinations of parts. (How about the head of a Guinness Stout, the
body of a Ferrari, the cool of Joe Torre and the portfolio of Anna
Kournikova?)
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Jorge, 33, the manager of a locksmith company in Queens
and the father of a 21-month-old son, was rhapsodizing on
fatherhood in a labor room with his very expectant wife, Yenny. He
loves arriving home from work to the squeal of ``Daddy!'' or
reading Disney books or watching television with his son, Dylan.
``I'll be watching basketball or baseball, and I'll say `Look,
there's the ball,''' Jorge said, ``And he'll say, `Ball, ball,
ball.'''
</P>
<P>
   He's exhilarated. ``I'm still trying to get used to the fact
that I'm a father,'' he said. ``It still hasn't sunk in, 21 months
later.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife was exhausted, braving contractions. Over the sound of
the heart monitor, she said, ``It better sink in this time,
right?''
</P>
<P>
   Rosemarie Ennis, a health educator at the hospital, said she was
a bit taken aback when a man showed up alone at a breast-feeding
class. ``I looked at him, and he said `Why are you looking at me?
My wife's not feeling well,''' she said. Not surprisingly, ``he had
the most questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Even among the newly minted fathers, you can pick out those who
one day will be loudly working the cell phone on the soccer
sideline or struggling to take a teen-ager's tattoo in stride. Not
that fatherhood is predictable anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Wendland grew up in a Long Island neighborhood with lots
of firefighters who worked second jobs when they weren't dousing
flames. Now a New York City firefighter, Wendland uses his unusual
work schedule to care for his 3-year-old son most days. ``I
actually hang out with another fireman who's a friend,'' he said,
as his wife Andrea, a physician's assistant, was in labor with
their second child. ``We'll go to places you can hang out with your
kids, Chuck E. Cheese or Fun Zone.'' Their first time at Fun Zone,
on a Wednesday, he said, ``I was with my friend and we were
standing around and suddenly there were five of us. We were all
firemen.''
</P>
<P>
   Every now and then, Paul Epstein, an anesthesiologist at the
hospital and a father of three, turns to a soon-to-be-father as
he's easing the pain of an expectant mother, and asks, ``Do you
have any idea what you're getting into?''
</P>
<P>
   They never do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
