</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGAIN, LAKERS FAIL TO CLOSE OUT A SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ So much for the Los Angeles Lakers' new-found
ability to close out a series. With an opportunity to close out the
Indiana Pacers at Conseco Fieldhouse in Game 5 Friday night and
garner their first National Basketball Association title since
1988, the Lakers stumbled horribly. It wasn't the first time. In
close-out games against Sacramento, Phoenix and Portland, the
Lakers had bombed.
</P>
<P>
   But this time was supposed to be different. Entering Game 5 on
the Pacers' home court, the Lakers said they had learned to
maintain their focus. They claimed to understand the importance of
keeping their intensity, of squashing an opponent that is down.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, these are apparently the same old Lakers, the ones who
overwhelm opponents in building commanding series leads, only to
start coasting and give life to the other team.
</P>
<P>
   After slumbering for almost all 48 minutes in Friday's
embarrassing 120-87 loss to the Pacers, the Lakers are 3-6 this
postseason in games in which they could have eliminated an
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a sense of urgency that you have to have that we
haven't developed yet as a team,'' said A.C. Green, who won NBA
titles with the Lakers in 1987 and 1988. ``We just don't execute
and do the things necessary to win games when we have a team in the
hole.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, who will be back home Monday night for Game 6 at the
Staples Center, were quick to give the Pacers credit. But Friday's
stunning onslaught was about more than the Pacers' excellence.
</P>
<P>
   As it has done so many times this postseason, Los Angeles simply
did not come ready to play. After outrebounding the Pacers in three
of the first four games, the Lakers were beaten, 46-34, on the
boards. They made 4-of-19 3-pointers and shot 40 percent overall.
</P>
<P>
   Their defense was even worse. The league's stingiest team during
the regular season was ravaged for a 1970s-era point total and 57.4
percent shooting. As if shooting alone at a morning practice, the
Pacers shot 75 percent in the first quarter and reached the
50-point mark 6 minutes 18 seconds before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're upset with ourselves,'' Coach Phil Jackson said.
``There's no one to blame but us in this situation. We're not going
to be angry about it one way or the other. We're frustrated that we
didn't execute very well, didn't move the basketball very well, did
too many things off the dribble. The thing that bothers us the most
as a coaching staff is defensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, we're sitting in the driver's seat, and we're not in
a situation where we have to get in a panic mode, but we have to
play with more energy and more control.''
</P>
<P>
   After going up by three games to one, the Lakers were queried by
reporters as if the series were over. They answered dozens of
questions about being a budding dynasty. They were asked to compare
themselves with the great teams of the past _ the Lakers and
Detroit Pistons of the 1980s, the Chicago Bulls of the 1990s. And
Kobe Bryant, coming off his spectacular 28-point performance in
Game 4, was being compared favorably to Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson even felt comfortable enough to speak about Bryant as
Jordan before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kobe's probably a better player at 21 than Michael was at
21,'' Jackson said. ``He has a wonderful future, and we hope that
he can fill those mighty big shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bryant was hurled violently back to the planet on Friday
night. Jalen Rose and Reggie Miller took turns obliterating his
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Regarded by many as the best defensive shooting guard in the
league, Bryant was juked ridiculously a couple of times. On the
other end, his night was even longer, as he scored just eight
points on 4-of-20 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kobe held himself,'' Miller said when asked about
stopping Bryant. ``He had a lot of good looks early. He probably
got fouled on a couple of shots. But hey, that's basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   There is not much question as to whether the Lakers, who lost a
second-round close-out game to Phoenix by 19 points, will forget
about this nightmare and play well in Game 6. But the 33-point
deficit, their worst of the season, rankled Jackson enough for him
to question his team's greatness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've bounced back from games like this before,'' Jackson
said. ``I don't like to think of a team that has championship
quality in it that loses by 33 points. We have to prove something
to ourselves when we go back home in this regard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers thrive on challenges, and Jackson just issued one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
