<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKIES ARE BETTER BUT NOT ON THE ROAD  
 (WITH BBO-NOTEBOOK) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service      
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the words of an executive with a competing club, ``They
changed everything from top to bottom and they wind up with the
same animal.''
</P>
<P>
   The animal that is the Colorado Rockies, though, is a more
attractive species this season. Many of the Rockies' ingredients
look similar to last year, but the team has made impressive
improvements in some key areas, and the difference is in the
standings.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping with the character of their 8-year-old franchise, the
Rockies have played as two different teams home and away. Before
Saturday night's game with the Arizona Diamondbacks in Denver, the
Rockies had a 35-27 record, 23-8 at home and 12-19 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   But their major league-best home record was enough to place them
only two games behind the first-place Diamondbacks in the National
League West. After the same number of games last season, the
Rockies had a 30-32 record and were eight games behind the
first-place Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to play better on the road,'' said Buddy Bell, who as
the first-year manager is one of many new members with the club.
``Only time will tell if we can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   When Dan O'Dowd, another newcomer, became general manager last
September, he set out to change the personality of the team. The
slugging attack had not worked so he decided to put together a
collection of players who could get on base a greater percentage of
the time and score without relying on home runs. He also wanted
pitchers who could throw strikes.
</P>
<P>
   O'Dowd's efforts have given the Rockies 15 new players on their
25-man roster. Two of the departed, Vinny Castilla and Dante
Bichette, were two of the team's sluggers who produced a .472
slugging percentage last season. The slugging percentage this
season? It's .471.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Dowd's changes have produced the desired effect in putting
runners on base. The Rockies' on-base percentage last season was
.348. It's up to .471 this season. Last season Bichette had a .354
on-base percentage and Castilla .331. Among the newcomers this
season Jeffrey Hammonds is at .435, Tom Goodwin .422 and Jeff
Cirillo .404. As a team, the Rockies are drawing more walks,
averaging one more walk a game (4.15) than last year (3.14).
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a pretty good chemistry,'' Bell said. ``Guys
understand what's needed at the time. They're not afraid to take a
walk. That's something Danny really felt was one of the most
important things for how our offense was. Our on-base percentage
last year wasn't very good so he was determined to make that
better. It's become more of a contagious thing.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Rockies were to score runs without a ton of home runs,
they were going to have to go for more stolen bases, and they have
succeeded there, too. Last year the team had 70 stolen bases, tied
for the next-to-lowest total in the league. This season they have
62, second in the league. But the home/road disparity continues.
Hammonds is hitting 178 percentage points better at home, Todd
Helton 131 points, Cirillo 112, Goodwin 102 and Larry Walker 100.
Imagine how good the Rockies' league-leading batting average (.296)
could be if they could hit in other teams' parks.
</P>
<P>
   On the pitching side of the ledger, the Rockies have made
significant improvement. From a franchise-record 6.01 earned run
average last season, the Colorado staff has sliced half a run,
compiling a 5.46 ERA so far this season.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons is the pitchers' improved control. As O'Dowd
designed it, they are throwing fewer balls and walking fewer
batters. They have averaged one fewer walk this season (3.50) than
last (4.55), giving them a total of 217, the third-lowest total in
the NL Last year they walked a league-record 737.
</P>
<P>
   Bell credited his relief corps with doing a solid job. Leading
that corps is the closer, Jose Jimenez, who as a rookie starter
last season pitched a no-hitter for St. Louis. The 26-year-old
right-hander has made a seamless transition to relieving, earning
11 saves in 13 opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimenez has helped solidify the roles everybody performs,''
O'Dowd said. ``We didn't say it, but that was the role we got him
for. We didn't know his durability or how he would handle things
mentally, but he's been fine.''
</P>
<P>
   So has the team's defense. From the middle of the pack last
season the Rockies have rocketed to the top, committing the fewest
errors (35) in the league. Besides being more sure-handed, the
infielders have demonstrated greater range. The combination makes
the pitchers better.
</P>
<P>
   Combine all of the improvements, and look at the Rockies in
second place, challenging the Diamondbacks for first place this
weekend. And if there are players out there who could make the team
even better, Bell is betting that O'Dowd will find them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is one relentless man,'' the manager said. ``I'm sure if
somebody told us we'd be in this position now we'd have taken it.
But he's always going to try to make us better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
