</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS SINK TO PAST; STRIKING OUT AT SOSA; MORGAN'S DOZEN;
SELF-CONTROL PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (With BBN-ROCKIES)  
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last time the Cleveland Indians were this far from first
place &QC; (6 1/2 games behind entering Saturday's games), Jeff Treadway
and Felix Fermin were their double-play combination, Junior Ortiz
was their catcher, Wayne Kirby their right fielder and Sam Horn
their designated hitter. Candy Maldonado and Randy Milligan were on
the team, and Manny Ramirez was there as a September callup. Dave
Mlicki and Bob Milacki were on the pitching staff, as was Jason
Grimsley, now with the Yankees. Jose Mesa was in his last season as
a starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   The season was 1993, and the Indians finished it a season-high
19 games from first place. The farthest the Indians have been from
first since that year was four games in 1994. In the past three
years their biggest deficits totaled five games.
</P>
<P>
   Striking Out at Sosa
</P>
<P>
   In what has become an orchestrated or an impromptu campaign to
denigrate Sammy Sosa _ in some instances to try to demonstrate why
the Yankees should not trade for him _ much has been made of the
frequency of his strikeouts and his weight. Sosa might have become
chubbier, but he is really not striking out at any greater rate
than he has in recent seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Saturday's game, Sosa had struck out 72 times in 255
times at bat, or once for every 3.54 times at bat. In his 66-homer
season in 1998, he struck out once for every 3.76 at-bats, and last
season his ratio was 1 or every 3.65. In each of those seasons he
struck out 171 times. In 1997, he struck out 174 times, or once for
every 3.69 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   If he were to bat this season the approximate number of times he
did in those seasons and continue striking out at this season's
ratio, he would finish the season with 179. That would be a
negligible increase in frequency.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it's SOS _ Same Old Sammy.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan's Dozen
</P>
<P>
   It took Mike Morgan nearly two and a half months, but he finally
extended one of his major league records to 12 teams last week.
When he started for Arizona and lost to Los Angeles, it marked the
12th team with which he has lost games. Morgan, who is 40 years
old, has played for more teams than any other player in any major
sports league (12), and he has won games for more teams than any
other major league pitcher. The Diamondbacks became No. 11 when
Morgan gained a victory in relief in April.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Zimmerman, a Morgan teammate last season with Texas, has
allowed 22 earned runs and 24 runs over all in 29 games and 28 2/3
innings. Last season he gave up 23 earned runs and 24 runs over all
in 65 games and 87 and two-thirds innings. Zimmerman, a rookie in
1999, gained a spot on the American League All-Star team and
pitched a hitless, scoreless inning. This year he has gained a
three-day vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Self-Control Problems
</P>
<P>
   When the Atlanta Braves sent John Rocker to the minor leagues
two weeks ago, they said it was for his pitching control, not his
self-control. When he returned to the Braves last week following an
injury to another reliever, he demonstrated that he had not solved
his control problem. He threw six pitches in his first game back,
and all were balls. It remains to be seen if he will demonstrate an
improvement in his self-control.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Belle, who has had his own problems with self-control,
was sent to the minors in 1991 after he failed to run out a
double-play grounder. That incident occurred a few weeks after he
threw a baseball at a fan in the stands. Did the three-week
demotion have a positive effect on him?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it did,'' John Hart, the Indians' general manager,
said. ``Maturity comes at different times. At that point in his
career, I remember very clearly Albert was young and struggling at
the major league level. He had the incident with the fan and he
didn't run out two or three balls. He wasn't playing well. It was a
message to Albert. When he came back, he became a poster child.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hargrove, a coach at Cleveland who became the manager 10
days after Belle returned to the Indians, said the outfielder was
different when he rejoined the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always intense batting,'' Hargrove said, ``but he
played the rest of his game with more intensity. He took his game
in the field more seriously. He was still a work in progress, but
we had something to work with in trying to get him to modify his
outlook.''
</P>
<P>
   Belle was 24 going on 25 at the time. Rocker is 25.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
