<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PEBBLE BEACH'S MOST PRECISE HOLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ From the tee down near the rocks of
Carmel Bay, you can't see the chasm. All you see is the grassy
horizon of the fairway with the dazzling expanse of Carmel's
crescent beach to the right. Beyond the fairway at the edge of the
chasm, out there about 260 yards, shaggy grass surrounds two small
signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danger,'' they warn in red. ``Steep cliff.''
</P>
<P>
   It's so steep that, according to Pebble Beach lore, a woman once
tried to commit suicide there by jumping off that cliff. Somehow
she suffered only a broken leg. Another time, the driver of a
fairway mower, realizing he couldn't stop in time, jumped off the
mower just before it plunged into the chasm.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 feet down at the bottom of the chasm, surf slaps
against the rocks and slides up the sand. Across the chasm, five
yawning bunkers and thick rough surround the sloping green of this
418-yard eighth hole at Pebble Beach, where Tiger Woods is trying
to win his first U.S. Open championship.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the most photographed hole at Pebble Beach, but it's
the most precise hole, the most demanding, the most threatening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the way the second shot sets up there,'' Jack Nicklaus
said before this Open started, ``it's my favorite shot in golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the shots that the best golfer in history has assessed,
he calls this shot to the eighth green his favorite. Pebble Beach
ought to plant a plaque with that rave review on it somewhere on
the edge of the chasm with those two danger signs.
</P>
<P>
   But your tee shot must be as precise as that second shot over
the chasm. Hit your tee shot too far and you don't have a second
shot. If your ball is not down in the chasm, it is in the rough
near one of those danger signs with nowhere to stand.
</P>
<P>
   In what the 60-year-old Nicklaus, the four-time champion, later
announced was his last Open round after a record 44 Opens, his tee
shot there Friday went too far into that rough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a 3-wood off the tee and I cut it up in the wind a
little bit to kill it, but it went too long by about a foot,'' he
said after an 82. ``I took a drop, then I hit a 7-iron 20 feet
short of the hole and it looked like it landed on a highway.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus later agreed that his double-bogey 6 there just about
finished his hope of making the 36-hole cut. But no matter which
way the wind is blowing, that chasm creates a decision for every
golfer as to what club to use on the tee.
</P>
<P>
   For Tom Kite, how he played the eighth hole in the final round
of the 1992 Open probably made the difference in his winning.
</P>
<P>
   Kite, in a duel for the lead with Jeff Sluman, arrived at the
eighth tee after a surprising birdie 2 on the 106-yard seventh hole
when his wedge from the rough scooted across the green and into the
cup. On the tee, pumped up by that birdie and with a wild wind at
his back, Kite was fingering the 3-iron in his bag until his
caddie, Mike Carrick, spoke up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the 4,'' Carrick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean the 3,'' Kite suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, the 4,'' Carrick repeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``How far is the cliff?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Two-sixty,'' the caddie said.
</P>
<P>
   Kite paused, nodded, yanked the 4-iron and hit it. When he
walked up the hill to the fairway, he saw his ball perched about
five yards short of the cliff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice call,'' Kite told his caddie.
</P>
<P>
   Had Kite hit the 3-iron, his ball would probably have
disappeared into the chasm along with his opportunity to win what
turned out to be his only major title. But with a par at the
eighth, Kite went on to shoot 72 for a three-under-par 285, two
strokes ahead of Sluman.
</P>
<P>
   The day before, Gil Morgan arrived at the eighth tee at 12 under
for the tournament, the first golfer in Open history to be in
double figures under par. After a good tee shot, Morgan's iron over
the chasm flew into the back bunker. He flubbed his explosion shot,
chipped long and two-putted for a double-bogey 6 on his way to a
77.
</P>
<P>
   With an 81 in the final round, Morgan skidded to a tie for 13th.
The eighth hole had wrecked him.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1972 Open, Nicklaus had a par at the eighth in the windy
final round and went on to win by three strokes. But in the 1982
Open, which Nicklaus lost by two strokes to Tom Watson, he had a
costly bogey there after a run of five consecutive birdies.
</P>
<P>
   ``My second shot landed in what they called `the character,' the
rough that was this high,'' the Golden Bear recalled, pointing to
his knees. ``I was only about 12 feet from the hole and I swung as
hard as I could, but I barely got it out. Bogey.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Watson saved par at the eighth with an 8-foot
putt. In the third round, Watson had birdied the eighth with a
4-wood and a 5-iron to about 18 feet.
</P>
<P>
   For better or for worse, something always seems to happen in the
Open at Pebble Beach's eighth hole where that chasm demands a
precise tee shot. Far, but not too far. Not too close to those
either of those two danger signs and certainly not into the chasm. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
