<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7110 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-RUN-OLY-ADKINS0618-CO     06-17 2366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-OLY-ADKINS0618-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hurdler's path to mental health takes toll on speed
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On a pleasant, late August night in 1996, in a hotel
room of the Ramada Cap`d'ail outside Monte Carlo, the face that
only weeks earlier at the Atlanta Olympics wore a gold-medal smile
was buried in a pillow.
</P>
<P>
   Crying in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Adkins should have been having the time of his young
life, fending off admirers in a glamorous European hot spot as a
freshly minted Olympic 400-meter hurdles champion. Instead, he was
restless and sad.
</P>
<P>
   He could not muster the strength to abandon his tiny room and
join his training partners for dinner. Instead, he dialed room
service and ordered a bottle of white wine. He drank it fast.
Finally, he dozed off and found temporary escape from his
depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was building up and building up,'' Adkins says. ``When I
got to the hotel that day, for some reason, everything just
crashed. It was a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Hungover and dehydrated, Adkins flew with other track athletes
to Berlin the next day. He was poised to split $250,000 with five
others if he took his specialty, the 400-meter hurdles, which he
had won earlier at three prestigious European stops.
</P>
<P>
   He came home a badly beaten third _ and lost what would have
been his biggest payday.
</P>
<P>
   That was it. Adkins knew he needed help.
</P>
<P>
   SIGNS OF DEPRESSION EARLY ON
</P>
<P>
   Growing up on Long Island, Derrick graduated in the top 5
percent of his high school class. He was an accomplished drummer
and member of the all-county band. His father, Earl, a
physical-education teacher and once a hurdler at Morgan State,
introduced the lanky youngster to the 400-meter hurdles. By his
senior year, Derrick was the No. 1 schoolboy hurdler in America.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Carole, recalls seeing Derrick cry as a youngster
only twice. But Derrick remembers sad days, days when he wanted to
be alone. When he was 9 or 10, he would go off by himself and cry
for no reason.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he reached Georgia Tech in the fall of 1988, he was
versed in warding off the valleys of depression. He occupied his
mind with a tiresome academic load, majoring in mechanical
engineering and making the dean's list, all while training as a
world-class athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Everything he undertook became an obsession. When he wasn't
training, he buried himself in his books.
</P>
<P>
   ``In college, that is what kept me going _ the work,'' he said.
``I was very driven, very motivated. It was almost like an
obsession. Actually, depression is related to obsession. So, a lot
of people who suffer depression become obsessants. My obsession was
training, running fast, getting good grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why, once I graduated, depression started to sink in.
The track was kind of like my escape from the depression.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, Adkins was the best hurdler in the world , the Olympic
favorite _ but his life had become a private hell.
</P>
<P>
   He began experiencing paranoia and insomnia, often going two and
three nights with little or no sleep. He lost his appetite and shed
17 pounds, down to a frail 170.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins always had been a savage worker, one of the most intense
lifters in the weight room. But he began tearing himself down as he
trained, getting weaker and slower.
</P>
<P>
   He thought about commiting suicide, about buying a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had never touched alcohol before, he tried drowning
his depression by drinking in his Midtown home, where his gold
medal now sits on a living room shelf amid trophies and a
photograph of him with former South African President Nelson
Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   He ventured to clubs and went through multiple relationships
with women. By the spring of 1996, with the Olympic Trials lurking,
his track workouts suffered, and the edge was coming off his
performance.
</P>
<P>
   UNWILLING TO REVEAL HIS DISPAIR
</P>
<P>
   Adkins didn't tell a soul what was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thought I was a such a happy person, that I had my
life together,'' he says. ``I didn't want them to think otherwise.
I would smile when I was in public, and I would put on an act.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was by myself, I would be extremely down. Sometimes I
would just sit in my house in the dark, just thinking about what
was wrong with me. I knew something was wrong, but I didn't know
what.''
</P>
<P>
   One sleepless night in April, thumbing through the telephone
yellow pages and praying that God would lead him, his eyes came
upon a small ad for Dr. Casandra Wanzo.
</P>
<P>
   He soon worked up the courage to visit her office. Dr. Wanzo
diagnosed his condition as clinical depression and prescribed the
antidepressant drug Luvox.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Wanzo, a fair-skinned, African-American woman with long
thick braids, says she realized almost immediately that Adkins was
suffering from a major depressive disorder _ not the normal mood
swings or reactive depression brought on by an experience such as
divorce, but a biological phenomenon influenced by brain
biochemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was affecting his energy level,'' she said. ``His appetite
had decreased. He had a loss of motivation and desire to do things
_ loss of ability to get pleasure out of life. He had crying
spells. He even had some suicidal thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Adkins shared the secret with his coach, Grover
Hinsdale. The coach had been bewildered by Adkins' lagging
workouts, but didn't know the reason. He had sent him to a
nutritionist. He sent him for blood work. The tests came back fine.
</P>
<P>
   Then after one April practice, Hinsdale sat transfixed in his
office as Adkins offered a chilling account of his depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he drank a bottle of wine and locked himself out of
the apartment, broke a window to get back in,'' Hinsdale said.
``Derrick doesn't even drink. This is a totally top-shelf young
man. Clean-cut. Hard working. Takes care of his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he told me the story, I couldn't have sunk any lower in
my chair. I knew then that this was more than just, `I don't feel
well.' But at least we knew what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   MOM'S INTUITION ON TARGET
</P>
<P>
   Hinsdale encouraged Adkins to tell his parents.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, a federal-court clerk in Brooklyn, already had an
inkling. After a weekend visit to Atlanta the previous fall, she
jotted down in her business diary: ``Derrick seems depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   When Adkins came home the last weekend in April, he appeared wan
and weary coming down the escalator at LaGuardia Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``His skin was ashen, pale,'' she remembers. ``He has high
cheekbones, but his cheeks were sunken in. He looked terrible. I'm
saying to myself, `What is going on?'
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got in the car he told me he had been sick, but that
he was all right now. That he was suffering from depression.''
</P>
<P>
   But Adkins didn't tell anyone when he brazenly stopped taking
the medication just weeks later. He stayed off the drug all summer,
because it made him feel lackadaisical and inhibited his
performance slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins didn't want to let anything interfere with his
performance, not with a gold medal up for grabs in Atlanta. Not
after 1992, when a badly sprained ankle cost him a sure spot in the
Barcelona Olympics. Not after a late-race fall that cost him an
NCAA title.
</P>
<P>
   He made it through the Atlanta Games on adrenaline and an
Olympic focus. Skipping his medication ``was a scary thing to do,''
he says, ``but I was so obsessed with the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning a gold medal was so important. I said, `I'm just going
to beat this without medication _ mind over matter or whatever.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel depression setting back in for a while. In May
and June, I was just so enthralled with the Olympics, plus it was
here in Atlanta. All the excitement surrounding the Olympics
drowned out pretty much everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympics was like a surreal experience that came and went.
It definitely was a highlight of my life. And, of course, I wasn't
depressed after I won the gold medal, but, several weeks after, it
started to set in.''
</P>
<P>
   And that night in Monte Carlo, he learned he no longer could
withhold medicine from his disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't live like that,'' he says. ``I would win a race,
but that would only last for a few hours before my body would sink
into depression. Most of the time I just felt terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   DRASTIC DROPOFF ON THE TRACK
</P>
<P>
   Today, properly medicated, Adkins isn't the hurdler of old,
although he trains with the same passion and still dreams of
competing in the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   He is back in school, studying for his master's degree in
divinity at the Atlanta-based Christian Life School of Theology. He
has come forward to share his experience in hopes of helping others
afflicted with the disease. Next month, he will release a
self-published inspirational book, ``Let's All Get High.''
</P>
<P>
   But on the track, Adkins is a lagging shadow of the figure who
just a few years ago aspired to the longevity of hurdling icon
Edwin Moses.
</P>
<P>
   Few athletes have fallen so quickly. Adkins sank from world and
Olympic gold medalist to a No. 8 world ranking in 1997 to complete
absence from the rankings the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   The year after the Olympics, he failed to make the finals in the
World Championships. Last summer, Adkins failed even to make the
U.S. team. His major shoe sponsor, Reebok, dumped him.
</P>
<P>
   He estimates that his struggles have cost him ``hundreds of
thousands of dollars.'' On his 1999 tax return, he reported a
$26,000 loss _ after making more than $300,000 in the Olympic year.
</P>
<P>
   His personal best time in the 400 hurdles is 47.54. He thinks
that he could have gotten down to 47-flat during the lost years _
and still might, if he gets his brain chemistry straightened out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic that there are athletes out there using drugs to
make themselves faster,'' he said. ``I have to run against those
same athletes, and my medication is making me slower.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hard when people say, `You're the Olympic
champion; how come you can't run well?' I didn't want to tell them
my problems. But I don't want people to think it was a fluke or
that I've taken it easy, because I train just as hard as I ever
have.''
</P>
<P>
   The embarrassment was its worst in 1998, when the Goodwill Games
were held on Long Island. Adkins grew up 4 miles from the Uniondale
track on a street the Lakeview townsfolk named for him after his
victory in Atlanta, Derrick Adkins Lane. His parents hired a
caterer to throw a barbecue for 300 or so friends at a local state
park. Later that night, they all had tickets to see Derrick run.
</P>
<P>
   And he did, coming home dead last.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of my friends were there,'' Adkins said. ``It was really
hard. I decided to quit.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't run again that season, but his sister Dianne pleaded
with him not to abandon the sport. She had been a New York high
school sprint champion and an inspiration. Her own running career
was halted while she battled ovarian cancer in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really took her words to heart, because of what she had been
through,'' he said. ``In some ways, she was living vicariously
through me, because she was such a great track athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   SIDE EFFECTS HURT PERFORMANCE
</P>
<P>
   But can the kid brother run fast again?
</P>
<P>
   Assisted by his mother, Adkins juggles the drugs like a chemist,
researching the Internet and medical journals for a way to balance
the side effects.
</P>
<P>
   One side effect of the drugs is a weakening and stiffening of
tendons, and Adkins thinks that it has caused his nagging hamstring
and Achilles' injuries. He can run with those injuries, but what he
can't overcome is the fatigue that settles in earlier during speed
workouts and races.
</P>
<P>
   The influence on performance might be only 5 percent. But a mere
second or two often is the difference between first and last over
the 10 hurdles of the 400 meters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't hold the speed, and I can't run as fast,'' he said.
``The first five hurdles, I used to run very fast. I was so fast
that I would be able to do that and last. Now, I can run the first
five hurdles just as fast, but it is a struggle to do so. I use up
so much energy that I have no energy for later in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually don't get fatigued until around the eighth hurdle.
On the medication, I might start to get fatigued around the third
hurdle. It's just very hard to hold on after that.''
</P>
<P>
   That's bad enough in a single race. It's a career-killer in top
competitions like the Olympic trials or the Olympic Games because
in qualifying rounds an athlete has three races in three days.
</P>
<P>
   But Adkins has learned that anti-depressants decrease blood
protein and cause dehydration. So he has become compulsive about
drinking fluids and has significantly upgraded his ``college diet''
to a low carbohydrate and high protein diet. He also consumes
liquid amino-acid supplements, which help offset protein deficiency
triggered by his anti-depressant drug.
</P>
<P>
   MENTAL APPROACH SUFFERING
</P>
<P>
   Some days, Hinsdale accepts that the medication takes away
Adkins' edge. Other days, he can't help but wonder whether some of
the fatigue is in Adkins' head _ whether he cautiously holds
something back, a reflex from too many races when he really was
beaten down.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins concedes that it has become more mental than physical. He
acknowledges that his confidence never has been lower. What he
won't do is risk everything for another gold medal. Instead, he
works for some sort of harmonious balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``My emotional well-being off the track is much more
important,'' he said. ``I would love to be able to run fast and
have emotional stability off the track as well. And I have never
had that. In '94 and '95, almost every time I stepped on the track,
I would win. The same was true the summer of '96, but during those
years I didn't have any emotional stability off the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then after those years, I have been very happy off the track,
but I haven't been able to run too well. It's been a tradeoff, and
I would like to have both.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sincerely believe I'll be able to do it,'' Adkins said. ``If
I didn't, I wouldn't be running anymore. I would just move on to
something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
