<HEADLINE>
JOYNER-KERSEE ENTERS OLYMPIC TRIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marion Jones' attempt to win five gold medals at the 2000 Summer
Olympics has received a potentially severe challenge. Jackie
Joyner-Kersee has entered the long jump at the Olympic trials next
month, apparently deciding to come out of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner-Kersee, who is 38, twice won gold medals in the Olympic
heptathlon and once won the Olympic long jump competition. She owns
the U.S. record in the women's long jump at 24 feet 7 inches. Her
last jump before retiring in 1998 was 20-11}.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say there's a 75 percent possibility that she'll
compete,'' Greg Foster, Joyner-Kersee's agent, said in remarks
released by organizers of the Olympic trials. ``She is training and
she's in shape. The important thing is that she wants to be
competitive in the Olympic Games.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, whose longest jump is 23-11}, has struggled this season.
If Joyner-Kersee regains her form, it will put tremendous pressure
on Jones to gain one of the three spots on the U.S. Olympic team.
</P>
</TEXT>
