<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7113 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-KRAYZELBURG-2TAKE     06-17 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-KRAYZELBURG-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MULTIPLE GOLD-MEDAL PROSPECT WAS BORN TO SWIM 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The boy arrived in the United States at age 13, and English for
him seemed like an unsolvable puzzle. He knew some of the words,
but he could not put them together. It would be four years before
he felt confident enough around strangers to assemble it all into
any real conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Swimming was different. The flint of a young boy's talent had
sparked the flame of a promising career back in Odessa, Ukraine.
Lenny Krayzelburg had flourished in the former Soviet system. He
entered an army-sponsored club at kindergarten age and, by 9, he
was put into a school with other swimmers and was given training
lessons twice a day. From 6 a.m. to 6 p.m., six days a week, he and
44 other swimmers remained together, taking lessons in the pool, in
the classroom, in the pool again.
</P>
<P>
   Twice, Krayzelburg won age-group medals at the national army
championships. His coach, Vitaly Ovakimian, told his father: ``Your
son can be a great athlete. He was born to be a backstroker.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach was right, but of course, he could not have known that
Krayzelburg's career would take a route far more circuitous than
the exhaustive, tedious back and forth of a swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg did become a great athlete, setting world records in
the 100-meter and 200-meter backstroke, establishing himself as a
multiple gold-medal favorite for the 2000 Summer Olympics in
Sydney, Australia. But he would first have to find a new country
that was politically stable and hospitable to his Jewish faith, a
new language and a new resolve to succeed in Los Angeles, a place
famous for its beaches and water but one that offers few training
opportunities for an elite swimmer in the inner city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been fortunate enough to learn from my parents about hard
work and dedication and committing yourself to a certain thing and
following it all the way to the end,'' Krayzelburg said in a recent
interview.
</P>
<P>
   He sat at breakfast, fueling an athletic furnace that burns
5,000 calories a day. At 6 feet 2 inches and 180 pounds, the
24-year-old athlete is movie-star handsome. With slicked-back hair,
he is often compared to Pat Riley, the basketball coach and
clotheshorse.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a seriousness about the voice and face of
Krayzelburg, a gravity in the squint of his eyes, that more closely
resembles the visage of the newsman Eric Sevareid. He has a degree
in finance from the University of Southern California, and he
speaks in complex terms about his life in the former Soviet Union,
a life that is infused with tones of gray, not simply black and
white.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked up a lot of good growing up in the Soviet system,
training so hard and intense at a young age,'' Krayzelburg said.
``When I got older, I realized they wanted us to train so hard, and
to commit to something and to dedicate our whole lives to it,
because that's what it took. There are no shortcuts if you want to
accomplish something. These are the things I carried on in my
career.''
</P>
<P>
   The late 1980s were a time of opening under the former Soviet
leader, Mikhail Gorbachev. According to Krayzelburg, his father,
Oleg, who managed a state-owned coffee shop, also had a small,
privatized food business. His mother, Yelena, was a bookkeeper at a
shoe factory. The army-sponsored school he attended gave him
vouchers for free meals. The family lived in a three-bedroom
apartment, and even though he had to share a bedroom with his
younger sister, Marsha, and relatives sometimes swelled the
occupancy to eight people, ``financially, we were above average,''
Lenny said.
</P>
<P>
   Other concerns, though, would convince the family to leave for
the United States. The Soviet Union had also been engaged in a
protracted war in Afghanistan, and Krayzelburg's parents worried
that Lenny would be called into some dangerous conflict when he
turned 18. His parents also worried about anti-Semitism that
carried well beyond name-calling in the schoolyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to leave; we wanted a better life for our kids,''
Yelena Krayzelburg said. ``We saw the discrimination around us. If
Russian kid wants to go to university, they cut the number of
Jewish kids getting higher education. When you fill out an
application for a job, and they ask for your nationality and they
find out you are Jewish, they try not to hire you.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there was the army. At that time, it was the Afghanistan
war, something very scary. We were afraid about Lenny.''
</P>
<P>
   The family applied for immigration, and in 1988, on Christmas
Day, when Lenny was 13 and the Eastern bloc was a year from
collapse, the Krayzelburgs departed for the new world, first to
Vienna, then Rome, finally arriving in West Hollywood, Calif., on
March 14, 1989. The family lived briefly with friends who sponsored
them, then found their own place. English was elusive, money was
tight. Oleg Krayzelburg took a job as a cook in a Russian
restaurant, and Yelena found employment at a pharmacy. For Lenny,
life in the United States was exciting, jarring. His father
insisted that he continue his swimming career. But where?
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of pools in Pasadena, and out in the San
Fernando Valley, or down in Orange County, but few in urban Los
Angeles. There was not even a swim team at Fairfax High, which he
attended. For a year, Krayzelburg took a 50-minute bus ride each
way to train at Santa Monica City College. He could swim only once
a day, not twice as he had done in Odessa, and the ennui of
insufficient training and public transportation sapped his
conditioning, draining his desire to continue in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Bored, he wanted to quit. ``This would be a bad thing to do,''
his father told him. ``You put in so many years in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to train closer to his home, Krayzelburg settled on the
Westside Jewish Community Center, which had a 25-yard indoor pool,
half the size of an Olympic pool. On Fridays, Krayzelburg said, the
pool was dedicated to recreational swimmers, so the elite group
trained in what amounted to a glorified sauna, 10 to 15 yards long,
where the water was about 100 degrees and 3 feet deep and toddlers
were taught their first strokes. Still, the center offered him a
job working 15 to 20 hours a week as a lifeguard, and he continued
to train there through high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rejuventated myself at Westside,'' Krayzelburg said. But he
could train only 90 minutes a day, four days a week. ``I saw no
potential,'' he said. ``I knew what I had done in Russia. It would
be impossible to accomplish something like that here.''
</P>
<P>
   During the spring of 1993, his senior year in high school,
Krayzelburg went to Santa Monica City College, where he had first
trained, to pre-enroll for classes the next fall. He stopped by the
office of the swim coach, Stu Blumkin, who offered to let him train
there in the morning, before his classes at Fairfax High. But,
Blumkin thought to himself: ``Fairfax doesn't even have a swim
team. How fast could this kid be?''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, he would know.
</P>
<P>
   Despite working 30 hours a week at the West Hollywood Recreation
Department, Krayzelburg won the 1994 California state junior
college championship in the 100- and 200-yard backstroke, setting a
national junior college record in the 200. Several months earlier,
Blumkin said, he wrote a note to himself, sealed it in an envelope
and had a friend sign it for authentication. ``He'll be one of the
best swimmers in the world,'' Blumkin wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Just before that 1994 junior college meet, Blumkin called Mark
Schubert, who coaches swimming at USC and will be the 2000 Olympic
men's coach. ``I have this backstroker who's going to win the state
championship next week,'' Blumkin said. ``I'd like to bring him in
and meet you.''
</P>
<P>
   Schubert got plenty of these calls. ``Yeah, yeah,'' he thought.
But Krayzelburg did win the state meet and, later that summer, he
shaved nine seconds off his personal best in the 200-meter
backstroke. Schubert offered him a scholarship to USC. ``You've got
the tools,'' Schubert told the swimmer. ``If you're willing to
work, you can be the best in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is he believed me,'' Schubert said.
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg and his family became U.S. citizens in 1995, and a
year later he finished fifth in the 200-meter backstroke at the
1996 Olympic trials. Now he owns six of the 10 fastest times in the
event, including the world record of 1 minute 55.87 seconds, as
well as the world mark at 100 meters in 53.60. He is a heavy
favorite to win both events in Sydney. Blumkin has since opened his
sealed forecast of Krayzelburg's greatness, which makes him the
Karnak the Magnificent of the swimming set.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the track, if you watch a horse walk, you won't see
anything special,'' Blumkin said. ``But the minute you see him
gallop, you know. Like the jockeys always say, `The horse has his
mind on business.' That's Lenny. First one in the pool, last one
out. Same thing in the weight room. He pushes everyone else up
another level.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
