<SLUG> BC-CAR-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR CRASH STUDY LEADS TO SAFETY TIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Often they are able to walk away. Occasionally they cannot.
NASCAR officials last week had to review videotape of yet another
horrific accident. The latest involved Elliott Sadler, a
25-year-old in only his second full season in the Winston Cup
Series.
</P>
<P>
   In practice before last week's race in Brooklyn, Mich., Sadler's
No. 21 Ford incurred a cut right rear tire, apparently from debris.
That spun the car into a rear-first position and, with the
horsepower-stuffed engine still wildly churning out RPM, it soon
was airborne. Landing, the car rolled an estimated 12 times,
winding up on its roof in a crumpled heap.
</P>
<P>
   As the smoking remains of Sadler's car sat on Turn 2, and
workers rushed to pry him out, his chances of survival appeared in
question. Yet he emerged with only a puffy right knee, and some
contusions and scrapes.
</P>
<P>
   As the NASCAR world knows all too well, Adam Petty was not as
fortunate. The 19-year-old, fourth-generation driver was killed
during practice at New Hampshire International Speedway last month,
after his car hit a wall. His popularity _ combined with the
stature of his family in NASCAR _ virtually ensures that the
chilling effect of his death will hang over the racing association
for years.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR is forever reviewing its safety rules, according to Gary
Nelson, the Winston Cup series director. But the reality is that
individual teams generally go beyond what is mandated, to give
their drivers an enhanced sense of safety.
</P>
<P>
   Some teams pad the bar to the left of the driver's head. Others
use netting designed to keep the head stabilized. Most drivers
prefer a full face mask, which helps one's safety but severely
limits peripheral vision, requiring more help from spotters. Nelson
said that even engineers could not agree which one was best, so
NASCAR made it optional.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody wants to do more, you've got to approach it like a
doctor,'' he said. ``You don't want to do harm with the cure.''
</P>
<P>
   At Daytona Beach, Fla., last February, Geoffrey Bodine's vehicle
in the truck series was hit multiple times and sheared off more
than 100 feet of catch fence before exploding. Nothing was left of
the vehicle but a mangled cage, yet Bodine survived.
</P>
<P>
   Replays showed one of Bodine's arms flailing around as his truck
grotesquely kept rolling. He later said that arm restraints would
have prevented him from breaking a wrist and sustaining numerous
arm contusions, and he has since incorporated them.
</P>
<P>
   Bodine credited a full face mask with limiting his injuries.
Even so, you will not find Dale Earnhardt, the seven-time Winston
Cup champion, wearing one. He likes to utilize his peripheral
vision too much.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler, it is clear now, benefited from new, unyielding safety
belts. Previous ones had been known to stretch in extreme
situations.
</P>
<P>
   As he was rolling over, Sadler said his first thought was
staying alive. ``I didn't know you could do so much praying in such
a short amount of time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As Sunday's action shifts to the flat, 2.5-mile triangle at
Pocono Raceway in Long Pond, Pa., a comment by the rookie Dale
Earnhardt Jr. highlights how the Winston Cup Series has become more
populated with youthful drivers, which means less-experienced
drivers who are maybe more error-prone.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt Jr., 25, had never driven a car at Pocono, which
requires significant acclimation because of three distinctively
different corners and a long stretch necessitating the shifting of
gears, until a lone practice two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   He has won two races this year but admitted his learning curve
is steep at the Pennsylvania track. ``We're really going to be
rookies this week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd Without a Victory
</P>
<P>
   In a year of parity, Ricky Rudd is struggling to find his share
of it.
</P>
<P>
   The Winston Cup series has had 12 different winners this season,
and the last time that happened was in 1994. With 20 races left,
Rudd is conspicuously among the non-winners.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the megabucks Robert Yates Racing this year appeared to
be a wonderful development for Rudd, competitive even as an
underfunded driver-owner trying to do things his way. Still, the
Virginian, ranked No. 8, is the only driver among the top 10 in
points who has yet to win.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd had a chance in Michigan, but two atypical things happened
in the last half of the race: his right-rear window fell out during
a pit stop, and a later stop left him with a loose lug nut.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, Joe Gibbs, the former NFL coach, appears on the way
to a dream season with his two teams. Bobby Labonte leads the
points race and is Pocono's defending champion, and second-year
driver Tony Stewart has moved to seventh in the standings on the
strength of consecutive victories.
</P>
<P>
   Going Far to Improve
</P>
<P>
   The extremes to which teams will go to maximize their
performance seem unlimited. Struggling A.J. Foyt Racing took its
No. 14 car to Canada for important wind-tunnel testing after
Sunday's race in Michigan. Meanwhile, the team's transporter headed
to North Carolina to pick up the necessary engines and parts. Then
they were to rendezvous in a hotel parking lot to make final
adjustments for the team's Pocono qualifying effort. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
