<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7118 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LABOR-SWEENEY0618-COX     06-17 1873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-SWEENEY0618-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Immigrants strengthening Big Labor's political clout
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Miguel Contreras was expecting a big crowd.
</P>
<P>
   As head of the labor federation for the county's unions,
Contreras for weeks had been exhorting union leaders to turn out
their members for an AFL-CIO immigration forum June 10.
</P>
<P>
   A week before the forum, Contreras revised his attendance
estimate from 5,000 to 8,000. The day before the event, organizers
confidently predicted 10,000 union workers from across the state.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time he took the stage at the Los Angeles Sports
Arena, even Contreras was overwhelmed by what he saw: 17,000 people
packed to the rafters. Another 3,000 to 4,000 stood outside, locked
out by fire marshals.
</P>
<P>
   They came, for the most part, from Los Angeles. But they
identified their countries of origin with black and white signs:
Mexico, El Salvador, Panama, Ecuador, Paraguay and Peru. In their
hands, they held plastic American flags, placed on the seats before
they arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raise up your flags to show this country that we belong!''
Contreras shouted to the crowd. For a few moments, the sea of faces
became a shimmering blur of red, white and blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are seeing the birth of a powerful new alliance,'' an
ecstatic Contreras declared afterward.
</P>
<P>
   After decades of setbacks and decline, organized labor is riding
a wave of new growth and resurgent political clout. Last year,
under the leadership of AFL-CIO President John Sweeney, unions
posted their biggest membership gains since the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Unions organized 600,000 workers in 1999 _ most of them in the
service industry and in government. Fifteen percent, or 91,000 new
members, were organized in Los Angeles County alone, including the
single biggest organizing campaign since 1938 _ the unionization of
74,000 home health care workers.
</P>
<P>
   A big part of labor's surge is coming from new immigrants,
particularly Latinos, who are settling in regions as diverse as
Gainesville, Ga., and Milwaukee, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Labor's bid to organize new immigrants is most pronounced in Los
Angeles, where Latinos are 44 percent of the region's 9.3 million
people.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, Latino union membership increased 3.7 percent last
year _ the most of any ethnic group _ and more Latinos belong to
unions now than in any time in labor history.
</P>
<P>
   In California, the alliance between organized labor and Latinos
is poised to deliver the biggest payoff to Vice President Gore and
House minority leader Richard Gephardt (D-Mo.).
</P>
<P>
   Gore already enjoys an advantage over Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas among California's expanding Latino population, and the
manpower that organized labor can deliver in Los Angeles, home to
800,000 union workers, will be a potent one-two punch in the fight
for California's 54 electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, the labor unions here have targeted 17 campaigns for
the city council, state legislature and Congress and won all but
one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Labor-backed candidates to the California state assembly helped
Democrats reclaim the chamber in 1996. In 1998, a strong turnout
from labor, particularly in Los Angeles and among Latinos, helped
elect Gov. Gray Davis, the first Democrat elected to the post in 16
years.
</P>
<P>
   Daisy Cabrera, a 27-year-old janitor who came to Los Angeles
from El Salvador 16 years ago, was a foot soldier in the '98
campaign, working the streets of her neighborhood on Davis' behalf.
Not yet a U.S. citizen, she cannot vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that doesn't mean we can't participate,'' said Cabrera,
who earns $7.02 an hour cleaning office buildings. ``There is no
reason why we can't tell those who can vote to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   This fall, the county federation plans to deploy thousands of
workers such as Cabrera to help defeat three House Republicans in
Los Angeles _ half the seats the Democrats need to regain the
House. Those targeted are Reps. James Rogan, Steve Horn and Steven
Kuykendall, who carried their districts in 1998 with no more than
53 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders here notched their first congressional victory of
the year in the March 7 California primary. Democratic state Sen.
Hilda Solis, a labor-backed candidate, defeated Rep. Matthew
Martinez (D-Calif.), an 18-year incumbent whom labor leaders viewed
as being soft on their issues, despite a strong labor voting
record.
</P>
<P>
   The unions also targeted Martinez to send a pointed political
message, Contreras said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to show all elected officials that we put them in
and we can take them out,'' said Contreras. ``We've shown over the
last four years that we can put them in. But we've never shown that
we can take you out, until this year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dirty fingernail work.'' That's what David Sickler calls
political campaigns, union style. Sickler, southern regional
director of the California Building and Construction Trades
Council, was labor's point man in the Solis campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Over a six-week period before the election, he coordinated
nearly 1,000 union volunteers, who called every one of the 17,000
labor union households in Martinez's district.
</P>
<P>
   On weekends, dozens of union members canvassed neighborhoods,
knocking on doors and talking to voters about Solis, who championed
a California ballot initiative to raise the minimum wage in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   On Election Day, about 60 union volunteers were up before dawn
distributing ``door hangers,'' printed literature on Solis that
provided the address of the voters' local polling place. By day's
end, 600 volunteers _ half union members _ walked precincts for
Solis.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our affiliates have a very good record of turning out
bodies and getting up early,'' said Sickler. ``They are used to
getting up at 5:30 in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez lost 2-to-1, becoming the only Democratic incumbent to
lose this year.
</P>
<P>
   Solis' victory was the culmination of a four-year strategy by
Contreras to spend union money on mobilizing union members to vote
instead of contributing directly to candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told the elected officials that the L.A. County Federation
of Labor is not now going to be an ATM machine for political
parties,'' said Contreras. ``What we have is our rank and file.''
</P>
<P>
   The political and organizing victories have made Los Angeles the
poster child of the AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think John Sweeney is really looking to California to lead
the American labor movement,'' said Kent Wong, a labor expert at
UCLA.ORGANIZATION REJUVENATED
</P>
<P>
   When John Sweeney assumed the reins of the 13 million member
AFL-CIO in late 1995, organized labor was in a tailspin. Union
workers in the work force, which peaked in the 1950s at 35 percent,
was plummeting toward single digits.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Republicans won control of the House for the first time
in four decades, and new House Speaker Newt Gingrich targeted Big
Labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Newt Gingrich did anything good for us, he scared the hell
out of us,'' said Sweeney, who built his campaign to succeed former
AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland around labor's thumping in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Under Sweeney, the AFL-CIO poured resources into helping the 68
member unions organize new workers. Sweeney also renewed the
AFL-CIO's emphasis on grass-roots activism and registering union
members to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has changed under Sweeney is a much more aggressive
effort in swing congressional districts with high levels of union
membership,'' said Richard Hurd, a labor expert at Cornell
University.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney has also encouraged unions to raise more political money
from members. This month, the Service Employees International
Union, the AFL-CIO's largest, gave an eye-popping $1 million check
to the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our members are just tired of not seeing any action on
prescription drugs, on the minimum wage, on expanding access to
health care,'' said Andrew Stern, SEIU's president.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of organized labor's sharpest critics give Sweeney
credit for helping to halve the Republican House majority in 1996,
and halving it again in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweeney is a tough competitor,'' said Bruce Josten, an
executive vice president at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. ``Anybody
who ignores him is a fool.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney was also among the first within the AFL-CIO to recognize
the potential for union growth among immigrants. In February, the
AFL-CIO reversed long-standing policy and embraced a call for
amnesty for the nation's 5 million to 6 million undocumented aliens
and an end to the sanctions against employers who hire them.
</P>
<P>
   The new platform is a dramatic turnaround for organized labor,
which historically regarded immigrants as a threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a real fear, I think, amongst a lot of workers
about losing jobs,'' said John Wilhelm, general president of the
Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees union, who spearheaded the
policy change. ``On the other hand, if you look at our history, the
labor movement was built by immigrants. It's going to be rebuilt by
immigrants or not at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, the 66-year-old son of Irish immigrants whose first
union job was in a New York City cemetery, found an instant ally
for his national vision in Contreras, one of six children born to
migrant farm workers.
</P>
<P>
   Contreras, 47, cut his teeth in the labor movement as a grape
picker in California's San Joaquin Valley, falling under the
charismatic spell of the late Cesar Chavez, the founder of the
United Farm Workers union.
</P>
<P>
   Contreras said he mastered the nuances of political power from
Chavez, whose giant portrait hangs behind his desk. From Chavez,
Contreras learned that even the poorest of the poor can wield power
if they join ranks.
</P>
<P>
   In his four years at the Los Angeles federation, which covers
350 local unions, Contreras has beefed up union organizing,
particularly among Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   He has also reached out to officials in the Catholic church such
as Cardinal Roger Mahony, who wield tremendous moral authority
among Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   Contreras has also brought the militancy he learned with Chavez
to the federation's political work, seeking ``warriors for working
families,'' those candidates who pledge to fight for labor's
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to hear in our endorsement hearings that somehow
we should support you because your grandfather belonged to a
union,'' he said. ``Don't come to us and tell me you are for
minimum wage because that's an insult. That for us is like saying
you are for the American flag. It's automatic. But what are you
going to do to assist our workers in organizing? Are you willing to
demonstrate, to visit owners, to help pass tough legislation giving
the workers the right to organize? That's what we are interested
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the November elections, Contreras is already looking
ahead to next year's Los Angeles city elections, when the mayor and
half the 15-member City Council stand for election.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to determine the political direction of Los
Angeles for decades to come, so it will be our No. 1 task,''
Contreras said. ``We will move heaven and earth to make sure that
our candidates win that election.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
