<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOATING-NEWPORT-BERMUDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YACHT IS A WORK OF ART IN RACE TO BERMUDA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Herb McCormick is the editor of Cruising World magazine.)  
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Friday, in a stiff southwesterly breeze over Rhode Island
Sound, 175 yachts answered the starting guns to begin the 42nd
running of the Newport-Bermuda Race. Among the boats competing for
top prizes were such modern thoroughbreds as Larry Ellison's
Sayonara, Jim Dolan's Sagamore and George Coumantaros' Boomerang.
</P>
<P>
   With a forecast of high pressure and light winds in the waters
off Bermuda, the prospect of a relatively easy but slow contest _
particularly for the smaller yachts _ appeared likely. But one of
the boats competing in this year's classic division, though not a
threat to the large, light front-runners, had already tasted glory
in a heavy-air edition of the race more than six decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   In 1936, in gusts of over 40 knots, the newly launched 53-foot
cutter Kirawan won the 635-mile biennial ocean race. Built in
Brooklyn for Robert P. Baruch, a member of the Manhasset Bay Yacht
Club, Kirawan launched the prestigious career of the yacht designer
Philip Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   Kirawan eventually moved to California, and in 1993 the film
producer Sandy Horowitz purchased her and began an extensive refit
under the direction of Tom Adams, a sailor and woodworker. ``I gave
Tom carte blanche to do the work, and he took this on heart and
soul,'' Horowitz said. ``Some people see boats as inanimate objects
but this one has a life of its own.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a rebuilt interior, hand-cut marble counters and even
a rolltop desk, Kirawan is a work of art. And with a seasoned
seven-man crew that includes John Rousmaniere, the yachting writer,
and John Jourdane, the former Whitbread racer, Kirawan may also
have some surprises for the upstarts. ``The nice thing is that she
really powers through a swell when those modern race boats are
pounding,'' Adams said. ``It's a pretty comfortable ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyon Sails in Record Time
</P>
<P>
   As they head south, some of the sailors in the Bermuda Race may
encounter the leading Open 60 monohulls en route to Newport to
complete the Europe 1 New Man trans-Atlantic race, which started
two weeks ago from Plymouth, England. The first finishers, in what
has been a wild affair, are due to arrive some time Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Sailing a 60-foot trimaran called Eure et Loir, the 44-year-old
Frenchman Francis Joyon last Wednesday won the multihull class in
record-setting style with a time of 9 days and 23 hours 21 minutes,
slicing nearly 10 hours off the mark set in 1988. The rugged Joyon
won with an old boat, small mast, tired sails and no sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   The story in the monohull class is no less intriguing. At or
near the front of the pack is the 23-year-old English sailor Ellen
MacArthur aboard Kingfisher, who took over the lead a week ago and
has been holding off the challenges of her countryman Mike Golding
and the French sailors Roland Jourdain and Catherine Chabaud.
Italy's Giovanni Soldini was also within striking distance.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen Open 60s started the race but, after three boats were
dismasted, it became an early war of attrition. MacArthur set a
frenetic pace and exhibited almost flawless tactics while weaving a
course through challenging weather systems.
</P>
<P>
   But she has not had an easy passage. Last week she fell through
a hatch and said, via e-mail: ``Terrible, terrible, terrible night.
Whacked my head and I think broke my finger.'' Later, her progress
came to a stunning halt when she collided with a whale. ``I'm not
sure what I'm more concerned about, the boat or the whale,'' she
reported, adding that the leviathan was probably killed in the
collision.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, it will take more than a giant sea creature to stop
Ellen MacArthur.
</P>
<P>
   A Record Atlantic Crossing  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the Bahamian island of San Salvador, New Zealand's Grant
Dalton and his crew aboard the 110-foot catamaran Club Med on
Sunday are also due to put the closing touches on a triumphant
trans-Atlantic crossing that started in Cadiz, Spain. The Club Med
team will almost certainly break the record for an east-to-west
Atlantic voyage. More importantly, with a 24-hour run of 625.7
miles last weekend _ an average speed of over 26 knots _ they also
smashed the record of 580 miles set by Steve Fossett's PlayStation.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first couple of hours we had a confused sea and we
weren't really going that fast,'' Dalton said last week via
satellite phone. ``When we thought we had a chance at the record
our intention was just to get one mile more than Fossett had got.
But when we did that with two hours to spare, we just kept pushing
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Dalton and Fossett are both using trans-Atlantic training runs
as a tune-up for The Race, the round-the-world event that begins
from Barcelona, Spain, on Dec. 31. ``We got a note from Fossett
saying he thought that 600 was possible but he was surprised to see
someone get through to 625,'' Dalton said. ``My feeling is that
he's pretty wily and he'll be itching to break our record.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, Dalton would like to race Fossett back across the
Atlantic, from New York to England, later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go on standby in the middle of July,'' Dalton said. ``If
we're able to make an arrangement with PlayStation that would be
fantastic. It would be a really good showdown.''
</P>
</TEXT>
