<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7124 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AT-HOME-REAL-NYT     06-17 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A METHOD OF CUTTING ESTATE TAXES 
</HEADLINE>
  By JAY ROMANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Although the House of Representatives voted this
month to kill the federal tax now imposed on estates that exceed
$675,000, the promise of a presidential veto has left tax planners
with ample incentive to continue advising clients about how to
reduce taxes on assets they will ultimately pass to their heirs.
</P>
<P>
   And with skyrocketing property values in the New York City
metropolitan area helping to propel more people into tax brackets
that could expose their estates to taxes _ at rates of up to 55
percent _ the planners say that one of the most talked-about
estate-planning strategies is the Family Limited Partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``FLPs are one of the hottest financial planning tools around,''
said Martin Shenkman, a Manhattan tax lawyer. ``They've been
packaged and sold as the estate-planning wonder drug of the
decade.'' Shenkman added, however, that like any estate-planning
strategy, a Family Limited Partnership must be used as only part of
an ``integrated overall estate and financial plan.''
</P>
<P>
   A Family Limited Partnership, Shenkman said, is a business
entity formed by members of a family to own and manage family
assets _ including real estate purchased as an investment. (Since
FLPs must have a business purpose to survive IRS scrutiny, they are
not used for primary residences or homes used solely for vacations.
Second homes that are rented out most of the year may be eligible.)
</P>
<P>
   As with any limited partnership, he said, the FLP has general
partners who run the business or manage the property _ usually the
parents _ and limited partners who have no say in management _
usually the children.
</P>
<P>
   And while the stated purpose of an FLP is to function as a
family business created to own and control one or more of the
family's assets, Shenkman said, one benefit of such an arrangement
is that the FLP can be used to transfer assets from the parents to
the children in a way that minimizes or even eliminates estate
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Engel, a Manhattan lawyer who specializes in estate
planning, explained that the tax savings that can be obtained using
an FLP are the result of three factors: the way that assets are
contributed to the partnership, the way that ownership of the
partnership itself is apportioned, and the way that each partner's
share of the partnership is valued for tax purposes.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, Engel said, assets like investment properties and
securities are transferred to the FLP by the general partners. And
while the general partners usually retain total control over
management of the partnership business, the documents used to
create an FLP typically give the general partners only a small
percentage of the actual ownership interest in the partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general partners can have as little as 1 percent interest
in the partnership,'' Engel said, adding that the remaining
ownership interests would be allocated as limited-partnership
interests. Those interests would then be given as gifts to the
children. What that accomplishes, he said, is that it allows
parents to transfer assets like investment properties into a
partnership owned almost entirely by the children _ without
requiring the parents to relinquish day-to-day control.
</P>
<P>
   And while the value of the transferred partnership interests
would be considered a gift for federal gift and estate tax purposes
_ thereby using up all or part of the $675,000 gift and estate tax
credit available to each parent (an amount that gradually increases
to $1 million in 2006) _ a significant tax savings ultimately
results because of the way the partnership interests are valued.
</P>
<P>
   Engel explained that since property owned by a limited
partnership is under the total control of the general partner, the
value of each limited partner's ownership interest is less than
what it would be if they owned the property outright.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, if property with a current market value of
$1.5 million is put into an FLP consisting of a general partner who
owns 1 percent of the partnership and three limited partners who
own 33 percent each, it is unlikely that any individual limited
partner's share would be worth $495,000 (33 percent of $1.5
million). That is because the general partner still has total
control over the property and because each of the limited partners
has only a minority interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means that putting the property in the FLP and
transferring limited-partnership interests to the children results
in a discount of its value for federal gift and estate tax
purposes,'' he said, adding that the amount of the discount _ which
must be determined by an appraiser _ can range anywhere from 25 to
60 percent of the market value of the property before the transfer.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he said, it is possible for a husband and wife to
transfer $1.5 million worth of investment property into an FLP _
and, ultimately, into the names of their children _ while using up
as little as $600,000 of their combined gift and estate tax
exemption.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald A. Fatoullah, a Forest Hills, Queens, estate-planning
lawyer, said that with careful planning and sufficient time, it may
even be possible for a married couple to transfer investment
property to their children without exposing any of the value to
gift and estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What many people do is they gift shares of the FLP to their
children or grandchildren in $10,000 yearly increments,'' he said,
explaining that under current tax law, a husband and wife can each
give each child and grandchild a tax-free gift of up to $10,000 a
year. Accordingly, Fatoullah said, instead of creating an FLP with
the children owning the majority of the limited-partnership
interests from the inception, some people will instead spread out
the transfer of those interests over a period of years to take
maximum advantage of the $10,000 annual gift exclusion.
</P>
<P>
   So, he said, a husband and wife who have three children and $1.5
million worth of investment property can transfer $60,000 worth of
limited partnership interests each year to the children without
using up any of their gift and estate tax credits. And if the value
of the partnership interests were to be discounted by, say, 50
percent, that same couple would actually be transferring up to
$120,000 in real property value each year.
</P>
<P>
   The three lawyers interviewed for this article emphasized
several points. First, no one estate-planning strategy is right for
every situation. For example, while FLPs can produce significant
estate tax savings, the beneficiaries would in all likelihood have
to pay capital-gains taxes when they ultimately sell the property.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, since the FLP is a partnership, the general partner is
personally liable for any claims against the partnership.
Accordingly, those who have serious concerns about liability might
want to opt for a limited liability company, a business structure
that provides benefits similar to those of an FLP while limiting
the liability of members to their actual investment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
