<SLUG> BC-REPUBLICAN-AD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW REPUBLICAN TV SPOT  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Republican and Democratic National Committees are on the air
this weekend with issue advertisements on behalf of Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas and Vice President Al Gore. The spots are running in
17 states, including crucial ones like Illinois, Michigan, Ohio and
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICAN SPOT
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Cold Harbor Films
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN: In the opening scenes, greeting-card images of
America _ an orange sunrise, a windmill on a wheatfield _ melt into
one another. Cut to a quick succession of shots of Bush mixing with
voters and then to a series of portraits of average citizens.
</P>
<P>
   SCRIPT ANNOUNCER: ``With our nation at peace and more prosperous
than ever, now is the time to find real solutions to America's
problems. George Bush knows that to keep our commitment to seniors
we must strengthen and improve Social Security now, or the
retirement of the baby boom generation will push it near
bankruptcy. He's proposing a bipartisan plan to strengthen and
improve Social Security. The Bush plan guarantees everyone at or
near retirement every dollar of their benefits. No cuts in Social
Security. You paid into it, it's your money and it will be there
for you. And the Bush plan gives younger workers a choice to invest
a small part of their Social Security in sound investments they
control for higher returns. Learn more about George Bush's
voluntary plan for personal Social Security retirement accounts.
The Bush blueprint: Better for seniors today, better for all of us
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY: With aging baby boomers inching ever closer to
eligibility for retirement benefits, shoring up Social Security has
become a signature issue of the presidential campaign. The party's
60-second commercial highlights Bush's plans for a partial
privatization of the system, allowing workers to invest part of
their payroll taxes as they see fit. Vice President Al Gore has
been a fierce critic of the idea, arguing that the less financially
savvy could fall prey to foolhardy investment schemes.
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD: A direct appeal to Bush's own generation. While polls
show that older people are wary of privatization plans for their
retirement money, younger voters are more amenable to the idea. The
spot is also an emblem of the Bush marketing style: no scare
tactics, just lots of postcard panoramas and loving snaps of the
candidate wading into crowds. As such, it is indistinguishable from
Bush's own commercials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 1711EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000617.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7133 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SEATTLE-REAL-1070(2TA     06-17 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-REAL-1070(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: HIGH-END RENTALS IN DOWNTOWN SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARRIET KING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Affluent workers willing to pay thousands of dollars
for monthly rent have created a brisk high-end apartment market
downtown, a turnaround from the mid-1990s, when few people wanted
to live in the business district, anchor retailers were leaving and
planners feared the city center was becoming blighted.
</P>
<P>
   Prospective renters began taking ``hard hat'' tours of 276
luxury apartments last month in the final two of four towers that
Harbor Properties is building a block from the waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   The $155.8 million Harbor Steps complex will have a total of 730
apartments, as well as 75,600 square feet of office and retail
space. A courtyard park slopes down the hillside site between First
and Western avenues. One of the new buildings will open in July,
the other in November. Both will have 17 stories.
</P>
<P>
   The 454 apartments occupied in the first two towers, each 25
stories, command top dollar for rent _ $955 to $5,000 a month.
Harbor Steps boasts 98 percent occupancy and is the only major
apartment complex in the central business district, although other
apartments have sprung up in Belltown to the north.
</P>
<P>
   Residents are close to waterfront restaurants and they can buy
groceries at the historic Pike Place Market a block north or browse
in the new Seattle Art Museum across First Avenue from the Harbor
Steps concierge desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apartments are ideal for people who work downtown and can
afford to buy homes or condominiums but who may have money invested
in other ways and don't need real estate as a tax write-off,'' said
Stephen Fina, Harbor Properties marketing director. ``Forty percent
of our renters are new to Seattle, often employed in high-tech
industries. They follow the job market and may be in Seattle today
and Silicon Valley next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The average age is 44, and the average stay 16 months. There are
few school-age children because of the lack of schools downtown. A
day-care center will be able to handle up to 60 preschool children
when the new towers are completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1994, when we marketed the first tower, we were nervous
about how long it would take to rent units,'' Fina said. ``We were
certain downtown living would be highly desirable, but had no idea
of the pent-up demand.'' Yet the apartments in the 25-story tower
leased completely within four months. The second 25-story tower
opened in July 1997, two years ahead of schedule and was fully
rented in two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference on First Avenue is like black and white, due to
the number of people now living in this neighborhood,'' said Tim
Warner, director of corporate communications at Immunex Corp., a
biotech company across Western Avenue from Harbor Steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two and a half years ago, I'd walk down the street at 9 p.m.
and the only other people out looked unsavory. But Harbor Steps is
making a dramatic impact. Now there are a lot of people out, some
in fancy clothes going to the art museum or the symphony at the new
Benaroya Hall on Second Avenue.'' Immunex houses new executives in
Harbor Steps until they get settled.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle's early years, First Avenue was called Front Street,
and businesses catered to workers on the docks and industrial
buildings and to sailors. In 1953, the elevated Alaskan Way Viaduct
was built along the harbor and it discouraged downtown waterfront
redevelopment.
</P>
<P>
   Stimson Bullitt, chairman of Harbor Properties, said he quietly
assembled the adjacent properties along First and Western avenues
in 1972 that would become Harbor Steps ``because they looked like
good bargains.'' He added: ``They were run-down and many were empty
ruins of taverns, pawnshops, tattoo parlors and flophouses. I
thought that since this is part of the center of town, the area had
a good future.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullitt, who comes from a prominent founding family in Seattle
that had long invested in downtown real estate, said he wanted to
create an urban neighborhood with housing and parks to revitalize
the waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   ``The downtown had a big concentration of office buildings and
more were going up in the 1980s and I thought there might be an
excess of office space,'' he recalled. ``But a great many jobs were
being created downtown and I thought it would be appealing to live
within walking distance from work.''
</P>
<P>
   He chose to build rental apartments rather than condominiums.
``With condos, if you hit the market right when your doors open,
you can make a lot of money,'' he said. ``But if the market is not
right, you end up with empty buildings and a big debt. With
apartments, if the market is not good, you can lower the rent and
cover financing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullitt could not get construction loans at first. ``Bankers
just rolled their eyeballs toward the ceiling,'' he said. ``They'd
look at the $5 million cost of the staircase park and ask what
revenues I'd get from that and turned me down as a fool. But after
the first building did well, financing was easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Harbor Steps was coming to market during tough years for
Seattle's downtown. In 1992, a department store anchor, Frederick &AMP;
Nelson, closed at Fifth Avenue and Pine Street and other retailers
followed, leaving boarded buildings smeared with graffiti. The
business district became a ghost town at night as people avoided
the skyscraper canyons out of concerns about safety.
</P>
<P>
   But when Nordstrom moved its flagship store into the Frederick's
building in a $100 million renovation in August 1998, it triggered
a stampede of new mixed-use development. Prominent national
retailers including Nike, FAO Schwarz, Banana Republic, Urban
Outfitters and Anthropologie arrived and the downtown gained a new
vibrancy.
</P>
<P>
   The redevelopment spark also caught on along First Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Boutiques like Flora &AMP; Henri Children's Clothier have replaced
some of the seedier businesses. However, adjacent to Harbor Steps
to the north is the Lusty Lady Live Show with a marquee that
proclaims, ``Now Showing: Everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Harbor Steps has become so popular that monthly rents are
soaring. In 1994, studios rented for $683 but jumped to $955 in
1998 and to $1,110 today. One-bedroom units leased for $944 in
1994, $1,372 in 1998 and $1,905 today, up 39 percent in two years.
Two-bedroom apartments leased for $1,437 originally and for $2,098
in 1998, and then rose 28 percent to $2,680 today. Penthouses cost
up to $5,000 today, more than double the $2,227 in 1994.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Tenney, a certified public accountant who is the chief
financial officer for three companies, moved into Harbor Steps in
February. Only studios were available, but residents are allowed
first crack at the new apartments under construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the hard-hat tour and fell in love with a fifth-floor
suite with a balcony overlooking the Harbor Steps plaza and park,''
he said. ``It was so charming I took out my checkbook immediately
and made a deposit.'' He will pay $2,400 a month for a one-bedroom
apartment and move in in July.
</P>
<P>
   Fina, the marketing director, wants to transform the outdoor
plaza into a spot where the anticipated 1,100 residents can mingle
and linger over carry-outs from coffee shops in the complex.
Indoors, residents can relax in three spas, work out in the fitness
center or basketball court or on the indoor climbing wall, and hold
Super Bowl parties in the big-screen theater room.
</P>
<P>
   Since many residents have been ordering groceries on the
Internet via HomeGrocer.com, Harbor Steps may set up a refrigerated
area where groceries can be delivered while residents work.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, northeast of Nordstrom at the edge of the retail
district on Seventh Avenue, Continental-Bentall, a developer, is
building Westlake Tower, a 366-unit apartment building. ``It
appeals to downtown professionals wanting to give up their commute
and be closer to the city's plethora of shopping, dining and
entertainment,'' said Claudio Guincher, Continental-Bentall's chief
operating officer.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind Westlake Tower are low-rise buildings ripe for
redevelopment. Gary Carpenter, chief operating officer of Bentall
U.S., says the downtown's future growth will spread here ``because
land is available _ we have plans for several other residential
properties and are bullish on that whole area.'' Both companies are
subsidiaries of Bentall Corp. of Vancouver, British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Scott a principal of Dupre &AMP; Scott Apartment Advisors,
which analyzes apartment pricing, said: ``Nobody downtown or in
Belltown has been in the same league as Harbor Steps with its
high-quality, high-end product, which is as good as rental housing
gets in Seattle. Westlake Tower will be its first competition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
