<HEADLINE>
ARCHBISHOP'S INSTALLATION IS BOTH SERVICE AND PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-EGAN) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Amid the haze of incense, the choral chants of
``Hallelujah'' and the overall gravitas of ancient Catholic rites,
the most crucial moment over the next two days of worship and
celebration at St. Patrick's Cathedral actually comes down to a
small bit of papal paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday afternoon, a letter from Pope John Paul II appointing
Edward M. Egan the archbishop of New York will be read aloud. Then,
Monsignor Edward D. O'Donnell, the chancellor of the archdiocese,
will notarize it, stamp it with the diocesan seal and order it
deposited in the archives.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, the installation of New York's ninth archbishop
will be official under canon law. But the praying and the partying
will have just begun.
</P>
<P>
   The installation of a Catholic archbishop typically offers a
balance of solemnity and revelry, of spectacular pageantry and
pious introspection. It is a time for jestful greetings and for
serious talk about the future of the diocese. The program for
Sunday and Monday incorporates it all.
</P>
<P>
   The worship will take place during two services at St.
Patrick's. On Sunday, the archbishop's official appointment, called
a ceremony of canonical possession, will precede the regular late
afternoon service of solemn vespers. On Monday, hundreds of
dignitaries will attend a celebratory Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The spectacle will come from two processionals, one of them a
parade on Monday from the Catholic Center, on First Avenue and 56th
Street, to St. Patrick's, with at least eight cardinals, 18
archbishops, more than 100 bishops and many priests and nuns.
</P>
<P>
   Presiding over much of the official ceremony will be Archbishop
Gabriel Montalvo, the apostolic nuncio who serves in Washington as
the Vatican's ambassador to the United States. He will welcome and
present the new archbishop to local prelates and read the pope's
letter of appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Egan will be the principal celebrant of Sunday's vespers service
and Monday's Mass. He will wear festive white vestments, which
Monsignor Ferdinando Berardi, the coordinating master of
ceremonies, said represent continuity in the church. He added that
the installation of the archbishop was a moment to reflect on
thousands of years of church traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's ceremony will begin about 3:30 p.m. with a procession
of banners, led by one proclaiming ``Unus Dominus, Una Fides, Unum
Baptisma'' _ ``one Lord, one faith, one baptism.'' It shows a map
of the Archdiocese of New York with the waters of baptism flowing
through it.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the processional from the Catholic Center will begin
about 1 p.m., with members of religious orders, students,
seminarians, deacons and priests in front and bishops, archbishops,
cardinals and finally Egan at the rear. The choir will be singing
``Hallelujah'' as he enters St. Patrick's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
