<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HABITAT-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: A LONGTIME HOMEOWNER TURNS TO ASSISTED LIVING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky.)   By TRISH HALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rose Strassburger was married for 60 years to Martin
Strassburger. They had met as teen-agers in Germany, leaving in the
late 1930s before the Nazis could send them to concentration camps.
They moved to New York City, married and lived in Manhattan in
Washington Heights, which was so thick with German Jews,
Strassburger said, ``we called it the Fourth Reich.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, they moved to Elmhurst, Queens, and bought a two-family
house where they raised their two sons, renting one half and living
in the other. They commuted together every day to Manhattan, where
they ran a women's accessories business. He was the talker, meeting
with buyers; she did the office work. ``I was always a
businesswoman,'' she said, ``even as a young girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, two years ago, her husband died, leaving her alone in a
way she had never been alone. She was inconsolable. Her sons
worried about her. ``The loneliness is something very bad,''
Strassburger said. She had her work with the sisterhood at the
synagogue, the Elmhurst Jewish Center, which she and her husband
had helped start. But it wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   And so, six months ago, exactly 50 years to the day she had
moved into her house, she left. ``My children begged me to go,''
she said. She left most of her furniture with the people who bought
the house, packed up her belongings, had the moving men take her
things, and locked the door behind her with absolutely no regrets.
``I don't feel sorry one bit,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she has been living at Atria in Kew Gardens, a
retirement home that opened late last year. It is called an
assisted-living facility because it provides meals for its 85
residents (it has room for 143) and, if needed, help with
activities that might have become difficult.
</P>
<P>
   This is nothing like a nursing home. It's more like a boarding
school in an attractively decorated hotel, but most people are in
their 70s or 80s instead of their teens. Strassburger lives in a
large two-room apartment with a kitchenette. Although she could
have some meals there, she prefers to go to the dining room. In
fact, she goes downstairs early for meals, as do most of the
residents, for a little socializing before it's actually time to
eat.
</P>
<P>
   The food is kosher, she said, and very good. ``Last night we had
a delicious pot roast,'' she said. ``I asked for more meat, and
that was no problem.'' There are always three choices of entree; if
she hadn't been in the mood for pot roast, she could have had
halibut, or barbecued chicken.
</P>
<P>
   She has her meals at Table 14 with the same group of people.
Some of the tables are made up of longtime Queens residents who
have known each other for years; one consists of four women
originally from Jamaica Estates.
</P>
<P>
   She likes the people she has met, and has not found it difficult
to make friends. ``I'm a very outgoing person,'' she said. ``I
greet people and I introduce myself.'' Occasionally, she goes to
lectures and parties, she said, but she skips many of the other
activities, which seem to be offered almost hourly. ``I'm not the
type to go into arts and crafts,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For those who don't like being in their own apartments all day,
there's a library with a computer; an open kitchen with coffee,
tea, cookies and fruit always available; a wellness center where
residents can meet with nurses and doctors; a movie room; a place
to play bingo; a beauty parlor; a smoking lounge; and a private
dining room for entertaining family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Architecturally, the nine-story brick building with its
underground parking garage fits in so well with the neighborhood
that it looks like it has been there forever. It was built by Jeff
Levine, president of Levine Builders, who lives in Queens, for
Atria Communities, a Louisville, Ky., company that owns 109
retirement communities nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Once a month there is a ``fireside chat'' with the woman in
charge, Larissa Kostal, whose own grandmother lives at Atria.
``Larissa is in the center like a queen,'' said Strassburger, who
is obviously fond of the young woman. At those talks, the residents
bring up issues that concern them. Some thought breakfast, at 8
a.m., was too early, and so they had a vote on whether to change
meal hours. ``Eighty-five percent voted to keep it the same,''
Kostal said. The democratic approach makes sense to her. ``This is
their home,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The average age of the residents is 82, she said, and they pay
$3,550 a month for a two-room suite with daily housekeeping and a
thorough weekly apartment cleaning, plus all their meals, with
additional charges for nursing care if needed. Many residents, she
said, take anti-depressant medication, which doesn't surprise her
given what they must cope with at their age. ``It's all about
loss,'' she said. ``Some are outliving their children. They get
here and they're all in the same boat together.''
</P>
<P>
   When Strassburger moved in, she brought the mezuzah _ a piece of
parchment inscribed with a passage from Deuteronomy that is encased
and affixed to the door post of a house _ from her old home.
``That's the first thing you put in a home when you move in,'' she
said. A wall in her bedroom holds a plaque in appreciation from her
synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still very active there,'' she said. ``That was my heart
and soul.'' The rabbi visits her once a week.
</P>
<P>
   On a typical day, she'll make phone calls after breakfast, to
her friends and family, which includes five grandchildren and four
great-grandchildren. After lunch, she tends to take a nap, and
watch her favorite soap opera, ``General Hospital.'' After dinner,
at about 7 p.m., she returns to her rooms for the night.
</P>
<P>
   She is particularly impressed by the skilled housekeeping at
Atria. ``The cleanliness in this house is something out of the
ordinary,'' she said. She no longer has to work in the yard, which
was tedious to her, or even clean up a kitchen. ``My fingernails
are so nice from not doing dishes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, she says, ``there is nothing missing here.'' And how do
her sons feel about the move they encouraged her to make? ``They
are happy because I'm happy,'' she said. ``Now, they are calling me
only two times a day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
