<HEADER>
A7138 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-EGAN-NYT &LR;      06-17 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-EGAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGAN BRINGS MANAGEMENT STRENGTHS TO N.Y. ARCHDIOCESE 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURIE GOODSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a ceremony at St. Patrick's Cathedral Sunday,
Bishop Edward Michael Egan of Bridgeport, Conn., will present a
parchment letter in Latin from Pope John Paul II that formally
appoints Egan the ninth archbishop of New York.
</P>
<P>
   It is still, to many church observers, a surprise choice. Egan's
name was not among the three candidates recommended to the pope to
succeed Cardinal John O'Connor, and he has not been particularly
prominent among the nation's Catholic bishops.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, a look at his record and his reputation suggests that
perhaps it is no surprise at all. New York is an archdiocese badly
in need of a corporate caretaker, and Egan is a consummate
corporate executive.
</P>
<P>
   Egan has mixed with the wealthy and the prominent at
fund-raisers and dinner parties, bringing in millions to support
Catholic charities and schools. He has been an attentive boss to
his employees, the clergy, from their training as seminarians to
their care in retirement. He has been decisive at downsizing and
consolidating schools and parishes.
</P>
<P>
   And in the five weeks since he was named as O'Connor's
successor, Egan has proved attentive to public relations in New
York. His picture has already been posted on the archdiocese's Web
site. He bantered with reporters in two news conferences. And when
he is asked about accusations of pedophilia by clergy members in
Bridgeport, he already knows to respond with a terse ``No
comment,'' to avoid supplying any usable television sound bites.
</P>
<P>
   But no leader is good at everything, and the question raised by
many familiar with Egan's past performance is whether he will also
prove to be a spiritual shepherd to New York's Catholic laity, the
common Christian faithful who make up the church's soul and 98
percent of its membership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cardinal O'Connor was a great pastor, and Ed Egan is a great
official,'' said Eugene Kennedy, a writer and former Maryknoll
priest who knows Egan. ``Ed Egan has always viewed the church from
behind a desk, while O'Connor saw men die and held them in his arms
in Vietnam. The great genius of the church is to be pastoral _ not
to be an efficient organization, or even a dominant organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, a retired professor of psychology at Loyola University
in Chicago, said Egan was a model of the church leader the Vatican
now prefers as its bishops.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain class of cleric to whom you apply the word
`churchman,' and that is what Ed Egan is, to his fingertips,''
Kennedy said. ``These men live and die for the institutional
church. They are therefore strong pillars, even if the rest of the
institution may be eroding in high winds or from internal problems,
such as priestly pedophilia, these pillars will stand.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the Bridgeport diocese was sued by 31 plaintiffs
claiming abuse by eight priests over more than 30 years. Under
Egan, the diocese's lawyers have aggressively fought the
complaints, and he has been criticized for refusing to discuss the
accusations and for making no overtures to the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Having now mounted one of the highest peaks in church
leadership, Egan will have an opportunity to make his mark on an
archdiocese that is badly in need of just the kind of
administrative experience that he brings.
</P>
<P>
   The New York archdiocese, which spends more than $527 million
annually, encompasses 413 parishes, 238 elementary schools, 55 high
schools, 17 hospitals, 13 day care centers and 11 mental health
residences. Many parishes can no longer support their neighboring
schools. Church finances are not public record, but some hospitals
are believed to face millions of dollars in debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be able to manage a complex entity, and he is very
capable of that,'' said Bill Baker, the president of WNET, who
belongs to a parish in Riverside, Conn., and who knows Egan.
</P>
<P>
   If Egan decides to consolidate or close parishes, schools or
hospitals, his abilities as a pastor and diplomat will be tested.
When he merged two congregations in Stamford, Conn., the Hispanic
parishioners at one said that he ignored their opposition to
joining with the Slovak congregation, and that he came across as an
autocrat.
</P>
<P>
   Egan, known as a man who does his homework, said he would spend
the summer traveling around the New York archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the key project for me now will be to learn about the
archdiocese,'' Egan said at a farewell news conference in
Connecticut last week. ``I don't know what the situation is in the
schools, about Catholic charities, or with the priests and the
religious. The truth of the matter is that all I can do is spend
this summer listening to the people.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Egan is also unlikely to celebrate Mass each week at St.
Patrick's Cathedral, and instead plans to spend Sundays visiting a
variety of parishes, his spokesmen said.
</P>
<P>
   To the people he will serve, the new archbishop is largely
unknown. In conversations at parishes on Friday, some did not
recognize his name, and others said they did not know anything
about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know in depth about him, but I hope he does good
because we need it,'' said Rhudy Correra, who is 15 and works at
the Church of the Incarnation in Washington Heights. ``I hope he
reaches out to the people that are less fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Correra's friend Franklin Rodriguez, voiced an observation
that illustrates just the sort of chasm facing Egan in an
archdiocese so divided by race and class.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not really well known in the minority community,'' said
Rodriguez, who is 16, ``because the church only explained him to
the upper-class areas.''
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, Egan courted the affluent, playing the piano at
benefit dinners and talking art history at parties. He persuaded
the executives and chairmen of such companies as General Electric,
Xerox, Pepsico, Merrill Lynch, Citi-Group and IBM to serve on the
board of a charity he founded, the Inner City Foundation for
Charity and Education, said Richard Stone, the foundation's
director. The foundation raises money for Catholic and nonsectarian
schools and charities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bishop is an eloquent speaker,'' Stone said, ``and he has
an excellent way of presenting a case and engaging individuals and
corporations to support his endeavors.''
</P>
<P>
   As O'Connor came to understand, the archbishop of New York has a
large constituency outside the church to charm. He is constantly
being challenged to ideological duels by a variety of religious and
secular groups _ Jews, gays, feminists and others. The archbishop's
reputation will be partly defined by how he responds to these
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the political situation in New York, the Hispanics, the
blacks, the Jews, in many ways it is the fish bowl of the world,
and if you sneeze everyone knows,'' said Rabbi Jack Bemporad,
director of the Center for Interreligious Understanding, in
Englewood, N.J., who used to run a similar center at Sacred Heart
University in Fairfield, Conn., where Egan is chairman of the
board.
</P>
<P>
   ``The archdiocese has a kind of exposure that I don't think
Bishop Egan is used to,'' Bemporad said. ``I think that Bishop Egan
can learn in the trenches, but I think he's got a way to go. This
is a very complicated position here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
