u a BC-OBIT-SPINGARN-NYT &LR;      06-17 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SPINGARN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATALIE SPINGARN DIES AT 78; ADVOCATE FOR CANCER SURVIVORS
</HEADLINE>
  By ERIC V. COPAGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Natalie Davis Spingarn, a medical writer who endured multiple
bouts of cancer and became a prominent spokeswoman for cancer
survivors, died on June 6 in Washington, D.C. She was 78.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was pancreatic cancer, her son Jonathan, said.
</P>
<P>
   Spingarn's latest book, ``The New Cancer Survivors: Living with
Grace, Fighting with Spirit,'' was published this year. Her
personal story ``Hanging in There: Living Well on Borrowed Time,''
was published in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``She created the `Cancer Survivor's Bill of Rights' for the
75th anniversary of the American Cancer Society,'' said Joann
Schellenbach, a spokeswoman for the society. The document, written
in 1988, was widely distributed among those with cancer, and
Spingarn became an important figure in the patient movement,
Schellenbach said.
</P>
<P>
   Spingarn's paper demanded that patients have a say in their
medical treatment, that former cancer patients be freed of any
social stigma and that employers and insurance companies not
discriminate against them.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer pervaded Spingarn's life and the lives of many around
her. She had a mastectomy in 1974. But the cancer spread, first to
her spine, for which she had radiation therapy in 1977, then to her
hip, for which she had chemotherapy in 1979. She had a second
mastectomy in 1981. Spingarn's grandmother died of cancer. Her two
sisters had breast cancer, and one died of pancreatic cancer. One
of her two sons is a lymphoma survivor.
</P>
<P>
   Natalie Davis was born May 26, 1922, in New York City, and
reared in New Rochelle. She graduated with a bachelor of arts
degree from Vassar College in 1943, and became a journalist, then
wrote on health and social policy for the federal government. In
the early 1960s, she became a staff assistant to Abraham Ribicoff,
the secretary of Health, Education and Welfare, and became his
executive assistant when he was elected senator from Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Spingarn is survived by her husband, Jerome Spingarn; two sons,
Jonathan of Atlanta and Jeremy of Norwood, Mass.; and two
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 1751EDT &QL; 
