<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7140 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-YONKERS-NYT &LR;      06-17 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-YONKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YONKER'S FIRES CONTENTIOUS SCHOOLS SUPERINTENDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATE ZERNIKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yonkers school board fired its schools
superintendent Friday night after he opposed the city's acceptance
of a federal court's lifting of the longstanding court order for
the system to desegregate its schools.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden firing stunned city politicians and residents,
despite weeks of escalating friction between the superintendent,
Andre J. Hornsby, and Mayor John Spencer. The board voted to fire
Hornsby, the city's first black superintendent, just after he
announced improved test scores and the narrowing of a gap in
achievement between black and white students _ precisely the
challenge he was brought in to address in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Hornsby was pressuring the mayor to provide more city money to
cover a school system deficit he estimated at $34 million. But the
dispute over money was inextricably tied to the contention over
diversity in schools in a city that has long been a battleground
for desegregation efforts.
</P>
<P>
   A federal court recently ruled that Yonkers, the state's
fourth-largest school district, was free of the vestiges of
segregation that had prompted the 1986 desegregation order, which
brought the system more money from city and state governments.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor and the school board were eager to escape the stigma
of desegregation, and voted not to appeal the decision. Hornsby
though, argued that there were still remnants of racism in the
system and that the decision should be appealed.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters applauded Hornsby as a champion of minority children
_ who now make up about 75 percent of the school district, compared
with 35 percent when the court ordered it to desegregate in 1988 _
and expressed concern that Hornsby's firing would allow the city to
walk away from its commitment to raising minority achievement.
</P>
<P>
   But school board members insisted they were not abandoning the
goals of desegregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our schools are desegregated,'' said Thomas Weibrecht, a board
member. ``Eventually every court order must come to an end, and
when your schools are desegregated and you're providing a quality
education for every child, it is time for the federal courts to
leave. Federal oversight takes away local control and allows some
judge in Manhattan to dictates to the people of this city, and
worse to the children of this city, how they should be educated.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornsby, a former college football player who spoke in the hard
charging metaphors of the game _ he once said he came at people
``head on'' _ increasingly angered the mayor with his public
declarations in support of continuing the desegregation order.
</P>
<P>
   ``He alienated forces he should have been working with,''
Weibrecht said. ``We're going to move forward, collaboratively and
cooperatively with the teachers union and the mayor, and all the
people that should have been working on this to begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornsby left the meeting Friday without comment, and could not
be reached Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a passion for academic excellence, that came from his
competitive spirit,'' said Joseph Pastore, a professor at Pace
University and the court-appointed monitor in the city's
desegregation case. ``The guy is used to competing in so many ways,
he was challenged by the opportunity to help children to ratchet up
their performance, and I think he would have done that.''
</P>
<P>
   While the dispute was at heart about race, Pastore said, in many
ways it was similar to ones in New York City, and in Yonkers, over
money and control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
