<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7142 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-ECKBO-NYT &LR;      06-17 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ECKBO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARRETT ECKBO, 89, CALIFORNIA LANDSCAPE ARCHITECT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Garrett Eckbo, a pioneer of modern landscape design and a
leading practitioner of California landscape architecture, died on
May 15 at his home in Oakland. He was 89.
</P>
<P>
   Through a broad scope of design work, from camps for migrant
farm workers to estate gardens for Hollywood grandees, Eckbo helped
establish modernist landscapes as a norm in gardening. His
extensive writings, full of passionate belief in the public role of
the landscape architect, are now considered important documents on
the formative years of modern landscape architecture, with its
emphasis on asymmetrical paved forms, native plantings and abstract
sculptural elements.
</P>
<P>
   Eckbo was determined to educate students and the public about
the significance of landscape design, ``beyond the confines of the
private garden to the level of the housing complex, the waterfront
and the city scale,'' in the words of George Hargreaves, chairman
of the landscape architecture department at Harvard University's
Graduate School of Design.
</P>
<P>
   Eckbo was born on Nov. 28, 1910, in Cooperstown, N.Y. The family
soon moved West so that his father could pursue new business
opportunities. Eckbo enrolled in Marin Junior College in Kentfield,
Calif., transferring to the University of California at Berkeley in
1932. His decision to enroll in the landscape program, he said in
later years, was almost random. ``I always liked to play with
plants in the garden, and my mother told me I was artistic,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   By 1936, he was on a scholarship at Harvard, chafing under the
elaborately codified tradition of the Beaux-Arts approach to
landscapes while students of architecture were pursuing modern
concepts of dynamic flow and material innovation under the auspices
of Walter Gropius and Laszlo Moholy-Nagy. Eckbo, with his
classmates James Rose and Dan Kiley, started exploring ways to
adapt modern principles borrowed from architecture, abstract
painting and science to landscapes. He took architecture courses
with Gropius and wrote a thesis called ``Contempoville: An
Examination of the Planned American Suburb.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1937, Eckbo married Arline Williams, who survives him, with
two daughters, Marilyn Kweskin and Alison Peper, both of Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Eckbo's first jobs upon graduation _ working with Norman Bel
Geddes on the General Motors Pavilion at the 1939 World's Fair and
for the U.S. Housing Authority on courtyards for public housing _
inspired a lifelong commitment to the public spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Back in California, Eckbo worked for the Farm Security
Administration in the 1940s on developing more humane housing for
migrant farm workers.
</P>
<P>
   The postwar housing boom allowed Eckbo plenty of opportunity to
develop his ideas. He formed a partnership with his brother-in-law,
Edward Williams, that evolved into EDAW, one of the leading
landscape design practices in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Eckbo's signature garden was typically asymmetrical, with
hedges, pavings and plantings used to delineate diagonals, arcs and
circles. He also experimented with introducing materials, plastic
or aluminum, to be seen as artificial abstractions within the
natural realm.
</P>
<P>
   Eckbo turned often to writing to express his opinions and
promote the tenets of modernism both to professionals and backyard
gardeners. He published his first book, ``Landscape for Living,''
in 1950. Around that time, he started teaching, first at the
University of Southern California and later at Berkeley, where he
was chairman of the landscape department from 1963 to 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Among Eckbo's projects were the Berkeley waterfront, the Alcoa
Forecast Garden in Los Angeles and the 256-acre Ladera planned
residential community near Palo Alto, which many scholars consider
the postwar period's finest subdivision plan, although it was never
completed.
</P>
<P>
   Eckbo's work for private clients included gardens for Gary
Cooper and Louis Mayer. In 1975, he received the American Society
of Landscape Architects Medal of Honor.
</P>
<P>
   In later years, Eckbo focused on environmental design, serving
as an urban landscape consultant in Brazil, Kuwait and Japan, while
continuing to write books and articles. In 1997, Berkeley's
University Art Museum presented an exhibition called ``Garrett
Eckbo: Modern Landscapes for Living.''
</P>
<P>
   Eckbo published his last book in 1998. Called ``People in a
Landscape,'' it continues his basic theme that landscapes can link
society and nature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
