<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000617.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7146 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SEMINARY-PRESIDENT061     06-17 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEMINARY-PRESIDENT0618-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas mom to head seminary
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A Texas minister who describes being a wife and mother
as her ``highest calling'' will become president of Columbia
Theological Seminary in Decatur later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The board of trustees of the mainline Presbyterian school
elected the Rev. Laura S. Mendenhall, 53, pastor of Westminster
Presbyterian Church in Austin., Tex., on Saturday. She takes office
Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Mendenhall is ``one of the top five female pastors in the
country in terms of her stature in the denomination,'' said Jerry
Van Marter, who heads news services for the Presbyterian Church
(U.S.A.).
</P>
<P>
   ``Columbia has a tradition of calling pastor-theologians. She is
certainly that,'' said Erskine Clarke, a faculty representative to
the search committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found in her a person of deep faith who possesses great
personal integrity, charisma and gifts of leadership to take the
seminary to new levels of service to the church.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendenhall will be the eighth president of the 172-year-old
seminary, and the first woman to hold that office. In a typical
Columbia graduating class, women make up 40 to 50 percent of
students receiving the Master of Divinity degree, the usual
preparation for pastors, said Clarke, interim dean of the faculty.
</P>
<P>
   Although she hates to leave her role as senior pastor,
Mendenhall said in a telephone interview, ``The idea of getting to
invite and encourage and prepare other people to do something that
has been so personally fulfilling to me is very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendenhall has two grown children. Her husband, who is president
of Presbyterian Children's Homes in Austin, Texas, will move to
Decatur and look for a job in metro Atlanta, she said.
</P>
<P>
   My passion is being a pastor. I love it with every cell in my
body.
</P>
<P>
   To be with a person who's dying, to be with folks whose family
is breaking up and help them heal, to baptize a person, to get to
bury the saints _ I think it's the greatest privilege there is.
It's not to be taken lightly. It's to be jumped into with both
feet.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mendenhall was a student at Austin College in Sherman,
Texas, the minister of the church she attended suggested that she
consider the pastorate, she said. ``I had no model for a woman as a
pastor. It looked to me if I pursued that, I would have to give up
the notion of being a wife and mom.''
</P>
<P>
   She intended to become an English teacher instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not have been good at teaching grammar, probably, but
I would have been good at helping people write and appreciate the
writing of others,'' she said. ``Often you're dealing with the same
questions we take to scripture. What is life? What is meaningful?
Where is God? Who am I? How can I find peace in life?''
</P>
<P>
   To further prepare to teach, she enrolled in Presbyterian School
of Christian Education in Richmond, Va. As a student there, she met
her husband, Charles ``Chuck'' Mendenhall, a student at Union
Seminary.
</P>
<P>
   She also became convinced that she could be wife and mother and
also pastor a church.
</P>
<P>
   Mendenhall served on the mission field in Zaire, taught Bible,
and served as associate or co-pastor of churches in Florida and
Texas before becoming senior pastor of the 850-member Westminster
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia had an enrollment last school year of 550 students.
Another 600 people took classes through the seminary's Lay
Institute of Theology.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 1809EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
