   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- June 17, 2000 -- MANHATTAN-MARATHON-SWIM --
Rex Painter, of St. Augustine, Fla. , a 40-year-old dentist, gets a
unique view of the Brooklyn Bridge as he participates in the 2000
Manhattan Island Marathon Swim with 35 other swimmers and two relay
teams in a 28.5 miles swim around Manhattan, Saturday. Painter
plans to swim the English Channel this summer. (Vincent Laforet/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) DAMASCUS, Syria -- June 17, 2000 -- SYRIA -- Syria's
Baath Party, the structural support beneath the 30-year rule of the
late Hafez Assad, gathered Saturday to pledge allegiance to his
34-year-old son, Bashar, and to vest him formally with the
political authority he had quietly exercised from the shadows in
the last two years of his father's illness. Dr. Bashar Al-Assad at
the Baath Party congress, which was first called to make him regent
but is now expected to endorse him as president. (Courtney
Kealy/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- June 17, 2000 -- VA-SENATE-RACE-2 -- At one
point, Democrtatic Sen. Charles S. Robb of Virginia trailed 12
points behind a formidable Republican challenger, former Gov.
George F. Allen, prompting widespread speculation that Robb might
wisely retreat and call it a decent career after 12 years in the
Senate. Sen. Robb,whose re-election campaign is going even better
that his fellow Democrats expected, met with students from George
Mason University at his office in Washington last week. (Paul
Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) EMPORIA, Va. -- June 17, 2000 -- VA-SENATE-RACE-1 --
Former Republican Gov. Goerge F. Allen of Virginia, a very popular,
ebulliently combative politician with a substantial record as
governor, has been campaigning across the state since 1998. He is
now in a close battle with Democratic Sen. Charles S. Robb of
Virginia, whose re-election campaign is going even better that his
fellow Democrats expected. Allen brought his Senate campaign to the
town of Emporia last week. (Justin Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- June 16, 2000 -- SUMMER-JOBS -- A decade of
unparalleled affluence may be prompting some parents to give
youngsters money, reducing their need to work summer jobs. For
other teen-agers, the boom still means working, but in jobs that
put them on career tracks more quickly. Sean Stevens, a Georgetown
University junior who speaks fluent Korean and Russian, says his
time is worth more than the $10 an hour many summer jobs pay. He
will spend the summer at a South Korean university. (Paul
Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) OLOVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina -- June 17, 2000 --
NATIONAL-GUARD-BOSNIA-3 -- Throughout the Cold War, the National
Guard was held in reserve. Now, as the pace of U.S. military
operations has increased, from the Balkans to the Persian Gulf, the
Army plans to turn more and more to its 564,000 reservists and
guardsmen to relieve the strain on its nearly 480,000 regular
troops. Capt. Geoffrey C. Ryan ofthe 49th Armored Division of the
Texas National Guard, center, supervises the clearing of land mines
in Olovo, Bosnia. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) EAGLE BASE, Bosnia-Herzegovina -- June 17, 2000 --
NATIONAL-GUARD-BOSNIA-2 -- As the Army relies more heavily on
National Guard and Reserve units, Guard and Reserve commanders
argue that the U.S. citizen-soldiers bring something else that
their active-duty counterparts cannot: experience and skills honed
in the civilian world. Capt. David B. Webb of the 49th Armored
Division of the Texas National Guard, when not on active duty,
works in Fort Worth, Texas, for Lockheed Martin, maker of F-16s.
Webb helped identify was the F-16 belonging to Capt. Scott O'Grady,
the American pilot shot down on June 2, 1995, during NATOs air
raids in Bosnia. Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SULTANAVICI, Bosnia-Herzegovina -- June 17, 2000 --
NATIONAL-GUARD-BOSNIA-1 -- When it comes to peacekeeping operations
like the one in Bosnia, which does not involve direct combat, there
are many who argue that the U.S. National Guard and Reserve are in
fact better prepared for the subtle tasks of rebuilding a nation
devastated by war. Maj. Gen. Robert L. Halverson, commander of the
49th Armored Division of the Texas National Guard, pulls off his
flack jacket after arriving in the Bosnian Muslim village of
Sultanavici. The village was devastated by Serbs during the Bosnian
war and is the site of several mass graves. (Fred R. Conrad/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- June 17, 2000 --
FBN-GIANTS-ROUNDTABLE -- Instead of draft picks and free-agent
signings, much of the news of professional football this off-season
has involved prosecutors, indictments and trials. Five players from
the New York Giants, discussing some trying times for the NFL at a
roundtable discussion with sports reporters and editors. From left,
Howard Cross, Greg Comella, Amani Tooner and Tiki Barber. (Don
Hogan Charles/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
