<P>
   For questions, please call 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   THE WEEKEND DUTY EDITORS ARE:
</P>
<P>
   IN ATLANTA: Diane Fall at 404 526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   IN WASHINGTON: Art Dalglish at 301 460-6176.
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON HEARTLAND POLITICAL PROJECT
</P>
<P>
   HEARTLAND-MAIN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ When national Republicans gather
Monday in Dayton to talk about improving Social Security and the
nation's schools, they'll be trying to get the attention of voters
like Dayton elementary school principal Gwen Jarvis. Jarvis is
among thousands of undecided voters across Ohio, Pennsylvania,
Michigan and Illinois whose support both Republican Gov. George W.
Bush and Democrat Al Gore need to win the presidency. Those four
states from the industrial heartland are the biggest prizes among a
handful of states that both parties consider competitive
battlegrounds in their efforts to gather the 270 electoral votes
necessary to get to the White House. Together the four states
account for 84 electoral votes. The states are known for farms that
grow corn and soybeans and for factories that turn out steel and
automobiles, but they also regularly determine the winners in close
presidential elections. ``The South and Mountain West have
basically been conceded to Bush, and California and New York have
basically been conceded to Gore, so the heartland states like Ohio
are it for these two guys,'' said Allan Lichtman, history
department chairman at American University in Washington, D.C.
(Hershey/Wagner, Dayton Daily News). 80. MOVED Friday in (a)
General News categories and (p) Politics.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   HEARTLAND-SWING _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The battle in the heartland is
really a battle for ``swing voters.'' These are people who haven't
enthusiastically backed one candidate or the other. To get an idea
of who these voters are, here are four mini-profiles of the kinds
of voters who will likely tip the balance in November: Demonica
Sikes, a 22 year-old community college student from Michigan, voted
for McCain; in November she says she'll probably vote for Gore but
will plug her nose. (Hershey, Dayton Daily News). 6-8. WITH PHOTO.
MOVED Friday in (a) General News categories and (p) Politics.
</P>
<P>
   HEARTLAND-UNDECIDED _ CLEVELAND _ Jim Hamulock, a mailman in a
Hispanic neighborhood in Cleveland, says if the economy is so good,
people should follow him on his route. He is undecided about who
he'll vote for. (Wagner, Dayton Daily News). 6-8. MOVED Friday in
(a) General News categories and (p) Politics.
</P>
<P>
   HEARTLAND-FARMER _ WILL TWP. Ill. _ Will Twp. (Ill.) farmer
Everett Schurman is a 70-year-old Republican who will lose his
farmland in favor of the proposed new airport in Peotone, southwest
of Chicago. Has always voted Republican, but this year he's not so
sure. A Republican administration will likely approve the airport,
he thinks, robbing Schurman of his land. (Bebbington, Dayton Daily
News). 6-8.
</P>
<P>
   HEARTLAND-STEELWORKER _ Profile of a steelworker from
Pennsylvania. (Montgomery, Dayton Daily News). 6-8. MOVED Friday in
(a) General News categories and (p) Politics.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SIDE_ DAYTON, Ohio _ He may not be on the ballot this
year, but President Clinton draws stronger reactions from many
voters across the heartland states than do either Democrat Al Gore
or Republican George W. Bush. (Hershey, Dayton Daily News). MOVED
Friday in (a) General News categories and (p) Politics.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA-BASHAR _ QARDAHA, Syria _ The mindset in this remote
mountain village _ birthplace of late Syrian President Hafez Assad
_ is indicative of why it will be difficult for heir-apparent Bahar
Assad to compromise in the Middle East peace process. At the mosque
where the elder Assad's funeral was held last week, the imam _ or
priest _ has a short answer for what people here would think of any
leader who settles for anything less than the entire Golan Heights:
``He would be a traitor.'' Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location, Atlanta; Category, International; Subcategory,
Other.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Friday in the (i) International category on the NYT
wire.
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-INVESTING _ BEIJING _ A little-known business association
here in Beijing has begun taking international groups to North
Korea to facilitate investment. In the wake of last week's Korean
Summit, we look at who is investing in the world's most secretive
country? Developing. (Chao, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location, Atlanta; Category, International; Subcategory,
Other.
</P>
<P>
   EDS: MOVED Friday on the NYT Wire in (i) International and (f)
Finance categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   HAITIAN-DEPORTATION _ ``Oh, Rego! Rego! Anything new? Are you
OK? Will they let you stay? Oh, I hope so!''
</P>
<P>
   Renee Scharf skitters across the polished clubhouse floor at
Gleneagles Country Club and, like so many residents here, stops to
get the latest from Rigaud Moise. Moise is a club ``houseman,'' a
better such employee is not to be found anywhere. For in this land
of card parties and club tournaments and Italian Night dinners,
Rigaud Moise is a worker bee, a 5-foot-4 whirlwind who walks with
his elbows pumping, to get there more quickly. And getting there,
he has discovered, is the easy part. In America, for Moise and
others like him, it's staying that's so hard. (Evans, Palm Beach
Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LOS-ALAMOS-SCENE _ SANTA FE, N.M. _ First came the spy scandal.
Then the wildfire that almost swallowed them whole. Now, secret
nuclear files from Division ``X'' are missing. Over the past year,
event after event has dropped like bombs over America's Atomic
City, shaking up the isolated, orderly existence this northern New
Mexico town and its nuclear weapons laboratory have enjoyed for
more than half a century. Once the very center of the world's
scientific research, Los Alamos has become an embarrassment - and
once-proud town residents are taking it on the chin. (Guthrie,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 70.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This story can be found on the WAN in the Atlanta Location
with a category of Lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-VEEP _ Behind the scenes, as quietly and deliberately as
possible, Gov. George W. Bush is exercising the most power power
granted to any one person in a democracy. In picking a running
mate, Bush will have the one-man authority to grant near-world
leader status to the person of his choice. It's a delicate exercise
devoid of checks and
</P>
<P>
   balances other than the electorate that involves considerable
political risk. A look at how Bush is doing it. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman). 35. MOVED Friday in (p) Politics and (a)
General News categories.
</P>
<P>
   DAVIDIAN-STAKES _ WACO, Texas _ A look at the issues _ legal,
financial, symbolic, philosophical _ at stake in the Branch
Davidian civil trial. (England, Waco Tribune-Herald).
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Waco, category National
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   DAVIDIAN-PRIMER _ WACO, Texas _ A primer on how the trial will
be conducted _ the players, who'll be allowed in to watch trial,
Davidian plaintiffs, issues of security related to the day-to-day
conduct of trial. (Witherspoon, Waco Tribune-Herald).
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Waco, category National
</P>
<P>
   SEMINARY-PRESIDENT _ Decatur, Ga. _ Laura S. Mendenhall is
expected to be elected the eighth president of Columbia Theological
Seminary in Decatur, Ga., by the seminary's Board of Trustees on
Saturday. Dr. Mendenhall is pastor of Westminster Presbyterian
Church, Austin, Texas. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-SWEENEY _ The American labor movement, once drifting
toward irrelevancy, is surging with new energy under the leadership
of AFL-CIO President John Sweeney. No where is labor's new potency
and political clout more on display than in Los Angeles, where
union membership swelled by 91,000 people last year, the most of
anywhere in the country. New immigrants account for much of labor's
increase and their numbers have helped the Democrats reclaim all
three branches of California's government. This year, the AFL-CIO
is poised to reverse a long-standing policy opposing amnesty for
immigrants in a move that reflects how important immigrant workers
have become to labor's economic and political future. (Foskett,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 60. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTOPHER_ WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore is turning to a
