A7167 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-MARSHALL-NYT &LR;      06-17 0282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MARSHALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE MARSHALL, 96, CIVIL RIGHTS ADVOCATE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ George Marshall, a vigorous proponent of civil rights
and a conservationist with a special passion for the Adirondack
Mountains, died in Nyack, N.Y., on May 21. He was 96.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall's involvement in civil rights was inspired by his
father, Louis Marshall, a co-founder of the American Jewish
Committee, and by his marriage to Elisabeth Dublin, a fellow
advocate, in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   As a pioneer in the civil rights movement of the '40s and 50s,
Marshall worked closely with people like Paul Robeson, and served
as chairman of the National Federation for Constitutional Liberties
and its successor, the Civil Rights Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1946, Marshall was called before the House Un-American
Activities Committee and cited for contempt when he refused to
produce records of the NFCL. He was convicted and served three
months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall's other passion was preservation of the wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   To publicize the need for protecting wilderness areas, Marshall,
his brother, Robert, and their mentor, Herb Clark, became the first
to climb the 46 highest mountain peaks in New York state. After
Robert Marshall died at age 38 in 1937, Marshall became a trustee
of the Robert Marshall Wilderness Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall attended the Ethical Culture School in New York City
and graduated from Columbia College. He earned a doctorate in
economics from the Brookings Institution in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall's wife died in 1993. He is survived by his son, Roger
Marshall of Springfield, Vt.; his daughter, Nancy Marshall Schultz
of Nyack; six grandchildren; and 10 great-grandchildren. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
