<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000617.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7168 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HAITIAN-DEPORTATION06     06-17 1961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITIAN-DEPORTATION0618-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Residents rally support for Haitian facing deportation
 &HT;    By Christine Evans
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELRAY BEACH, Fla. _ ``Oh, Rego! Rego! Anything new? Are you OK?
Will they let you stay? Oh, I hope so!''
</P>
<P>
   Renee Scharf, a small woman with stylishly large sunglasses,
skitters across the polished clubhouse floor at Gleneagles Country
Club and, like so many residents here, stops to get the latest from
Rigaud Moise. He is standing center stage in the big, cream lobby,
shaking hands like a rock star with his many fans.
</P>
<P>
   Moise is a club ``houseman,'' which means he does a little of
everything and does it all very well, and, as any club member will
tell you, a better such employee is not to be found anywhere. For
in this land of card parties and club tournaments and Italian Night
dinners, Rigaud Moise is a worker bee, a 5-foot-4 whirlwind who
walks with his elbows pumping, to get there more quickly. And
getting there, he has discovered, is the easy part. In America, for
Moise and others like him, it's staying that's so hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, thank you so much,'' he says to his admirers,
taking time to shake each hand. ``You are so very kind to ask after
me.''
</P>
<P>
   And ask they do, and do, and do. At Gleneagles, a sweeping,
green retirement haven tucked like an emerald in the western
suburbs here _ a sweet dewdrop of a place populated by retired
professionals who now devote their days to teeing off under the
palms _ the big news is not about the school shooting or the
presidential race or even the estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   No. The big news is all about ``Rego,'' as nearly everyone here
calls him. After 10 years in this country, the beloved houseman
faces deportation back to Haiti _ back to the country he sees in
his nightmares, the place he fled, he says, his voice gone soft, to
save his life. It seems an impossible prospect. With his wife,
Cinette Dorlus, he is raising a family here, in the United States.
His youngest child, Rickerson, 6, was born here and is a U.S.
citizen. Moise owns a home in Pompano Beach. He pays his taxes. He
loves his job, his neighborhood, his church. He has a little slice
of the big American life.
</P>
<P>
   But what he does not have is a permanent place in America. The
right to stay. It will be a hard fight, but he has company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody _ everybody _ in this place has been touched by
Rego,'' says Steve Matlaga, the club's affable general manager and
the man who began a vigorous public relations campaign to help him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just _ well, it's just the nature of Rego. He's so
genuine, he's so giving, he's so hard-working. He has this
wonderful family. He has a son who is a U.S. citizen. He came from
a country where he was persecuted, and he's honest about the fact
that, if he went back, he thinks they'd kill him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rego and his story, they're 100 percent the real thing. That's
why we felt we had to get the word out.''
</P>
<P>
   GET THE WORD OUT THEY DID
</P>
<P>
   It was spring, and the Elian Gonzalez case had secured its place
on the front page of every newspaper when the first whisper of the
houseman's predicament broke on the lush green campus at
Gleneagles. It trickled out over bridge hands and Cobb salad
lunches, then rushed like a river out to the two 18-hole golf
courses, where normally masterful players shook their heads and
missed their putts.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if you're wondering what kind of place Gleneagles is _ it
is neatly positioned in the far reaches of the county, far removed
from rubberneckers _ you might want to ask Mort Mazor, the club's
self-appointed communications czar: ``People here like to look
beyond their own four walls. We're comfortable, but we don't put on
the ritz. If somebody's in need, we like to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially when it's Rego.''
</P>
<P>
   The call to arms came via the now famous ``Rego Video,'' a
special in-house production that played over the club's popular
channel for ``social news'' twice an hour for four days straight.
Steve Matlaga, the general manager, wrote the script and appeared
against a high-tech blue background in the role of newscaster. A
club staffer who used to cover the civil rights struggle for TV
news put the thing together in the editing booth, and the star of
the show smiled cheerfully as he zipped around the club grounds in
a white pick-up and prepared the dining room for a banquet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, everyone,'' the slightly nervous Matlaga said from his
anchorman's chair. ``I'd like to take a few moments of your time
today to ask you for your support and help . . . ``
</P>
<P>
   The Rigaud Moise story is not unlike the stories of thousands of
others who fled Haiti with fake passports and hearts full of fear.
People who felt the heat of military thugs, who worried for the
safety of their spouses and children, who could not guess _ and did
not want to know _ when the next spray of bullets would let loose
on the streets outside their homes. Some of those people, perhaps
3,000 according to immigration experts, had children after they
settled in the U.S., and those children, perhaps 5,000 of them, are
bonafide American citizens. And now _ what if those parents are
deported?
</P>
<P>
   Do they take their U.S. citizen children back with them? Back to
Haiti? The poorest nation in the hemisphere? A violent land those
children have never seen? Or, do they leave them here, to fend for
themselves, virtual orphans in a land of plenty?
</P>
<P>
   Impossible questions, these.
</P>
<P>
   And so, the general manager continued his report:
</P>
<P>
   ``As you've seen in the news lately,'' he told the good citizens
of Gleneagles, who were eating breakfast or paying bills or riding
the exercise bike, ``an immigration battle over a Cuban boy, Elian
Gonzalez, has been daily news headlines. What you haven't seen is
that there are other situations regarding Haitian immigrants . . .
This particular situation now affects us here at home, where one of
our great employees, Rego Moise, faces a very tough decision, where
his American citizen child would either be taken back to Haiti with
him or stay here in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, for the folks at Gleneagles, the intricacies of
immigration law were no longer abstractions to be followed only on
slow Sunday mornings when they had time for the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, they were real.
</P>
<P>
   It was no production error that the video included the phone
number for Janet Reno, just in case any of the club's 2,000
residents felt moved to pick up the phone and ask the U.S. attorney
general to do something _ which, as you might have guessed, they
did. It also included a clip from the NBC Nightly News, in which
Tom Brokaw, who learned of the case through the media grapevine,
featured the Moise family's plight in a bit of enterprise reporting
during the heat of the Elian crisis. The lead-in said, ``For other
immigrants, there's great frustration _ and great outrage.''
</P>
<P>
   And that might have been the end of it, except this is
Gleneagles, so it wasn't. When Congressman Robert Wexler, D-Boca
Raton, opened his mail this spring, he found 500 letters expressing
support for one Rigaud Moise.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what?
</P>
<P>
   They all carried the same postmark.
</P>
<P>
   LIVING THE AMERICAN DREAM
</P>
<P>
   It is a Monday afternoon, and everybody's favorite houseman has
asked for the day off to meet at his home with a reporter. His boss
said yes right away.
</P>
<P>
   His is an American Dream house, pink on the outside and lace
curtains inside, not too big or fancy but comfortable, with a
computer in the dining room. There's a porch and a nice back yard,
and if you drop by on a summer afternoon, you might hear Jean
Moise, handsome at 13, trying out a few tunes on the trumpet. His
sister, Phara, 11, plays the flute, and she likes it well enough,
but music is just a pastime: She is definitely going to be a
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   And then, there's Rickerson, the boy. You can ask him questions,
and he might say something or he might not, because he's shy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does it mean to be an American citizen, Rickerson?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Um.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It means you live here. Not there.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the dining room table, his parents nod their heads. That is
what it means, precisely.
</P>
<P>
   Rigaud Moise and Cinette Dorlus were married May 11, 1987, in a
town near Port-au-Prince. He had a job in the military.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years later, according to the story he has told
since he stepped onto American soil, his captain ordered him to
shoot into a street full of anti-government demonstrators, and he
refused. ``I said, 'No, I will not. I will not take people's
lives.''' Eventually, he was jailed, and military thugs shot at the
roof of his home while his wife and baby daughter shivered inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so scared,'' Cinette Dorlus says, ``that my breast milk
changed; the baby got sick.'' She felt sick herself with nerves
when she obtained a fake passport and with her tiny daughter got on
a plane to Miami. The doctored paper was good enough to get out of
Port-au-Prince, but in Miami, ``They held it to my face and said,
'This is not you.''' She spent a night in detention and then, like
so many refugees, was released to live with relatives and begin the
lengthy asylum process.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, her husband came to America, too. He slipped away
from his captors, collected his 3-year-old son from his mother, and
traveled by plane _ one of 10,000 Haitian refugees to arrive with
false documents in the '80s and early '90s. Moise told immigration
officials his story, and, like his wife, was released. Right away
he landed a job _ at Gleneagles _ and applied for asylum.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, an immigration judge said no: Moise had not been
physically mistreated, and he could not prove he would be
persecuted if he returned to Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   Now his lawyer, Michael D. Ray, is waiting for more bad news.
</P>
<P>
   The family has applied for residency under the Haitian Refugee
Immigration Fairness Act, but Ray says they certainly won't get it.
The 1998 law does not include special provisions for people who
came with false documents and do not have a close relative living
legally in the United States _ children like Rickerson do not
count.
</P>
<P>
   After the Fairness Act, the family has one more appeal, and it
will probably drag on, as appeals do.
</P>
<P>
   And then, says Cinette Dorlus, crying, ``It's goodbye to
America.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a sliver of hope, a sparkling fairy tale in Rigaud
Moise's mind. He considers it now, sitting with his family at his
dining room table in Pompano Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is thinking of passing a bill that would give refugees
like the Moises the right to stay in America on humanitarian
grounds. It is a complicated proposition, and nobody is saying it
will pass anytime soon, but it might pass sometime, especially if
anybody up on the Hill reads all those letters the folks at
Gleneagles are sending.
</P>
<P>
   ``See this,'' the houseman says, pulling out a brochure and
pointing to the men and women who populate the United States
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very fine people of Gleneagles sent me to Washington to
lobby with Rickerson. I saw this lady, Ileana Ros-Lehtinen. And Mr.
Robert Wexler. And this one, Mr. Alcee Hastings.''
</P>
<P>
   There are more names. He reads them off. He remembers how
Rickerson wore his clip-on tie.
</P>
<P>
   For just a moment, he smiles.
</P>
<P>
   No, perhaps the bill won't pass. No, he does not have his
citizenship, or even permanent residency. No, he might not be able
to stay in America. Yes, he might have to decide what to do with
his youngest son if everybody else in his family is deported.
</P>
<P>
   But still, there's this:
</P>
<P>
   Rigaud Moise has been to Washington, and for a very brief
moment, he stood like any good American on the steps of the
Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
