<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7176 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-POCONO-ADVANCE061     06-17 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-POCONO-ADVANCE0618-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Earnhardts side by side for Father's Day
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG POND, Pa. _ Dale Earnhardt Jr. doesn't plan on giving his
dad any presents today for Father Day's _ at least on the race
track.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jr. and his famous father will start side-by-side together
on eighth row of today's Pocono 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really hadn't thought too much about Father's Day,''
admitted Dale Jr. ``Dad and I are starting on the same row, and
he's probably going to want me to cut him some slack. But he knows
that won't happen. There's not much you can do to help anyone get
around this track.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Dale Sr. has needed anyone's help recently. ``The
Intimidator''has had four consecutive finishes in the top 10,
including being the runner-up in the rain-shortened Michigan race
last Sunday. He is confident he can extend it to five races in row
today.
</P>
<P>
   Pocono is an important race for the Chevy No. 3 driver. Winston
Cup points leader Bobby Labonte swept the two events at the
tri-oval last year. Dale Sr. is second in the point standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a top-10 car right now, but we're not a top-five car
yet,'' Dale Sr. said. ``We're going to tune it and get it where
it's a top-five car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby Labonte is there every week. We were faster than him in
practice, but that doesn't mean a lot. Tony Stewart is strong
again. He's running good, so we've got our work cut out for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been an Earnhardt family reunion at Pocono this weekend.
Dale Sr. was on the headsets Saturday, giving tips to his oldest
son Kerry, who won his first ARCA race. Today, he will start next
to his son Dale for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jr. does have a Father Day's wish: ``It'd be great if Dad
and I ended up racing for the win. Hopefully, that will happen
sooner or later, but it would be real neat if it happened on
Father's Day.''
</P>
<P>
   After today's race, Dale Sr. will devote his attention to his
youngest daughter, 11-year-old Taylor Nicole. Wife Teresa and the
two are leaving for a three-day camping trip to New Mexico on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get away for a few days before we go to Sears
Point,'' Dale Sr. said. ``I haven't taken her out on a trip like
this before. If the fishing is any good, we might do it. We're
going to camp, roast marshmallows, tell ghost stories, whatever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll probably tell Indian stories. A lot of history of the
Apache Indians is around the place. Racing keeps me busy, so this
will be a good chance to spend some time with Taylor.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
