<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTRACT NOT CONCERN FOR BAKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dusty Baker has more wins than any San Francisco
Giants manager, but just how many he'll tack on after this season
is in question.
</P>
<P>
   Baker's contract expires after the season, and negotiations
aren't expected to begin again until the season ends. Baker, adored
by his players and widely regarded as one of the top managers in
the game, received a two-year contract offer before the season
worth about $1.2 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what transpires,'' Baker said. ``Right now, the ball
is in my court. I want to concentrate on getting the team going,
seeing more consistency from them. That's what my focus is now. The
contract stuff will take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker passed Roger Craig with his 587th victory in Monday's 10-2
win against Cincinnati. He's 590-541 since taking over in 1993.
Craig was 586-566 from 1985 to 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Getting Baker a new contract isn't the motivation of the
players, but they know the situation. And they understand Baker's
importance to the Giants' success. They entered Saturday 32-31, 5
games behind Arizona and in fourth place in the National League
West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some managers have $90-million payrolls to work with, Dusty is
doing it with $60 million or less,'' Giants second baseman Jeff
Kent said. ``People want to play for him. I don't know what the
Giants are going to do. Dusty is a guy players want to play for.
He's a quality manager, and he's earned the respect of his players.
One of the reasons I signed on here was the attributes he brings to
the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim delivers: Arizona's submarining right-hander Byung-Hyun Kim
has saved the past three Diamondbacks wins and is manager Buck
Showalter's closer, taking the job from Matt Mantei.
</P>
<P>
   Kim has everything you want in a closer, which is the ability to
throw strikes and strike out batters. He's 2-3 with a 1.67 ERA, but
the most impressive thing the 21-year-old has done is strike out 55
in 32 innings. He's walked 12, and the Diamondbacks public
relations office is pushing for an All-Star bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see why,'' the Angels' Garret Anderson said of Kim's
strikeout ratio. ``Here's somebody throwing something you don't see
every day. If he keeps the ball down and throws strikes the way he
is, he is going to continue to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   But the catch is Kim wants to be a starter like fellow Korean
Chan Ho Park of the Los Angeles Dodgers. He's been saying that
since signing a four-year, $2.25-million deal before the 1999
season.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble in Atlanta (again): As if the Braves haven't had enough
problems with their bullpen, right-hander Rudy Seanez is out for
the season after an MRI revealed a completely torn medial
collateral ligament in his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Seanez was 2-4 with a 4.29 ERA in 23 games. He'll become the
15th pitcher in the organization to undergo the so-called Tommy
John surgery in the past two years. With John Rocker unable to find
the plate (or his sense), manager Bobby Cox said he'll turn to
Kerry Ligtenberg to close games.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington, Rockies meet: Colorado Rockies general manager Dan
O'Dowd visited with first-round pick Matt Harrington of Palmdale
and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing is to sit with the family and talk to them
about the organization, our people, our goals, where their son fits
in, the development system, how he's going to be treated,'' O'Dowd
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things that a mother and father are worried about. After that,
we'll get the kid in here so he can see the facilities, meet the
quality of ownership and all the people he's going to be working
for, and after that you begin to talk about money. There's more
issues at this stage in their life than money.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington is expected to ask for between $3 million and $4
million.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome back: There was an Alex Gonzalez sighting in
Philadelphia. The Florida Marlins shortstop, benched this month
because of anemic hitting, had three extra-base hits and five RBI
in one game. Gonzalez was hitting .160, worst in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a shortstop, ladies and gentlemen,'' Marlins manager
John Boles said. ``Welcome back, Alex.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashby on market: Philadelphia right-hander Andy Ashby is on the
trading block, and scouts from Cincinnati, Arizona, St. Louis and
the Yankees went to watch him pitch last week. Ashby is 2-7 with a
6.16 ERA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
