REDS NOT MAKING LIFE EASY FOR McKEON 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Cincinnati Reds general manager Jim Bowden brought
home the city's favorite son.
</P>
<P>
   It's caused nothing but inflated expectations and the type of
losing that brings job security into question.
</P>
<P>
   Jack McKeon, heralded last season for managing a bullpen to
near-perfection and getting the fiscally aware Reds into a one-game
playoff with the Mets, all of a sudden can't manage. Or, that's
what the inside word is, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. has boosted attendance in Cincinnati, but that
doesn't mean much these days.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds entered Saturday's game at San Diego with one win in
seven games on their current road trip, losers of nine of their
past 10 and 13 of their past 18 to fall 5 games behind St. Louis in
the National League Central.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden met with the coaching staff and McKeon in San Diego on
Thursday. And while he's saying McKeon, last season's manager of
the year, is safe, there's an undercurrent in the clubhouse that
wouldn't mind a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the manager,'' Bowden said. ``He can't pitch for them,
hit for them or field for them. It's the same manager and coaching
staff that won 96 games last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Team captain Barry Larkin, in the middle of his own contract
negotiations that aren't going too well, thought about a team
meeting to drag the Reds out of the doldrums that has dropped them
to 32-33.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a message from someone in the front office that it was
time for a meeting,'' Larkin said. ``I talked to some players; the
consensus is that we're really busting our (butt). There's nobody
sloughing off.''
</P>
<P>
   McKeon and Larkin talked about a possible team meeting, and
McKeon agreed with his shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that going to get any runs?'' McKeon said. ``What we're
looking for is something between the lines. Talk is not going to
get it. We're playing for professional pride. I think some of the
guys have to look in the mirror and figure it out for themselves.
Yeah, I have an occasional meeting. But I don't like to beat them
(players) when they're down.''
</P>
<P>
   While Larkin is the captain and is highly respected in the
clubhouse, talk of a meeting sounded fine to left-hander Denny
Neagle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are little things you can do as individuals and as a
team to spark ourselves,'' Neagle said. ``Last year we did that. We
always knew the right time to fire guys up, when to call a
players-only meeting. Whether it's time or not, some of us veterans
need to sit down and talk about that.''
</P>
<P>
   At the crux of the Reds' losing is a lack of run production. The
Reds are in the bottom half of the National League with 218 runs
scored. But Cincinnati isn't pitching well, either. Its 4.85 ERA is
10th in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at Friday's loss to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Steve Parris allowed five runs in the first inning
and lasted just three innings in falling to 2-10. That puts an
enormous burden on the bullpen, which was rested after Thursday's
off day but then had to throw five innings against the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's amazing that we're in second place, only 5 games
out of first, the way we've played,'' Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the impact of Griffey Jr. isn't what anyone expected.
He tried to doctor his swing early in the season and that didn't
work. Now, the thinking is he may be trying to do too much,
especially at home. He's hitting .229.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a unit, we're not playing together yet,'' Bowden said.
``Sometimes when you add new faces, it takes time for a team to
jell. But it's only June. We have time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
