<SLUG> BC-SYRIA-BASHAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULT-LIKE STATUS TRANSFERRED TO ASSAD'S SON AT PARTY SESSION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS _ As Bashar Assad strode into the modern marble and
glass conference center Saturday in his dark suit, cutting through
the burst of camera flashes with a confident gait, he looked like a
campaigner in any Western democracy.
</P>
<P>
   But that was where comparisons to democracy ended at the opening
of the ruling Baath Party's first convention in 15 years, where the
34-year-old Bashar is expected to be anointed its new leader.
</P>
<P>
   For the Baath Party, led for 30 years by Bashar's father, Hafez
Assad, there is no opposition, no challenge to the appointment
during the five-day gathering. Such a move is part of the carefully
scripted succession plan by the elder Assad, the Syrian president,
who died of a heart attack on June 10.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the cold, imposing Socialist-style architecture of the
conference hall, the 1,000 party delegates bristled when Western
reporters pressed them about Bashar's ascendancy and Syria's
profound economic and political challenges.
</P>
<P>
   When questioned directly, many of the Baath delegates simply
pursed their lips, quickly shook their heads, and walked away.
</P>
<P>
   The heavily guarded gathering began somberly, with a minute of
silence. Then delegates, without music or applause, began chanting
the party anthem.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, party leaders heaped praise upon the politically
inexperienced Bashar, 34, an ophthalmologist who had never held a
formal party post. ``We salute the hope of the future . . . Bashar
Assad,'' declared Suleiman Qaddah, the party's assistant secretary
general, to widespread applause. ``We are with you, comrade, and
behind you we will continue the march to express our commitment and
loyalty to the path of'' Assad.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the nation seems to be dutifully transferring the
cult-like status it gave to Hafez Assad to his son. On street
corners, in shop windows, and in the back windows of Damascus's
battered old cars, there are posters and banners declaring Bashar
the nation's hope for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Coverage of his daily activities and endless photographs of him
fill the pages of the country's newspapers _ all tightly
state-controlled.
</P>
<P>
   The party hierarchy seems to view Bashar as a symbol of both
continuity and change. He is a candidate who will continue his
father's hard line on foreign policy but also set out on his own
course of economic reform and modernization.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the party announced its nomination of Bashar for
president. A formal nomination is expected to be announced during
the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Then the parliament, the People's Assembly, will endorse the
nomination. When parliament reconvenes on June 25, it will set a
date for a nationwide referendum, which is not expected to be held
until the end of the traditional 40-day period of mourning over the
death of the late president.
</P>
<P>
   Bashar is, of course, one of the estimated 2 million Baath Party
members. That is roughly one-quarter of the estimated 8 million
Syrians of voting age.
</P>
<P>
   He assumed the path to the presidency after his elder brother,
Basil, who was being groomed for the job, died in a car accident in
1994. Before that, Bashar was quietly pursuing his own career as an
eye doctor and studying at a university in London.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, in the huge, wood-paneled convention hall, oil-painted
portraits of both his brother and his father looked down upon
Bashar as he set out on an uncertain course in the shifting
political landscape of the Middle East.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 1856EDT &QL; 
