<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KREUTER-FETTERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KREUTER, FETTERS CLICK WITH DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When their teammates start joking around, Chad
Kreuter and Mike Fetters turn to each other and smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at each other and say this is nothing compared to what
we did in college,'' said Fetters, adding that most of their antics
``can't be put on paper.''
</P>
<P>
   What could be put on paper is how well the pair performed on the
baseball field as teammates at Pepperdine in the mid-1980s. The two
are together again after making the Los Angeles Dodgers as
non-roster invitees this year, and both are having seasons that
rank with the best of their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Fetters, a 35-year-old from Van Nuys, spent much of last year
recovering from elbow surgery and went on the disabled list again
this season with elbow problems, but he has been one of the
Dodgers' most effective relievers when healthy.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander entered this weekend's series against the St.
Louis Cardinals with one save in 16 appearances, the staff's lowest
ERA (1.76) and a 2-0 record, marking the first time since 1996 he
has won more than one game.
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter's performance is a bigger breakthrough. The 35-year-old
catcher entered the season with a .236 career batting average and
having hit better than .275 only once in 12 major-league seasons.
He is hitting over .300 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Getting regular playing time while Todd Hundley is on the
disabled list has helped, but Kreuter has hit consistently since
getting three hits in his Dodgers debut on the second day of the
season. He had a 10-game hitting streak that ended in early June
and has reached base in 23 of 25 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised at all,'' Fetters said of Kreuter. ``It's
something I've expected out of Chad Kreuter. In college, he was one
of our better players, and it's carried over to the pros. He's
always been hard-nosed, always giving 100 percent each time he
steps on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter attributes the improved numbers to patience at the plate
and trying to put backspin on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the first things (hitting coach Rick Down) said to me
in spring training is, `I want you to lead the league in fly
balls,''' Kreuter said. ``It sounds funny, but for me, if I'm
hitting fly balls, I'll be hitting a lot of line drives rather than
ground balls. I'm not gonna beat out a lot of ground balls in the
infield.''
</P>
<P>
   As well as Kreuter is doing, he has no delusions of remaining
the full-time catcher when Hundley soon returns from a strained
rib-cage injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I signed here as a No. 2 guy, and I'd be kidding myself if I
wasn't true to that,'' Kreuter said. ``I do what I can do. Once you
try to do too much, you fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a role player, there's two different levels of
making it difficult on yourself. If you're a guy who feels like
he's not getting a fair shake, that he's not in there enough, you
make it difficult on yourself. It's harder to play because you go
out there with so much pressure on yourself to perform while you're
in there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my situation this year is that I know what my role is. I
know I'm the No. 2 guy no matter what I do on an everyday basis. It
doesn't matter if I go 4 for 4 on a Sunday. On Monday, Todd's gonna
be back in there. Knowing that makes it easier to prepare.''
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter and Fetters were both used to being starters when they
led Pepperdine to postseason appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Fetters, who holds the Waves' record for innings pitched in a
season, began his professional career as a starting pitcher but
settled in the bullpen when the Angels, and then the Brewers, both
had established rotations.
</P>
<P>
   Only once in the majors has Kreuter played in more than 100
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Chad doesn't play for a month, he'll be prepared the day he
gets in a game,'' Fetters said. ``If he plays every day, he's
prepared every day. He's constantly working on his game. Chad's a
guy that's always prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like me, all he wants to do is win. That's what the game
is all about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
