<HEADLINE>
POLICE ARREST ANOTHER IN CENTRAL PARK SEX ASSAULT CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The police announced another arrest Saturday in a
series of sexual assaults in and near Central Park last Sunday.
Meanwhile, the police said, an arrest was thrown out after a victim
reviewed videotapes and said an earlier identification of one of
her attackers had been in error.
</P>
<P>
   The day's events left 15 young men charged in the case as the
number of victims climbed to 50, said Detective John Giammarino, a
police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Commissiong, 20, of Brooklyn, N.Y., was charged when he
surrendered in the early hours of Saturday morning after learning
that detectives had been looking for him at his home. The
investigators were acting on a tip to the Police Department's Crime
Stoppers telephone line.
</P>
<P>
   The police also voided the arrest of one of the men already
charged in the case, said Sgt. Elias Nikas, another police
spokesman. Nikas said the man, Anthony Bryant, 25, had surrendered
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant had been in the park near the scene of some of the
attacks and was on one of 10 amateur videotapes that the police
used to cull pictures of suspects, Nikas said. The tape shows him
talking on a cellular telephone, but one of the victims pointed him
out and said he had abused her, the sergeant said. But after
viewing the tape at a slower speed, she said that the attacker had
looked very much like Bryant but was in fact a different man, Nikas
said.
</P>
<P>
   The police were expected Saturday to release photographs of six
additional suspects, Giammarino said.
</P>
</TEXT>
