<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAPLES CENTER HASN'T BEEN KIND TO PACERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Indiana Pacers were feeling good after their
33-point thrashing of the Los Angeles Lakers in Game 5 on Friday
night. Not too good, but still very good.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pacers know they still trail the best-of-seven NBA
Finals 3-2 and now have to win two games in a place where they've
yet to win - Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers lost their only regular-season game at Staples, and
then the two opening games of the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Conseco Fieldhouse proved a warm environment for their shooting,
but Staples has been another story.
</P>
<P>
   And since no team in NBA history has ever come back from a 3-1
deficit in the Finals, the Pacers know there is still imposing work
ahead at Staples, blowout win or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always concerned about going on the road and playing,''
Pacers coach Larry Bird said. ``It's not the homecourt. We haven't
played well in Staples Center this year, but now we have a bit more
confidence than we've ever had going there. Hopefully, we can pull
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Pacers forward-center Sam Perkins figures the Pacers
have new life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we do,'' he said. ``There's no reason why we don't
think we can win down there. We've fared well on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't in the first two games there, but that seems like so
long ago. It seems like we have a handle on things, and we'll just
have to adjust.''
</P>
<P>
   Home is where the shot is: One of the big reasons for the
Pacers' success at Conseco Fieldhouse is how well they shoot there.
</P>
<P>
   They feel comfortable at home, and it's been reflected in their
shooting during the first five games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   In the three games at Conseco Fieldhouse, the Pacers shot .509
from the floor and .474 from beyond the 3-point line.
</P>
<P>
   In their two losses at Staples Center, they were .396 from the
field and .294 on their 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's all mental,'' Pacers guard Reggie Miller said.
``You have to go in there, concentrate and hit shots. They're
hitting shots, so you know there's really nothing wrong with the
rims.''
</P>
<P>
   Hold that parade: The Pacers were proud and cautious after their
win Friday (neither team worked out Saturday).
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it's just one win,'' Pacers forward Jalen Rose said.
``We're not in control. They're still the team in control, they're
still the team with three (victories).
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're still the team that has fight. We know California's
going to be ready to celebrate. We heard about the parade that they
have planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``That won't be tomorrow, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Said guard Mark Jackson: ``So many people got ready for a
celebration, which was disrespectful to us and the character we
have on this team. We wanted to give ourselves a chance to go back
and see what we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's honest talk: Rose, after going just 5 of 16 from the
field in the fourth-game overtime loss, went 12 of 18 in the fifth
game to lead the Pacers with 32 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand we have what it takes to beat L.A.,'' Rose said.
``But it means nothing talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And since I felt like I've been doing nothing but talking
about it, especially when they got up 3-1, I figured I was going to
shut up and go out and play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
