<HEADLINE>
INDIANS FANS CAN'T STOP STUFFING IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Thank you, Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   If ever there was a reason to change the method of All-Star
voting, the fans of Cleveland are making it clear.
</P>
<P>
   A check of the American League voting shows the Cleveland fans
are stuffing the ballots to the point where they have an Indian
leading the balloting at three of the eight positions.
</P>
<P>
   If the voting were to end today, Jim Thome would start at first
(ahead of Jason Giambi and Carlos Delgado?), Roberto Alomar would
be starting at second (ahead of Luis Alicea and Ray Durham?), and
Manny Ramirez would be starting in the outfield (ahead of Darin
Erstad and Carl Everett?).
</P>
<P>
   Even more ridiculous is Sandy Alomar (second in the voting at
catcher). Then there is Travis Fryman, who ranks second at third
base behind only Cal Ripken, and outfielders Kenny Lofton and David
Justice, who rank fourth and sixth, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the fans should be a part of the voting. So here's the
solution to make the voting fair and still keep the fans involved.
</P>
<P>
   First, eliminate online voting. Stop the cyber-geeks from
dropping 5,000 votes a day on a player who once gave him/her an
autograph in a shopping mall. While it's true Major League Baseball
gets good PR by including the fans online, it's not worth it.
</P>
<P>
   So, how to distribute the ballots? Handing stacks of ballots to
fans at games only makes each ballot virtually worthless. A fan
with a hundred or so ballots will stuff it with his/her favorite
team's players, then maybe make a joke of other ballots, like
picking the players from their fantasy-league team.
</P>
<P>
   In order to make a ballot valuable, hand one ballot to each
ticketed fan at each major-league game. This rewards fans who
actually go to games. It also makes the ballot special, because a
fan is less likely to make a joke of his/her ballot if he/she gets
only one.
</P>
<P>
   It also rewards season-ticket holders, or fans who go to
numerous games. They would get a ballot each time they cross the
turnstile at the ballpark gate because they deserve it. They've
seen more baseball than fans who get their daily dose of highlights
on SportsCenter.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa to Sox?: One team that figures to have the best shot at
trading for the Cubs' Sammy Sosa is the Red Sox. Sosa signed to
play for the Red Sox during the strike of 1994-95, but the contract
was rescinded once the strike was settled. But it's clear the Red
Sox are one team for which Sosa would gladly leave Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox infielder Manny Alexander, a former Cub and close friend
of Sosa's, has been talking to Sosa during the recent hoopla over
Sosa's status with the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hopes he gets traded, and he hopes he gets traded here,''
Alexander told the Boston writers. ``We've got a lot of Latin
players here, plus Boston is a lot like Chicago. He's thinking
about coming here already to be with us all the Latin players here,
especially Pedro (Martinez), (Jose) Offerman, Ramon (Martinez).
Sammy loves to play where he's got a lot of friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa is making $10 million this season and is signed for $11
million next season, but salary should not be a problem for Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Short hops: Omar Olivares won a combined 15 games last season
with the Angels and A's, and the A's seemed to get a steal when
they acquired him from the Angels (along with Randy Velarde) for a
package of minor-leaguers. But Olivares has reverted to his
journeyman form - he's 0-5 with an 8.47 ERA in his past six starts
and is in danger of losing his spot in the rotation. ... Mariners
GM Pat Gillick is in the market for a second baseman. Mark McLemore
is struggling and still has to serve a suspension for charging the
mound to fight the Devil Rays' Esteban Yan. ... Blue Jays
outfielder Raul Mondesi broke a tooth recently. He explained it
happened when he was brushing his teeth ``too hard.'' Sure. ...
Former Dodgers prospect Karim Garcia, toiling in the Tigers'
minor-league system, was traded to the Orioles for future
considerations. Garcia was assigned to Triple-A Rochester. Garcia
played in eight games with the Tigers this season, hitting .176 (3
for 17).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
