<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Bush criticizes Clinton about security
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush chastised the Clinton administration on Saturday
for its handling of nuclear secrets at the Los Alamos weapons
laboratory, saying that ``America's nuclear security should not be
a matter of lost and found.'' Bush, appearing with his brother,
Florida Gov. Jeb Bush, at the state convention of the Veterans of
Foreign Wars, also blamed the administration for a ``slow slide to
military weakness'' shown through poor military recruiting and low
troop morale. Bush pledged to rebuild military strength with
lighter and more lethal weapons, and to restore morale by giving
troops clear missions and reducing peacekeeping assignments. On
Friday, two computer hard drives containing nuclear secrets were
found at Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   JEB BUSH PREDICTS FLORIDA WIN
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush predicted Saturday his older brother, George W. Bush,
will win Florida and contended Al Gore's campaign was ``bluffing''
about its ability to compete in the state. ``This reminds me a
little of '88, where the Dukakis campaign came in with a field
organization and they were talking about how they were going to
compete and do all these things, and then by the end, we had a
going-away party for them with a vote,'' Jeb Bush said referring to
the 1988 election when his father, former president George Bush,
won the state over Democrat Michael S. Dukakis. Democrats outnumber
Republicans in the state, which has 25 electoral votes, fourth most
in the country. A Florida poll in May put George W. Bush at 47
percent and Gore at 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Also Saturday, Bush won the endorsement of the Florida chapter
of LULAC, the League of United Latin American Citizens, the
nation's oldest and largest Hispanic organization.
</P>
<P>
   POLL: BUSH BEATS GORE BY 10 POINTS
</P>
<P>
   A new national poll found that Bush is leading Gore by a
10-point margin, 50 percent to 40 percent. The poll released Friday
by The Los Angeles Times found that Bush's support among fellow
Republicans was stronger than Gore's support among Democrats. Nine
of 10 Republicans said they backed Bush, while seven of 10
Democrats said they supported Gore. Bush also had substantially
more support among Democrats than Gore had among Republicans. The
poll of 1,600 voters has a margin of error of plus or minus three
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH BASHES GORE'S TAX PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Bush accused Gore of doubling the size of a proposed tax cut as
a last ditch way to attract voters. This week, Gore doubled the
size of his proposed tax cut to $500 billion over 10 years _ still
not as big as Bush's $1.3 trillion tax-cut plan. A Gore aide even
suggested Friday that Gore could increase the tax cut by another
$20 billion to $30 billion if more surplus money becomes available.
``Surely America doesn't want a focus group-driven presidency,''
Bush said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
