u p BC-NY-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      06-17 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY WALKS IN A PREDECESSOR'S FOOTSTEPS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SARAH KERSHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HYDE PARK, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton, who has often
identified herself with Eleanor Roosevelt, spent 20 minutes
Saturday touring the two-story stone cottage to which Mrs.
Roosevelt retreated and where she lived out what she termed a
``complicated life.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sat in Roosevelt's chairs, stood on her famous sleeping
porch and gazed at her books, her shortwave radios and her dining
room table, where world leaders like Winston Churchill joined her
for meals.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady went to the Eleanor Roosevelt National Historic
Site to officially designate the cottage, called Val-Kill, as a
project of a national program raising money for homes and other
landmarks in need of repair and restoration.
</P>
<P>
   Then she headed north to stump for her U.S. Senate campaign at a
county fair in Altamont, west of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Allida Black, a professor at George Washington University and a
Roosevelt historian, introduced Clinton to several hundred donors
and others gathered under a tent outside the cottage as ``maybe the
only person on the planet who understands Eleanor Roosevelt more
than I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Clinton has often mentioned the life and work of
Roosevelt, who, at Val-Kill, was a prolific writer, churning out
newspaper columns, hundreds of articles, several books and, on
average, 150 personal letters a day.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Clinton, who visited the cottage in 1995, noted
that Roosevelt was her age, 52, when she made Val-Kill a permanent
home in 1945, after her husband, President Franklin D. Roosevelt,
died.
</P>
<P>
   During her remarks, Clinton drew heavily on the political
symbolism of Roosevelt's work for human rights and other causes,
and spoke of ``keeping her dream alive.''
</P>
<P>
   She also alluded to the ridicule that erupted after Bob
Woodward, in a 1996 book, ``The Choice,'' said she carried on
imaginary conversations with Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   She said that during one of her first public appearances as
first lady, she told a crowd during an event at Lincoln Center in
New York City, ``You know, the White House just encourages me to
have conversations with Mrs. Roosevelt.''
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd began laughing, she added, ``I meant it as a
metaphor. But it became yet again one of those things people talked
about, I guess sort of suggesting I really had gone off the deep
end. But you know, it's not a bad idea, to think about what Mrs.
Roosevelt would do or say.''
</P>
<P>
   In closing her remarks and thanking donors who had contributed
$150,000 to help restore the cottage, which has sustained water
damage and is missing pieces of furniture that were auctioned off
after Roosevelt died in 1962, she said, ``Next time I talk to her,
I will tell her everything you have done.''
</P>
<P>
   The guide who led Clinton through Val-Kill, Franceska Macsali
Urbin, the same guide who did so in 1995, said that on the first
tour Clinton was full of questions.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, she said, ``she wanted to drink in atmosphere and
feel what it would be like to be here when Mrs. Roosevelt was
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 2107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
