<HEADER>
A7200 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-BBNOTES-SOSA-BOS &LR;      06-17 2257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BBNOTES-SOSA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEEPLY DIVIDED ON SOSA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When one Red Sox veteran first heard that the team was exploring
the possibility of trading for Sammy Sosa, he shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home runs,'' he said, ``are overrated.''
</P>
<P>
   There is truth in what on the face of it seems such a dismissive
remark. It has been written in these pages before, and it bears
repeating now, as Dan Duquette contemplates making a deal that
could be as franchise-defining as the Pedro Martinez trade after
the 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   The last home run champion to play in a World Series was Hall of
Famer Mike Schmidt of the Phillies, and that was 20 years ago. You
have to go back to the 1985 Kansas City Royals and Steve ``Bye
Bye'' Balboni to find a World Series champ with a 35-homer hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sosa is a drawing card, a home run hitter, and he ain't
anything else,'' said an executive with another major league club.
``His defense has gone downhill, his arm has gone downhill, he's a
one-man band.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's Harry Caray with a bat. Harry wasn't the best announcer
of all time, but he was a great promoter. And Sosa isn't the best
player of all time, either.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if any team should know the value of having
one of the game's greatest sluggers, it should be the Sox, whose
last World Series title came the year before they sold the man who
was the Sammy Sosa of his day.
</P>
<P>
   ``In American League parks,'' the same executive conceded,
``he'd be good. And in Boston, he could be huge. And the next two
or three years, while Pedro is still on top of his game, will be
Duquette's best chance to win anything for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the Sox can land Sosa is another story. The same
team that built a dynasty around Babe Ruth may do whatever it takes
to ensure that Sosa will be in Yankee pinstripes to help them win
their third successive World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``If George is really in this,'' one scout said of George
Steinbrenner, ``then it's already all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees general manager Brian Cashman, like his Boston
counterpart, has been looking for a bat for weeks. Entering the
weekend, the Sox and Yankees, though at the top of the American
League East, ranked 12th and 13th, respectively, in runs. The
Yankees can offer the Cubs a package that includes big league
outfielders Ricky Ledee and Shane Spencer, shortstop Alfonso
Soriano, outfield prospect Jackson Melian, and a pitcher such as
Eddie Yarnall.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox feel they have more attractive prospects in pitchers
Tomo Ohka and Sunny Kim, first baseman Dernell Stenson, and catcher
Steve Lomasney, and that Trot Nixon is a better big leaguer than
Ledee.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen, of course, whether the Cubs agree. It
also remains to be seen whether Duquette will strip his system of
top prospects to land Sosa, though the GM hasn't been shy about
parting with young pitching in other deals.
</P>
<P>
   A compelling case can be made that the Sox need another starting
pitcher more than they need another bat. Or that Sammy just isn't
the right fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy whiffs a lot,'' another big league scout said. ``He's a
terrible defensive player. He'll be changing leagues. And you're
going to have to give him six or seven years in an extension, and
in a couple of years who knows how many home runs he's going to hit
for you? And he'll change the makeup of your club.''
</P>
<P>
   But when you've gone 82 years without winning a World Series,
two years down the road ceases to be the primary consideration.
Martinez is giving this team a rare window of opportunity that
could close within a moment's notice. The sight of him throwing in
the high 80s last Wednesday in New York while he nursed a sore
oblique muscle should be reminder enough of the man's mortality.
</P>
<P>
   Do you pass on Sosa because he might disrupt your team's
chemistry? Not from this vantage point, you don't. Carl Everett,
for all his splendor on the field, is not universally admired in
the Sox clubhouse, because he frequently is the last one in the
house, the last one on the field to stretch, and the first to utter
comments that teammates find either too provocative or nonsensical.
But as long as Everett produces and plays hard, teammates will be
willing to look the other way at the other stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's biggest sins, from what we gather, include complaints
about the clubhouse music, the presence of a brigade-sized
entourage, and the overuse of cell phones, which were banned from
the Cubs clubhouse. Jimy Williams has no such restrictions on cell
phones, there's a team rule against playing music in the clubhouse,
and Sammy let his entourage in Chicago know they can't invade the
clubhouse. So much for Sammy turning the clubhouse inside-out.
</P>
<P>
   And those whispers about Pedro and Sammy not getting along? It's
true they're not the best of friends. They operate in different
circles, even if Martinez could throw a baseball from the balcony
of his condo into Sosa's backyard in Santo Domingo. Sosa has
grabbed every endorsement opportunity; Martinez has by and large
stuck to playing baseball. But could they coexist? No question.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa strikes out a lot, yes. But checking the leaderboard, the
top whiffers in baseball were names such as Jim Thome, Jim Edmonds,
Jeff Bagwell, Ken Griffey, Mo Vaughn, and Dean Palmer. Any of those
guys you wouldn't want to have in your lineup?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the price for Sosa would be high, especially if it included
the gritty Nixon. One scout, who didn't require a Breathalyzer,
insisted he would rather have the Red Sox right fielder than the
import from Chicago. ``That guy will just get better and better,''
the scout said.
</P>
<P>
   But while Sosa may not run into as many walls as Nixon, his arm
is adequate to play right field, and his name always appears on the
lineup card. He played in every game in 1997 and 1999, and in '98
he missed just three. A slacker, he isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Are the Cubs seriously contemplating going through with this?
Absolutely. They see this as a rare chance to acquire three or four
top young prospects, then with the money they save from not signing
Sosa add an elite player or two in the free agent market. Suddenly,
you're talking about six players instead of one for a team that is
a long way away from winning anything with Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Can the Sox afford to pay Sosa? Their Opening Day payroll was
close to $78 million, which ranked seventh in the big leagues. But
there are a half-dozen veterans in the last year of contracts _ Tim
Wakefield, Tom Gordon, Mike Stanley, Rod Beck, Jeff Frye, and Jeff
Fassero _ whose combined salaries total almost $24 million. Most,
if not all, of those players won't be back next season. Duquette
clearly has room to maneuver, not only for Sosa but another
front-line pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Will the Cubs trade Sosa? Yes. Can the Sox get him? Yes.
Duquette had him five years ago, signing him to a contract during
the labor stoppage that was later thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   Will he mean a World Series ring? That one goes unanswered. But
the Sox would have a better chance to be there with him than
without him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wasdin as a Pac-man?
</P>
<P>
   The ``Way-Back'' crowd may not have John Wasdin to kick around
much longer. More than one club has acknowledged that the Sox have
been shopping Wasdin, and one National League scout said the Giants
are looking at him as an extra starter and long man. Forget the
jokes about Wasdin making a big splash for the Giants, though he'd
likely give up a few home runs in Pac Bell Park that would land in
the Bay. A change of scenery might be just what he needs, and
perhaps the Sox could use Wasdin as a way to get a third baseman in
return. Russ Davis, whom the Sox had interest in a year ago, isn't
playing much for the Giants but is still hitting over .300 as a
part-time player. He also has some power _ a total of 61 home runs
in the previous three years _ and he'd come pretty cheap. He's
signed for $1 million, of which the Sox would be obligated to pay
around $600,000. Davis would be a stopgap solution that takes some
of the pressure off rookie Wilton Veras, who may not be quite ready
to play every day . . . The Sox did inquire about Astros outfielder
Moises Alou, but forget the suggestion that he would be a much
cheaper alternative to Sosa. Alou has a complete no-trade clause in
his contract, and while he's due to be paid $6 million next season,
it's virtually certain he would demand that his contract be
renegotiated before agreeing to waive the no-trade. Would the
Astros move him? Absolutely. They tried to deal him as long ago as
the World Series last October, and they actually were close to a
deal with the Rockies but it fell apart because of the no-trade
language. The Astros would have been much happier to deal Alou than
Carl Everett, who is younger and a better all-around player. But
they haven't even asked Alou yet if he'd be willing to waive the
no-trade, and Alou also has told associates that he prefers to stay
in the National League . . . Two Amherst guys are working opposite
sides of the Sosa deal. There's Duquette, who recently gave his
alma mater a gift in honor of his father (money to build a new
baseball office). And one of Duquette's good friends, Tom Bourque,
is scouting for the Cubs in Pawtucket, checking out Sox and Mets
prospects . . . Is it possible that Vaughn's bitter parting with
the Red Sox could affect whether Sosa comes here? Cubs outfielder
Glenallen Hill, one of Sosa's closest friends, thinks it could. As
a 10-5 man (10 years of big league service, 5 with the same club),
Sosa has the right to veto any deal. Hill played for the Blue Jays,
Indians, and Mariners in the AL. ``I would lay it on the line,''
Hill said when asked if he would recommend Boston to Sosa. ``All
the pros, all the cons. The pros? It's the American League, a
hitter's league, and Boston is a real good team.'' The cons? ``The
weather. Boston's very cold. Sure, it gets cold here, but Boston is
a different kind of cold. Cold and wet. To play there all the time
might be tough. Boston is also a very conservative place. I think a
guy of his color would have to take a lot of things under
consideration about playing there. Boston has a reputation of being
very conservative. That's a fact. I think Sammy has to look at a
player parallel to his situation in Mo Vaughn, who was very much a
fan favorite in Boston and the center of attention wherever he
went, and look at how things turned out there. I think he has to
assess what Mo's feelings were, and how he reacted to the
attention, and what happened that made him leave. Yes, they're
different people, but the situations are similar. Sammy knows he
has a lot of options to consider. It's fair to him, it's fair to
anybody, that you don't want to go someplace where ultimately
you're going to be unhappy.'' . . . Damon Buford, who played with
Vaughn in Boston and now plays alongside Sosa in Chicago, politely
disagreed with Hill's suggestion. ``To me,'' said Buford, ``every
situation is different. Every team has a history of positives and
negatives. I could bring up the Steve Avery thing as a positive,
the way Jimy pitched him so he could get his contract option. You
just can't always weigh the negative. Sammy and Mo are in entirely
different situations. Mo came up with Boston and was there 10
years. There's no telling what happened there. Sammy would be
coming in as a new face.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just a minor tiff
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the spat between Pawtucket pitchers Tomo Ohka and
Sunny Kim couldn't have been worse, what with their names having
surfaced as part of a possible Sosa deal, and with scouts in
Pawtucket to watch them pitch. Ohka and Kim had to be separated in
the dugout in Durham, N.C., last Wednesday night, and the bad
feelings carried over to the next day in the team hotel, where they
again mixed it up. Ohka came away from that one sporting a bruise
on his cheek, and on Friday, after they'd met with farm director
Kent Qualls, it was announced that both players were suspended for
five days. But Dave Jauss, Boston's minor league field coordinator,
makes plenty of sense when he says not to make a big deal of the
altercation. ``I believe it's history, I really do,'' Jauss said.
``Things like that go on all the time in the big leagues, minor
leagues, and college baseball. All the time. And you know the two
guys don't feel good about it. As long as it's been taken care of,
it should be over, and I think the ball club handled it really
well. This is an aggressive sport, where players are paid to be
aggressive. Two people argue, and you hope it doesn't come to more,
but it did. That's something that can happen in all of our lives.
It happened to be two of our quality pitchers, two of our Asian
pitchers, but it just as easily could have been anybody else. These
are good kids.'' Ohka, who is Japanese, and Kim, who is Korean,
come from countries that historically have been ancient enemies,
and Qualls was sensitive to this not turning into a political
issue. But Jauss's straight talk, and acknowledgment that
intramural scraps are as old as the game itself, was a refreshing
counterpoint to the unnecessarily high-minded press release put out
by the Red Sox, which preached about how the organization has
``zero tolerance for conduct that includes hostility between
co-workers on or off the field. The organization makes every effort
to foster a workplace where each individual treats each other with
dignity and respect.'' Save it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
