<HEADER>
A7201 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-JONES-B     06-17 1649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-JONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES WAS AN OPEN BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just over a year ago, at the news of Gene Sarazen's death, Rees
Jones was explaining why it was particularly painful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost a piece of golf history that was special,'' he
said, ``and the game needs to hold onto its history.''
</P>
<P>
   So there was Jones on Thursday, accepting condolences on the
death of his father, Robert Trent Jones Sr., himself a huge piece
of golf history. Not that it was a shock _ Jones was 93 and had
suffered a stroke just after last year's US Open _ but it is ironic
that his death comes at a time when American golf is celebrating
its greatest championship. Especially because Jones, the architect
of hundreds of golf courses, was perhaps best known as ``The Open
Doctor'' _ that is, the man who refurbished and strengthened
classic layouts to meet the US Open challenge.
</P>
<P>
   In that capacity, his work included Congressional in Bethesda,
Md., Southern Hills in Tulsa, Oakmont in Pittsburgh, the Olympic
Club in San Francisco, Baltusrol in New Jersey, and Oak Hill in
Rochester, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   However, it was at Oakland Hills in Bloomfield, Mich., in 1951
that Jones solidified his reputation. Fourteen years earlier, Ed
Furgol had shot 281 to win the Open at Oakland Hills, but the
greatest player of the era, Ben Hogan, needed 287 to triumph in
1951. Why? Jones had come at the USGA's request and toughened up
the classic Donald Ross layout.
</P>
<P>
   Rees Jones was a young boy in 1951, though he'd be hard-pressed
to conjure up a more pleasant memory than the one he has of that
final round at Oakland Hills. Standing next to his mother, Ione,
Rees recalls Hogan coming over to pay his respects to a woman who
was quite popular to those in the golf business.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your husband had to play his own courses,'' Hogan said to
Ione Jones, ``he'd be in the bread line.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the type of comment that made Robert Trent Jones Sr.
smile, because he felt the best players in the world should face
the most challenging of challenges. ``Every hole should be a hard
par and an easy bogey,'' he once said. ``The shattering of par
without a proper challenge is a fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   Another legendary story stems from Jones's work at Baltusrol. He
took a par-3 of about 120 yards and lengthened it to 192, bringing
water into play and causing a furor. Much too hard, screamed club
members, a charge Jones shrugged off. To prove his point, Jones
accompanied professional Johnny Farrell and two members to the hole
and teed off at 165 yards, the members' tee. Hitting fourth, Jones
borrowed a 4-iron and made a hole-in-one. ``Gentlemen,'' he said,
``I think that the hole is eminently fair,'' and to this day it is
considered by many one of the best holes in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The father was a harsh critic of both sons (Robert Trent Jones
Jr. and Rees) who followed him into golf course architecture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a subjective business,'' said Rees, who recently
completed a spirited layout in Sutton, Mass., called Blackstone
National, and is at work on one of three courses at the Pinehills
development in Plymouth, Mass. ``And he was hard on me. But it gave
me great pride that he liked what we did to Congressional. That
pleased him.''
</P>
<P>
   A tireless worker, Jones had courses virtually everywhere _
``The sun never sets on a Robert Trent Jones golf course,'' he was
fond of saying _ and he refused to slow down. He showed up at
Pinehurst No. 2 for last year's US Open, celebrating his 93d
birthday with his sons and members of the media, many of whom he
knew personally.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his last visits with his father, Rees had the
following conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me who the greatest golf course architect was, and I
said, `You are, dad.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There was a slight pause before Rees returned the question,
asking about No. 2, and the great man said: ``That would be you,
Rees.''
</P>
<P>
   More silence, then Robert Trent Jones Sr. spoke again. ``No,
wait a minute. Donald Ross would be second. I think you're third.''
</P>
<P>
   Rees Jones broke into a wide smile. Another memory to cherish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Daly dose of nonsense
</P>
<P>
   With 52 threesomes going off, and after three days of buildup,
the start of any golf tournament _ particularly a US Open _ offers
many possibilities. Whom to follow? What to look for? So when a
colleague said he was going to follow John Daly, I shrugged.
Something always happens with him, I said, and sure enough, it did.
His behavior on the 18th hole _ he hit one drive out of bounds, two
more into the ocean, eventually took a 14, then withdrew after
shooting a first-round 83 _ was childish. He may be one of the
best-hearted people on tour, but Daly has worn out his welcome.
USGA officials must be cheering silently that his five-year
exemption has expired, because Daly has caused them grief two
straight years. He was Jekyll and Hyde (isn't he always?) at
Pinehurst, praising the USGA for a marvelous course setup after an
opening 68, then cowardly ripping it when he finished 81-83. The
stories of his generosity are too many to list (a personal
favorite: he entered a pro shop one day, saw a kid fondling a set
of clubs, and ripped off six $100 bills and bought them for him),
but for each one, there are probably 10 tales that show his total
disrespect for the game and lack of concern for his own well-being.
He has acknowledged his problems in the past, but in each case his
remedy could be called ``drive-through rehab,'' that is, he'll
check himself in a for few weeks, then return to the lonely,
high-pressure life of the PGA Tour. The game deserves better than
that. So, too, does Daly . . . Running a close second to Daly in
the ``tired, old news'' category is Mark James. Please, Mark,
enough. You've written a book, taken cheap shots at plenty of
people, made your money, and gained your moment in the sun _ now
please ease yourself into 74th place in a series of European Tour
events and shut up. Apparently, that's not possible. He continued
to hurl gasoline into the fires by claiming, ``(Tom) Lehman and his
friends can . . . bury their heads in the sand and pretend nothing
went wrong at Brookline. I want to sort this out. I want people to
be aware golf had a problem so we can sort it out for next year,
and in particular for the 2003 Ryder Cup.'' How convenient that in
his role as self-appointed diplomat he's making plenty of money in
the process . . . Yet another golf Web site to add to your list:
caddiechat.com. As the name suggests, it is a site whereby caddies
discuss what is going on out on Tour. During the US Open, a special
feature is a daily diary written by Mike Hicks, whose 12-year
association with Payne Stewart culminated with last summer's
historic triumph at Pinehurst.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's LPGA's turn
</P>
<P>
   The US Open will fade from view, leaving the golf spotlight _ at
least for this week _ to the women. The McDonald's LPGA
Championship gets under way Thursday at DuPont CC in Wilmington,
Del., and much of the attention will be on Karrie Webb (10
victories in 17 months), her rivalry with Annika Sorenstam, the
quest of Juli Inkster to defend this major crown, and the possible
emergence of Grace Park as a weekly threat. That won't leave much
room for players such as Meg Mallon, whose career has never
received the attention it deserves. When she prevailed in a
rainstorm at the Rochester (N.Y.) International, it was Mallon's
12th win since bursting onto the scene 14 years ago. In that time,
two things have remained constant for this Natick, Mass., native _
her great play and her smile. But she thinks things could have been
sweeter. ``I feel like I put myself in this position to win a lot
of tournaments, which is what you want to do,'' said Mallon, ``but
I don't feel like I've gotten over that hump to have multiple
victories.'' In 1991, Mallon won four times _ including a pair of
majors _ and while it's a wonderful entry on her resume, it left a
daunting challenge. ``It's almost like the expectations got so high
that no matter what I've done since then, it seems to pale in
comparison,'' she said . . . The Mass. Open tees off Monday at the
Country Club of Pittsfield, with amateur Kevin Quinn defending the
title. Rodney Butcher, the 1998 champion, withdrew, given his
commitment to the US Open. Butcher's swing coach is Tom Creavy, who
learned the game as a youngster playing the Hyannisport Club.
Creavy, who was at Pebble Beach with Butcher, teaches at the David
Leadbetter Academy in Florida . . . As some of the game's greatest
names practiced their putting just off the first tee at Pebble
Beach during Thursday's first round, it was announced that fog had
crept into play, making the par-3 fifth hole a particularly
time-consuming affair. It was so backed up that officials
instituted a half-hour delay on tee times to ease the congestion on
the course. Fifth-hole problems? Jack Nicklaus peered up as he
stood over a putt, and quipped, ``Poor design.'' Of course,
Nicklaus received rave reviews for his redesign of that hole a few
years ago . . . Not far from Pebble Beach is Pasadera, a new
private club that had its grand opening last Sunday. Designed by
Nicklaus, the layout, by all reports, is quite breathtaking, with
some dramatic elevation changes. One par-3 plays just over 200
yards _ all of it carry over a 200-foot gorge. What follows is a
par-4 that can play 596 yards from the tips. No, that's not a typo.
It's a par-4 of 596 yards. Good Lord, that's a three-shot hole
after a short taxi ride for me, but those who have played it say
the elevated tee to a fairway hundreds of feet below makes it play
much shorter. How short? Orel Hershiser reportedly hit driver-wedge
and reached easily. Which leads one to believe that if the USGA got
its hands on that hole, it would be a par-3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
