<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS LONG FOR A TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Which active franchise among the four major professional sports
_ major league baseball, the NFL, the NBA, and the NHL _ has gone
the longest since its inception without winning a championship?
</P>
<P>
   Don't rack your brain. It's your New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   While the Red Sox have gone an amazing 82 years without a
championship, they did win the World Series early in the 20th
century, as did the equally snake-bitten Chicago Cub and Chicago
White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have had a sad history since they started up in
1960, getting to an AFL championship game in 1963 and falling to
the San Diego Chargers, and twice losing in the Super Bowl (in 1986
to the Bears and 1997 to the Packers).
</P>
<P>
   No current professional franchise has started this pathetically.
And we're being generous in our criteria by counting AFL and NFL
championships prior to the first Super Bowl. In hockey, we are
counting AVCO Cup championships in the old World Hockey Association
as well as the Stanley Cup. In basketball, we allow the four
holdovers from the American Basketball Association to count rings
earned before they entered the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Vikings, for instance, haven't won a Super Bowl
since they played their first NFL game in 1961, but they won what
was still known as the ``NFL Championship'' in 1969 (they lost to
AFL champion Kansas City that season in Super Bowl IV).
</P>
<P>
   Other NFL teams have experienced even greater futility but
haven't been around as long as the Patriots. The Atlanta Falcons,
who made it to the Super Bowl two years ago but lost to Denver, are
on a 35-year championship-free streak. New Orleans has been waiting
34 years, the Cincinnati Bengals are in their 33d year, and the
Seattle Seahawks and Tampa Bay Buccaneers are in their 25th years
without a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Teams that won AFL championships include Buffalo, which won the
'64 and '65 crowns; the Houston Oilers/Tennessee Titans, who won
the first two titles in 1960 and 1961 but haven't won since; and
San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The 1967 NHL entries of the St. Louis Blues and Los Angeles
Kings have yet to win Lord Stanley's Cup, and the 1970 Buffalo
Sabres and Vancouver Canucks continue their quests.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix Suns have certainly been competitive over the years,
but the NBA title has eluded them since they entered the league in
1968. The Cleveland Cavaliers have been without a title since they
became a team in 1970. Ditto for the Buffalo Braves/San Diego and
LA Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Rockets/Nuggets were one of four ABA teams to enter
the NBA in 1976, along with the New York/New Jersey Nets, Indiana
Pacers, and San Antonio Spurs. The Rockets/Nuggets never won an ABA
crown, nor have they won an NBA title. The Pacers won three ABA
titles but haven't won an NBA crown. The Nets have never won the
NBA title but won the final ABA crown. We know you're thinking of
the Sacramento Kings, one of the league's most hapless franchises,
but they were once the Rochester Royals, and in 1951 they took the
NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   No comments are necessary from the Patriots on this subject.
When Bob Kraft bought the team from James Busch Orthwein in 1993,
he was a long-suffering Red Sox and Patriots fan who hoped to bring
a football championship here within five years. Unfortunately, one
window closed when the team failed to win in 1997 under Bill
Parcells. The Patriots thought they could win under Pete Carroll,
but poor drafting and the steady loss of key players hindered that
effort. Now Bill Belichick inherits a team void of depth, with huge
problems on both the offensive and defensive lines, and at running
back and safety.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have avoided the public wrath usually associated
with such failure because the Kraft ownership has kept the team
competitive, and you can always point to the Red Sox' long history
of falling short and the current doldrums of the Bruins and Celtics
as reasons not to be too hard on the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft had the third-highest player salary expenditures in the
league last year, a sign that he's not afraid to spend the money to
win. But after an 8-8 season, the Patriots thought it was enough to
hire a new coach and not bring in major free agents. Obviously,
Kraft doesn't have an unlimited supply of money buried underneath
the old racetrack, and there is a salary cap to contend with.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the current team has glaring needs.
</P>
<P>
   It will enter the 2000 season still searching for someone to run
the football. With rookie J.R. Redmond's status uncertain after
groin surgery and veteran Raymont Harris coming back to football
after a year off, the running situation is as tenuous as ever. The
Patriots passed on a chance to trade for Jamal Anderson last year.
They passed on a chance to sign restricted free agent Priest Holmes
of the Ravens in the offseason. They have not inquired about Barry
Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Since Robert Edwards went down, they've been amazingly
nonchalant in their pursuit of a 1,200-yard rusher. Yet they still
have Drew Bledsoe and Terry Glenn, two very exciting players, and
they hope that new schemes on the offensive line will make a
difference in Bledsoe's protection and in opening holes for Harris,
Redmond, or Kevin Faulk.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say, the Patriots aren't proud of the distinction
they hold in professional sports. Who would be? Some of it is bad
luck. Some is due to mismanagement. But Patriots fans would like to
see the team pull out all the stops one of these years and sign
some great players, as the Washington Redskins have done. The
Redskins may not get the ultimate prize, but owner Daniel Snyder
thinks the nine years since the Redskins' last Super Bowl
championship are too many. And love him or hate him, he's doing
something about it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Missing in action
</P>
<P>
   About 10 Patriots didn't complete the offseason strength and
conditioning program. The two most prominent were Glenn and Henry
Thomas. Glenn started out well but decided to return to his
Columbus, Ohio, home to do the rest of his workouts with Ohio State
strength coach Dave Kennedy. Glenn has always said he knows his
body has certain limits; apparently, he reached them. Thomas said
he worked out in Houston, where he lives. It doesn't appear that
either will suffer any consequences, though. The Patriots can ill
afford to lose Glenn, while the salary cap hit on cutting Thomas
doesn't make fiscal sense . . . The Patriots will not be able to
get into the Sean Dawkins hunt, as agent Angelo Wright is asking
for a guarantee that Dawkins will start and for money the Patriots
can't or won't pay . . . The NFL is hung up on workouts and not on
what a player can do in games. Ben Coates had an excellent workout
in Detroit last week, for instance. Coates usually won't look great
working out but he's a lion on the field. Ditto for Doug Flutie.
During the Bills' minicamp, there was talk of how great Rob Johnson
threw the ball in comparison to Flutie. But whom would you rather
have on the field to win a tough game? The Bills found that out in
the playoffs against Tennessee, when you just knew Flutie would
have found a way to beat the Titans . . . Bruce Armstrong still
awaits an insulting offer from the Patriots . . . Fall River's Marc
Megna has had an extremely productive season playing linebacker for
the Barcelona Dragons, and he should land a spot as a backup
linebacker for the Patriots this summer. Speaking of which, one of
the key competitions in camp will be between Tedy Bruschi and Andy
Katzenmoyer at inside linebacker. Bruschi reportedly is not a lock
to start . . . Edwards is not expected to play next season as he
continues to recover from his ugly knee injury. He has been working
out with Bob Kersee in St. Louis and Orlando . . . Some opinions
never change. Bill Walsh thought Rick Mirer was going to be a great
pro quarterback. He was wrong. But after losing Steve Young to
retirement, Walsh signed Mirer to back up Jeff Garcia in San
Francisco . . . What's going on with tight end Dave Stachelski, the
Patriots' fifth-round pick out of Boise State? Much suspicion has
been created with the team and the player's agent, William Heck,
not giving out any information other than the small scrap from
Belichick a few weeks ago that Stachelski underwent a minor knee
arthroscopy in Seattle. Heck said he's been told all information
about his client has to go through the Patriots, another oddity.
It's not common for a rookie to have surgery someplace other than
with his own team, but Stachelski had his procedure done by the
Seahawks' team physician and then worked out at Boise State. Former
Boston College assistant Dirk Kuetter, now the head coach at Boise,
said Stachelski was due back in Foxborough early this week. Kuetter
called Stachelski a ``physical specimen with great upside.''
Kuetter said Stachelski fell from a projected second-round pick
because of two factors: he had relatively little experience as a
tight end because he began his career as a defensive end, and he
has a tendency to get down on himself. Kuetter said Stachelski has
had injuries to his shoulders and knees, which also may have
dropped his stock, but he still thinks the Patriots may have a find
. . . The NFL gets more and more like a dictatorial state each day,
as teams try desperately to control the news and prevent their
players from speaking freely. The Bengals are taking it to the next
level, actually trying to include language in contracts that
prohibits players from publicly criticizing coaches and management.
Richard Berthelsen, general counsel for the NFL Players'
Association, is writing to the league to express his dismay. That
players are actually signing these contracts is a big blow, not
only for freedom of speech but for the NFLPA, which has always
lagged behind the other player unions in professional sports in
getting the most for its players. Several players have criticized
the Bengals in recent years, including Patriots punter Lee Johnson
two years ago. Johnson was later released. There have been other
incidents around the league in which a player speaks out and
suddenly finds himself out the door. Coates is a perfect example .
. . The Dolphins finally cut their losses with wide receiver Yatil
Green and signed Leslie Shepherd, whom the Patriots never could
pull the trigger on despite showing the most interest in him early
in the free-agent process. Green was an extremely promising
receiver, but training-camp knee injuries sidelined him his first
two years, and assorted leg injuries limited him to eight games
last season. He now finds himself in the same position as another
injury-prone, once-promising star, Ki-Jana Carter, who was cut by
the Bengals after five bad-luck years . . . Shawn Jefferson cut a
deal with tight end Rod Monroe to get No. 84 in Atlanta. Monroe
switched to No. 49 . . . Carroll was ripped here when he took his
team bowling. Well, the Packers' Mike Sherman did the same thing at
a minicamp last week. If the Packers underachieve, I guess we'll
know why.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 2139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
