<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-METROSTARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION TAKE ONE STEP BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Revolution seemed to have cast a
spell on the MLS's Eastern Division in the first half of the
season. But their dominance ended in a 4-2 loss to the MetroStars
Saturday, which left them in first place but facing four more
successive road games.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Revolution's first loss to a division opponent in
six games this season, and it could be costly since they appeared
vulnerable after squandering the lead, and lost Leonel Alvarez (red
card) and Ivan McKinley (accumulation of yellow cards) to
suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams tackled hard and emphasized running over conserving
energy, making this an especially difficult match in 88-degree
heat. Revolution midfielder Mauricio Ramos, who returned Friday
after a 17-hour flight from Japan, departed at halftime, and
defender Brian Dunseth collapsed on the field at the final whistle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave them two presents,'' Revolution coach Fernando Clavijo
said. ``It's not shocking, because we've been playing well and our
goalkeeper (Jeff Causey) has been playing great. The important part
is that we realize our mistakes and learn from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to be facing more of that kind of treatment
because we are first in our division. We have to be prepared to
face that kind of challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Clavijo went with Jamar Beasley in the starting lineup a week
after Beasley had provided two goals as a substitute in a 3-0 win
over San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Beasley provided a subtle threat in the first half, helping open
space, but he squandered a point-blank chance on an open net in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   But by failing to hold a 2-1 lead in the final minutes of the
first half, the Revolution raised some self-doubt. They also faced
a deficit, and though they created opportunities, it was too much
to expect a rally in the conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to come back from two goals down,'' MetroStars
midfielder Mark Chung said. ``Especially in that heat, because
whatever they say the temperature is, there is no wind on that
field and it's 10 degrees hotter than it is outside the stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez provided a strong presence in midfield and quickly
limited Tab Ramos's effect on the game. But the Revolution broke
down in other areas, allowing Billy Walsh to launch an uncontested
28-yard drive for the first goal in the 20th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Franchino played a give-and-go with John Harkes to earn a
penalty that Imad Baba converted to tie the score in the 24th
minute. Alvarez and Mauricio Ramos combined in the 29th minute, but
Mike Ammann deflected the advance to Baba, who sent a hard 20-yard
drive toward goal. Ammann again saved it just outside the goal
area, but this time the rebound fell to Wolde Harris, who sent a
shot under Ammann for a 2-1 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution seemed to be in control but failed to close down
Adolfo ``El Tren'' Valencia. And the MetroStars regained the
advantage as Mike Petke stabbed an interception and Valencia
outmaneuvered Dunseth and Mauricio Ramos for a 2-2 tie in the 41st
minute. Two minutes later, the Revolution defense again broke down
and Chung's rebound off the bar was followed by Steve Shak for a
3-2 edge.
</P>
<P>
   Clint Mathis's free kick in the 49th minute gave the MetroStars
a two-goal lead and appeared to clinch the victory. Yet, the game
remained wide open and both teams continued to threaten. Ivan
McKinley entered for Rusty Pierce (back strain) and ignited the
offense as the Revolution shifted to a 3-5-2 alignment. Mauricio
Wright stifled Valencia for long periods. And Harris dribbled
through the defense, drew out Ammann, and laid off for Beasley to
shoot wide from the goal area with the net open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've scored on plays like that millions of times,'' Beasley
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution had also been in the habit of winning these types
of games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed open chances which could have changed the game,''
Clavijo said. ``But we are still on track for everything we are
trying to do. This was just a step backward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
