<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7204 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-NBAFINALS-ROSE-BO     06-17 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAFINALS-ROSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH ROSE ON RISE, PACERS STOOD TALLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The game was over, but the disappointment
lingered for Jalen Rose. His Pacers had just fallen behind, 3-1, in
the NBA Finals, losing an overtime heartbreaker to the Lakers in
which he, to be charitable, struggled.
</P>
<P>
   He could not shake the game or the sting, so he stayed at
Conseco Fieldhouse until his teammates had left and only the
workmen were still around, tending to their various clean-up tasks.
It was then Rose picked up a basketball, in the early morning
hours, and practiced on the same floor where he had just gone 5 for
16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt I needed to shoot some more,'' he said. ``I could
live with being 5 of 16, or even 1 of 16, if we won the game. You
can't leave anything in the tank, because if you do, the season is
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever he did, it worked.
</P>
<P>
   Two nights later, in Game 5, Rose was sensational. He scored 32
points in 44 active minutes. He was 12 for 18 from the field,
slashing, cutting, and knocking down jumpers, including 4 of 5 from
international waters. He had 6 rebounds, 5 assists, and 2 steals.
He led the Pacers to a 120-87 rout of the Lakers Friday that sent
the series back to Los Angeles with Indiana trailing, 3-2. Game 6
is Monday night at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand we have what it takes to beat LA, but it means
nothing talking about it,'' Rose said. ``And since I felt like I've
been doing nothing but talking about it, especially when they got
up, 3-1, I figured I was going to shut up and go out and play. I
was very determined to come out and play my game.''
</P>
<P>
   And his game can be a sight to behold.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 feet 8 inches, Rose can be a matchup nightmare for opposing
coaches. He can shoot from the outside, put the ball on the floor,
post up. As Rose put it, matter-of-factly, ``I think I'm a tough
matchup for a lot of guys because I'm taller than people expect and
I have the ability to shoot the three, as well as dribble, drive,
and post.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, he has improved exponentially since Larry Brown all
but gave up on him a few years back. His current coach, Larry Bird,
would like Rose to work a little harder, but he had no complaints
with what he saw Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's hitting his shots, it's almost impossible to stop
him,'' said Bird, under whom Rose has bloomed to become one of the
league's rising stars and, thanks to timing, one of its more
desirable free agents this summer. ``He keeps the defense off
balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Phil Jackson put it, ``We anticipated that Jalen was
going to respond, but not quite like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose and Reggie Miller were a lethal 1-2 punch, combining for 57
points. It was Rose who set the tone, scoring 22 in the first half.
The two had a chat during warmups, reminding each other of the dire
consequences of a loss: It would mean a Laker celebration on their
floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time the Pacers have been to the NBA
Finals,'' Rose said. ``It can be old hat in California. They've had
great players, great teams. Their city thrives on so many things.
Indiana thrives on basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose has thrived under Bird's stewardship. Bird recognized what
he had and made the decision to put Rose into the starting lineup,
a move that sent veteran All-Star Chris Mullin to the bench. It was
a move Bird could no longer avoid; he had a burgeoning star on his
hands and nowhere else to put him.
</P>
<P>
   With the increase in playing time (and confidence), Rose won the
Most Improved Player award, establishing career highs in just about
every statistical department. He led the Pacers in minutes and
started every game (80) in which he played. He also led in scoring,
snapping Miller's long reign as the team's scoring champ.
</P>
<P>
   For Miller, the emergence of Rose meant an adjustment, both
mental and physical. The longtime go-to guy ceded some of his
clutch time to the new kid while also trying to learn how to play
with such a versatile player. Mullin and Derrick McKey had been
there before, and neither plays like Rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came in here understanding that he would start, from Day
1,'' Miller said. ``It took some time for us to find a balance with
one another. I was so used to working with Derrick as well as Chris
the last two and three years. It took us time to get our rhythm.
Now that we've found a comfortable balance, it's starting to show a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   It showed a lot on Friday. And whether that was a sign of more
to come or simply a stay of execution, it was unquestionably a
vintage Rose performance. That's why re-signing Rose is No. 1 on
team president Donnie Walsh's ``to do'' list this summer. The way
Rose can play, is there an alternative?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
