<HEADER>
A7205 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-NBANOTES-ONEAL-BO     06-17 1651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-ONEAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEAL REALLY COMING OF AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that we've devoted the obligatory space and time to
slobbering over Kobe Bryant, can we get back to reality and the
reason the Lakers are where they are? It is, of course, because of
Shaq. But everybody knows that.
</P>
<P>
   The Laker who most resembles Michael Jordan is not the player
who walks, talks, and tries to be like Mike. The Laker who most
resembles the dominating, best-in-the-business Mike is the
320-pound Shaquille O'Neal. And it's a bit scary to look at the two
of them, along with two other icons from the 1980s, Magic Johnson
and Larry Bird, to see how closely their careers mirror one
another's.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with the obvious: the Most Valuable Player award.
O'Neal was a worthy winner this year. It's his first, and he's 28.
That seems to be the Age of Reason in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan won his first MVP in 1988. He was 25. But he won his
second three years later, which also was the year he won his first
NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   Bird turned 28 in 1984, the year he won the first of three
straight MVPs and the second of his three NBA titles.
</P>
<P>
   And Magic? He already had three rings on his hand when he won
his first MVP in 1987. His age? 28.
</P>
<P>
   Shaq and Michael appear to bond in the dynasty department as
well. Magic and Bird had each other and their respective Hall of
Fame rosters to balance the scales in the 1980s. There was no such
equalizer for the Bulls in the 1990s, and there may be no one in
this decade who can keep the Lakers honest. As Shaq put it last
week, ``Hopefully, this will be the start of something.'' Needless
to say, Shaq and Jordan also share the erudite Phil Jackson, who
knows about dynasties.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's early. But the Lakers are winning this year with the
MVP, a burgeoning star in Bryant, and basically a lot of everyday
players. Glen Rice was once an All-Star before getting neutered in
LA. But that's it. The rest of the roster would have trouble with
Rapid City or Yakima.
</P>
<P>
   But with Shaq and Kobe healthy and committed, is there a team
out there that can keep up with the Lakers? Portland might have
been better and deeper this season _ the Trail Blazers did outplay
LA in five of the seven games in the conference finals. But the
Blazers may be getting weaker, not stronger. Arvydas Sabonis is
telling teammates he may retire, Jermaine O'Neal wants to be
traded, Brian Grant may opt out of his contract (though he may
re-sign), and Scottie Pippen (35 in September) isn't getting any
younger.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio? Last year, Tim Duncan was being anointed the game's
top player, and he is still at least No. 2 or No. 3. But unless
Grant Hill goes there to accompany him and help ease David Robinson
into the sunset, the Spurs are going to be merely good, not great.
They're old, as well. Phoenix? If the Suns can land Dikembe
Mutombo, they may have a short window before the Big Guy goes AARP
on them. Utah? No chance. Houston? It'll be better after Hakeem
Olajuwon retires. Minnesota? It needs more oomph.
</P>
<P>
   There's no one in the East. If Duncan and Hill are serious about
uniting, they should do so in Orlando to avoid seeing the Lakers
until the Finals. They'd instantly make the Magic prohibitive
favorites in the East. The Knicks, Heat, Sixers, and Pacers all are
going to be adequate, but, to recall Pat Riley's wise words when
Jordan was still around, ``We're all going to be playing for second
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, you have to think the Lakers will be stronger once
general manager Jerry West unearths a real power forward and/or
backup center. When you have the aura, as the Lakers do, not to
mention the roster and the weather, that ``middle class'' exception
becomes very attractive.
</P>
<P>
   That's a sobering thought. The Lakers won 67 games and could be
even better next season. Jackson won't let them get complacent, and
Shaq will want to prove this year was not a fluke. He's looking
back and telling everyone, ``You had your chances, but now it's all
mine.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Michael did. And there was no one around to stop
him. Only time will tell whether there's anyone out there to stop
Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The good life
</P>
<P>
   There are still a few coaching vacancies (New Jersey, LA,
Toronto), and already we've had two college coaches, both bereft of
NBA experience, move up to the big time. That hasn't happened since
1970, when Bill Fitch left Minnesota to take over the expansion
Cleveland Cavaliers and Cotton Fitzsimmons departed Kansas State to
take over the Suns. We've had others over the years, from Dick
Motta to John MacLeod to Jerry Tarkanian to John Calipari to Tim
Floyd. Is the NBA a preferable lifestyle now? The money makes it
so, but it's more than that. ``I think my run in New Jersey
certainly didn't hurt the chances of college coaches,'' Calipari
said. ``They can look and say, `He turned it around in short order.
He did it.' There was a time when none of us were being
considered.'' (And all this time, we foolishly thought Cal killed
it for the college coaches. Silly us.) Calipari said he got calls
from Tom Izzo (who spurned the Hawks) and others picking his brain
about making the jump. ``I told them that it can be a great run,''
he said. ``But also don't go in there thinking that because I'm
here, we're going to win 10 more games. You better have the bodies.
I enjoyed it, and when you see what happened, it's further
confirmation of what went down. I may do it again.'' Added P.J.
Carlesimo, who left Seton Hall to go to Portland in 1994, ``I think
the NBA always has been an attractive situation for the college
coaches. It's changed a little over the years, mostly in financial
terms. There was a time when you got paid more in college. It's
different now. I think more college coaches would consider the NBA
now than they would have, say, 10 years ago.'' There are other
reasons besides money. Recruiting is getting more and more
unseemly. College coaches have to be everywhere in July scouting
prospects. They have to deal with the kids, the coaches, the
parents, the AAU, the hangers-on, the siblings, and, of course, the
NCAA. Academic requirements are stricter now, and if a player gets
caught breaking a law, it's the coach's problem. The NBA doesn't
have that. You charter everywhere, stay in great hotels, and,
depending on what you want, can basically take off the summer with
a couple of camps. That might be one reason why Floyd was telling
friends during the predraft camp in Chicago he'll never go back to
college. Sure, it's about the money. It's just not all about the
money . . . Carlesimo, by the way, said he was still looking to get
back into the NBA, although he did say he thought the job at the
University of Miami was an attractive one. ``My clear preference is
to stay in the league,'' Carlesimo said. Wonder whether Rod Thorn
would consider bringing Carlesimo back to New Jersey. The two have
not only the NBA tie-in, but also one from USA Basketball, as
Carlesimo was an assistant coach on the first (and only) Dream Team
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Celtics &UR;  &LR; squeezed
</P>
<P>
   One of the problems with the Celtics' interest in Jermaine
O'Neal: the dreaded base-year compensation. Portland would be able
to take back only a player who makes one-half of O'Neal's salary.
But the Celtics would have to find the room to absorb the whole
salary. That's why the Bulls and Magic are in such an enviable
spot. Both teams have plenty of cap room, so either one could trade
one of its draft picks and take O'Neal . . . The NBA is concerned
enough about audience no-shows to try to do something about it. Of
course, the logical move would be to create a better product, but,
failing that, commissioner David Stern says the league is trying to
identify the unused tickets and make them available for resale
prior to games. ``We're focused on the issue of no-shows, and we
think we can improve that next year,'' Stern said. ``It's our job
to let people know that more, not less, of our teams are
interesting to watch.'' Good luck . . . You have to wonder whether
part of Jackson's compensation package was tied in some way to the
total de-fanging of Rice. Here was a guy who, when he came to the
Lakers, had every right to think he'd be getting a huge payday when
his contract expired. But after what's happened in LA this year, he
has become, at best, an exception player. If he were to declare he
wouldn't talk to the Lakers, the best he'd do would be a team's
middle-class exception. That's about a $12 million drop-off. The
Lakers likely will re-sign him with a salary of up to 15 percent
more than his current $7 million, then trade him. One option is to
Philadelphia for Toni Kukoc, although it's hard to picture Larry
Brown wanting a 33-year-old defensive liability . . . The Knicks
weren't the only losers when the Pacers eliminated them from the
playoffs. Also losing big were the maintenance men, mainly
electricians, at Madison Square Garden. While the NBA had reserved
the building for Games 3, 4, and 5, it was also being used by Bruce
Springsteen during the week. It would have been a bonanza for
workers to dismantle the Boss's set and then set it up again. NBA
officials conceded they also were concerned about practice sites on
off-days . . . Big center Brad Millard of St. Mary's almost lapped
the field at the Chicago predraft camp in one area: weight. He
checked in at 360 pounds, some 70-plus more than the next two big
guys, Mario Bland (who is 6-5, but checked in at 287) and Greek big
man Iakovos Tsakalidis, who tipped the scales at 283. DeMarr
Johnson, meanwhile, who is on the Celtics' wish list, weighed only
201 (he's 6-9), but Jerome Moiso checked in at 7 feet, 232 pounds.
Fears that Marcus Fizer might measure small proved unfounded; the
Iowa State bull is 6-9 in sneakers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
