<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPENSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT MIGHT BE AN OPEN-AND-SHUT CASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ They went with more than 18 holes of golf
again Saturday, trying to catch up in the fog-delayed,
darkness-delayed U.S. Open. And You Know Who was again the big
topic of conversation between rounds.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular question: Could anybody prevent Tiger Woods
from winning this centennial championship?
</P>
<P>
   Jesper Parnevik, who failed to make the cut after playing three
straight rounds with Woods (including a practice round Wednesday),
suspects this Open might already be closed to all but the world's
No. 1 golfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that can stop Tiger from winning is Tiger,''
Parnevik said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he was very happy about the way he played the
second round (which Woods completed Saturday morning at 2-under-par
69). But he's good enough to play under par even when he's not
playing his best . ... If he can keep on doing what he's doing, he
should win it pretty easy.''
</P>
<P>
   What Woods did Saturday morning was tie and break Open records
with a 134 midway score that gave him a six-stroke advantage over
the field.
</P>
<P>
   His 134 tied Jack Nicklaus (Baltusrol in 1980), T.C. Chen
(Oakland Hills, 1985) and Lee Janzen (Baltusrol, 1993) for the
lowest 36-hole score in Open history. The six-stroke lead (over
Denmark's Thomas Bjorn and Spain's Miguel Angel Jimenez) bettered a
97-year-old Open midway- margin record set by Willie Anderson at
Baltusrol in 1903.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, Nicklaus and Janzen went on to win those Opens. Is
Woods headed for similar success? His competition admits he could
be hard to catch unless he starts to back up to the field.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mickelson, considered one of the top contenders this week
but 10 strokes off the lead entering Saturday's delayed third
round, opted for optimism after Woods got as low as 9 under par
before giving a stroke back with a bogey on No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there were two dozen guys up there at 9 under, then you've
got to make a bunch of birdies to get there.'' Mickelson reasoned.
``But with only one guy up there it's up to him. If he comes
tumbling back, we all want to be there to catch him .... If he
doesn't, there's nothing we can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Spain's Jose Maria Olazabel, seven strokes off the lead starting
third- round play, said Woods' excellence on a difficult course has
distorted perception of good golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, before the tournament started, somebody told me that I'd
be 1 under par after two days, I'd be very, very pleased,''
Olazabel said. ``In the U.S. Open, anything under par is great.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why it seems as if there are two tournaments this week
- the one being played by Woods and the one played by everyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awesome to see,'' Olazabel said. ``Very impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lehman, 10 strokes off the lead entering the third round,
was counting on USGA-toughened Pebble Beach to help bring the field
closer to the leader:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take some great golf to catch him, but it's the
kind of course where even the best players can make some mistakes.
Those of us chasing are going to have to play our best golf and
hope he makes a mistake or two.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But will Woods retreat to the field,? Or will he just shrug
off a triple-bogey - as he did on his third-round third hole
Saturday afternoon - and offset it with three birdies in his next
four holes?
</P>
<P>
   ``If he keeps playing like he is,'' said Jim Furyk, ``it doesn't
give very many people a chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
