<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYNOTES-KOREA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH, SOUTH KOREA GETTING IT TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not only are North and South Korea likely to march together
(under the Olympic flag) in the opening ceremonies in Sydney, they
could compete as one team at the Winter Games in Salt Lake City in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   During last week's presidential summit in Pyongyang, the South
proposed that the two countries send one team to this fall's Asian
Cup soccer and next year's world table tennis championships. Korea
has never competed under its own flag at the Olympics. Before the
country was divided after World War II, it was occupied by Japan
and its athletes (most notably 1936 marathon champion Sohn Kee
Chung) competed under the flag of the Rising Sun.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whirlpool of rumors
</P>
<P>
   With Dutch swimmer Inge de Bruijn still on her incredible record
spree _ seven world marks broken or tied in three weeks _ the drug
whispers are starting to swirl. Australia's Susie O'Neill, who
broke Mary T. Meagher's ``unbreakable'' record in the 200 butterfly
this year, said de Bruijn's performances are ``pretty suss''
(suspicious). ``I absolutely understand that people think that
there is something strange,'' said the 26-year-old de Bruijn (no
relation to disgraced Irish swimmer Michelle Smith de Bruijn). ``I
am truly shocked myself.'' De Bruijn's marks would be much more
suspicious if she weren't already among the world elite. ``It's not
like she's going from 50th in the world,'' said Paul Bergin, her
part-time US coach. In any case, world swimming records are falling
like autumn leaves this year. Five were broken (three by teenager
Ian Thorpe) at the Australian championships, and Alexander Popov
(50 free) and Roman Sludnov (100 breast) broke a pair at last
week's Russian nationals . . . With Grant Hill (broken ankle) off
the US basketball team, Lakers star Kobe Bryant is the people's
choice to take his place. Hill's absence leaves Gary Payton as the
only returnee from the 1996 gold-medal team . . . How did the US
women's soccer team end up in the ``Group of Death'' at the
Olympics? Bad luck and dumbness by the international federation,
which gave the weak host Australians a top seed in one of the two
four-team prelim divisions. That's how three of the top four teams
in the world (US, China, Norway) ended up on the same side, along
with fleet and physical Nigeria. On the other side are Brazil,
Germany, Sweden, and the Aussies. Much better deal for the US
males, who get the Czech Republic, Cameroon, and Kuwait. The women,
who ended up winning the Pacific Cup when the Chinese lost to the
Canadians, are back in the States this week for the CONCACAF Gold
Cup. They'll play Trinidad &AMP; Tobago in Hershey, Pa., on Friday,
Costa Rica in Louisville on Sunday, and Brazil in Foxborough a week
from Tuesday . . . Unpleasant exit last week by the US Olympic
Committee's longtime doping-control director, who said he was
working in ``increasingly hostile, racist, threatening,
jeopardy-laden, intolerable'' conditions. Dr. Wade Exum, the USOC's
top-ranking black staffer, also claimed that the USOC was
``deliberately encouraging the doping of athletes.'' The USOC
called Exum's charges ``patently false'' and said his performance
had been under review. Exum, who quit the job after nine years,
would have been gone anyway after the Sydney Games, when the new
independent anti-doping agency takes over.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Putting out the fire
</P>
<P>
   By choosing an Aborigine (1996 field hockey gold medalist Nova
Peris-Kneebone) as the first Olympic torchbearer on Australian
soil, the Sydney organizers were moving to defuse a delicate
domestic issue. Aboriginal leaders, furious that the Australian
government won't apologize for its former policy of forcibly
putting Aboriginal children (the ``Stolen Generation'') into white
families, have threatened a protest march on the opening day of the
Games . . . As expected, there will be a record number of female
athletes (3,952) in Sydney. That's 38 percent of the total, 4
percent more than the Atlanta figure, and it's more than 10 times
as many women than competed at Melbourne in 1956, the last time the
Games were held Down Under . . . There's a strong chance that the
US rowing team will qualify all five of its remaining boats
(women's single and double, men's pair, four, and quad) at next
month's last-chance regatta in Lucerne. The Americans need to place
in the top two in everything but the single, where top three will
do. Making the trip are West Newton's Ted Murphy (pair) and
Norwood's Carol Skricki (double). Ruffled feathers, meanwhile, in
the women's sculling camp. After last year's quad of Hilary Gehman,
Jen Dore-Terhaar, Laurel Korholz, and Kelly Salchow failed to make
the Olympic trials finals rowing in doubles, the six who did
(Skricki, Ruth Davidon, Elizabeth Smith, Julia Chilicki, Leslie
Burns Rawley, Kate MacKenzie) argued that they should be the
Olympic double and quad. Coach Igor Grinko isn't buying it (Gehman
et al. did finish fourth at the world regatta). But since the camp
is competitive enough, US Rowing may want to have a showdown trials
after all instead of having Grinko name the quad. If Skricki and
Davidon don't qualify in the double at Lucerne, they'll be in the
quad mix, too . . . Maybe they should encase the US Olympic boxing
team in bubble wrap. Three of the 12 members _ light welterweight
Ricardo Williams Jr., welterweight Dante Craig, and super heavy
Calvin Brock _ are all nursing hand injuries, with Craig and Brock
both requiring surgery . . . Yes, the Greg Gibson who'll be
competing in the greco-roman event at this week's US wrestling
trials is the same Greg Gibson who won the Olympic silver medal in
1984. He's 46.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tumbling, rumbling
</P>
<P>
   With as many as five of the Magnificent Seven (all but Kerri
Strug and Amanda Borden) coming back to take on Vanessa Atler,
Kristen Maloney, Elise Ray et al., next month's US gymnastics
nationals in St. Louis and the August Olympic trials at the
FleetCenter could be the most competitive ever. ``The values are so
close among the first six spots, it's going to be brutal,''
predicted team coordinator Bela Karolyi. ``A dogfight out there.''
. . . With the ranking deadline three weeks away, the US Olympic
tennis team is shaping up this way: Andre Agassi, Pete Sampras (if
he wants to go), Todd Martin, and Michael Chang on the men's side,
Lindsay Davenport, Venus Williams, and Monica Seles on the women's.
If Sampras opts out, as he did last time, Chris Woodruff is next in
line. The women's situation is iffy, since Williams says she might
stay home if sister Serena doesn't qualify. If Venus says nix,
Jennifer Capriati, the 1992 champion, is heiress apparent. Agassi
and Davenport are the defending gold medalists . . . Looking solid
for a spot on the US Olympic road cycling team is Marblehead's
Tyler Hamilton. Not only has he been racing well in France, he's
also Lance Armstrong's wingman. Antonio Cruz grabbed one berth by
winning last month's trials. The rest of the team will be picked
next month . . . Who'll be hosting the nightly medal ceremony in
downtown Salt Lake during the 2002 Winter Games? Just-retired 49ers
quarterback Steve Young, who has signed on as SLOC's
ambassador-at-large. He'll also help with fund-raising and be a
community liaison . . . Now that the Salt Lake organizers have the
feds off their back, they can turn their attention to more mundane
issues. Like, what's for dinner. The South Koreans have been
worrying that they'll be subsisting on Egg McMuffins and chicken
tenders during the 2002 Winter Games. But SLOC chief Mitt Romney
has assured them that he'll have chefs on hand who can whip up
bulgogi with kim chi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
