<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTONOTES-BOSTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIFFERENT TWIST ON BOSTON DRIVING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine this: It is a warm summer day in the Back Bay. The
deafening din of turbocharged, eight-cylinder racing engines fills
the air. Gleaming open-wheel cars from the Championship Auto Racing
Teams circuit _ piloted by drivers such as Paul Tracy, Jimmy
Vasser, Kenny Brack, Dario Franchitti, Michael Andretti, and this
year's Indianapolis 500 winner, Juan Montoya _ are tearing around a
2-mile street circuit lined with fans.
</P>
<P>
   Barriers and temporary grandstand seating have been erected
around the Public Garden. On Charles Street, between the Public
Garden and Boston Common, there is a temporary pit road and paddock
area. The speed limit on Beacon Street, Arlington Street, and
Commonwealth Avenue is now in excess of 100 miles per hour as cars
circle the Garden, scream down a high-speed straightaway on Comm.
Ave, make a hairpin turn on Exeter Street, and head back toward the
start/finish line on Charles Street.
</P>
<P>
   If CART officials have their way, and find a promoter to step
up, that scenario could play out two years from now. It is all part
of a recently-announced initiative by CART, with the joint
cooperation of Dover Downs Entertainment, to develop new markets
beginning in 2002. The cities where CART hopes to stage street
races are Atlanta, Denver, New York, Philadelphia, Phoenix, San
Francisco, and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But can a CART race really fly in this city, where for nine
years traffic has been affected by that giant pothole known as the
Big Dig?
</P>
<P>
   Before he was fired Friday as CART's CEO and president, Andrew
Craig expressed optimism about such a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional way in which we have located new venues is to
wait for someone to come along and tell us that they either have
built or are thinking about building a track in whatever city,''
Craig said in a telephone interview from Detroit Thursday. ``Then
we say, `Well, we're not interested,' or `We are interested.' And
that's not really a very good way to run your business.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidently, Craig came to that realization a little too late.
Though the series under Craig's stewardship expanded beyond US
borders to Brazil, Japan, and Australia, CART's domestic attendance
figures and television ratings have sagged. Much of the decline was
attributed to the divisive open-wheel feud CART has waged with the
Indy Racing League.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it seems, that cost Craig his job.
</P>
<P>
   He will be replaced on the nine-member CART board by Bobby
Rahal, a former driver and current car owner, who will step in
until a permanent successor is found. James Hardymon, the former
chairman and CEO of Textron Inc., replaced Craig as CART's board
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the shakeup, CART remains committed to the expansion of
its series to larger American markets. CART will not return to St.
Louis after this season and took steps Friday to solidify its 2001
schedule by announcing that the race at Homestead-Miami Speedway
was no longer on the slate.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're looking for are cities which tend to have more
young people than the average, with a somewhat higher-than-average
income _ large cities, obviously, where we'd perform better on TV
than elsewhere,'' Craig said. ``And Boston makes the cut on all of
those, so certainly it is somewhere we'd like to race.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a bold initiative to bring races to the masses instead of
drawing the masses to remote locales such as Nazareth, Pa., which
will no longer be on the CART schedule after 2001, and Loudon,
N.H., where attendance pales in comparison to crowds drawn by the
NASCAR Winston Cup Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we recognize that we're looking at eight possible
venues and that we may not go to every one of those,'' Craig said.
``We recognize that the Big Dig is a huge issue, but I think we
clearly want to put our flag in the ground and say `Look, this is a
city we'd like to be in,' and we hope that causes a constructive
discussion of sorts among potential race promoters who may look at
the opportunity. There are always opportunities in every city that
can be worked out if there's somebody who really wants to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   If a race in Boston does happen, Craig's only regret will be
that he won't be here to preside over it as CART's president and
CEO.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back in gear
</P>
<P>
   A week after winning the Indy 500, Montoya began defense of the
CART title he won as a rookie in 1999 by capturing the rain-delayed
Miller Lite 225 at West Allis, Wis. It was Montoya's first CART
FedEx victory of the season, and the first for his Toyota engine
supplier, making the 24-year-old wunderkind from Bogota, Colombia,
the sixth different winner in as many CART events this season,
matching a series record established in 1991. Montoya, who scored
22 points to move into a fourth-place tie with Andretti in the CART
FedEx standings, will try to make it two in a row in Sunday's
Tenneco Automotive Grand Prix of Detroit. ``It was frustrating not
to get a win until our sixth (CART) race,'' said Montoya, ``but I
know we'll be back on the podium soon.'' Montoya was subjected to
some good-natured ribbing during a Thursday night appearance on
``Late Show with David Letterman'' for his wild opening toss at a
recent Yankees game and the steamy kiss he shared with his
girlfriend in Victory Lane at Indy. But when pressed by Letterman
on rumors of his imminent departure to Formula One, Montoya said he
was in the second year of a three-year contract with car owner Chip
Ganassi and planned to return next year to the CART series . . .
NASCAR Winston Cup driver Tony Stewart will go for his third
victory in a row in Sunday's Pocono 500. Stewart backed up his
first victory of the season at Dover, Del., two weeks ago with a
rain-shortened triumph in the Kmart 400 last weekend at Michigan
Speedway. Stewart, who set rookie records last season with three
victories and a fourth-place finish in points, is seventh in the
current standings, 295 points behind Joe Gibbs Racing teammate
Bobby Labonte. ``I'm happy winning two in a row. I don't know
anybody that wouldn't be,'' said Stewart, who had two crashes and a
mechanical failure in the first 14 races of his grueling 34-race
schedule . . . Melling Racing announced it would join the Dodge
Motorsports lineup, becoming the fourth NASCAR team to commit to
campaigning the Dodge Intrepid next season, along with Evernham
Motorsports (which will field cars for Bill Elliott and Casey
Atwood), Bill Davis Racing (Ward Burton and Dave Blaney), and Petty
Enterprises (Kyle Petty and John Andretti). Car owner Mark Melling,
who will switch from Ford to Dodge, said he signed away the rights
to his traditional No. 9 to Elliott and will field car No. 92 next
season. ``That's 92 for nine the second time around,'' Melling said
. . . Busch North driver Tracy Gordon made it two in a row with his
victory in the Primestar 150 at Beech Ridge Speedway in
Scarborough, Maine, last weekend. Gordon now leads Brad Leighton,
last year's series champion, in the Busch North standings, 874-787
. . . The Indy Racing League recently signed an agreement with
Texas Motor Speedway to host two races each year through 2004,
including the first race after the Indy 500 and the IRL season
finale. ``Texas Motor Speedway is a five-star motorsports facility,
and we are proud to know that the Indy Racing Northern Light Series
will have a home here for the next four years,'' said IRL founder
Tony George. The IRL will look to expand its nine-race schedule
next year with races at new oval venues in Chicago and Kansas City,
Kan. . . . Scott Sharp recorded the closest margin of victory in
IRL history when he beat Robby McGehee across the finish line by a
scant .059 seconds in last weekend's Casino Magic 500 at Texas
Motor Speedway. Sharp's victory, his first of the IRL season and
fifth of his career, was closer than Robby Buhl's .064-second win
over Vincenzo Sospiri at NHIS Aug. 17, 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
