<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7212 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-CYCLE-NHIS-SUPERBIKE-     06-17 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYCLE-NHIS-SUPERBIKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MLADIN EARNS POLE FOR SUPERBIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ It was a magnanimous gesture, to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   Mat Mladin had no sooner won the pole position in record fashion
for the Superbike event of Sunday's 77th AMA Loudon Classic when he
suggested that Eric Bostrom, who was fastest during Friday's
preliminary qualifying, was equally deserving of the honor.
</P>
<P>
   Mladin wasn't being charitable. He was merely speaking the truth
when he said, ``Eric should be sitting here on the pole.''
</P>
<P>
   Bostrom, who set a track record with his lap of 1 minute 10.042
seconds (82.236 miles per hour) on the 12-turn, 1.6-mile road
course at New Hampshire International Speedway, figured his time
would land him the pole for Sunday's AMA Chevy Trucks Superbike
Championship race when Saturday's second qualifying session was
interrupted by a two-hour rain delay.
</P>
<P>
   However, once the track was deemed sufficiently dried, AMA
officials gave the green light on qualifying. It was a move that
caught Bostrom by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there was still two more 750 qualifying sessions
left,'' he said. ``When they called us out (to qualify), I was
still in my street clothes. It caught me off guard, for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Bostrom, as a result, struggled to get up to speed on track
conditions he described as ``sketchy,'' turning a fast lap of
1:10.007. With about 8 minutes left in the session, Mladin vaulted
to the pole when he surpassed Bostrom's track record with a fast
lap of 1:09.947 (82.348 m.p.h.) on his Suzuki 750.
</P>
<P>
   It resulted in Mladin's third pole of the Superbike season and
14th overall of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should've let us stay on the schedule (in which case the
2:30 qualifying session would've been rained out),'' said Mladin,
28, of Australia, who will take a scant 1-point lead (171-170) over
Nicky Hayden, 18, of Owensboro, Ky., in the AMA Superbike
standings. ``They should've let us stay on the times (from Friday's
session) and not run this qualifying session . . . Eric should be
sitting here on the pole.''
</P>
<P>
   Bostrom, whose fast lap came one lap after Mladin's
record-setting tour, will start on the front row on his Kawasaki
along with Yamaha rider Hayden and Aaron Yates.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jaime Bowman of Boynton Beach, Fla., recorded his first career
AMA victory in Saturday's Lockhart Phillips USA 750 Supersport
race. It was the second podium finish of his career after a
third-place effort in last year's race at NHIS. ``I like all the
racetracks,'' said Bowman, who took the checkered flag on his Team
Hooters Suzuki over runner-up Jimmy Moore and third-place finisher
Damon Buckmaster. ``This one is a test. It's really tough and I
just hung in there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After crashing in qualifying Friday, Kurtis Roberts of Modesto,
Calif., took another step toward defending the Formula Xtreme
championship he won last year with his third straight win of the
season in Saturday's race at NHIS. Joshua Hayes of Gulfport, Miss.,
finished runner-up to his Erion Racing Honda teammate, while Jake
Zemke of Paso Robles, Calif., finished third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
