<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7214 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBO-XFL-NEWLEAGUE-BOS     06-17 1870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-XFL-NEWLEAGUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WWF BRINGS ITS TOUCH TO XFL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ They were sitting around a conference room
table, coming up with up names for their racy, no-holds-barred
television show. They were thinking along the lines of MTV's
``Unplugged.''
</P>
<P>
   One member of the World Wrestling Federation Entertainment Inc.
brain trust said, ``It has to be something raw, and out there.''
Eyebrows were raised. ``Oh, raw.'' That was it.
</P>
<P>
   Later, according to WWF fan services administrator Adam Hopkins,
they toyed with the word. Someone said it backward. Raw. War.
``They started calling it `Raw is War' and they figured it was a
nice palindrome,'' said Hopkins.
</P>
<P>
   That led to spinoffs from WWFE, the unabashed 20-year-old
entertainment giant that long ago discovered a common pulse among a
viewing audience of different ages _ and presumably different
tastes. It locked in on that pulse and has been holding on with a
grip that could choke a cow.
</P>
<P>
   WWFE stages approximately 200 live events each year, produces
nine hours of original programming each week, and distributes its
wares in 120 countries in 11 languages . . . WWF's ``Raw Is War''
is the No. 1-rated regularly scheduled program on all of cable
television . . . WWF's ``Smackdown!'' is the top-rated program on
United Paramount Network . . . The WWF event ``King of the Ring''
scheduled for June 25 at the FleetCenter, sold out in 4 1/2 minutes
. . . Autobiographies of WWF superstars The Rock and Mankind both
topped the New York Times Bestseller list.
</P>
<P>
   The company now wants to get its grip on the pulse of the
nation's football fans, with a new league whose season will begin
almost immediately after the Super Bowl. They believe you want to
watch more football after January, and they plan to give it to you
with an uninhibited, fan-oriented edge that has made programs like
``Raw'' popular.
</P>
<P>
   But what to call it? Early on, they thought along the same lines
as their flagship show. ``Raw Football''? No, that didn't work.
Then they thought along the lines of the latest craze among young
people: extreme sports.
</P>
<P>
   How about the Extreme Football League? Not quite. They needed
something shorter and catchier, something folks could remember,
like NFL, NBA, NHL.
</P>
<P>
   How about XFL? That was it. Doesn't stand for anything. Just
XFL.
</P>
<P>
   The XFL is a $100 million joint venture of WWFE and NBC, each of
which will invest $50 million and own 50 percent of the league.
NBC, which lost its NFL coverage three years ago, will carry XFL
games on Saturday nights in prime time leading up the championship
game April 2, 2001. UPN also will televise 10 regular-season games
and one playoff game on Sunday afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   WWFE has lured some top names in sports and entertainment for
the venture, including former NBC executive producer Michael
Weisman (as broadcast consultant), former MLS president Billy Hicks
(administrative vice president), former NFL and USFL executive Mike
Keller (football operations), and former Dallas Cowboys star
receiver Drew Pearson (advisory panel member).
</P>
<P>
   WWFE has announced four of the eight XFL cities: New York,
Chicago, Orlando, and Los Angeles. Sources close to the company
said San Jose, Memphis, and Birmingham will be announced soon. The
eighth site has yet to be determined, but it will not likely be
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Playing by their own rules
</P>
<P>
   Already XFL officials are boasting about the league's style of
play, which unlike the WWF will not be scripted or staged: It will
be 1960s and 1970s smashmouth football, with no fair catches or
touchbacks, less protection for the quarterback, and bump-and-run
play for wide receivers and cornerbacks.
</P>
<P>
   End zone celebrations will be allowed. Cameras and microphones
will be attached to players and coaches, on the sidelines and in
the locker room. There will be a 10-minute halftime and a 35-second
play clock. There's even talk of allowing the head slap.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're looking to do is not get a shift in the (nation's
football) ritual,'' said XFL president Basil DeVito. ``We're
looking to provide an extension of that ritual.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, this is not another throng of deep-pocketed investors
trying to invade NFL airspace; this is one of the world's most
successful entertainment companies trying to succeed in the world
of mainstream sports.
</P>
<P>
   For years, they've pushed the entertainment envelope with their
outrageous, controversial _ some would say perverse _ wrestling
programs. But the WWF's secret to success, its officials say, can
be illustrated in one image: Picture a father entering a room while
his teenage son is seated before a blaring TV set. Dad takes a
seat. Son doesn't move. And both the volume and the channel remain
the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is something dads and teens connect on,'' said DeVito, a
former WWF president. ``Don't ask me why. I'm not a sociologist.''
</P>
<P>
   Now they will try to make that same connection with the nation's
football fans, who historically have shown only a temporary
interest in anything beyond the NFL. XFL officials plan to move
right past the novelty stage by making a lasting impression from
day one.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only a certain amount of curiosity to anything,''
said Vince McMahon, the WWF's cofounder and chairman, and one of
its most visible figures. ``We are long-range oriented, big on
hype, but bigger on substance. We always say that if we don't beat
the marketplace this week, the public won't have the same
expectations from us the next week.''
</P>
<P>
   McMahon said he has considered starting up a new league for
about five years, and before that he thought about purchasing the
Canadian Football League or the Minnesota Vikings. He wants not so
much to be what other leagues aren't as to put the WWF stamp on
professional football.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were running the NFL, I would make one of the
prerequisites for owning a team having to line up and be the
tackling dummy for an afternoon,'' he said. ``Know what the game is
all about. Know about contact. Know the passion of the players.
Play and understand the game and get in it, rather than sitting in
a skybox having margaritas.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever wonder what prompts those confrontations between coach and
player you've seen on NFL sidelines? That won't be a problem in the
XFL. Cornerback and wide receiver taunting each other at the line
of scrimmage? You'll hear it in the XFL.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the XFL will give fans an opportunity to express
themselves during games.
</P>
<P>
   Because there are so many opportunities to unveil
behind-the-scenes aspects of the game, XFL officials say, there
won't be a need for the scripts and prearranged outcomes of the
WWF.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a great deal of story-line drama when Roger Clemens
goes back to Boston to pitch,'' said DeVito, ``and it's a matter of
how you present that drama. There is no need, in competitive
sports, to script that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to allow the natural personalities of the game and
the athletes to be brought out, exposed, and promoted as never
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you give a player who just created the winning play an
opportunity to express himself with his helmet off, you're going to
get some real, raw emotion. And that's what we're looking for:
emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting the word out
</P>
<P>
   When former University of New Haven football players Mario
Didino and Dave Menard were interviewed about their possible
participation in the XFL, they had almost as many questions as
answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What have you heard about it? What do you think?'' said
Didino, an offensive lineman from Providence who was contacted by
XFL officials after being cut by the Barcelona Dragons of NFL
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The XFL, which sent out questionnaires to 3,700 prospective
``clients'' and will hold its first draft in October, clearly has
its work cut out when it comes to educating players about the
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``You probably know as much about it as I do,'' said Menard, a
linebacker from Attleboro, Mass., who was cut by the Cleveland
Browns during preseason camp last year. ``I'm honored that they've
shown interest in me, and I would love to be an ambassador for a
league just starting out, but I just don't know much about it yet.
No one does.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the players' concerns is safety, which is not surprising
considering the problems in disseminating information about the
league. An Internet site called XFLFootball.com, which is not
affiliated with WWFE, has a cartoon of a disheveled placekicker
with a caption that reads, ``Not only is roughin' the kicker
allowed . . . It's encouraged!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a player call up and he said, `Geez, are you really
going to be doing these things? I don't know if I want to play in a
dangerous game,' '' said Keller, a former Dallas Cowboys
linebacker. ``And I said, `No, we believe in players' safety more
than players do.' There are just rules in there that create great
competitive matchups that go back to the toughness that the game
was.''
</P>
<P>
   One aspect of the league that will make players want to learn
more: It will be the best-paying football league outside of the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Players will receive a base salary of $50,000, and there will be
a pool of money to be split among those on the winning team after
each game. Ties will be discouraged, as neither team will split the
pot in that event. Each member of the championship team will
receive another $25,000-$30,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say a team goes 7-3 during the regular season, wins the
playoff and the final,'' said DeVito. ``The player who would have
played the entire 12-game schedule would earn about $110,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's another lure: XFL-contracted players will be allowed to
play in other leagues. Make a name for yourself with the XFL, get
noticed by an NFL team, and you can sign with them, as long as you
honor the remaining portion of your XFL contract.
</P>
<P>
   Said Keller, ``How can I look you in the eye and say, `You can't
go on and make $500,000, you have to stay here and make $75,000?' I
wouldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But will this turn the XFL into nothing more than a farm system
for the NFL?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of it depends on an individual's promotional
contract when we develop our own stars, whether they play in the
NFL or stay where they are,'' said McMahon.
</P>
<P>
   XFL officials, many of whom have NFL roots, say they are
confident NFL officials will welcome their league _ even though
some in the XFL have taken indirect shots at the NFL by saying no
felons will be allowed. NFL officials declined comment on the XFL.
</P>
<P>
   Though XFL officials might use WWF venues to promote XFL events,
you won't see wrestlers in XFL uniforms. Hopkins said stars such as
The Rock and Steve Austin earn up to $5 million a year and would
not take a pay cut to suit up for the new league.
</P>
<P>
   But Hopkins did offer this suggestion to McMahon during a
roundtable discussion: Change the popular WWF event known as the
Royal Rumble to the Royal Fumble, in which a football is dropped
among wrestlers in a steel cage and they must battle for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sort of looked at me cross-eyed and said, `Stick to
football,' '' said Hopkins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
