<SLUG> BC-BOX-CASTILLO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASTILLO TAKES WBC LIGHTWEIGHT TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MORALES  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELL GARDENS, Calif. _ With supporters shouting, ``Mexico,
Mexico,'' Jose Luis Castillo of Guymas, Mexico, lived out a dream
Saturday at the Bicycle Club Casino.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo, in a workmanlike performance, took the World Boxing
Council lightweight title from Stevie Johnston of Denver with a
majority 12-round decision before 1,200.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Dr. James Jen-Kim favored Castillo, 116-111. Dick Young
scored the bout a 114-114 draw. And Gelasio Percy had Castillo
winning, 115-113.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston, 27, is 30-2. He was attempting to make his 10th title
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo, 26, improved to 41-4. It was his first shot at a major
world championship. That he won this particular belt was especially
pleasing to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a dream of mine to bring the lightweight title back to
Mexico for all the other (Mexicans) who had it; Julio Cesar Chavez,
Cesar Bazan and Miguel Angel Gonzalez,`` Castillo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was winning the fight because I was pressing all
the rounds.''
</P>
<P>
   That he was. More than anything, it was the inside fighting of
Castillo that provided the edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy was just a great inside fighter, you gotta give it to
him,'' said Johnston, who suffered a cut over his right eye, which
was nearly shut at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan was to fight him a little farther out, but I stayed
too close in. That was my mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Featherweight Steven Luevano of La Puente didn't waste any time
making an impression in his professional debut.
</P>
<P>
   Luevano, aggressive from the outset, stopped Hugo Rosales (1-2)
of Mexico at 2:32 of the second round after connecting with a right
uppercut.
</P>
<P>
   The bout was scheduled for four rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Luevano, 19, was fighting before about 35 friends and relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little nervous,'' said Luevano, who was 189-16 as an
amateur, including 11 national titles and a recent second-place
finish in the Olympic Trials box-offs at 125 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of shaky in the beginning,'' Luevano said. ``I was
wondering what he was going to be like. But he wasn't doing
anything. He was just waiting for me. So I was just boxing like I
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Luevano caught Rosales midway through the second round with a
left cross. Shortly thereafter he hammered Rosales with the right
uppercut, and the referee stopped the bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want nothing bad to happen, like get caught with a
lucky shot and go down,'' Luevano said. ``I got hit with one good
punch, but it didn't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Luevano also said he liked not having to wear the headgear for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see the punches coming more easily,'' Luevano said.
</P>
<P>
   Luevano's cousin, Marshall Martinez of Fontana, also won his
professional debut. Martinez, 19, won a four-round unanimous
decision over Armen Kalagian (0-1-1) of Yerezen, Armenia, in the
lightweight division.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez suffered a gruesome cut on the left side of his nose
from a head-butt in the first round. It bled profusely. Martinez
had rocked Kalagian a couple of times in the round, but after the
cut he changed his strategy and became more of a boxer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to stay away so I wouldn't get hit more in the
nose,'' Martinez said. ``The nose really hurt. I had to start
boxing. I had to lose my brawling style.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez won by three scores of 40-36.
</P>
</TEXT>
