<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7216 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-DELAHOYA     06-17 1578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-DELAHOYA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA WOULDN'T PAY, BUT ARUM DID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Oscar De La Hoya made a statement last week to
boxing's three crime families, the World Boxing Council, World
Boxing Association, and International Boxing Federation. So did his
promoter. As is often the case with fighter and promoter, they
didn't say the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya said he would no longer do business with the WBC,
whose welterweight title he defended Saturday night against Shane
Mosley. He said this by refusing to pay its extortionist
sanctioning price, a ``fee'' charged for the right to fight for a
plastic belt that no longer carries much meaning because of the way
the three organizations have distorted rankings and sold out one
fighter after another.
</P>
<P>
   Arum, who says he often agrees with De La Hoya's point that the
organizations exploit boxers, promoters, and managers alike and
testified to that effect a week ago in federal court, nevertheless
resorted to business as usual with the WBC. And for the usual
reason: money.
</P>
<P>
   The standard 3 percent fee would have been a pretty good day for
the WBC because De La Hoya's purse could run well over $10 million,
depending on pay-per-view sales. De La Hoya refused to pay,
however, and made a public declaration to that effect Wednesday
with WBC president Jose Sulaiman standing in the back of the room
with a sour look on his face. But Arum gave in, agreeing to pay the
WBC a fee out of his proceeds. According to Arum, it would have
cost him several million dollars in international television
revenue if the WBC had removed its sanction.
</P>
<P>
   With or without the sanction, the winner surely would have been
recognized as the WBC welterweight champion. But De La Hoya,
Sulaiman, and Arum all knew the promoter did what promoters and
managers have done for decades now. He paid the ``fee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I wasn't going to pay fees anymore and I'm not,'' De La
Hoya said. ``I'm standing by my word. No more taking advantage of
the fighters. I'm sticking to my guns. They're still getting paid,
but that's on Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   Arum said he needed the WBC sanctioning to maximize income from
international television and to promote De La Hoya for a world tour
beginning in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand why they need to generate millions of
dollars per annum,'' said Cedric Kushner, Mosley's promoter. ``I
wonder who is receiving this money. If it's not the fighters, who
is it benefiting?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer is being driven home day after day in a federal court
in New Jersey, where IBF president Bob Lee is on trial for
accepting bribes for rankings and where Arum testified against him:
The sanctioning bodies are benefiting.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya tried to do his part to change that.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad Arum didn't join him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Short jabs
</P>
<P>
   One reason former junior middleweight champion David Reid
decided to move up to middleweight after losing the 154-pound title
to Felix Trinidad was that he was told by noted conditioning expert
Mackie Shilstone that he had only 2.9 percent body fat despite
weighing 165 pounds. Reid, the WBC's No. 2 middleweight, believes
he could beat champion Keith Holmes easily. He is willing to return
to 154 to fight Trinidad or IBF champion Fernando Vargas in title
fights but otherwise is seeking a shot at IBF middleweight champion
Bernard Hopkins, his rival from Philadelphia. Problem is, Hopkins
wants to pursue light heavyweight champion Roy Jones Jr. on the way
up or Trinidad at 160, while Jones wants to pursue Evander
Holyfield and Trinidad wants a second shot at De La Hoya's chin.
Chances are, none of them will catch up to each other soon . . .
HBO Sports vice president Kery Davis believes the recent signing of
Trinidad to a multifight deal, which should carry him through
mid-2002 exclusively on HBO and TVKO, has done more than assure HBO
of a rematch between Trinidad and De La Hoya. ``It gives us four of
the six best fighters in the world,'' Davis said. ``Even if a
rematch with Oscar doesn't happen, we should still get some other
big fights with Trinidad and Vargas or Hopkins. Mosley would fight
him at a catch weight if he beats Oscar. This (between 147 and 160)
is the most exciting division in boxing right now. It's similar to
the days of (Marvin) Hagler, (Thomas) Hearns, (Sugar Ray) Leonard,
and (Roberto) Duran, and we have the top guys.'' . . . To build
interest in Trinidad in the United States, HBO will heavily promote
his July 22 fight in Miami, a mandatory defense of the WBA super
welterweight title against Mamadou Thiam. ``We intend to make it an
HBO event,'' Davis said. ``We want to try to raise Felix's
visibility and his popularity. He doesn't speak English, which is a
problem, but the bottom line is he may be the best fighter in the
world.'' . . . One problem with a possible De La Hoya-Trinidad
rematch is weight; as the gap widens, De La Hoya will become less
inclined to fight him. Last week, Trinidad indicated for the first
time his willingness to come down several pounds from the 154 he
says he now fights at, but he still insisted De La Hoya come up 4
or 5 pounds, which De La Hoya is not ready to do. If Trinidad does
as he has suggested and moves up to 160 to challenge for Hopkins's
middleweight title while De La Hoya remains at 147, then the
likelihood of a rematch is nil. ``You get 13 pounds between them
and you got a problem,'' Davis said . . . Mike Tyson's assistant
trainer, Jay Bright, had an interesting description of what
happened to Michael Grant when he froze up against Lewis and was
destroyed in less than two rounds in April. ``He didn't show his
true talent,'' Bright said. ``Michael Grant let his feelings
constipate his abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Around and around
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Mayweather Jr. is facing possible isolation after HBO
pulled its contract offer off the table for the second time because
of new manager James Prince's demands on Mayweather's behalf.
Mayweather's reaction was to evict his father-trainer Floyd Sr.
from his Las Vegas home for nonpayment of rent and to repossess his
father's car. He also evicted his younger sister the day before her
high school graduation in Las Vegas. Mayweather and Prince then
went looking for a new trainer and reportedly have been turned down
by Emanuel Steward, Miguel Diaz, and even Mayweather's uncle Roger
. . . Prince has also taken over the career of WBA welterweight
champion James Page. Not long after that, Page announced he will
not fight for promoter Don King again after a mandatory defense vs.
Andrew Lewis. King says he has a long-term contract, and with King
that often means until three days after you're dead. If Page and
Prince try to break it, they may find out how long a champion can
go without work. The way Prince is going, he's going to have the
biggest stable of unemployed or underpaid world champions in boxing
. . . New York promoter Joe DeGuardia has been charged with double
dipping for allegedly taking a one-third manager's fee from the
purse of Lou Del Valle when he fought Jones last July 18 and then
also accepted a check for $132,500 as a promotional fee from
Kushner, the promoter of record. DeGuardia was paid $238,833.33
from Kushner as his slice of Del Valle's $798,000 purse and his
promotional company received a second check for the remainder, a
violation of a New York law. Asked if DeGuardia knew what was going
on at the time, Kushner said, ``He's a lawyer, isn't he?'' . . .
Tyson's trainers, Bright and Tommy Brooks, insist their man will
appear as scheduled June 24 in Glasgow to meet Lou Savarese despite
Tyson delaying his arrival in England to attend the funeral of a
friend who was shot on a Brooklyn street corner last week. The
fight has been postponed twice by Tyson, but Tyson reportedly has
been training diligently of late to peel off some of the 274 pounds
he had swollen to during the idle time since his quick blowout of
Julius Francis in February. The fight is expected to attract
40,000-plus at Hamden Park, a Scottish soccer stadium . . .
Savarese's trainer, Jesse Reid, once trained Tyson for 10 days
before he was fired after a string of angry exchanges. Reid now
claims, ``Tyson walks a tightrope. I do not think he's right
mentally. He has a lot of negativity in his mind. We're going to
work on that and try to bring it out. We're going to try to break
his heart and mind. When you do that to a fighter, you've got
him.'' . . . David Tua made such quick work of Obed Sullivan that
Nevada Athletic Commission executive director Marc Ratner approved
Tua as an instant opponent for John Ruiz June 10 if King wanted to
use him as a substitute for Holyfield, but neither King nor Ruiz
was interested. Ratner said he would have approved the quick
turnaround for Tua because he defeated Sullivan in less than a
minute and passed a postfight physical . . . IBF junior
welterweight champion Zab Judah has a new opponent for his first
title defense next weekend. He was originally set to fight Jason
Rowland (24-1) but now will be in with another Brit, Junior Witter,
about whom he knows very little. What he does know is that although
the IBF recently named Terron Millett ``champion in recess,''
school's out on the IBF title because he now holds it. The IBF has
termed him ``interim champion,'' but Judah is of the opinion that
his term will be a long one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
