<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-PRONGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRONGER'S DOUBLE AWARD BRINGS HART-ACHE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chris Pronger, the NHL's top defenseman and most valuable
player?
</P>
<P>
   Where did they get the ballot boxes this year, out of some
back-county Alabama sheriff's race?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Pronger is truly one of the game's fine talents. Once a
struggling soul on the Forever .500s backline, he has spent the
last three years chiseling himself into an impressive chunk of
granite in the Blues' game plan. Given his age (28), his size (6
feet 6 inches), and what looks to be an extending growth curve in
his game, he probably would be the first defenseman any of the
Original 30 would select in an open draft.
</P>
<P>
   But Norris Trophy and Hart Trophy? Hello, Professional Hockey
Writers' Association? Has that repetitive-stress disorder worked
its way up your arms?
</P>
<P>
   I'll grant the Norris without argument, although the good folks
in Detroit might wonder just what Nicklas Lidstrom has to do take
home that prize: He has been runner-up three straight seasons. The
last guy to finish second three straight years was then-Ranger Brad
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Now, before I get into the Hub's indignity over Pronger, let's
review the definition of the Hart (MVP) Trophy: ``The player
adjudged to be the most valuable to his team.'' We don't even have
to get into the discussion about who is the best player in the game
and blah, blah, blah.
</P>
<P>
   Just working off the definition, it says here that goaltender
Roman Turek was the player most valuable to the Blues in 1999-2000.
Take Turek out of the cage and the Blues would be back around .500
at best. Losing Pronger would not be nearly as damaging. So the
argument should end right there in the Kiel Center.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as for the rub in the Hub.
</P>
<P>
   Pronger, who edged Jaromir Jagr by a single point (396-395) in
the balloting, now stands shoulder to shoulder with Bobby Orr as
the only ones to win the Norris and Hart in the same season. Orr
did it three times ('70-72). Placing Pronger on a par with Orr is
just as inappropriate as comparing Michael Jordan to anyone playing
in the NBA today. History will now link Orr and Pronger. Someone
get me the bolt cutters, titanium-coated please.
</P>
<P>
   Next, let's travel back 10 years and review the outcome of the
'90 Hart balloting:
</P>
<P>
   Winner _ Mark Messier; runner-up _ Ray Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   Response now, as it was then: What!?
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, edged by 2 points in the balloting, didn't win then
because many voters held that defensemen were accorded due
recognition with the Norris Trophy alone. That kind of thinking
changed in the '90s when goaltender Dominik Hasek copped
back-to-back Harts. A goalie hadn't been MVP since Jacques Plante
in '62.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, without question, should have won the Hart in 1990.
Messier was still a valuable part of the Oiler dynasty, but the
Bruins without Bourque never could have dreamed of making it to the
Stanley Cup finals (against Messier's Oilers) for a second time in
three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   To see the old defensemen-need-not-apply standard dropped now
makes it even harder to look at Bourque both Cupless and Hartless.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes going wild
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes, with Wayne Gretzky at the money wheel, say they're
committed to not cutting payroll for 2000-01, and it appears
they'll make room to pay Nikolai Khabibulin the $4 million-$5
million he wanted last summer before moving to the sidelines for
the full 1999-2000 season. Meanwhile, Mikael Renberg, obtained from
Philadelphia in the late-season swap for ex-Bruin Rick Tocchet,
told the Desert Dogs last week that he'll play the next five years
back home in Sweden (Lulea). There's a saving of $2 million right
there, although there are better ways to save dough than to lose a
28-year-old right winger who not long ago looked as if he could
score 60-80 points every season . . . By the way, don't be
surprised if Tocchet, 35, an unrestricted free agent, signs back on
with the Coyotes. Prior to agreeing to buy in as a partner, Gretzky
consulted regularly about the Desert Dogs with his old pal from LA
days . . . The Sabres all but cut ties with tough guy Rob Ray. They
also don't expect to bring back fellow pugilist Paul Kruse, the
30-year-old left winger who finished out the season in the minors.
Unless GM Darcy Regier goes shopping over the summer, the Sabres
will start the season without a resident ruffian . . . Petr Sykora,
last seen headed to Palookaville via a crushing, dirty check by
Derian Hatcher in Game 6 of the finals, recovered in time to take
the Devils' flight home from Dallas the next morning. Think anyone
on that flight had a bigger headache than Sykora? Linemate Patrik
Elias, as his pal Sykora was being wheeled off the ice on a
stretcher: ``Don't worry, we are going to win the Cup for you.'' .
. . Petr Bondra wants out of Washington and the Capitals want him
out of Washington. Trouble is, at $3.9 million, there won't be a
lot of takers. If he can't get it done with Adam Oates dishing him
the biscuit, then who is going to help him light it up? . . . NHL
insiders believe that Columbus still owes Colorado a favor for
picking up goalie prospect Marc Denis for only a second-round draft
pick. It could be that the Blue Jackets also agreed to take Rick
Tabaracci off the Avalanche's hands in Friday's expansion draft,
thus minimizing Colorado's risk of losing a serviceable forward or
defenseman . . . His game was gone when he came to the Bruins (37
games/15 points in '95-96), but it was nice to see ex-BC Eagle Joe
Mullen get voted into the Hall of Fame last week. Hockey dads keep
in mind: Mullen, who grew up in Hell's Kitchen, didn't pull on
skates until age 10. For his first ice time, he had to make his way
to New Jersey via bus or train. There were times, said Mullen, ``We
would be (accidentally) hitting commuters on the heads with our
sticks.'' Mullen will enter with Denis ``Spinarama'' Savard; Walter
L. Bush Jr., president of USA Hockey; and old pal Jim Matheson,
hockey columnist for the Edmonton Journal. Induction is Nov. 13.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And a cherry on top
</P>
<P>
   Pronger, by the way, picked up an extra $500,000 for his two
awards, a nice sweetener for his salary of $3.425 million. He's
headed into the final year of his contract, with a base salary of
$3.675 million, but look for Blues GM Larry Pleau to try to work
out a long-term extension over the summer. Pronger is one of the
few talents who could entice a club to forfeit five first-round
picks to sign him to a Group 2 free agent offer sheet . . . Shayne
Corson's scoring touch has faded, but a lot of clubs feel he still
has enough grit and soul to be an everyday asset. Montreal coach
Alain Vigneault said at the NHL Awards ceremonies Thursday night
that the Habs still want him back, but word around Montreal is that
they've offered only a three-year deal worth a total of $4.5
million (only $500,000 more than the one-year option they
declined). Corson is thinking more like $8 million over four years
. . . Remember this during Friday's expansion draft: In 1993, both
Florida and Anaheim figured the 28-year-old Czech goalie that
Buffalo left unprotected wasn't worth the time of day. And you know
the rest of Hasek's story . . . In a conference call last week, new
Rangers GM Glen Sather said this of ex-Bruin Stephane Quintal: ``I
think we are going to trade him.'' That said, the most likely
landing spot would be Montreal. Quintal was booted off the Rangers
for the final week of the regular season after being quoted in a
Montreal paper as saying that, on the whole, he would rather be
back with the Habs. The ``Q'' could make a nice fit behind the
Boston blue line, too, especially if the Bruins lose free agent Don
Sweeney. But the Rangers first would have to agree to pay at least
half of the $12 million he is due over the next three seasons . . .
No fewer than 45,000 Devil worshipers showed up in the Meadowlands
parking lot for New Jersey's victory party. Larry Brooks, hockey
columnist for the New York Post, now refers to 16W as the ``Exit of
Champions.'' Not quite the Canyon of Heroes, but it works.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Checking the Oil
</P>
<P>
   The position hasn't been finalized, but the next Oilers head
coach will be ex-Bruin Craig MacTavish, who was just 19 when he
first came to the Bay State as a University of Lowell pivot. Now
41, he'll succeed Kevin Lowe, who moved up to GM . . . Lou
Crawford, whose only shot at the big time came here with the Bruins
at the start of the '90s (26 games/3 points) has the top minor
league job for the Maple Leafs, coaching the AHL club in St.
John's, Newfoundland. He'll have ex-Whaler draft pick Kevin
McClelland, a four-time Cup winner with the Oilers, as his top aide
. . . Just three years ago, the three names in the mix as
prospective Bruins coaches were Pat Burns, Robbie Ftorek, and Jack
Parker. Of the three, who do you suppose is happiest this morning?
Ftorek, by the way, could see his name etched into the Cup, if the
Devils were to petition for it. ``I don't expect that,'' said
Ftorek, who was fired with eight games to go in the regular season.
``The only thing I'm working on now is my resume.'' . . . Roger
Neilson, still recovering from treatment for multiple myeloma, has
applications in to be head coach in Columbus, Minnesota, Calgary,
and Edmonton. Got to love the guy's guts and his passion . . . The
Colorado deal Bourque agreed to last week will add at least $6.5
million to his coffers, perhaps as much as $11.5 million if he also
plays in 2001-02. If the Avalanche don't want him back after paying
him $5.5 million next season, they'll essentially have to pay a
kill fee for '01-02, not unlike the $2 million the Canucks will
have to give Messier for negating the final two years of his deal,
worth $12 million . . . Ex-Bruin Wayne Cashman hasn't been asked
back to Philadelphia as an assistant. He wanted the No. 2 job in
Tampa Bay, but GM Rick Dudley also is considering John Tortorella
and Neilson . . . . . . In case you missed it, ex-Bruin Greg
Hawgood, a.k.a. Hawgie Hockey, signed again with Vancouver for a
bargain-basement $450,000. Left unprotected, he could be bound for
Columbus or Minnesota, which would give him eight cities on his NHL
resume . . . Meanwhile, the Canucks will hold an informal rookie
camp in Vancouver in July, and hope that prized rookies Daniel and
Henrik Sedin attend the freshman mixer . . . Pavel Bure picked up
the Rocket Richard Award as the league's leading goal scorer. To
his surprise, he also picked up a personalized photo, one of the
last things Rocket autographed before his death . . . Ex-Bruin Joe
Juneau flew from Quebec to Boston last week _ piloting a plane he
made himself. For those of us who never quite mastered the
one-timer, and also cringe at Toys ``R'' Us boxes that read, ``Some
assembly required,'' that makes Juneau some kind of wonderful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
