<SLUG> BC-BBA-SOXSIDE-CORDOVA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORDOVA IS JUST VISITING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marty Cordova was sitting on the top step of the Toronto dugout
and making small talk with teammate John Frascatore.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the place he thought he'd be when he signed as a free
agent with Boston six months ago. He was to be the outfield
insurance the Red Sox were desperately seeking.
</P>
<P>
   However, Marty Cordova isn't looking back. He's pleased to be
where he is. The Toronto Blue Jays are his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't play for the Sox anymore and whatever the situation
was over there is in the past. Now I play for the Blue Jays,''
Cordova said. ``My job now is to try and beat the Red Sox, the
Yankees, and all the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordova wasn't in the starting lineup Saturday when the Blue
Jays took the field against the Red Sox after a 41-minute rain
delay, but he has given Toronto everything it had hoped for when he
signed March 27 _ a day after he was released by the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   He filled in nicely when starting left fielder Shannon Stewart
went on the disabled list with a right hamstring pull. But with
Stewart back in the lineup, Cordova has been relegated to spot
duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played a lot when he was hurt, but since he's been back,
it's been mostly against lefties and we haven't seen a lot of
lefties lately,'' he said. ``I think I've only been in three games
the past two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordova played in 37 of Toronto's first 68 games. He was hitting
.277 with a pair of home runs and 11 runs batted in. He hit
successfully in 23 of 33 starts.
</P>
<P>
   His numbers compare favorably with those of the two men Cordova
had hoped to share playing time with in Boston. Darren Lewis was
hitting .301 with one home run and four RBIs, and Troy O'Leary was
batting .210 with five homers and 17 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Cordova, who was the 1995 American League Rookie of the Year
with Minnesota when he hit .277 (24 HRs, 84 RBIs), would love to be
in the lineup more often.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who's content to not be playing every day shouldn't
even be wearing a uniform,'' he said. ``I want to play every day
but you have three quality outfielders out there who deserve to be
there. I had my opportunity to play every day in Minnesota but I
let that get away from me so I have nobody to blame but myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever my role is here, if it's just playing against
lefties, then I'll do the best I can do. Whenever I'm out there
I'll always give it my best.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordova said he hasn't paid much attention to the trade rumors
that have Sammy Sosa coming to Boston for a host of minor leaguers
and possibly Trot Nixon, but doesn't see how any team couldn't want
the slugging Cubs outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, I really haven't given it a thought,''
he said, ``but I don't think anyone who'll hit 60 home runs and
drive in 100 runs can hurt. He can only help. I don't know what
their needs are over there, but I bet they'd love to have him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
