<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ILLEGAL RECRUITMENT CHARGE BEING STUDIED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Dodgers plan to ``aggressively
contest'' allegations that they illegally recruited and signed a
Venezuelan pitcher who is now a part of their minor-league system.
</P>
<P>
   The issue centers on whether the Dodgers signed Felix Arellan to
a legal contract before his 16th birthday in 1997, which would be a
violation of baseball's minimum-signing-age rule.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner's office informed the Dodgers that it will soon
begin an investigation of the matter, based on the content of a
letter it received last month claiming misconduct in the signing of
Arellan, now 19 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers senior vice president Derrick Hall declined to discuss
the specifics of the case Saturday, citing the upcoming
investigation, but said the team will protest every allegation made
in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``At no time did we ever claim to have a binding contract with
him before he was the age of 16,'' Hall said. ``In fact, that
shouldn't even be in question ... all the facts will come out soon
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation will be the third in 12 months regarding the
Dodgers' possible illegal contact with foreign players. Last June,
two Cuban players, Juan Carlos Diaz and Josue Perez, were declared
free agents after baseball officials determined that the Dodgers
illegally recruited the players and arranged for their defections.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, the commissioner's office ruled that the Dodgers
signed third baseman Adrian Beltre in the Dominican Republic before
his 16th birthday, although Hall quickly dismissed any connection
between the three incidents and stressed that the Arellan case did
not involve falsification of documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make it perfectly clear that this is in no way close
to the Beltre or the Cuban players situation,'' Hall said. ``In
this case there is no falsification of a birth certificate (as in
the Beltre case). That is not even in question.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will fight this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Arellan nor his agent, Gus Dominguez, who also
represents the two Cuban players, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Arellan, a left-hander, began his second season with the
Dodgers' rookie-league team in Great Falls, Mont., last week.
</P>
<P>
   Nice knowing you: The Dodgers traded backup catcher and former
UCLA standout Adam Melhuse to the Colorado Rockies on Saturday for
a player to be announced, less than 24 hours after they recalled
him from Triple-A Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   The move was necessitated by the return of Beltre, who started
Saturday for the first time since going on the disabled list May 29
with a strained right hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre singled and doubled in four at-bats, and the 28-year-old
Melhuse, who struck out Friday in his only at-bat with the Dodgers,
seemed to relish the chance to get a fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's definitely the way I see it,'' Melhuse said. ``I've
never been involved in a trade before, but I interpret that as (the
Rockies) really want me there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be a better opportunity than what I got
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowd favorite: The biggest cheer of the afternoon came in the
top of the seventh inning, when Mark McGwire hit a fastball from
Antonio Osuna halfway up the left-field bleachers to give the
Cardinals a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was McGwire's third home run against the Dodgers this year,
and he received a standing ovation from approximately
three-quarters of the Dodger Stadium fans. The home run was his
24th of the season and 546th of his career, putting McGwire two
short of Mike Schmidt for seventh on the all-time list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
