<HEADER>
A7407 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-CARDINALS     06-17 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-CARDINALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREW'S THREE-RUN HOMER DOWNS DREIFORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Over the course of nine innings, the outcome of a
single pitch doesn't typically alter the course of a baseball game
all that much.
</P>
<P>
   It took just one pitch, however, to dampen the spirits of Darren
Dreifort and his Los Angeles Dodgers teammates Saturday afternoon,
as J.D. Drew's three-run home run in the fifth inning made the
difference in St. Louis' 4-3 victory before 46,048 at Dodger
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dreif had great stuff, it was just that one pitch,'' said
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson, who also watched reliever Antonio
Osuna give up a home run to Mark McGwire in the seventh. ``The 0-2
pitch just got up and over the middle of the plate, and (Drew)
crushed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort (4-5) escaped a one-out, bases-loaded jam in the fourth
inning and had seven strikeouts going into the fifth, but the
right-hander's luck finally ran out.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Renteria led off with a single, and Dreifort hit Jim
Edmonds with the next pitch. He came back to strike out McGwire and
Ray Lankford, but Drew drove an errant fastball over the fence in
right-center field for a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right pitch, bad location,'' Dreifort said. ``If they don't
give Edmonds first base on a ball that didn't hit him - it missed
him by 10 inches - we're still playing right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort ended the fifth with his 100th pitch, and was pulled
for a pinch hitter in the bottom half of the inning to end another
frustrating outing. Dreifort, who struck out nine and allowed eight
hits and two walks, has won just one of his past six starts, but
that includes two no-decisions in which he threw well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for Philadelphia and the Angels,'' Dreifort said,
referring to games in which he allowed a combined 13 runs in seven
innings, ``I think I've done pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew's home run wouldn't have meant nearly as much had the
Dodgers capitalized on two excellent scoring chances earlier in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hollandsworth singled to lead off the first and advanced to
third on Gary Sheffield's one-out single, but Shawn Green flied to
left and Eric Karros struck out to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Beltre, activated from the disabled list before the game,
doubled to lead off the second and reached third on Paul LoDuca's
sharp single to left, but St. Louis pitcher Andy Benes retired the
bottom two hitters in the Dodgers' order, Alex Cora and Dreifort,
and got Hollandsworth to ground out.
</P>
<P>
   Benes (7-3) struck out 10, walked two and gave up seven hits in
six innings, and stumbled only once, when Gary Sheffield hit a
two-run, two-out home run to left field.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers cut the deficit to one run in the eighth off
reliever Matt Morris, when Sheffield doubled into the right-field
corner, took third base when Eric Davis misplayed the ball, and
scored on Green's fielder's choice grounder to second.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis closer Dave Veres retired the side in order in the
ninth to earn his second save in two games and his 13th overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a team (St. Louis) that you have to score on,''
Johnson said. ``Four runs against them is a good pitching job.
We're a little sluggish with the bats, but you have to tip your hat
to them because they made some good pitches when they had to.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort said the team isn't sluggish, just worn down from a
trying month full of injuries, roster moves and the fallout of the
Wrigley Field incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like a hockey team with five guys in the penalty box and
the other team has a power play every time,'' Dreifort said. ``We
still have a hell of a team, no matter who is out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
