<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7430 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-KC-MURDERS-3TAKES-KAN     06-17 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-MURDERS-3TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOSE LINKED TO JOHN ROBINSON SHARE ONE CHARACTERISTIC: ALL WERE
FEMALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Their names may forever appear on the same
page from one of the ugliest chapters on area crime. But for now,
the 11 dead and missing persons linked to John E. Robinson Sr.
share just one obvious characteristic.
</P>
<P>
   All were female.
</P>
<P>
   The first to vanish, Paula Godfrey, 19, was a hometown skater
with a confident, competitive way on the ice and a bright future 16
years ago. And the last to die, Suzette Trouten, 27, was lured away
this spring from her restaurant job in Michigan by someone
promising to pay her well as a nurse.
</P>
<P>
   In between are middle-age women, a disabled teen-ager, a baby
and her 19-year-old mother, a college student born in Poland and
two victims still unidentified. A few were local; several were from
out of town, apparently drawn to Robinson because of loneliness or
a quest for adventure or sex.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the women who have crossed paths with this married,
middle-age father of four have made the headlines. Some not listed
among the missing or dead appear from court records to have been
prostitutes. Others got involved intimately, but escaped his orbit.
Still others shunned his propositions completely.
</P>
<P>
   From all that, does another pattern emerge?
</P>
<P>
   Investigators won't yet discuss what lies within a high stack of
legal papers on Robinson, who has spent much of his life
flimflamming people and now is jailed on five counts of murder and
linked with six other missing persons. But Johnson County, Kan.,
District Attorney Paul Morrison hinted at a ``developing financial
angle'' in the case.
</P>
<P>
   None of the missing or dead women appears to have been rich.
Most, in fact, were young and struggling, far separated from their
families. Yet some had access to checks _ Social Security or
alimony payments, for example _ or were allegedly hired to help
Robinson's companies make money.
</P>
<P>
   Women and money. Records suggest that Robinson has long obsessed
on both, exploiting one to get the other.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his alleged victims wanted to see the world.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly J. Bonner, the oldest, talked of going overseas in a new
line of work after leaving her library job at the Western Missouri
Correctional Center in Cameron, Mo. Robinson had served time there
between 1991 and 1993 on theft and fraud convictions.
</P>
<P>
   A friend, Eugenia Reece, recalled Bonner's departure from
Cameron:
</P>
<P>
   ``She had tears running down her cheeks. She was such a darling
woman, and I don't think she wanted to leave her friends. But she
was excited about this job.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Bonner's name would appear on papers filed in Missouri as
president for Hydro-Gro Inc., ostensibly a horticultural firm that
appears much like defunct Kansas firms Robinson created in the
1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson and Bonner may have first met each other decades
earlier in Kansas City, when both worked at Mobil Oil Corp.'s
credit offices on West 10th Street. Robinson was a systems analyst
there in 1970; Bonner was a supervisor in another division.
</P>
<P>
   ``A sharp gal,'' said Jim Chappell, a former Mobil employee.
``She was very businesslike and hard-working, but very friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's brief tenure at Mobil ended when he was charged with
stealing more than $300 in postage from the company. Bonner _ then
known as Beverly Lake _ continued to work for Mobil until 1981.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1990s she was married to William Bonner, an amiable
physician on good terms with most of the inmates he treated. He
recently recalled the marriage that ended in 1994 with some
bitterness, saying she had extramarital affairs, possibly even with
Robinson in the prison library.
</P>
<P>
   She dropped from sight in 1994, at 49.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, investigators found her body in a barrel in
a Raymore storage locker she rented years ago. The locker, now
linked to Robinson, also had two other barrels containing as yet
unidentified bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The circumstances of her disappearance parallel those of other
alleged victims: women searching for direction, landing jobs that
promised travel and clinging to false hopes of fresh starts.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Clampitt, 27, a one-time drug user seeking to
rehabilitate, moved in 1987 from Wichita Falls, Texas, to Overland
Park, Kan. Her brother, Robert Bales, said her hopes were lifted
when she found work at Equi-II, a management consulting firm
created by Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It promised a great job, a lot of traveling and a new
wardrobe,'' Bales said.
</P>
<P>
   She remains missing.
</P>
<P>
   More than a decade later, Suzette Trouten moved to Lenexa, Kan.,
from Michigan after meeting Robinson on the Internet, investigators
said. She told relatives she had found a $65,000-a-year job,
complete with worldwide travel, taking care of a man's aging
father.
</P>
<P>
   Her body was found in a barrel on Linn County farm property
owned by Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the women mentioned in the Robinson investigation, the
one whose disappearance is least understood may be Godfrey's, whose
family reported her missing in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's probation officer, Steve Haymes, who had become
suspicious of his activities, noted in a report: ``Robinson had
allegedly hired her to be a sales representative. Overland Park
Police Department later received a letter from this girl stating
that she was thankful for John Robinson's help and that she was
o.k.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, old friends say she was hardly the vulnerable type.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a happy girl, very outgoing. She wasn't gullible,''
said Jan Kunzle. ``I think she would have realized it if she was in
trouble. She seemed book smart; street smart, too.''
</P>
<P>
   (More)
</P>
<P>
   Izabela Lewicka also was book smart. Before she vanished last
fall at age 21, her parents back home in Indiana told neighbors of
her supposed trips to California and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she was working in Johnson County for Robinson's trade
magazine venture _ Manufactured//Modular Home Living, a publication
related to the mobile home industry.
</P>
<P>
   Within months of leaving home, she applied for a marriage
license in Johnson County with a man listed on the document as
``John Anthony Robinson,'' whose birth date matched John E.
Robinson's.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1998, she was frequently with Robinson as the two
cobbled the magazine together. She handled the advertising and he
produced the copy, said Pamela Guthrie, a free-lance graphic artist
who designed one of the issues.
</P>
<P>
   The artist, who last week spoke with investigators, said Lewicka
referred to Robinson as her uncle.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he'd have his hands all over her,'' she said. ``Hands on
her back, across her shoulder, resting near her breast. I thought,
`That's no uncle.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie said her dealings with Robinson and Lewicka lasted only
a couple of months. The bill for her free-lance work _ $1,800 _
never was paid, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Lewicka's body, discovered in another barrel in Linn County, was
identified last week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It happens, experts say. A woman yearning to find her direction
and purpose in life falls prey to a controlling, often violent man
_ sometimes a virtual stranger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is a system of blind control, and it can happen
quickly,'' said Palle M. Relinger, executive director of the
Metropolitan Organization to Counter Sexual Assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``For someone who may be at a low point in life, some extra
attention and the promise of something better can be hard to
resist. Sex offenders typically are looking for that
vulnerability.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura L. Douglas, 34, said she first met Robinson at the Belton
mobile home park where both lived in the mid-1990s. She was a
single mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``To begin with, he was very polite. Nice. Minded his manners,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   But after she went to work for Robinson painting a mobile home,
``he was very handsy. When he wasn't attempting to touch, he was
making references.'' She thought Robinson knew she was coming out
of an unhappy relationship, and his repeated passes prompted her to
stop working for him.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas said Robinson tried to persuade her to move to Florida
with him to remodel mobile homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was going to divorce his wife and the whole nine
yards,'' she said. ``His kids were down there, and it would be away
from his wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Her memories of constant harassment echo those of other women in
the Olathe mobile home community where Robinson was living when he
was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a dirty old man,'' Douglas said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's past is spotted with questions _ and some accusations
_ of sexual impropriety.
</P>
<P>
   While running a hydroponic gardening enterprise under the
Hydro-Gro name in the late 1970s, he surprised some investors in
his greenhouses near Hutchinson, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   A woman in her early 30s ``appeared like magic one day,'' an
investor who insisted on anonymity said last week. ``He told us he
(was) saving her for some friends of his.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, she actually lived there in one of the greenhouses!
She loved living there. She'd pick the tomatoes and care for the
plants, but I told him ... she had to leave or I'd be gone from the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next time we visited, she was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1980s, after Robinson was convicted of embezzling
from Guy's Foods Inc. in Liberty, Haymes and the FBI moved toward a
theory that ``Robinson is involved in prostitution,'' according to
Clay County court records.
</P>
<P>
   Haymes, the probation officer, also was investigating reports
that a young mother, Lisa Stasi, had disappeared from Overland Park
with her infant daughter, Tiffany.
</P>
<P>
   Stasi _ described in a police report as ``unstable, lonely and
gullible'' _ had earlier met with a man claiming to represent a
charity organization. The group offered to provide her with
housing, job training and a high school equivalency degree.
</P>
<P>
   Stasi and her baby have not been found. Some authorities at the
time suspected the infant may have been sold on the black market.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of that investigation, FBI agent Tom Lavin told
Haymes that a Kansas City, Kan., woman _ not Stasi _ ``was asked by
Robinson to prostitute for him and//or run some girls who are
prostituting for him,'' according to notes Haymes compiled at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to revoke Robinson's probation, authorities called yet
another young woman to testify that he made her ``dress entirely in
black'' and to wear a blindfold for a sadomasochistic sexual
encounter she said she had with a Robinson friend. She also said he
had sexually assaulted her with a handgun.
</P>
<P>
   When Robinson took the stand, Clay County assistant prosecutor
Michael Murphy asked him point-blank if he was involved in ``any
kind of prostitution or escort service.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, sir,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   (More)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
