<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7432 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-KC-MURDERS-3rdtake-KA     06-17 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-MURDERS-3rd </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOSE LINKED TO JOHN ROBINSON SHARE ONE CHARACTERISTIC: ALL WERE
FEMALE 
</HEADLINE>
 take-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shortly after Stasi disappeared, one of the women linked to
Robinson spread a story designed to find its way to Overland Park
police. The woman said that she had recently seen Stasi and that
she was well and avoiding her family.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed by federal agents and police, the woman confessed
that she made up the story at Robinson's behest because he had nude
photographs of her, court records say.
</P>
<P>
   Accusations of extortion would again be leveled against Robinson
15 years later.
</P>
<P>
   A Texas-licensed psychologist who met Robinson this spring for a
sadomasochistic encounter told police that Robinson had tried to
photograph her, then threatened to expose her to Texas authorities,
after he brutalized her beyond terms of their agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The woman stepped forward anyway, and police charged Robinson
with sexual battery, just weeks before investigators uncovered
bodies on his property.
</P>
<P>
   At least two women from other states apparently knew him through
his ``Slavemaster'' identity on the Internet. One lost a $17,000
investment in one of Robinson's businesses; the other told police
another episode of too-rough sex.
</P>
<P>
   Whether by Internet or a personal ad in a newspaper, Sheila Dale
Faith was also drawn to strangers offering romance and happiness.
Especially ``John.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Guerrero, Faith's neighbor in Pueblo, Colo., said Faith in
1994 described her new friend as a ``dream man.'' Faith, seeking
companionship, started using personal ads after her husband died in
1991. This new prospect, she told another acquaintance, was
``really nice. ... We're going to go to Kansas.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Faith and her teen-age daughter Debbie, who used a
wheelchair, vanished from the neighborhood. Their mail _ including
Debbie's disability checks, according to Guerrero _ was forwarded
to a post office box in Olathe.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is Robinson's wife, Nancy, who married him in
1964 and stayed through arrest after arrest for his white-collar
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   She apparently lost their comfortable home with its riding
stable and lake when he was sent to prison for theft in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   In a Kansas corrections evaluation of Robinson in 1990, a
psychologist referred to Robinson calling Nancy ``loving and loyal
... (she) supported him through this whole ordeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's former defense attorney, Bruce Houdek, recently
concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nancy's a really nice lady,'' he said shortly after John
Robinson's arrest this month. ``She loved John and stuck by him
forever.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, her testimony on her husband's behalf during the
probation revocation hearing was thin on personal details, but it
revealed her to be a thorough and diligent record-keeper.
</P>
<P>
   The husband she described on the stand paid close attention to
his business and was careful to make time for his children's music
and sports programs in the Blue Valley School District.
</P>
<P>
   His family echoed that sentiment recently, when the Robinsons
issued a statement expressing sympathy for the victims' families
and stressing:
</P>
<P>
   ``The John Robinson we know has always been a loving and caring
husband and father, the type of parent who has never missed a
sporting event, a school function, or missed an opportunity to be
there with his family.''
</P>
<P>
   At least once, however, their marriage teetered, as Nancy filed
for divorce in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   She never followed through on the action. But according to Scott
Davis, a former neighbor in the Stanley community of Overland Park,
she spent many tearful hours discussing her marriage with Davis'
mother, who lived across the street from the Robinsons.
</P>
<P>
   The troubles resulted, Davis recalled, from an affair John
Robinson was having.
</P>
<P>
   Other friends Nancy made later while managing large mobile home
communities in Belton and Olathe think she was unaware of the
darker elements of her husband's life. ``I don't think she had a
clue,'' one said.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after authorities arrested her spouse this month,
police apparently gave her information about the evidence they had
gathered.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was devastated,'' said Alberta Merritt, who helped Nancy
Robinson run the office at the Santa Barbara Estates mobile
community. ``She just didn't know what to do. ... I felt sorry for
her, and I still do. And I think she should be left alone.''
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
