<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPENNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELS HAPPY HE'S GOT `HALF A CHANCE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ It looked easy for the Big Easy.
</P>
<P>
   Two-time U.S. Open champion Ernie Els, who earned his nickname
with one of the most-fluid swings in golf, negotiated wind-buffeted
Pebble Beach Golf Links in 3-under-par 68 Saturday during a third
round that sent most scores soaring.
</P>
<P>
   His secret?
</P>
<P>
   ``I made some good saves,'' said Els, who finished with four
birdies and an eagle to move to 2 over par for the tournament and
into third place, within 10 strokes of front-running Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably one of the best rounds I've played in major
golf, considering the weather conditions,'' Els said.
</P>
<P>
   What does it mean for the big South African, who won Open titles
in 1994 at Oakmont and '97 at Congressional?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got half a chance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the field would like those odds.
</P>
<P>
   Area update: Seven players with area ties failed to make the cut
of 7-over-par 149, including 1995 U.S. Open champion Corey Pavin,
the one-time UCLA All-American who finished 150 after bogeying the
final hole of his second round.
</P>
<P>
   Former USC player Brian Henninger also missed by a stroke at
150, a stroke better than another ex-Trojan, Craig Stadler.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-UCLA players Duffy Waldorf of Valencia and Brandt Jobe also
finished 151. Agoura's Steve Pate, another former Bruin, finished
154, as did David Berganio Jr. of Sylmar.
</P>
<P>
   Former Cal State Northridge player Jon Levitt wound up 157.
</P>
<P>
   Television ratings: Bobby Clampett, the CBS golf commentator who
was born in nearby Monterey and got in the tournament as a
qualifier, made the cut with a 36-hole score of 145. Curtis
Strange, who won back-to-back U.S. Open titles in 1988 and 1989 and
now serves as golf commentator for ABC, missed the cut at 162.
</P>
<P>
   Golden oldie: Four-time champion Jack Nicklaus, playing in a
record 44th consecutive U.S. Open, missed the cut at 155 but not
before showing his old form to Tom Watson during the fog-delayed
first round.
</P>
<P>
   When a Nicklaus tee shot disappeared into the mist shortly
before play was suspended Thursday, Watson, waiting on the tee in
backed-up playing conditions, told the 60-year-old Golden Bear,
``You hit it out of sight.''
</P>
<P>
   Mixed emotions: David Gossett, who won the 1999 U.S. Amateur
championship at Pebble Beach shortly after completing his freshman
season at Texas, was paired with Nicklaus for the first two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a bittersweet experience,'' said Gossett, who
finished 13-over-par 155 and failed to make the cut. But he
tremendously enjoyed being in the same group with the greatest
golfer in the history of the game - a man he called ``Mr.
Nicklaus'' for two days until he Golden Bear convinced him to
``call me Jack.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To see him getting those standing ovations was really
something special,'' Gossett said. ``He's a great man. He does it
with class and he's a fine competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   What lessons did Gossett learn?
</P>
<P>
   ``Patience and he's extremely competitive. I just learned that
he plays really smart golf, and he's really systematic the way he
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   So that's why: Qualifier Jeff Coston, the golf academy operator
who faded to 77 after a brief stay on the leaderboard with a
first-round 70: ``I tried too hard, took too long and thought too
much. Maybe I needed a lobotomy.''
</P>
<P>
   Quotable: Loren Roberts on his fog-suspended first-round score
of 68, accomplished Thursday and Friday, which enabled him to make
the cut despite shooting 78 in the second round: ``Sure I'm happy
with it, especially since it took 24 hours to play it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
