<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA OFFICIALS NOT CHARITABLE TO KOBE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles is the sort of place where you can
share a common wall with someone for years and never see the
person, much less strike up a single conversation. So we were a
little suspicious when we heard that Kobe Bryant and Reggie Miller
kept running into each other at a gym over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind there are a hundred places to work out in the
narcissistic city. Miller is so sneaky, we're not surprised he got
Bryant to divulge some of his trade secrets. In their summer
one-on-one sessions, Indiana's star guard prevailed upon Bryant to
show him a couple of flashy ball-handling moves guaranteed to help
him create off the dribble.
</P>
<P>
   We're guessing the former UCLA standout worked Bryant the same
way he does game officials, leaning on him until he plain wore him
down.
</P>
<P>
   What the 34-year-old Miller did for Bryant in return is not real
clear. He certainly didn't divulge any of his secrets for drawing
fouls like a magnet does nails.
</P>
<P>
   For all his lip-flapping and flopping in the NBA Finals, Miller
deserves an Emmy nomination for Best Actor in a drama series.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two games of the ongoing best-of-seven championship
series (Game 6 is Monday at Staples Center), Miller wended and
whined his way to the free-throw line more times than anybody save
for Shaquille O'Neal. While in the act of shooting, he finagled
eight fouls out of seven Los Angeles Lakers - he victimized Derek
Fisher twice - and converted 15 of 16 free throws. He also made
three free throws off technical fouls.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, meanwhile, didn't try a single free throw in Games 4 or
5. Incredibly, inexplicably, he has been sent to the line only once
in the series, in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the sore left ankle that sidelined Bryant for most of
Game 2 and all of Game 3 has limited his aggressiveness in the past
two games. But drawing zero fouls in 84 minutes while putting up 47
shots? That's every bit as astonishing as was his acrobatic putback
of Brian Shaw's miss for the winning basket in overtime of Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, it was hard to believe what you were seeing.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, 21, might have launched a thousand comparisons to
Michael Jordan with his eight-point performance in the five-minute
overtime period in Game 4. But it would appear the league's finest
officials are less generous than the media when it comes to
granting him superstar status (and the auspicious calls that go
along with it).
</P>
<P>
   All we know is that during the regular season, the slash-happy
Bryant averaged 6.1 free throws a game, which was fewer than Vince
Carter (6.7) or Grant Hill (8.2), the latter of whom Bryant could
end up replacing on the Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's Game 5 blowout loss, Miller appeared to graze
Bryant's arm as the fourth-year guard was putting up one of his six
errant shots of the first half. From our seat behind the basket,
you could hear the thwack.
</P>
<P>
   The next sound we heard wasn't an official's whistle, but
Bryant's plaintive ``Hey!'' in response to nothing being called.
Bryant would go on to pick up his second and third fouls in the
span of 12 seconds late in the second quarter. He would finish the
game with five.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two games, Bryant has been whistled for nine fouls
to Miller's two. If that doesn't make you go hmmmm, then you're
obviously a Hoosier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's frustrating for him,'' Shaw said of Bryant,
``because he'll be close to somebody on their team, breathe on them
and they call the foul on him. And then he won't get the same call
on the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   What more does Bryant have to do to earn his due? He was named
to the league's first-team defensive unit this season. He has
worked hard to become a fundamentally solid defender, to dull down
some of his flashy offensive game, to prove he isn't a
one-dimensional wonder.
</P>
<P>
   It has to freeze him - either that or fry him - just a little to
be under the hottest spotlight of his young career and be picking
up fouls like lint and getting precious little chance to prop up
the Lakers' foul free-throw shooting (Bryant converted 82 percent
of his attempts from the line during the regular season).
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Bryant should look at his not receiving much charity as a
back- handed compliment. Just as O'Neal is so much taller and wider
and stronger than everybody he is made to suffer more non-calls on
the offensive end, so, perhaps, is Bryant's talent viewed as so
ridiculously large as to put opponents at a decided disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   The danger, of course, is that in trying to even the playing
field the officials are making a mockery of it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 2246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
