<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7445 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-WHITESOX-NY     06-17 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-WHITESOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE SOX BEAT YANKEES, 10-9 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The day was headed for certain disaster. The Yankees
were self-destructing in torturous fashion against the best team in
the American League. They trailed the Chicago White Sox, 8-0, the
air was as stagnant as their bats, and it was only the bottom of
the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until after a 57-minute rain delay that day turned
into night, and the Yankees, led by Bernie Williams, mitigated
disaster and found a silver lining in a bizarre marathon game with
emotions running from personal horror to team consolation.
</P>
<P>
   The early meltdowns of the rookie starter Jake Westbrook and
reliever Jason Grimsley, the miscue of shortstop Derek Jeter and
the continuing horror of Chuck Knoblauch were nearly rendered
irrelevant amid a dramatic late-inning comeback, thanks mostly to
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   But while Williams cranked out a season-high seven runs batted
in, his effort and his teammates' redoubled effort after the rain
delay were not enough to keep the Yankees from losing to Chicago,
10-9. It was their third consecutive loss.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who had been just 5 for 20 on the six-game homestand,
came alive Saturday. After his walk in the first inning, he went 4
for 4.
</P>
<P>
   He hit a double for two runs in the third inning, another double
that scored three in the sixth inning, and then, with the Yankees
trailing by 10-7 with two outs in the eighth inning, blasted a
two-run home run, bringing the Yankees within one run.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have a great day and not win the game doesn't mean that
much,'' Williams said. ``We keep fighting. We just keep coming up
short.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was hope and exultation in the dugout once again
late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just feel we can never stop bleeding, and that was the bad
part,'' Manager Joe Torre said. ``I'm pleased with the way we're
able to come back against people.''
</P>
<P>
   Westbrook, a 22-year-old right-hander touted within the Yankees
organization for being poised and promising, took his place in the
steamy fishbowl for his first major league start.
</P>
<P>
   It was his first trip to Yankee Stadium, and no sooner did he
take the mound than he started to melt. First, waterfalls of sweat
fell from under his new cap. Then the hits poured from the White
Sox bats.
</P>
<P>
   Westbrook's initiation was a terrible unraveling in one and
two-thirds innings that took nearly an hour. He gave up six runs
and seven hits, fulfilling none of the expectations the Yankees had
for him as the temporary replacement for the injured Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Torre just wanted Westbrook to get the Yankees to the middle of
the game. Instead, Torre had to empty the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   After Westbrook burned a fastball born of pure adrenaline past
Ray Durham on his first pitch, he struggled with his control. He
got out of a jam in the first inning, allowing just one run on two
hits and a walk, but he had thrown 20 pitches already.
</P>
<P>
   The next inning finished him off. He gave up a leadoff double to
Carlos Lee, Greg Norton hit a sacrifice fly to center field, and
Shane Spencer, playing for Paul O'Neill in right field, trapped a
short fly by Brook Fordyce. Durham followed with a shot up the
middle past Westbrook. Frank Thomas singled and then Magglio
Ordonez belted a fastball for a three-run home run to left-center
field.
</P>
<P>
   Westbrook finished his debut with a walk to Paul Konerko, and
Jason Grimsley came on to relieve him. The inning could have been
over when Chris Singleton hit a soft liner to Jeter, but he bobbled
it for an error before Lee struck out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley's troubles began in the third when he gave up a leadoff
single to Norton and followed with a walk to Fordyce. A single and
two sacrifice flies later, the Yankees trailed, 8-0.
</P>
<P>
   By the fourth inning, they trailed by 9-3, which was when things
got strange again.
</P>
<P>
   Although Knoblauch returned to the lineup after his ignominious
three-error game on Thursday, he had no ground ball chances Friday
night. On his first chance Saturday, he showed that nothing had
changed, that the demons had only been sleeping. He collected a
grounder by Norton, cocked his arm and sent the ball fluttering
into the seats along the first-base line.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch had been crucial in the Yankees' third-inning rally,
hitting a single off an 0-2 pitch from Cal Eldred and coming around
to score on Williams' double.
</P>
<P>
   But the defensive woes would not go away. He admitted Friday
night that his problem _ mental, not physical _ was not solved by
just returning to the ballpark. Saturday, though, he was also
affected physically, playing with his left ankle taped after
injuring it on a slide Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   After the rain delay, Knoblauch was better, like his teammates.
He turned an easy ground ball into an out in the seventh, which
seemed to settle him down.
</P>
<P>
   And after the delay, Eldred returned and got out of the fifth,
allowing just a single to Williams. Eldred started promisingly in
the sixth as well, with two quick outs. But Knoblauch drew a walk,
Jeter followed with a single and O'Neill walked to load the bases.
In came Kelly Wunsch, a sidearming left-hander, and Williams
promptly doubled to the center-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's second baseman, Durham, threw the relay wide to the
catcher Fordyce, allowing O'Neill to score. Tino Martinez cracked a
single to short center off Wunsch, to bring the Yankees within
10-7.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' home run made it 10-9, but the comeback ended there. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
