r s BC-BKN-MODESTI-LADN     06-17 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS ARE BRAND X, NOT BRAND NAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Indiana crowd never did get the hang of ``Beat
L.A.!''
</P>
<P>
   In other places, the chant is delivered in the same insistent
left-right-left cadence as ``U-S-A!'' or ``We're Number 1!'' But
with the Conseco Fieldhouse public-address announcer setting a bad
example - yes, in Indiana, the PA guy is an unabashed cheerleader -
it came out in syncopated rhythm as ``Beat ... Uh-Laaay! Beat ...
Uh-Laaay! Beat ... Uh- Laaay!''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Indiana Pacers fans never had much practice over the
years, Games 3, 4 and 5 of these NBA Finals marking the first time
they ever considered the possibility of their team beating the
Lakers with a trophy at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever - it's not how they say it, it's the thought that
counts, and in a low-glamour NBA city like Indianapolis, the plea
is heartfelt.
</P>
<P>
   Why do they hate us? We're friendly folk here in Los Angeles, as
long as you don't expect us to actually say good morning when
passing on the sidewalk. We respect the right of way of the
pedestrian as long as he gets a move-on. We work hard while
awaiting our cinematic breaks.
</P>
<P>
   The animosity is easier to understand if you look at it from the
point of view of frustrated Indianans.
</P>
<P>
   Since franchise player Reggie Miller's rookie season in 1987-88,
the Pacers have qualified for the playoffs 10 times and advanced to
the Eastern Conference finals five times, yet had to wait until now
to play for the NBA championship. In the same stretch, the Lakers
have been able to win the 1988 title at the climax of one dynasty,
wave goodbye to all of those stars and endure back-to-back sub-.500
seasons in 1992-93 and 1993-94, then rebuild quickly enough with
fresh stars to stand today one victory away from a new title and a
view to a new dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   Before these Lakers of Shaquille O'Neal, Kobe Bryant and Phil
Jackson, the only teams to pull off such quick nosedives and
recoveries had been the Lakers of Magic Johnson and the Boston
Celtics of Larry Bird.
</P>
<P>
   Such things seem to happen for the glamour franchises, not for
the Pacers and, say, the Milwaukee Bucks.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the result of an NBA conspiracy. It is the result of a
force that will be no easier for franchises like the Pacers to
overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``They start with a little bit of an advantage because it's Los
Angeles, because it's the Lakers, because of their history,'' David
Kahn, the Pacers' general manager, said Friday before Indiana's
120-87 victory cut the Lakers' series lead to 3-2 and sent
everybody back west for Game 6 Monday night. ``I think the Lakers'
brand name still means something, much like the Bulls' still does,
and the Celtics'.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``advantage'' pertains to the ability of those teams to
attract players who have the freedom to choose their homes. Kahn
wasn't complaining, merely stating a fact and praising Lakers
executive vice president Jerry West and general manager Mitch
Kupchak for taking advantage of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, being in Los Angeles has not been much help to the
Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (West and Kupchak) deserve an immense amount of credit
for two things. One is that when they had that moment when they got
under the cap, they managed to attract the guy who obviously will
be !ital!the!off! star player in our league for the next six or
seven years,'' Kahn said of the 1996 free-agent signing of O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``On top of that, several teams passed on Kobe Bryant,'' Kahn
said, referring to Bryant lasting until the 13th pick in the 1996
draft. ``That was their mistake. But it was certainly Jerry West's
wise decision-making in making that pick.''
</P>
<P>
   The view from Indiana is tinged with envy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the Lakers) look a little bit to me like what Chicago
was in the decade of the '90s,'' said Kahn, the guiding force
behind the construction of Conseco Fieldhouse, the delightfully
retro arena that will become the Pacers' best built-in recruiting
tool. ``With those two huge cornerstones in place, they're just
adding in those other components.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not to say that's not hard to do. But when you have
those two monsters there, I think it's easier than trying to build
a whole team. You're basically just sprinkling in specialists.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Harper, signed in October, might be the sprinkle that put
the Lakers over the top this season. Rick Fox, signed in 1997, is a
subtler example of the L.A. advantage. Fox passed up larger offers
from other teams to sign one-year contracts in 1997 and 1998 and a
relatively modest six-year, $24-million contract last summer. The
attraction: Fox knew playing with O'Neal gave him a shot at a title
and - though he says Hollywood wasn't a major factor - he's an
aspiring actor as well as husband of singer-actress Vanessa
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where else to play?'' Kahn said. ``They (the Lakers) took
advantage of it, though. They should be commended; seeing that
situation, they used it to their best advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The golden history, the media exposure, the proximity to
Hollywood - wouldn't you be jealous of the Lakers if you didn't
live here? The ability of West and Kupchak to turn that glamour
into baskets - wouldn't you hate the way they keep finding ways?
</P>
<P>
   ``They sure did make themselves championship caliber (again) in
a pretty short period of time,'' Kahn said. ``They've done an
incredible job. And not just for the present, but if you look
(ahead) six or seven years, they'll be awfully hard to beat year in
and year out. They are poised to be, unfortunately for the rest of
us, the team of the next decade. The rest of us will have to be
scrambling to figure out ways to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   However it's said, ``Beat L.A.!'' could be everybody's goal for
years to come.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 2329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
