<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK OF A CHAMPION? LAKERS AREN'T THERE YET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Phil Jackson sits on a familiar platform, before a
familiar audience, at a very familiar event, elaborating on
well-worn topic: The outstanding achievements of his team. But
suddenly the discussion is anything but familiar.
</P>
<P>
   A championship-caliber team, losing its focus? Again? Failing to
close out a series? Again? Getting routed? Again?
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Bulls never did this, did they?
</P>
<P>
   Jackson certainly lived through a few setbacks while guiding the
Bulls and Michael Jordan to six NBA championships, but never did
they push the limits of his understanding as the Los Angeles Lakers
have in his first year.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's 33-point loss to the Indiana Pacers ranked as the worst
this season for the Lakers - and it came in Game 5 of the Finals.
Of course,it will mean nothing if the Lakers win Monday, or even
Wednesday, to claim the championship. But the fact remains: they
are muddying up their own fantastic season with these frequent
blunders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to think of a team that has championship quality
in it that loses by 33 points,'' Jackson said. ``We have to prove
something to ourselves ... in this regard.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they have something to prove to historians as well. Their
67-win season instantly pushed the Lakers into elite company, the
third-best season in NBA history. Their 19-game winning streak also
ranked third all-time, and they were the third team ever to post
three double-digit winning streaks.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they follow all that with a championship, the Lakers
have lost the look of a dominant team. Consider how they stack up
against nine other teams that won 65 or more games and the
championship:
</P>
<P>
   ---The Lakers are 3-6 in elimination games (0-5 on the road). No
other 65-win team lost more than two closeout games, and the
previous worst elimination-game record was 3-2, by the 1967
Philadelphia 76ers.
</P>
<P>
   ---The Lakers are 14-8 in the playoffs, the worst record among
the 65-win teams (the previous worst was the 1992 Bulls, at 15-7).
</P>
<P>
   ---The Lakers are the only the second 65-win team not to sweep a
playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   ---Among the 65-win teams, the Lakers are the only one that
needed seven games to win the conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ---And the Lakers are more likely than any prior 65-win team to
get blown out in a playoff game. They are 8-5 in games decided by
10 or more points; no other 65-win team lost more than three games
by double digits.
</P>
<P>
   And as Jackson noted, champions aren't supposed to lose by 33
points in the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We laid an egg,'' Ron Harper said. ``We've laid the egg
before. This is nothing new to us. This is our third egg in the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, the Lakers always rebound quickly, which is
how they've survived to this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn,'' Glen Rice said. ``When you get your butts kicked,
you learn. You really go out and you try and stay focused on what
happened in that game. And you try and stop that for the next game.
And we've been doing a pretty good job of bouncing back.''
</P>
<P>
   So after losing by 13 points to Sacramento, the Lakers routed
the Kings by 27 points in Game 5 to close out the first round. And
after losing by 19 points to Phoenix, the Lakers held the Suns to
65 points in Game 5 to finish the second round. A 29-point loss to
Portland was followed by two victories on the Trail Blazers' home
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much that we're not capable of winning these
games,'' Rick Fox said. ``It's that we abandon, almost, the
persistence in execution that we have to have to work our way back.
We did it in Game 3 and 4 in the Portland series after being down.
But as you saw again (Friday), being down 15, 16, 17 points, we
took a lot of jumpshots, we tried to get it all back with the
15-point shot, which doesn't exist in the game of basketball. And
when you're looking to get it back as quickly as we did,and not
work, you continue to dig yourself a hole.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers would like to think that at least some of the trend
has to do with tough opponents playing well on their home court.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Pacers) were up against the wall,'' Fox said, ``and
they've been a good team, especially on their home floor. You have
to think that they play at least one half of great basketball,
which they did. We played one half of terrible basketball, which
there's no excuse for. Yet it's not the first time we've seen this.
And we'd like to right this sometime this year before we look back
at this championship run and have it not amount to aesthetically
pleasing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-17-00 2335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000617.0239 </DOCNO>
