<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, June 18. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
KOREA _ Last week, leaders of the two Koreas stunned the world by
signing an agreement to work toward reunifying their divided
homeland, stirring a range of emotions among Korean veterans and
families. It would mean, in a sense, victory _ a word seldom used
in connection with the war, said Ted Barker, a spokesman for the
Korean War Project. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BARRETT _ Paradise Valley resident Craig Barrett, Intel's president
and chief executive officer, is one of the most powerful business
leaders in the world. But because of his low-profile personality,
he can walk Valley streets and hike local peaks in almost complete
anonymity. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MEXICO-ELECT _ Public opinion polls leading up to the July 2
presidential election show a strong majority of Mexican voters are
disenchanted with the ruling PRI, or Institutional Revolutionary
Party. Many Mexicans, however find themselves torn between anger at
PRI's 71-year stewardship and anxiety about what the future would
be like without it. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MEXICO-ECONOMY-ELECT _ Should either challenger Vicente Fox,
candidate of the right-leaning National Action Party, or Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas, candidate of the left-leaning Democratic Revolution
Party, win the Mexican presidency, neither is likely to shift much
from the government's policies of encouraging private investment in
state enterprises and supporting free trade. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN _ (Undated)
</P>
<P>
   By EJ MONTINI. Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K''
categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TV-GOODY (Undated) - Every niche cable network needs an offbeat
hit. And with Iron Chef, the Food Network definitely has one. By
BILL GOODYKOONTZ. Story will move in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
